// AUTO-GENERATED. Re-run: node build.mjs
window.SE_CONTENT = [{"id":"course-welcome-how-a-tech-company-works","section":"Course","title":"Welcome: how a tech company works","html":"<h1 id=\"module-1--welcome-how-a-tech-company-actually-works\">Module 1 —\nWelcome: how a tech company actually works</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> a tech company is a giant city\nof machines that never sleep, and your job is to keep them healthy and\nfix them when they break.</p>\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>Imagine a huge toy factory that runs 24 hours a day, every day.\nNobody ever turns it off. The factory has thousands of rooms. Each room\nhas one machine that does one specific job. One machine wraps presents.\nAnother machine checks if toys are in stock. Another machine sends\nemails when a toy ships.</p>\n<p>Some people in the factory BUILD new machines. They are the\ninventors. Other people WATCH the machines and FIX them when something\ngoes wrong. They are the mechanics.</p>\n<p>You used to help the inventors build machines during your earlier\nexperience. Now you are becoming one of the mechanics who keeps them\nrunning.</p>\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p>A tech company is not one big program. It is thousands of small\nprograms running at the same time on thousands of computers all over the\nworld. Each small program is called a <strong>service</strong>. A\nservice does ONE job and does it over and over again, millions of times\na day.</p>\n<p>For example, one service calculates how much money an employee should\nbe paid. Another service tracks when someone punches in and out of work.\nAnother service sends a text message when someone's shift changes.</p>\n<p>These services never stop. They run in what we call\n<strong>production</strong>. Production means \"the real thing that real\npeople are using right now.\" When you clock in at work, you are using\nproduction. When you check your paycheck, you are using production. If\nproduction breaks, real people cannot do their work.</p>\n<p>There are two main roles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Software Development Engineer (SDE)</strong> — they BUILD\nnew services or add new features to existing services</li>\n<li><strong>Support Engineer (SE)</strong> — they WATCH services, answer\nquestions about them, and FIX them when something goes wrong</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You were an engineer. You helped build things. Now you are becoming\nan SE. Your job is to keep things alive and working.</p>\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>Every service on the job is owned by a team. That team is responsible\nwhen it breaks. If the payroll service crashes, people do not get paid\non time. If the time-tracking service crashes, managers cannot see who\nis working. These are real problems that hurt real people.</p>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, you are the first line of defense. When\nsomething goes wrong, you are the one who investigates. You figure out\nWHAT broke, WHY it broke, and HOW to fix it. Sometimes you fix it\nyourself. Sometimes you route it to the right engineer. But you are\nALWAYS the person who makes sure the problem gets solved.</p>\n<p>You are not expected to know everything. Nobody does. A tech company\nis too big. What you ARE expected to know is WHERE to look and HOW to\nask for help. This course teaches you that.</p>\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<p>Here is what happens when a service runs in production:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>A service sits on a computer somewhere.</strong> That\ncomputer is called a <strong>host</strong>. The host is running in an a\ntech company data center.</li>\n<li><strong>Someone or something asks the service to do work.</strong>\nFor example, an employee clocks in using an app. The app sends a message\nto the time-tracking service saying \"record this punch.\"</li>\n<li><strong>The service does the work and answers back.</strong> It\nsaves the punch to a database and replies \"done.\"</li>\n<li><strong>Logs get written.</strong> The service writes down what it\ndid in a file called a <strong>log</strong>. Logs are like a diary. They\nsay \"at 9:00 AM, employee 12345 clocked in.\"</li>\n<li><strong>Metrics get recorded.</strong> The service also tracks\nnumbers like \"how many punches did I process in the last minute?\" These\nnumbers are called <strong>metrics</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Alarms watch the metrics.</strong> If something looks wrong\n(like the service is too slow or it starts failing), an\n<strong>alarm</strong> fires. The alarm sends a message to the team that\nowns the service.</li>\n<li><strong>The Support Engineer investigates.</strong> You look at the\nlogs, the metrics, and the error messages. You figure out what\nbroke.</li>\n<li><strong>You fix it or route it.</strong> Sometimes you can fix it by\nrestarting something or rolling back a bad change. Sometimes you need to\nask an SDE to write code to fix the root cause.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This is the loop. Service runs, logs and metrics flow, alarms fire\nwhen something is wrong, you investigate and fix.</p>\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Service</strong></td>\n<td>A program that does one job and runs forever</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Production</strong></td>\n<td>The real system that real people are using right now</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Host</strong></td>\n<td>A computer that runs a service</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Log</strong></td>\n<td>A diary file where the service writes down what it did</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Metric</strong></td>\n<td>A number that tracks how the service is doing (like speed or error\ncount)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Alarm</strong></td>\n<td>A warning that fires when a metric looks bad</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)</strong></td>\n<td>A ticket system where you track problems and fixes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>On-call</strong></td>\n<td>Being the person who gets paged when alarms fire</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Deployment</strong></td>\n<td>Pushing a new version of a service to production</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Rollback</strong></td>\n<td>Undoing a deployment and going back to the old version</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<p>Your day-to-day work will look like this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Monitor alarms.</strong> You watch dashboards that show\nwhich services are healthy and which are not.</li>\n<li><strong>Investigate tickets.</strong> Someone reports a problem. You\nread the logs, check the metrics, and figure out what happened.</li>\n<li><strong>Answer questions.</strong> A teammate asks \"why did this\nservice slow down yesterday?\" You go find out.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix small things.</strong> Sometimes you can fix a problem\nby changing a config or restarting a service.</li>\n<li><strong>Route big things.</strong> If the fix needs code changes,\nyou file a ticket for an SDE and explain what is broken.</li>\n<li><strong>Document what you learn.</strong> You write down how to fix\ncommon problems so the next person does not have to start from\nzero.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You are NOT expected to know how every service works inside. You ARE\nexpected to know how to INVESTIGATE. That is the skill this course\nteaches.</p>\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>What is the difference between an SDE and an SE?</strong>\n(Hint: one builds, one fixes)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>What is \"production\" and why does it matter?</strong>\n(Hint: real people, right now)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>If an alarm fires at 3 AM, whose job is it to\ninvestigate?</strong> (Hint: you, if you are on-call)</p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Next module:</strong> The 4 buckets of onboarding (welcome\ndesks, driving school, language class, the map)</p>\n","text":"module 1 — welcome: how a tech company actually works the one line version: a tech company is a giant city of machines that never sleep, and your job is to keep them healthy and fix them when they break. picture this (the analogy) imagine a huge toy factory that runs 24 hours a day, every day. nobody ever turns it off. the factory has thousands of rooms. each room has one machine that does one specific job. one machine wraps presents. another machine checks if toys are in stock. another machine sends emails when a toy ships. some people in the factory build new machines. they are the inventors. other people watch the machines and fix them when something goes wrong. they are the mechanics. you used to help the inventors build machines during your earlier experience. now you are becoming one of the mechanics who keeps them running. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) a tech company is not one big program. it is thousands of small programs running at the same time on thousands of computers all over the world. each small program is called a service . a service does one job and does it over and over again, millions of times a day. for example, one service calculates how much money an employee should be paid. another service tracks when someone punches in and out of work. another service sends a text message when someone's shift changes. these services never stop. they run in what we call production . production means \"the real thing that real people are using right now.\" when you clock in at work, you are using production. when you check your paycheck, you are using production. if production breaks, real people cannot do their work. there are two main roles: software development engineer (sde) — they build new services or add new features to existing services support engineer (se) — they watch services, answer questions about them, and fix them when something goes wrong you were an engineer. you helped build things. now you are becoming an se. your job is to keep things alive and working. why you should care every service on the job is owned by a team. that team is responsible when it breaks. if the payroll service crashes, people do not get paid on time. if the time tracking service crashes, managers cannot see who is working. these are real problems that hurt real people. as a support engineer, you are the first line of defense. when something goes wrong, you are the one who investigates. you figure out what broke, why it broke, and how to fix it. sometimes you fix it yourself. sometimes you route it to the right engineer. but you are always the person who makes sure the problem gets solved. you are not expected to know everything. nobody does. a tech company is too big. what you are expected to know is where to look and how to ask for help. this course teaches you that. how it works, step by tiny step here is what happens when a service runs in production: 1. a service sits on a computer somewhere. that computer is called a host . the host is running in an a tech company data center. 2. someone or something asks the service to do work. for example, an employee clocks in using an app. the app sends a message to the time tracking service saying \"record this punch.\" 3. the service does the work and answers back. it saves the punch to a database and replies \"done.\" 4. logs get written. the service writes down what it did in a file called a log . logs are like a diary. they say \"at 9:00 am, employee 12345 clocked in.\" 5. metrics get recorded. the service also tracks numbers like \"how many punches did i process in the last minute?\" these numbers are called metrics . 6. alarms watch the metrics. if something looks wrong (like the service is too slow or it starts failing), an alarm fires. the alarm sends a message to the team that owns the service. 7. the support engineer investigates. you look at the logs, the metrics, and the error messages. you figure out what broke. 8. you fix it or route it. sometimes you can fix it by restarting something or rolling back a bad change. sometimes you need to ask an sde to write code to fix the root cause. this is the loop. service runs, logs and metrics flow, alarms fire when something is wrong, you investigate and fix. words you will hear term plain meaning service a program that does one job and runs forever production the real system that real people are using right now host a computer that runs a service log a diary file where the service writes down what it did metric a number that tracks how the service is doing (like speed or error count) alarm a warning that fires when a metric looks bad the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) a ticket system where you track problems and fixes on call being the person who gets paged when alarms fire deployment pushing a new version of a service to production rollback undoing a deployment and going back to the old version what you actually do with this your day to day work will look like this: monitor alarms. you watch dashboards that show which services are healthy and which are not. investigate tickets. someone reports a problem. you read the logs, check the metrics, and figure out what happened. answer questions. a teammate asks \"why did this service slow down yesterday?\" you go find out. fix small things. sometimes you can fix a problem by changing a config or restarting a service. route big things. if the fix needs code changes, you file a ticket for an sde and explain what is broken. document what you learn. you write down how to fix common problems so the next person does not have to start from zero. you are not expected to know how every service works inside. you are expected to know how to investigate. that is the skill this course teaches. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. what is the difference between an sde and an se? (hint: one builds, one fixes) 2. what is \"production\" and why does it matter? (hint: real people, right now) 3. if an alarm fires at 3 am, whose job is it to investigate? (hint: you, if you are on call) next module: the 4 buckets of onboarding (welcome desks, driving school, language class, the map)","words":1224},{"id":"course-first-days-access-where-to-look","section":"Course","title":"First days: access & where to look","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-2--your-first-days-laptop-logins-and-where-to-look\">Module 2\n— Your first days: laptop, logins, and where to look</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> On day one, you get your\nlaptop and spend time tapping your security key, joining groups that\ngive you permissions, and learning where to find answers when stuck.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>Imagine your first day at a huge library. The librarian hands you a\nlibrary card (your laptop + login). But not all books are open to\neveryone. Some rooms need a special key. So you get a small metal key\nyou tap on doors (your security key / a hardware security key). Each\ntime you tap, a door unlocks for a few hours, then locks again.\nSafe.</p>\n<p>Some books are only for certain clubs. The librarian adds your name\nto club lists (POSIX groups). Once you are on the \"Reference Desk Club\"\nlist, you can walk into that room. No list = no entry.</p>\n<p>The library has a giant manual at the front desk (the internal docs\nhub) that explains every room, every tool, every rule. When you are\nlost, you check the manual first. If the manual is confusing, you ask\nthe friendly assistant at the help desk (a tech company AI assistant,\nthe AI chat). If still stuck, you ask your assigned library buddy. If\nyour buddy does not know, you ask the help channel (a chat room where\nother people answer questions all day).</p>\n<p>That is your first week on the job.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p>A tech company's network is locked down tight. You cannot just open\nany internal website or tool. You have to prove you are you, over and\nover. That proof system has three layers:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Your laptop login</strong> — username + password. This gets\nyou into the machine.</li>\n<li><strong>company single sign-on (SSO)</strong> — a security\ncheckpoint that pops up when you try to reach internal websites (like\nwikis, the internal docs hub, the ticketing system (like Jira or\nPagerDuty), the code review tool (like GitHub pull requests)). company\nsingle sign-on (SSO) asks you to tap your security key to prove you are\nreally you, not someone who stole your password.</li>\n<li><strong>POSIX groups / LDAP groups</strong> — named lists of people\nwho are allowed to do specific things. Example: the group\n\"CloudWatch-ReadOnly\" gives you permission to read CloudWatch logs. If\nyour name is on that list, you get in. If not, you see \"Access\nDenied.\"</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Your first days are spent getting added to the right groups, tapping\nyour security key a lot, and learning where to look when you do not know\nsomething.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>If you do not have the right groups, you cannot do your job. You will\nhit \"Access Denied\" on tools you need. Knowing how to request access\n(and who to ask) is a survival skill.</p>\n<p>If you do not know where to find answers, you waste hours guessing or\nwaiting for someone to notice you are stuck. Learning the \"ask flow\"\n(the internal docs hub → a tech company AI assistant → buddy → help\nchannel) makes you self-sufficient fast.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<h3 id=\"1-you-get-your-laptop\">1. You get your laptop</h3>\n<p>IT hands you a MacBook (most common) or a Linux machine. It is\nalready set up with your a tech company login. Username is usually your\nalias (the short name before @your-company.example). Password is what\nyou set during onboarding.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2-you-log-in\">2. You log in</h3>\n<p>Type your username and password. The laptop opens. You see a desktop.\nNothing a tech company-specific yet.</p>\n<h3 id=\"3-you-try-to-open-an-internal-website\">3. You try to open an\ninternal website</h3>\n<p>You open a browser. You go to your team's internal docs (or any a\ntech company internal site). The page does not load yet. Instead, a new\npage pops up: <strong>company single sign-on (SSO)</strong>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"4-company-single-sign-on-sso-asks-for-your-security-key\">4.\ncompany single sign-on (SSO) asks for your security key</h3>\n<p>company single sign-on (SSO) is the gatekeeper. It says \"Tap your\nsecurity key to continue.\" You pull out your <strong>a hardware security\nkey</strong> (a small USB stick or NFC device IT gave you). You plug it\nin or tap it on your laptop. A light blinks. company single sign-on\n(SSO) says \"OK, you are in.\" The original website loads.</p>\n<p>This happens every few hours. company single sign-on (SSO) times out.\nYou tap again. It is annoying but keeps attackers out.</p>\n<h3 id=\"5-you-hit-access-denied-on-a-tool\">5. You hit \"Access Denied\" on\na tool</h3>\n<p>You try to open CloudWatch. The page says \"You do not have\npermission.\" This means you are not in the right POSIX group yet.</p>\n<h3 id=\"6-you-request-access\">6. You request access</h3>\n<p>You search the internal docs hub for \"CloudWatch access.\" The doc\nsays \"Join group XYZ via <link>.\" You click the link. A form opens. You\nsubmit. A human (or automated system) approves it. You get an email:\n\"You are now in group XYZ.\" You try CloudWatch again. It works.</p>\n<p>This pattern repeats for every tool. the ticketing system (like Jira\nor PagerDuty), the code review tool (like GitHub pull requests),\nPipelines, the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD), the cloud\naccess tool (AWS account access), the company directory, wiki write\naccess. Each has a group. You join groups as you need them.</p>\n<h3 id=\"7-you-find-your-onboarding-portal\">7. You find your onboarding\nportal</h3>\n<p>You go to <strong>A tech company portal</strong> (https://your\ncompany portal). This replaced the old the old intranet site (which dies\nmid-June 2026, so do not bookmark old the old intranet links). A tech\ncompany portal is your HR home. Paystubs, benefits, learning courses, IT\nhelp tickets, all here.</p>\n<h3 id=\"8-you-take-the-three-starter-courses\">8. You take the three\nstarter courses</h3>\n<p>A tech company portal points you to your onboarding hub. Three\nmandatory short courses:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Developing Software on the job</strong> (~1 hour) — how we\nwrite code, review code, deploy code</li>\n<li><strong>A tech company's Operational Culture</strong> (~45 min) —\non-call, metrics, alarms, COEs (postmortems)</li>\n<li><strong>Finding Answers on the job</strong> (~15 min) — where to\nsearch, who to ask</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You watch videos, click through slides, take tiny quizzes. They are\nboring but teach real survival skills.</p>\n<h3 id=\"9-you-meet-your-onboarding-buddy\">9. You meet your onboarding\nbuddy</h3>\n<p>Your manager assigns a teammate as your <strong>onboarding\nbuddy</strong>. This person is your first-line question answerer. Not\nyour manager. A peer. Someone who remembers being new. You Slack them\ndumb questions. They do not judge. They help.</p>\n<h3 id=\"10-you-join-the-help-channel\">10. You join the help channel</h3>\n<p>You join <strong>#new-hire-help</strong> on Slack (or your team's\nequivalent). This is a chat room where new hires ask \"How do I get\naccess to X?\" or \"What does Y mean?\" and experienced people answer fast.\nAsking here is encouraged. Suffering in silence is not.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>company single sign-on (SSO)</strong></td>\n<td>The security checkpoint page that makes you tap your a hardware\nsecurity key before loading internal websites. Pops up every few\nhours.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>a hardware security key / Security Key</strong></td>\n<td>A small physical device (USB stick or NFC tap) that proves you are\nyou. You tap it to pass company single sign-on (SSO). IT gives you one\non day one.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>POSIX group / LDAP group</strong></td>\n<td>A named list of people allowed to do something. Example: \"the\nticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)-ReadOnly\" group gives you read\naccess to the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) tickets. Being\n\"added to a group\" gives you the permission.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>A tech company portal</strong></td>\n<td>The new employee home portal (replaced old the old intranet). HR,\nbenefits, learning, IT tickets. https://your company portal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>A tech company AI assistant</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's internal AI chat assistant. Like ChatGPT but\ntrained on a tech company docs. You ask it \"How do I get CloudWatch\naccess?\" and it gives you a link.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the internal docs hub</strong></td>\n<td>The giant manual for all a tech company tools. If you do not know\nhow a tool works, search the internal docs hub first. your team's\ninternal docs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Onboarding buddy</strong></td>\n<td>A teammate assigned to help you in your first weeks. Your first-line\nquestion answerer. Slack them anything.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>#new-hire-help</strong></td>\n<td>A Slack channel where new hires ask questions and experienced people\nanswer. \"new-hire-help\" is the channel where new engineers ask setup\nquestions.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<h3 id=\"day-1\">Day 1</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Log into laptop with username + password</li>\n<li>Tap a hardware security key every time company single sign-on (SSO)\npops up (get used to this, it never stops)</li>\n<li>Go to a tech company portal, find your onboarding portal, start the\nthree short courses</li>\n<li>Slack your onboarding buddy: \"Hi, I am <your name>, excited to join\nthe team. When is a good time to chat?\"</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"first-week\">First week</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Every time you hit \"Access Denied,\" search the internal docs hub for\n\"<tool name> access request\"</li>\n<li>If the internal docs hub is confusing, ask a tech company AI\nassistant: \"How do I get access to the ticketing system (like Jira or\nPagerDuty)?\"</li>\n<li>If a tech company AI assistant gives a broken link or vague answer,\nask your buddy</li>\n<li>If your buddy does not know, ask #new-hire-help</li>\n<li>Keep a running list of groups you joined, so you remember what you\nhave access to</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"first-month\">First month</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Finish the three onboarding courses (required)</li>\n<li>Get added to all the groups your team uses (your buddy or manager\nwill tell you the list)</li>\n<li>Build the habit: stuck → the internal docs hub → a tech company AI\nassistant → buddy → help channel, in that order</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>What is company single sign-on (SSO), and why does it pop\nup?</strong> Answer: company single sign-on (SSO) is the security\ncheckpoint that asks you to tap your a hardware security key to prove\nyou are really you before loading internal websites. It pops up every\nfew hours to keep attackers out even if they steal your\npassword.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>What is a POSIX group, and why do you need to join\nthem?</strong> Answer: A POSIX group is a named list of people allowed\nto do something (like read CloudWatch logs or write the ticketing system\n(like Jira or PagerDuty) tickets). You need to join groups to get\npermissions. No group = Access Denied.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You are stuck. You do not know how to request access to a\ntool. What is the ask flow?</strong> Answer: (1) Search the internal\ndocs hub for \"<tool> access request.\" (2) If that is confusing, ask a\ntech company AI assistant. (3) If a tech company AI assistant does not\nhelp, ask your onboarding buddy. (4) If your buddy does not know, ask\nthe help channel #new-hire-help.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Next up:</strong> Module 3 will teach you what a Support\nEngineer actually DOES day-to-day (spoiler: you are the bridge between\ncustomers who are stuck and engineers who can fix the root cause).</p>\n","text":"module 2 — your first days: laptop, logins, and where to look the one line version: on day one, you get your laptop and spend time tapping your security key, joining groups that give you permissions, and learning where to find answers when stuck. picture this (the analogy) imagine your first day at a huge library. the librarian hands you a library card (your laptop + login). but not all books are open to everyone. some rooms need a special key. so you get a small metal key you tap on doors (your security key / a hardware security key). each time you tap, a door unlocks for a few hours, then locks again. safe. some books are only for certain clubs. the librarian adds your name to club lists (posix groups). once you are on the \"reference desk club\" list, you can walk into that room. no list = no entry. the library has a giant manual at the front desk (the internal docs hub) that explains every room, every tool, every rule. when you are lost, you check the manual first. if the manual is confusing, you ask the friendly assistant at the help desk (a tech company ai assistant, the ai chat). if still stuck, you ask your assigned library buddy. if your buddy does not know, you ask the help channel (a chat room where other people answer questions all day). that is your first week on the job. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) a tech company's network is locked down tight. you cannot just open any internal website or tool. you have to prove you are you, over and over. that proof system has three layers: 1. your laptop login — username + password. this gets you into the machine. 2. company single sign on (sso) — a security checkpoint that pops up when you try to reach internal websites (like wikis, the internal docs hub, the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty), the code review tool (like github pull requests)). company single sign on (sso) asks you to tap your security key to prove you are really you, not someone who stole your password. 3. posix groups / ldap groups — named lists of people who are allowed to do specific things. example: the group \"cloudwatch readonly\" gives you permission to read cloudwatch logs. if your name is on that list, you get in. if not, you see \"access denied.\" your first days are spent getting added to the right groups, tapping your security key a lot, and learning where to look when you do not know something. why you should care if you do not have the right groups, you cannot do your job. you will hit \"access denied\" on tools you need. knowing how to request access (and who to ask) is a survival skill. if you do not know where to find answers, you waste hours guessing or waiting for someone to notice you are stuck. learning the \"ask flow\" (the internal docs hub → a tech company ai assistant → buddy → help channel) makes you self sufficient fast. how it works, step by tiny step 1. you get your laptop it hands you a macbook (most common) or a linux machine. it is already set up with your a tech company login. username is usually your alias (the short name before @your company.example). password is what you set during onboarding. 2. you log in type your username and password. the laptop opens. you see a desktop. nothing a tech company specific yet. 3. you try to open an internal website you open a browser. you go to your team's internal docs (or any a tech company internal site). the page does not load yet. instead, a new page pops up: company single sign on (sso) . 4. company single sign on (sso) asks for your security key company single sign on (sso) is the gatekeeper. it says \"tap your security key to continue.\" you pull out your a hardware security key (a small usb stick or nfc device it gave you). you plug it in or tap it on your laptop. a light blinks. company single sign on (sso) says \"ok, you are in.\" the original website loads. this happens every few hours. company single sign on (sso) times out. you tap again. it is annoying but keeps attackers out. 5. you hit \"access denied\" on a tool you try to open cloudwatch. the page says \"you do not have permission.\" this means you are not in the right posix group yet. 6. you request access you search the internal docs hub for \"cloudwatch access.\" the doc says \"join group xyz via <link .\" you click the link. a form opens. you submit. a human (or automated system) approves it. you get an email: \"you are now in group xyz.\" you try cloudwatch again. it works. this pattern repeats for every tool. the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty), the code review tool (like github pull requests), pipelines, the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd), the cloud access tool (aws account access), the company directory, wiki write access. each has a group. you join groups as you need them. 7. you find your onboarding portal you go to a tech company portal (https://your company portal). this replaced the old the old intranet site (which dies mid june 2026, so do not bookmark old the old intranet links). a tech company portal is your hr home. paystubs, benefits, learning courses, it help tickets, all here. 8. you take the three starter courses a tech company portal points you to your onboarding hub. three mandatory short courses: developing software on the job (~1 hour) — how we write code, review code, deploy code a tech company's operational culture (~45 min) — on call, metrics, alarms, coes (postmortems) finding answers on the job (~15 min) — where to search, who to ask you watch videos, click through slides, take tiny quizzes. they are boring but teach real survival skills. 9. you meet your onboarding buddy your manager assigns a teammate as your onboarding buddy . this person is your first line question answerer. not your manager. a peer. someone who remembers being new. you slack them dumb questions. they do not judge. they help. 10. you join the help channel you join new hire help on slack (or your team's equivalent). this is a chat room where new hires ask \"how do i get access to x?\" or \"what does y mean?\" and experienced people answer fast. asking here is encouraged. suffering in silence is not. words you will hear term plain meaning company single sign on (sso) the security checkpoint page that makes you tap your a hardware security key before loading internal websites. pops up every few hours. a hardware security key / security key a small physical device (usb stick or nfc tap) that proves you are you. you tap it to pass company single sign on (sso). it gives you one on day one. posix group / ldap group a named list of people allowed to do something. example: \"the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) readonly\" group gives you read access to the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) tickets. being \"added to a group\" gives you the permission. a tech company portal the new employee home portal (replaced old the old intranet). hr, benefits, learning, it tickets. https://your company portal a tech company ai assistant a tech company's internal ai chat assistant. like chatgpt but trained on a tech company docs. you ask it \"how do i get cloudwatch access?\" and it gives you a link. the internal docs hub the giant manual for all a tech company tools. if you do not know how a tool works, search the internal docs hub first. your team's internal docs onboarding buddy a teammate assigned to help you in your first weeks. your first line question answerer. slack them anything. new hire help a slack channel where new hires ask questions and experienced people answer. \"new hire help\" is the channel where new engineers ask setup questions. what you actually do with this day 1 log into laptop with username + password tap a hardware security key every time company single sign on (sso) pops up (get used to this, it never stops) go to a tech company portal, find your onboarding portal, start the three short courses slack your onboarding buddy: \"hi, i am <your name , excited to join the team. when is a good time to chat?\" first week every time you hit \"access denied,\" search the internal docs hub for \"<tool name access request\" if the internal docs hub is confusing, ask a tech company ai assistant: \"how do i get access to the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty)?\" if a tech company ai assistant gives a broken link or vague answer, ask your buddy if your buddy does not know, ask new hire help keep a running list of groups you joined, so you remember what you have access to first month finish the three onboarding courses (required) get added to all the groups your team uses (your buddy or manager will tell you the list) build the habit: stuck → the internal docs hub → a tech company ai assistant → buddy → help channel, in that order how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. what is company single sign on (sso), and why does it pop up? answer: company single sign on (sso) is the security checkpoint that asks you to tap your a hardware security key to prove you are really you before loading internal websites. it pops up every few hours to keep attackers out even if they steal your password. 2. what is a posix group, and why do you need to join them? answer: a posix group is a named list of people allowed to do something (like read cloudwatch logs or write the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) tickets). you need to join groups to get permissions. no group = access denied. 3. you are stuck. you do not know how to request access to a tool. what is the ask flow? answer: (1) search the internal docs hub for \"<tool access request.\" (2) if that is confusing, ask a tech company ai assistant. (3) if a tech company ai assistant does not help, ask your onboarding buddy. (4) if your buddy does not know, ask the help channel new hire help. next up: module 3 will teach you what a support engineer actually does day to day (spoiler: you are the bridge between customers who are stuck and engineers who can fix the root cause).","words":1901},{"id":"course-the-developer-environment","section":"Course","title":"The developer environment","html":"<h1 id=\"module-3--your-workshop-the-developer-environment\">Module 3 —\nYour workshop: the developer environment</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> Your developer environment is\nthe computer setup where you write code, run tools, and fix problems —\nit can live on your laptop or in the cloud.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>Imagine you are building a house out of LEGO bricks.</p>\n<p>You need a table to work on. You need your bricks in boxes nearby.\nYou need the instruction booklet open. You need good light. You need\nenough space so you do not knock things over.</p>\n<p>That whole setup — the table, the organized boxes, the booklet, the\nspace — is your workshop.</p>\n<p>A developer environment is your digital workshop. It is the place\nwhere you build software.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p>A <strong>developer environment</strong> is a computer (or a piece of\na computer) set up with all the tools you need to write code, test it,\nand ship it.</p>\n<p>It has:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A place to type commands (called a <strong>terminal</strong> or\n<strong>command line</strong>)</li>\n<li>A folder where your code lives (called your\n<strong>workspace</strong>)</li>\n<li>Tools installed (like the build system for building, git for version\ncontrol, aws for cloud stuff)</li>\n<li>A way to run your code and see if it works</li>\n</ul>\n<p>on the job, you have two main choices:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Local</strong> — your laptop is the workshop. Everything\nruns on your machine.</li>\n<li><strong>a cloud dev machine / a cloud dev environment</strong> — a\ncomputer in the cloud (a tech company's data center) is the workshop.\nYou connect to it over the internet. Your laptop is just the window\nlooking at it.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Most engineers use a cloud dev machine for heavy work. It does not\nmelt your laptop battery. It has more power. If your laptop dies, your\nwork is still safe in the cloud.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>You cannot write code without a place to write it.</p>\n<p>You cannot test code without a place to run it.</p>\n<p>You cannot ship code without tools to build and deploy it.</p>\n<p>Setting up your developer environment correctly saves you hundreds of\nhours. You do it once carefully. Then it works forever.</p>\n<p>A broken environment feels like trying to build LEGO on a wobbly\ntable in the dark with half the bricks missing. You spend all day\nfrustrated instead of building cool things.</p>\n<p>A good environment feels invisible. You type commands. Things work.\nYou focus on solving problems instead of fighting your tools.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<h3 id=\"step-1-pick-your-workshop-a-cloud-dev-machine-or-local\">Step 1:\nPick your workshop (a cloud dev machine or local)</h3>\n<p>Most Support Engineers use <strong>a cloud dev machine</strong> (also\ncalled <strong>a cloud dev environment</strong> in some docs). It is a\nLinux computer running in AWS. You log in through a web browser or a\nspecial app.</p>\n<p>Why a cloud dev machine wins:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Your laptop stays cool and fast</li>\n<li>Heavy builds run on a big machine, not your battery</li>\n<li>Your setup is backed up automatically</li>\n<li>You can access it from anywhere</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"step-2-open-a-terminal\">Step 2: Open a terminal</h3>\n<p>A <strong>terminal</strong> is a window where you type text commands\nto the computer. It looks old school (black background, green text). It\nis powerful.</p>\n<p>Think of it like texting your computer. Instead of clicking buttons,\nyou type: \"build this code\" or \"show me the files\" or \"run this\ntest.\"</p>\n<p>On a cloud dev machine, you click the terminal icon. A black window\nopens. You are ready.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step-3-understand-your-workspace\">Step 3: Understand your\nworkspace</h3>\n<p>Your <strong>workspace</strong> is a folder where your code\nlives.</p>\n<p>on the job, most people keep code in <code>/workplace/</code> (on a\ncloud dev machine) or <code>~/workplace/</code> (on local laptop).</p>\n<p>Inside that folder, you have folders for each project. One project\nmight be <code>the payroll-calculation service</code>. Another might be\n<code>the time-tracking service</code>. Each project has its own code,\ntests, and config files.</p>\n<p>You use the terminal to move between folders. The command\n<code>cd /workplace/the payroll-calculation service</code> means \"change\ndirectory to that project folder.\"</p>\n<h3 id=\"step-4-install-the-tools-with-the-dev-tools-installer\">Step 4:\nInstall the tools with the dev-tools installer</h3>\n<p>A tech company has a tool called <strong>the dev-tools\ninstaller</strong>. It installs and updates all a tech company dev tools\nfor you automatically.</p>\n<p>You run it once when setting up. Then you run it again every few\nweeks to get updates.</p>\n<p>the dev-tools installer installs things like:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>the build system</strong> (the build system)</li>\n<li><strong>git</strong> (version control)</li>\n<li><strong>cr</strong> (code review tool)</li>\n<li><strong>aws CLI</strong> (talk to AWS services)</li>\n<li><strong>the cloud-login CLI</strong> (log into AWS accounts)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You do not install these one by one. the dev-tools installer does it\nall.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step-5-follow-the-setup-checklist\">Step 5: Follow the setup\nchecklist</h3>\n<p>A tech company has a <strong>Developer Environment Setup</strong>\nguide on the internal docs hub: your team's internal docs</p>\n<p>It walks you through:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Setting up a cloud dev machine (or local)</li>\n<li>Running the dev-tools installer</li>\n<li>Checking that everything works</li>\n<li>Cloning your first code package</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Follow it step by step. Check off each item. Do not skip steps.\nSkipping step 3 means step 7 breaks in a weird way later.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step-6-test-that-it-works\">Step 6: Test that it works</h3>\n<p>After setup, try a simple command:</p>\n<pre><code>the build command</code></pre>\n<p>If it says \"BUILD SUCCESSFUL\" at the end, your environment works. You\nare ready to write code.</p>\n<p>If it fails, the error message tells you what is missing. Usually it\nis \"you skipped step 4 in the setup guide.\"</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Terminal</strong></td>\n<td>A window where you type text commands to the computer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Command line</strong></td>\n<td>Same as terminal (people use both names)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Workspace</strong></td>\n<td>The folder where your code lives</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>a cloud dev machine</strong></td>\n<td>A computer in AWS that you connect to over the internet</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>a cloud dev environment</strong></td>\n<td>Another name for a cloud dev machine (older docs use this)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the dev-tools installer</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's tool that installs and updates all the dev tools\nfor you</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shell</strong></td>\n<td>The program inside the terminal that reads your commands (usually\nbash or zsh)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>cd</strong></td>\n<td>\"Change directory\" — the command to move between folders</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>ls</strong></td>\n<td>\"List\" — the command to see what files are in a folder</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>pwd</strong></td>\n<td>\"Print working directory\" — the command to see which folder you are\nin right now</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<p>Every day you:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Log into a cloud dev machine (or open terminal on your laptop)</li>\n<li>Navigate to your workspace folder:\n<code>cd /workplace/MyProject</code></li>\n<li>Type commands to build code, run tests, or deploy changes</li>\n<li>Use the terminal to check logs, search files, or debug problems</li>\n</ol>\n<p>You do not click through menus. You type. It is faster once you learn\nthe commands.</p>\n<p>The first week feels slow. You have to look up every command. By week\nthree, your fingers remember. By month two, you are flying.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>What is a terminal?</strong> A window where you type text\ncommands to the computer (instead of clicking buttons).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Why do most a tech company engineers use a cloud dev\nmachine instead of their laptop?</strong> It keeps the laptop cool and\nfast. Heavy builds run on a big machine in AWS instead of draining the\nlaptop battery. Your setup is backed up automatically.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>What does the command\n<code>cd /workplace/MyProject</code> do?</strong> It changes the current\nfolder (directory) to the MyProject folder inside /workplace/. After\nrunning it, any commands you type will apply to files in that\nfolder.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Next up:</strong> Module 4 — The terminal command survival\nkit (the 10 commands you will type 1000 times).</p>\n","text":"module 3 — your workshop: the developer environment the one line version: your developer environment is the computer setup where you write code, run tools, and fix problems — it can live on your laptop or in the cloud. picture this (the analogy) imagine you are building a house out of lego bricks. you need a table to work on. you need your bricks in boxes nearby. you need the instruction booklet open. you need good light. you need enough space so you do not knock things over. that whole setup — the table, the organized boxes, the booklet, the space — is your workshop. a developer environment is your digital workshop. it is the place where you build software. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) a developer environment is a computer (or a piece of a computer) set up with all the tools you need to write code, test it, and ship it. it has: a place to type commands (called a terminal or command line ) a folder where your code lives (called your workspace ) tools installed (like the build system for building, git for version control, aws for cloud stuff) a way to run your code and see if it works on the job, you have two main choices: 1. local — your laptop is the workshop. everything runs on your machine. 2. a cloud dev machine / a cloud dev environment — a computer in the cloud (a tech company's data center) is the workshop. you connect to it over the internet. your laptop is just the window looking at it. most engineers use a cloud dev machine for heavy work. it does not melt your laptop battery. it has more power. if your laptop dies, your work is still safe in the cloud. why you should care you cannot write code without a place to write it. you cannot test code without a place to run it. you cannot ship code without tools to build and deploy it. setting up your developer environment correctly saves you hundreds of hours. you do it once carefully. then it works forever. a broken environment feels like trying to build lego on a wobbly table in the dark with half the bricks missing. you spend all day frustrated instead of building cool things. a good environment feels invisible. you type commands. things work. you focus on solving problems instead of fighting your tools. how it works, step by tiny step step 1: pick your workshop (a cloud dev machine or local) most support engineers use a cloud dev machine (also called a cloud dev environment in some docs). it is a linux computer running in aws. you log in through a web browser or a special app. why a cloud dev machine wins: your laptop stays cool and fast heavy builds run on a big machine, not your battery your setup is backed up automatically you can access it from anywhere step 2: open a terminal a terminal is a window where you type text commands to the computer. it looks old school (black background, green text). it is powerful. think of it like texting your computer. instead of clicking buttons, you type: \"build this code\" or \"show me the files\" or \"run this test.\" on a cloud dev machine, you click the terminal icon. a black window opens. you are ready. step 3: understand your workspace your workspace is a folder where your code lives. on the job, most people keep code in /workplace/ (on a cloud dev machine) or ~/workplace/ (on local laptop). inside that folder, you have folders for each project. one project might be the payroll calculation service . another might be the time tracking service . each project has its own code, tests, and config files. you use the terminal to move between folders. the command cd /workplace/the payroll calculation service means \"change directory to that project folder.\" step 4: install the tools with the dev tools installer a tech company has a tool called the dev tools installer . it installs and updates all a tech company dev tools for you automatically. you run it once when setting up. then you run it again every few weeks to get updates. the dev tools installer installs things like: the build system (the build system) git (version control) cr (code review tool) aws cli (talk to aws services) the cloud login cli (log into aws accounts) you do not install these one by one. the dev tools installer does it all. step 5: follow the setup checklist a tech company has a developer environment setup guide on the internal docs hub: your team's internal docs it walks you through: 1. setting up a cloud dev machine (or local) 2. running the dev tools installer 3. checking that everything works 4. cloning your first code package follow it step by step. check off each item. do not skip steps. skipping step 3 means step 7 breaks in a weird way later. step 6: test that it works after setup, try a simple command: if it says \"build successful\" at the end, your environment works. you are ready to write code. if it fails, the error message tells you what is missing. usually it is \"you skipped step 4 in the setup guide.\" words you will hear term plain meaning terminal a window where you type text commands to the computer command line same as terminal (people use both names) workspace the folder where your code lives a cloud dev machine a computer in aws that you connect to over the internet a cloud dev environment another name for a cloud dev machine (older docs use this) the dev tools installer a tech company's tool that installs and updates all the dev tools for you shell the program inside the terminal that reads your commands (usually bash or zsh) cd \"change directory\" — the command to move between folders ls \"list\" — the command to see what files are in a folder pwd \"print working directory\" — the command to see which folder you are in right now what you actually do with this every day you: 1. log into a cloud dev machine (or open terminal on your laptop) 2. navigate to your workspace folder: cd /workplace/myproject 3. type commands to build code, run tests, or deploy changes 4. use the terminal to check logs, search files, or debug problems you do not click through menus. you type. it is faster once you learn the commands. the first week feels slow. you have to look up every command. by week three, your fingers remember. by month two, you are flying. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. what is a terminal? a window where you type text commands to the computer (instead of clicking buttons). 2. why do most a tech company engineers use a cloud dev machine instead of their laptop? it keeps the laptop cool and fast. heavy builds run on a big machine in aws instead of draining the laptop battery. your setup is backed up automatically. 3. what does the command cd /workplace/myproject do? it changes the current folder (directory) to the myproject folder inside /workplace/. after running it, any commands you type will apply to files in that folder. next up: module 4 — the terminal command survival kit (the 10 commands you will type 1000 times).","words":1368},{"id":"course-how-code-lives-git-packages","section":"Course","title":"How code lives: Git & packages","html":"<h1 id=\"module-4--how-code-lives-files-git-and-packages\">Module 4 — How\ncode lives: files, Git, and packages</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> Code lives in files on your\ncomputer, Git is a time machine that tracks every change, and a tech\ncompany keeps all the code safe in the central Git server so teams can\nshare it.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>Imagine you are writing a story in a notebook. Every page is a file.\nWhen you finish a chapter, you write \"Chapter 3 done, added the dragon\nscene\" on a sticky note and slap it on that page. That sticky note is a\ncommit. Your notebook is the Git repository.</p>\n<p>Now imagine you want to try a crazy alternate ending where the dragon\nWINS. You do not want to mess up the real story. So you make a photocopy\nof the whole notebook and scribble on the copy. That copy is a branch.\nThe original notebook is the mainline (or main branch). If the alternate\nending is good, you carefully paste it back into the real notebook. That\npaste-back is called merging.</p>\n<p>Finally, imagine you keep a SECOND copy of the notebook in a\nfireproof safe at the library. That safe is the central Git server.\nEvery time you finish a chapter, you mail a copy to the safe. If your\nhouse burns down, the story is still safe in the library.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p><strong>Source code</strong> is a bunch of text files that tell the\ncomputer what to do. It is written in a programming language like Java,\nPython, or TypeScript. The computer reads it like a recipe.</p>\n<p><strong>A file</strong> is one piece of that recipe. It has a name\nand an extension (like <code>Calculator.java</code>). The extension\ntells you what language it is written in. Files live in folders (also\ncalled directories).</p>\n<p><strong>Git</strong> is a version control system. That means it\ntracks every change you make to the code over time. Every save-point is\ncalled a commit. A commit has a message saying what you changed, who\nchanged it, and when. You can go back to any old commit if something\nbreaks.</p>\n<p><strong>A repository (or repo)</strong> is a folder that Git is\nwatching. It has a hidden <code>.git</code> folder inside that stores\nthe entire history. You do not edit the <code>.git</code> folder. Git\ndoes that automatically.</p>\n<p><strong>A branch</strong> is a parallel copy of the code where you\ncan make changes safely. You always work on a branch, not on mainline.\nWhen your changes are ready and reviewed, you merge your branch back\ninto mainline. That keeps the shared code clean.</p>\n<p><strong>Mainline (or main or master)</strong> is the real shared\nversion of the code that everyone trusts. You do not commit directly to\nmainline on the job. You commit to a branch, create a code review, get\nit approved, then merge. This protects the shared code from\naccidents.</p>\n<p><strong>the central Git server</strong> is a tech company's internal\nsystem that stores all the code repositories. It is like GitHub but\ninside a tech company. When you push your branch to the central Git\nserver, it backs up your work and lets other engineers see it for\nreview.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>If you do not understand Git, you will be terrified every time you\ntouch code. You will worry you will break something and not be able to\nundo it. With Git, NOTHING is permanent. Every change is saved. You can\nundo any mistake. That makes you brave.</p>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, you will read code to understand how a feature\nworks. You will look at commit history to see when a bug was introduced.\nYou will sometimes make a small fix and push it through review. All of\nthat needs Git.</p>\n<p>Also, on the job, every piece of code has a history. If a customer\nhits a bug, you might need to trace which commit caused it. Git lets you\ndo that.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>You clone a repository.</strong> That means you download the\ncode from the central Git server to your laptop. Now you have a local\ncopy.</li>\n<li><strong>You create a branch.</strong> You type\n<code>git checkout -b my-branch-name</code>. Now you are working on a\nsafe copy, not mainline.</li>\n<li><strong>You edit files.</strong> You open a file in your text editor\n(like VS Code), change it, and save.</li>\n<li><strong>You stage your changes.</strong> You type\n<code>git add &lt;filename&gt;</code>. This tells Git \"I want to save\nthis file in the next commit.\"</li>\n<li><strong>You commit.</strong> You type\n<code>git commit -m \"Fixed the typo in the error message\"</code>. Git\nsaves a snapshot of your changes with that message.</li>\n<li><strong>You push your branch to the central Git server.</strong> You\ntype <code>git push origin my-branch-name</code>. Now your branch is\nbacked up and visible to others.</li>\n<li><strong>You create a code review.</strong> on the job, you use a\ntool called the code review tool (like GitHub pull requests). You type\n<code>cr -o</code> and it opens a review for your branch. Teammates look\nat your changes and comment.</li>\n<li><strong>You fix any comments.</strong> If a reviewer says \"please\nadd a null check here\", you edit the file, stage, commit, and push\nagain. The review updates automatically.</li>\n<li><strong>The review is approved.</strong> Once everyone says it looks\ngood, you merge your branch into mainline. The code is now shared.</li>\n<li><strong>You delete your branch.</strong> You do not need it anymore.\nThe changes are safely in mainline.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>source code</strong></td>\n<td>Text files that tell the computer what to do. Written in a\nprogramming language.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>file</strong></td>\n<td>One piece of code. Has a name like <code>Main.java</code>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>folder / directory</strong></td>\n<td>A box that holds files. Folders can have subfolders.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Git</strong></td>\n<td>A time machine for code. Tracks every change. Lets you go back.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>repository / repo</strong></td>\n<td>A folder Git is watching. Contains code + history.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>commit</strong></td>\n<td>One save-point in Git. Has a message saying what changed.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>branch</strong></td>\n<td>A parallel copy of the code where you try changes safely.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>mainline / main / master</strong></td>\n<td>The real shared version everyone trusts. You do not commit directly\nto it.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>merge</strong></td>\n<td>Taking changes from your branch and putting them into mainline.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>clone</strong></td>\n<td>Downloading a repository from the central Git server to your\nlaptop.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>push</strong></td>\n<td>Uploading your branch to the central Git server so others can see\nit.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>pull</strong></td>\n<td>Downloading the latest changes from the central Git server to your\nlaptop.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the central Git server</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's internal system that stores all code\nrepositories.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the code review tool (like GitHub pull\nrequests)</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's code review tool. You create reviews with the\n<code>cr</code> command.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>diff</strong></td>\n<td>A view of what changed. Shows old code in red, new code in\ngreen.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<p><strong>As a Support Engineer:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Read code to understand a feature.</strong> You clone the\nrepo, open files in VS Code, read the logic.</li>\n<li><strong>Trace when a bug was introduced.</strong> You use\n<code>git log</code> to see the commit history. You find the commit\nwhere the bad code appeared.</li>\n<li><strong>Make a small fix.</strong> Maybe a typo in an error message,\nor a missing null check. You create a branch, fix it, commit, push, open\na review, and merge.</li>\n<li><strong>Check what version is deployed.</strong> You look at the\ncommit hash on the production server and match it to the code in the\ncentral Git server.</li>\n<li><strong>Collaborate with developers.</strong> You comment on their\ncode reviews. You test their fixes on your own machine.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You do NOT need to be a Git wizard. You need to know clone, branch,\ncommit, push, and how to read a diff. The rest you learn as you go.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>What is a commit?</strong> (Answer: A save-point in Git. It\nhas a message, a timestamp, and a snapshot of the code at that\nmoment.)</li>\n<li><strong>Why do we use branches instead of committing directly to\nmainline?</strong> (Answer: Branches let you try changes safely. If\nsomething breaks, mainline is still clean. You only merge to mainline\nafter review.)</li>\n<li><strong>What is the central Git server?</strong> (Answer: A tech\ncompany's internal system that stores all code repositories. It is the\nbackup and the place where teams share code.)</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you can answer those three, you have the core. Everything else is\njust practice.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-is-next\">What is next</h2>\n<p>Module 5 will teach you how code RUNS. What a build is. What a deploy\nis. How code on your laptop becomes a running service in AWS. That is\nwhere the magic happens.</p>\n","text":"module 4 — how code lives: files, git, and packages the one line version: code lives in files on your computer, git is a time machine that tracks every change, and a tech company keeps all the code safe in the central git server so teams can share it. picture this (the analogy) imagine you are writing a story in a notebook. every page is a file. when you finish a chapter, you write \"chapter 3 done, added the dragon scene\" on a sticky note and slap it on that page. that sticky note is a commit. your notebook is the git repository. now imagine you want to try a crazy alternate ending where the dragon wins. you do not want to mess up the real story. so you make a photocopy of the whole notebook and scribble on the copy. that copy is a branch. the original notebook is the mainline (or main branch). if the alternate ending is good, you carefully paste it back into the real notebook. that paste back is called merging. finally, imagine you keep a second copy of the notebook in a fireproof safe at the library. that safe is the central git server. every time you finish a chapter, you mail a copy to the safe. if your house burns down, the story is still safe in the library. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) source code is a bunch of text files that tell the computer what to do. it is written in a programming language like java, python, or typescript. the computer reads it like a recipe. a file is one piece of that recipe. it has a name and an extension (like calculator.java ). the extension tells you what language it is written in. files live in folders (also called directories). git is a version control system. that means it tracks every change you make to the code over time. every save point is called a commit. a commit has a message saying what you changed, who changed it, and when. you can go back to any old commit if something breaks. a repository (or repo) is a folder that git is watching. it has a hidden .git folder inside that stores the entire history. you do not edit the .git folder. git does that automatically. a branch is a parallel copy of the code where you can make changes safely. you always work on a branch, not on mainline. when your changes are ready and reviewed, you merge your branch back into mainline. that keeps the shared code clean. mainline (or main or master) is the real shared version of the code that everyone trusts. you do not commit directly to mainline on the job. you commit to a branch, create a code review, get it approved, then merge. this protects the shared code from accidents. the central git server is a tech company's internal system that stores all the code repositories. it is like github but inside a tech company. when you push your branch to the central git server, it backs up your work and lets other engineers see it for review. why you should care if you do not understand git, you will be terrified every time you touch code. you will worry you will break something and not be able to undo it. with git, nothing is permanent. every change is saved. you can undo any mistake. that makes you brave. as a support engineer, you will read code to understand how a feature works. you will look at commit history to see when a bug was introduced. you will sometimes make a small fix and push it through review. all of that needs git. also, on the job, every piece of code has a history. if a customer hits a bug, you might need to trace which commit caused it. git lets you do that. how it works, step by tiny step 1. you clone a repository. that means you download the code from the central git server to your laptop. now you have a local copy. 2. you create a branch. you type git checkout b my branch name . now you are working on a safe copy, not mainline. 3. you edit files. you open a file in your text editor (like vs code), change it, and save. 4. you stage your changes. you type git add <filename . this tells git \"i want to save this file in the next commit.\" 5. you commit. you type git commit m \"fixed the typo in the error message\" . git saves a snapshot of your changes with that message. 6. you push your branch to the central git server. you type git push origin my branch name . now your branch is backed up and visible to others. 7. you create a code review. on the job, you use a tool called the code review tool (like github pull requests). you type cr o and it opens a review for your branch. teammates look at your changes and comment. 8. you fix any comments. if a reviewer says \"please add a null check here\", you edit the file, stage, commit, and push again. the review updates automatically. 9. the review is approved. once everyone says it looks good, you merge your branch into mainline. the code is now shared. 10. you delete your branch. you do not need it anymore. the changes are safely in mainline. words you will hear term plain meaning source code text files that tell the computer what to do. written in a programming language. file one piece of code. has a name like main.java . folder / directory a box that holds files. folders can have subfolders. git a time machine for code. tracks every change. lets you go back. repository / repo a folder git is watching. contains code + history. commit one save point in git. has a message saying what changed. branch a parallel copy of the code where you try changes safely. mainline / main / master the real shared version everyone trusts. you do not commit directly to it. merge taking changes from your branch and putting them into mainline. clone downloading a repository from the central git server to your laptop. push uploading your branch to the central git server so others can see it. pull downloading the latest changes from the central git server to your laptop. the central git server a tech company's internal system that stores all code repositories. the code review tool (like github pull requests) a tech company's code review tool. you create reviews with the cr command. diff a view of what changed. shows old code in red, new code in green. what you actually do with this as a support engineer: read code to understand a feature. you clone the repo, open files in vs code, read the logic. trace when a bug was introduced. you use git log to see the commit history. you find the commit where the bad code appeared. make a small fix. maybe a typo in an error message, or a missing null check. you create a branch, fix it, commit, push, open a review, and merge. check what version is deployed. you look at the commit hash on the production server and match it to the code in the central git server. collaborate with developers. you comment on their code reviews. you test their fixes on your own machine. you do not need to be a git wizard. you need to know clone, branch, commit, push, and how to read a diff. the rest you learn as you go. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. what is a commit? (answer: a save point in git. it has a message, a timestamp, and a snapshot of the code at that moment.) 2. why do we use branches instead of committing directly to mainline? (answer: branches let you try changes safely. if something breaks, mainline is still clean. you only merge to mainline after review.) 3. what is the central git server? (answer: a tech company's internal system that stores all code repositories. it is the backup and the place where teams share code.) if you can answer those three, you have the core. everything else is just practice. what is next module 5 will teach you how code runs. what a build is. what a deploy is. how code on your laptop becomes a running service in aws. that is where the magic happens.","words":1554},{"id":"course-the-build-system","section":"Course","title":"The build system","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-5--the-build-system-how-a-tech-company-builds-software\">Module\n5 — the build system: How a tech company Builds Software</h1>\n<h2\nid=\"the-build-system--the-kitchen-that-turns-your-recipe-into-a-cooked-dish\">the\nbuild system — The Kitchen That Turns Your Recipe Into a Cooked\nDish</h2>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> the build system is a tech\ncompany's build system that turns your human-readable code into\nsomething the computer can run, checks it is not broken, and makes sure\neveryone builds the same thing.</p>\n<h3 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h3>\n<p>Imagine you are baking a cake. You have a recipe (your code). The\nkitchen is the build system. Here is what the kitchen does:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>It reads your recipe and gathers all the ingredients (dependencies —\nthe other code pieces your code needs).</li>\n<li>It mixes everything together in the right order (compiles — turns\nJava code into bytecode the computer understands).</li>\n<li>It bakes the cake (packages everything into a runnable\nartifact).</li>\n<li>It tastes the cake to make sure it is not poisoned (runs\ntests).</li>\n<li>It tells you \"CAKE IS GOOD\" or \"CAKE IS BURNED, FIX IT.\"</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Without the kitchen, you just have a recipe on paper. You cannot\nserve that to a customer. the build system is the kitchen. Your code is\nthe recipe. The runnable service is the cake.</p>\n<h3 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h3>\n<p>the build system is a tech company's in-house build system. It does\nfour main jobs:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Compiles your code</strong> — turns human-readable Java (or\nPython, TypeScript, etc.) into machine-readable bytecode or\nartifacts.</li>\n<li><strong>Manages dependencies</strong> — pulls in all the other code\nlibraries your code needs (like the service framework (like gRPC or\nSpring Boot), Guice, AWS SDK).</li>\n<li><strong>Runs tests</strong> — executes your unit tests and\nintegration tests to verify nothing broke.</li>\n<li><strong>Packages artifacts</strong> — bundles everything into a\ndeployable package (a JAR file, a Docker image, a Lambda zip,\netc.).</li>\n</ol>\n<p>the build system is used across ALL of a tech company. If you write\ncode on the job, you use the build system. It is not optional. It is THE\nbuild system.</p>\n<h3 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h3>\n<p>If you cannot build your code, you cannot ship it. Period. As a\nSupport Engineer, you will:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pull code from the central Git server to investigate a bug.</li>\n<li>Make a small fix or add logging.</li>\n<li>Run <code>the build command</code> to verify your change did not\nbreak anything.</li>\n<li>Raise a pull request (code review) if the build passes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If the build fails, you CANNOT proceed. \"BUILD SUCCESSFUL\" is the\nonly signal that matters. A failed build blocks everything.</p>\n<h3 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h3>\n<p>Here is the full cycle from \"I want to work on a service\" to \"I\nshipped my change\":</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Create a workspace</strong> — a folder on your laptop where\nyou will work. Think of it as your personal kitchen counter.</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>build workspace create --name my-workspace\ncd /Volumes/workplace/my-workspace</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Add a package</strong> — a package is one unit of code (one\nservice, one library, one tool). Think of it as one Lego set in its own\nbox.</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>build workspace use --package the time-tracking service</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Sync dependencies</strong> — the build system reads the\nversion-set (a list of exact versions for every package) and downloads\neverything your package needs.</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>build sync</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Navigate into the package folder</strong> — this is\ncritical. You do NOT build from the workspace root. You cd into the\npackage folder first.</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>cd src/the time-tracking service</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"5\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Build the code</strong> — this compiles everything and runs\nfast checks.</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>the build command</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"6\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Build with full tests</strong> — this is the REAL gate. It\nruns all unit tests. This is what you run before every commit.</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>the build command</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"7\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Check the output</strong> — scroll to the bottom. You are\nlooking for:</li>\n</ol>\n<pre><code>BUILD SUCCESSFUL\nBUILD SUCCEEDED</code></pre>\n<p>If you see those two lines, you are good. If you see\n<code>BUILD FAILED</code>, read the error above and fix it.</p>\n<ol start=\"8\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Commit your change</strong> — only after BUILD SUCCESSFUL.\nNever commit broken code.</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>git add &lt;your-files&gt;\ngit commit -m &quot;Fix: &lt;description&gt;&quot;</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"9\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Raise a pull request</strong> — this creates a code review\nfor your teammates to approve.</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>cr --summary &quot;Fix: &lt;description&gt;&quot; -o</code></pre>\n<h3 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h3>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Build</strong></td>\n<td>Turn code into something runnable and check it is not broken</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Package</strong></td>\n<td>One unit of code that does a job (one service, one library)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Workspace</strong></td>\n<td>A folder on your laptop where you pull packages to work on them</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Version set</strong></td>\n<td>A precise list of exact versions for every package a tech company\nuses</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dependency</strong></td>\n<td>Another piece of code your code needs to run (like the service\nframework (like gRPC or Spring Boot), Guice)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Compile</strong></td>\n<td>Turn human-readable code (Java) into machine code (bytecode)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Artifact</strong></td>\n<td>The final output of a build (a JAR file, Docker image, etc.)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the build command</strong></td>\n<td>Command to compile code and run fast checks</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the build command</strong></td>\n<td>Command to compile AND run full test suite (the real gate)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>BUILD SUCCESSFUL</strong></td>\n<td>The magic words. If you see this, your build passed.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>BUILD FAILED</strong></td>\n<td>Your build broke. Read the error, fix, rebuild.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h3>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, here is your the build system workflow:</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario: You need to investigate a production\nissue.</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Create a workspace and pull the package:</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>build workspace create --name debug-issue\ncd /Volumes/workplace/debug-issue\nbuild workspace use --package the payroll-calculation service\nbuild sync</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Navigate into the package:</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>cd src/the payroll-calculation service</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Check out the production branch (usually\n<code>mainline</code>):</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>git fetch origin mainline\ngit checkout mainline</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Build to verify you have a clean starting point:</li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>set up your environment correctly\nthe build command</code></pre>\n<p>(The <code>set up your environment correctly</code> is a gotcha —\nsome tests fail if AWS_REGION is set. This is a workaround.)</p>\n<ol start=\"5\" type=\"1\">\n<li><p>Make your code change (add logging, fix a null check,\netc.).</p></li>\n<li><p>Rebuild:</p></li>\n</ol>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>the build command</code></pre>\n<ol start=\"7\" type=\"1\">\n<li>If BUILD SUCCESSFUL → commit and raise CR. If BUILD FAILED → read\nerror, fix, repeat step 6.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h3>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h3 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h3>\n<p>Answer these in your head:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>What does \"build\" mean?</strong> (Turn code into something\nrunnable and check it is not broken.)</li>\n<li><strong>What is the difference between\n<code>the build command</code> and\n<code>the build command</code>?</strong> (First is fast checks, second\nruns full test suite. Always use <code>release</code> before\ncommit.)</li>\n<li><strong>Where do you run <code>the build command</code> — workspace\nroot or package folder?</strong> (Package folder. Always\n<code>cd src/&lt;PackageName&gt;</code> first.)</li>\n<li><strong>What are the two magic words you are looking for at the end\nof build output?</strong> (BUILD SUCCESSFUL and BUILD SUCCEEDED.)</li>\n<li><strong>What is a version set?</strong> (A list of exact versions\nfor every package, so everyone builds the same thing.)</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you can answer those, you understand the build system well enough\nto build code as a Support Engineer. The rest you will learn by\ndoing.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Resources (real internal links):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>the internal docs hub the build system docs: your team's internal\ndocs</li>\n<li>the hands-on onboarding workshop (the hands-on onboarding workshop,\nincludes the build system basics): your team's internal docs</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Next:</strong> Module 6 will cover the code review tool (like\nGitHub pull requests) (how a tech company does code reviews). You will\nlearn what a pull request is, how to raise one, how to read reviewer\ncomments, and how to push a new revision without making a mess.</p>\n","text":"module 5 — the build system: how a tech company builds software the build system — the kitchen that turns your recipe into a cooked dish the one line version: the build system is a tech company's build system that turns your human readable code into something the computer can run, checks it is not broken, and makes sure everyone builds the same thing. picture this (the analogy) imagine you are baking a cake. you have a recipe (your code). the kitchen is the build system. here is what the kitchen does: 1. it reads your recipe and gathers all the ingredients (dependencies — the other code pieces your code needs). 2. it mixes everything together in the right order (compiles — turns java code into bytecode the computer understands). 3. it bakes the cake (packages everything into a runnable artifact). 4. it tastes the cake to make sure it is not poisoned (runs tests). 5. it tells you \"cake is good\" or \"cake is burned, fix it.\" without the kitchen, you just have a recipe on paper. you cannot serve that to a customer. the build system is the kitchen. your code is the recipe. the runnable service is the cake. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) the build system is a tech company's in house build system. it does four main jobs: 1. compiles your code — turns human readable java (or python, typescript, etc.) into machine readable bytecode or artifacts. 2. manages dependencies — pulls in all the other code libraries your code needs (like the service framework (like grpc or spring boot), guice, aws sdk). 3. runs tests — executes your unit tests and integration tests to verify nothing broke. 4. packages artifacts — bundles everything into a deployable package (a jar file, a docker image, a lambda zip, etc.). the build system is used across all of a tech company. if you write code on the job, you use the build system. it is not optional. it is the build system. why you should care if you cannot build your code, you cannot ship it. period. as a support engineer, you will: pull code from the central git server to investigate a bug. make a small fix or add logging. run the build command to verify your change did not break anything. raise a pull request (code review) if the build passes. if the build fails, you cannot proceed. \"build successful\" is the only signal that matters. a failed build blocks everything. how it works, step by tiny step here is the full cycle from \"i want to work on a service\" to \"i shipped my change\": 1. create a workspace — a folder on your laptop where you will work. think of it as your personal kitchen counter. 2. add a package — a package is one unit of code (one service, one library, one tool). think of it as one lego set in its own box. 3. sync dependencies — the build system reads the version set (a list of exact versions for every package) and downloads everything your package needs. 4. navigate into the package folder — this is critical. you do not build from the workspace root. you cd into the package folder first. 5. build the code — this compiles everything and runs fast checks. 6. build with full tests — this is the real gate. it runs all unit tests. this is what you run before every commit. 7. check the output — scroll to the bottom. you are looking for: if you see those two lines, you are good. if you see build failed , read the error above and fix it. 8. commit your change — only after build successful. never commit broken code. 9. raise a pull request — this creates a code review for your teammates to approve. words you will hear term plain meaning build turn code into something runnable and check it is not broken package one unit of code that does a job (one service, one library) workspace a folder on your laptop where you pull packages to work on them version set a precise list of exact versions for every package a tech company uses dependency another piece of code your code needs to run (like the service framework (like grpc or spring boot), guice) compile turn human readable code (java) into machine code (bytecode) artifact the final output of a build (a jar file, docker image, etc.) the build command command to compile code and run fast checks the build command command to compile and run full test suite (the real gate) build successful the magic words. if you see this, your build passed. build failed your build broke. read the error, fix, rebuild. what you actually do with this as a support engineer, here is your the build system workflow: scenario: you need to investigate a production issue. 1. create a workspace and pull the package: 2. navigate into the package: 3. check out the production branch (usually mainline ): 4. build to verify you have a clean starting point: (the set up your environment correctly is a gotcha — some tests fail if aws region is set. this is a workaround.) 5. make your code change (add logging, fix a null check, etc.). 6. rebuild: 7. if build successful → commit and raise cr. if build failed → read error, fix, repeat step 6. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself answer these in your head: 1. what does \"build\" mean? (turn code into something runnable and check it is not broken.) 2. what is the difference between the build command and the build command ? (first is fast checks, second runs full test suite. always use release before commit.) 3. where do you run the build command — workspace root or package folder? (package folder. always cd src/<packagename first.) 4. what are the two magic words you are looking for at the end of build output? (build successful and build succeeded.) 5. what is a version set? (a list of exact versions for every package, so everyone builds the same thing.) if you can answer those, you understand the build system well enough to build code as a support engineer. the rest you will learn by doing. resources (real internal links): the internal docs hub the build system docs: your team's internal docs the hands on onboarding workshop (the hands on onboarding workshop, includes the build system basics): your team's internal docs next: module 6 will cover the code review tool (like github pull requests) (how a tech company does code reviews). you will learn what a pull request is, how to raise one, how to read reviewer comments, and how to push a new revision without making a mess.","words":1354},{"id":"course-how-services-talk-to-each-other","section":"Course","title":"How services talk to each other","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-6--the-service-framework-like-grpc-or-spring-boot-how-machines-talk-to-each-other\">Module\n6 — the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot): How Machines Talk\nto Each Other</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> the service framework (like\ngRPC or Spring Boot) is a tech company's kitchen recipe for building\nservices that talk to each other reliably, with clear jobs for each part\nso nothing gets messy.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>Imagine a restaurant. You (the customer) walk in and ask for a\nburger. The waiter takes your order, writes it down, and checks if you\nsaid something weird like \"burger with ice cream on top\" (you did not,\ngood). The waiter hands the order to the chef. The chef decides how to\ncook it (medium rare, add lettuce, toast the bun). The prep cook\nassembles everything on the plate. The pantry person fetches the bun and\nlettuce from the storage room. Finally, the waiter brings your burger\nback to you.</p>\n<p>Every person has ONE job. The waiter does not cook. The chef does not\nfetch ingredients. The pantry person does not decide how to cook. If the\npantry runs out of buns, the pantry person raises their hand and says\n\"we are out of buns.\" Everyone knows what went wrong and where to fix\nit.</p>\n<p>That is exactly how the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot)\nservices work. Each piece has one clear job. Requests come in, get\nchecked, processed, assembled, and sent back. If something breaks, you\nknow which piece raised its hand.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p><strong>the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot)</strong> is\na tech company's service framework. A service is just a program that\nsits on a server, waiting for other programs to ask it questions. When\nanother program asks (we call that a <strong>request</strong>), the\nservice does some work and gives back an answer (we call that a\n<strong>response</strong>).</p>\n<p>An <strong>API</strong> (Application Programming Interface) is the\nmenu of questions you can ask. The menu says \"you can ask me for\nemployee time-off balance\" or \"you can ask me to save a paycode.\" The\nAPI lists every allowed question.</p>\n<p>A <strong>service framework</strong> is code that handles the boring\nplumbing: reading the request, checking if it is valid, talking over the\nnetwork, turning data into the right format, catching errors, logging\nwhat happened. the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot) does all\nthat boring stuff so YOU only write the interesting part (the business\nlogic, the \"what should this service actually do?\").</p>\n<p>the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot) organizes your code\ninto <strong>layers</strong>. Each layer has one job. The four layers\nyou will see everywhere on the job are:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Activity</strong> — the front door. Takes the request,\nchecks if it makes sense, logs it, hands it to the next layer.</li>\n<li><strong>Component</strong> — the brain. The business logic lives\nhere. \"Should I allow this? Should I call another service? What is the\nanswer?\"</li>\n<li><strong>Builder</strong> — the assembler. Takes raw data and builds\nthe response object or request object for another service.</li>\n<li><strong>Accessor</strong> — the storage talker. Reads from or writes\nto the database (DynamoDB, S3, whatever). This is the only layer allowed\nto touch the database.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Why layers? Because when something breaks, you know WHERE to look. If\nthe database call failed, you look in the Accessor. If the business\nlogic is wrong, you look in the Component. If the incoming request had\nbad data, you look in the Activity. Layers make debugging fast.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, you will investigate tickets where a service\nbroke. The ticket might say \"employee X tried to submit time-off and got\nan error.\" You will look at CloudWatch logs, see the error, and need to\nunderstand where in the service it broke. If you know the layers, you\ncan trace the path: Activity logged the request → Component called\nanother service → that service returned an error → Component wrapped it\nin a DependencyServiceException → Activity logged the exception and\nreturned it to the customer.</p>\n<p>You will also read code when escalating bugs. If you can say \"this\nComponent method is calling the wrong Accessor method,\" the SDE who gets\nyour escalation will trust you immediately. You sound like you know what\nyou are talking about because you DO.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<p>Let's walk through a real request hitting a the service framework\n(like gRPC or Spring Boot) service.</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>A request arrives.</strong> Another service or a UI sends\na network request to your service. the service framework (like gRPC or\nSpring Boot) reads the bytes off the network and turns them into a Java\nobject (the request object).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The Activity checks it.</strong> The Activity is the\nfront door. It looks at the request and says \"is this valid?\" For\nexample, if the request says \"give me time-off balance for employee ID\nempty-string,\" the Activity says \"nope, that is bad input\" and throws a\n<strong>ValidationException</strong>. The request stops here. the\nservice framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot) catches the exception, logs\nit, and sends back an error response to the caller.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>If valid, the Activity calls the Component.</strong> The\nActivity hands the request to the Component and says \"you decide what to\ndo.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The Component thinks.</strong> The Component is the\nbrain. It might check a rule (\"is this employee allowed to see this\ndata?\"). It might call ANOTHER service to get more data. It might call a\nBuilder to assemble a complex object. It might call an Accessor to read\nfrom the database.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The Accessor talks to storage.</strong> If the Component\nneeds data from DynamoDB, it calls the Accessor. The Accessor has the\nDynamoDB client code, the retry logic if DynamoDB is slow, the error\nhandling if DynamoDB is down. The Accessor fetches the data and gives it\nback to the Component.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The Builder assembles the response.</strong> The\nComponent has all the data it needs. It calls a Builder and says \"build\nme a response object with these fields filled in.\" The Builder does the\nassembly (like putting data into a specific format) and gives back the\nresponse object.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The Activity sends the response.</strong> The Component\ngives the response object to the Activity. The Activity logs what\nhappened (success!), and the service framework (like gRPC or Spring\nBoot) turns the Java object back into bytes and sends it over the\nnetwork to the caller.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>If ANYTHING went wrong in steps 3-6, the Component or Accessor throws\nan exception. the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot) catches\nit, logs it, and sends back an error response instead of a success\nresponse.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th><strong>Term</strong></th>\n<th><strong>Plain meaning</strong></th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API</strong></td>\n<td>The menu of questions you can ask a service. Each API has a name and\na list of inputs/outputs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Request</strong></td>\n<td>The question you send to a service. \"Give me employee 12345's\ntime-off balance.\"</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Response</strong></td>\n<td>The answer the service sends back. \"Employee 12345 has 40 hours of\ntime-off.\"</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Service</strong></td>\n<td>A program that sits on a server, waiting to answer requests.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Service framework</strong></td>\n<td>Code that handles the boring plumbing (network, logging, errors) so\nyou only write the logic.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Layer</strong></td>\n<td>A piece of the service with one clear job. Activity, Component,\nBuilder, Accessor.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Activity</strong></td>\n<td>The front door layer. Checks the request, logs, hands to\nComponent.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Component</strong></td>\n<td>The brain layer. Business logic lives here.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Builder</strong></td>\n<td>The assembler layer. Builds request or response objects.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Accessor</strong></td>\n<td>The storage layer. Talks to the database.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>ValidationException</strong></td>\n<td>The service raising its hand to say \"you asked me something\nwrong.\"</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>DependencyServiceException</strong></td>\n<td>The service raising its hand to say \"something I depend on broke,\nnot my fault.\"</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>InternalServiceException</strong></td>\n<td>The service raising its hand to say \"I have a bug, my fault.\"</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, you:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p><strong>Read logs to trace the request path.</strong> The\nActivity logs when the request came in. The Component logs when it calls\nanother service. The Accessor logs when it queries DynamoDB. If you see\nthe Activity log but no Component log, you know it failed at the\nActivity (probably a ValidationException).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Identify which layer broke.</strong> If the log says\n\"DynamoDB timeout,\" you know the Accessor broke. If the log says \"null\npointer exception in Component,\" you know the Component broke. You tell\nthe SDE \"this broke in the Component at line 123.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Check if the error is customer's fault or ours.</strong>\nValidationException = customer sent bad data, teach them how to fix it.\nDependencyServiceException = something we depend on broke, escalate to\nthat team. InternalServiceException = we have a bug, escalate to the\nservice owner.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Find the code.</strong> If you escalate, you can say \"the\nerror happened in the payroll-calculation service, Component layer,\nSubmitPaycodeComponent.java, line 87.\" The SDE can jump straight\nthere.</p></li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>If a request fails because the employee ID was blank,\nwhich layer caught it and which exception did it throw?</strong>\n(Answer: Activity caught it, threw ValidationException.)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>If the service needs to read an employee's time-off\nbalance from DynamoDB, which layer does that?</strong> (Answer:\nAccessor.)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>If the business rule is \"only managers can approve\ntime-off,\" which layer checks that rule?</strong> (Answer:\nComponent.)</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you got all three right, you understand the service framework\n(like gRPC or Spring Boot) layers. You are ready to read real service\ncode.</p>\n","text":"module 6 — the service framework (like grpc or spring boot): how machines talk to each other the one line version: the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) is a tech company's kitchen recipe for building services that talk to each other reliably, with clear jobs for each part so nothing gets messy. picture this (the analogy) imagine a restaurant. you (the customer) walk in and ask for a burger. the waiter takes your order, writes it down, and checks if you said something weird like \"burger with ice cream on top\" (you did not, good). the waiter hands the order to the chef. the chef decides how to cook it (medium rare, add lettuce, toast the bun). the prep cook assembles everything on the plate. the pantry person fetches the bun and lettuce from the storage room. finally, the waiter brings your burger back to you. every person has one job. the waiter does not cook. the chef does not fetch ingredients. the pantry person does not decide how to cook. if the pantry runs out of buns, the pantry person raises their hand and says \"we are out of buns.\" everyone knows what went wrong and where to fix it. that is exactly how the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) services work. each piece has one clear job. requests come in, get checked, processed, assembled, and sent back. if something breaks, you know which piece raised its hand. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) is a tech company's service framework. a service is just a program that sits on a server, waiting for other programs to ask it questions. when another program asks (we call that a request ), the service does some work and gives back an answer (we call that a response ). an api (application programming interface) is the menu of questions you can ask. the menu says \"you can ask me for employee time off balance\" or \"you can ask me to save a paycode.\" the api lists every allowed question. a service framework is code that handles the boring plumbing: reading the request, checking if it is valid, talking over the network, turning data into the right format, catching errors, logging what happened. the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) does all that boring stuff so you only write the interesting part (the business logic, the \"what should this service actually do?\"). the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) organizes your code into layers . each layer has one job. the four layers you will see everywhere on the job are: 1. activity — the front door. takes the request, checks if it makes sense, logs it, hands it to the next layer. 2. component — the brain. the business logic lives here. \"should i allow this? should i call another service? what is the answer?\" 3. builder — the assembler. takes raw data and builds the response object or request object for another service. 4. accessor — the storage talker. reads from or writes to the database (dynamodb, s3, whatever). this is the only layer allowed to touch the database. why layers? because when something breaks, you know where to look. if the database call failed, you look in the accessor. if the business logic is wrong, you look in the component. if the incoming request had bad data, you look in the activity. layers make debugging fast. why you should care as a support engineer, you will investigate tickets where a service broke. the ticket might say \"employee x tried to submit time off and got an error.\" you will look at cloudwatch logs, see the error, and need to understand where in the service it broke. if you know the layers, you can trace the path: activity logged the request → component called another service → that service returned an error → component wrapped it in a dependencyserviceexception → activity logged the exception and returned it to the customer. you will also read code when escalating bugs. if you can say \"this component method is calling the wrong accessor method,\" the sde who gets your escalation will trust you immediately. you sound like you know what you are talking about because you do. how it works, step by tiny step let's walk through a real request hitting a the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) service. 1. a request arrives. another service or a ui sends a network request to your service. the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) reads the bytes off the network and turns them into a java object (the request object). 2. the activity checks it. the activity is the front door. it looks at the request and says \"is this valid?\" for example, if the request says \"give me time off balance for employee id empty string,\" the activity says \"nope, that is bad input\" and throws a validationexception . the request stops here. the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) catches the exception, logs it, and sends back an error response to the caller. 3. if valid, the activity calls the component. the activity hands the request to the component and says \"you decide what to do.\" 4. the component thinks. the component is the brain. it might check a rule (\"is this employee allowed to see this data?\"). it might call another service to get more data. it might call a builder to assemble a complex object. it might call an accessor to read from the database. 5. the accessor talks to storage. if the component needs data from dynamodb, it calls the accessor. the accessor has the dynamodb client code, the retry logic if dynamodb is slow, the error handling if dynamodb is down. the accessor fetches the data and gives it back to the component. 6. the builder assembles the response. the component has all the data it needs. it calls a builder and says \"build me a response object with these fields filled in.\" the builder does the assembly (like putting data into a specific format) and gives back the response object. 7. the activity sends the response. the component gives the response object to the activity. the activity logs what happened (success!), and the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) turns the java object back into bytes and sends it over the network to the caller. if anything went wrong in steps 3 6, the component or accessor throws an exception. the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) catches it, logs it, and sends back an error response instead of a success response. words you will hear term plain meaning api the menu of questions you can ask a service. each api has a name and a list of inputs/outputs. request the question you send to a service. \"give me employee 12345's time off balance.\" response the answer the service sends back. \"employee 12345 has 40 hours of time off.\" service a program that sits on a server, waiting to answer requests. service framework code that handles the boring plumbing (network, logging, errors) so you only write the logic. layer a piece of the service with one clear job. activity, component, builder, accessor. activity the front door layer. checks the request, logs, hands to component. component the brain layer. business logic lives here. builder the assembler layer. builds request or response objects. accessor the storage layer. talks to the database. validationexception the service raising its hand to say \"you asked me something wrong.\" dependencyserviceexception the service raising its hand to say \"something i depend on broke, not my fault.\" internalserviceexception the service raising its hand to say \"i have a bug, my fault.\" what you actually do with this as a support engineer, you: read logs to trace the request path. the activity logs when the request came in. the component logs when it calls another service. the accessor logs when it queries dynamodb. if you see the activity log but no component log, you know it failed at the activity (probably a validationexception). identify which layer broke. if the log says \"dynamodb timeout,\" you know the accessor broke. if the log says \"null pointer exception in component,\" you know the component broke. you tell the sde \"this broke in the component at line 123.\" check if the error is customer's fault or ours. validationexception = customer sent bad data, teach them how to fix it. dependencyserviceexception = something we depend on broke, escalate to that team. internalserviceexception = we have a bug, escalate to the service owner. find the code. if you escalate, you can say \"the error happened in the payroll calculation service, component layer, submitpaycodecomponent.java, line 87.\" the sde can jump straight there. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. if a request fails because the employee id was blank, which layer caught it and which exception did it throw? (answer: activity caught it, threw validationexception.) 2. if the service needs to read an employee's time off balance from dynamodb, which layer does that? (answer: accessor.) 3. if the business rule is \"only managers can approve time off,\" which layer checks that rule? (answer: component.) if you got all three right, you understand the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) layers. you are ready to read real service code.","words":1682},{"id":"course-infrastructure-as-code","section":"Course","title":"Infrastructure as code","html":"<h1 id=\"module-7--cdk-building-the-ground-your-code-stands-on\">Module 7\n— CDK: building the ground your code stands on</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> CDK lets you write code to\ndescribe the infrastructure your service needs, so you can rebuild it\nexactly the same way every time instead of clicking buttons and\nforgetting what you did.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>You built a Lego castle. It took three hours. You followed no\ninstructions. You just stacked bricks. The castle is beautiful. Your\nfriend loves it. Then you have to take it apart and rebuild it tomorrow\nfor a show. You forgot where every brick went. You rebuild it. It looks\ndifferent. Some parts are missing. Some are wrong.</p>\n<p>Now imagine you write the instruction booklet WHILE you build the\nfirst castle. Step one: place the red 2x4 brick here. Step two: stack\nthe blue tower on top. When you have to rebuild it tomorrow, you read\nyour instructions. Five minutes later, the castle is exactly the same.\nAnyone can build it. You can tear it down and rebuild it a hundred\ntimes. Same castle. No memory needed.</p>\n<p>That is CDK. Instead of clicking buttons in a web console to create a\ndatabase or a queue or a place for your code to run, you WRITE the\ninstructions in code. The code remembers. The code is the instruction\nbooklet. You can rebuild the exact same infrastructure whenever you\nwant.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p>CDK stands for Cloud Development Kit. It is a tool many companies\n(and AWS) uses to build infrastructure as code.</p>\n<p><strong>Infrastructure</strong> means the stuff your code needs to\nrun. Your Java service needs a database to store data. It needs a\ncompute environment (a machine or container) to run on. It needs a queue\nto receive messages. It needs a load balancer to distribute traffic.\nThat is infrastructure.</p>\n<p>The old way: you log into the AWS console. You click buttons. You\ncreate a DynamoDB table. You click more buttons. You create an SQS\nqueue. You write the table name on a sticky note. Two weeks later you\nforget. Someone else on your team has to recreate it. They create it\nslightly different. Now prod and staging do not match. That is manual\ninfrastructure. It breaks.</p>\n<p>The CDK way: you write Python code (or TypeScript, Java, etc). The\ncode says \"I need a DynamoDB table named SchedulesTable with these\nattributes.\" You run the code. CDK translates your code into\nCloudFormation (a language AWS understands). CloudFormation builds the\ntable. Next week you run the same code again. Same table. Same name.\nSame attributes. You never forget. The code remembers.</p>\n<p>on the job, we use <strong>a secure infrastructure-as-code construct\nlibrary</strong> by default. a secure infrastructure-as-code construct\nlibrary is a collection of safer building blocks. Instead of raw CDK,\nyou use a secure infrastructure-as-code construct library constructs.\nThey have security baked in. Encryption on. Logs on. Access locked down.\nYou start from a safer place.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, you will see tickets where infrastructure is\nwrong. The queue is missing. The table has the wrong permissions. The\nLambda function ran out of memory.</p>\n<p>If infrastructure is code, you can fix it by changing the code and\nredeploying. You do not have to log into five consoles and click buttons\nand hope you clicked the right ones. You change one line in the CDK\nstack. You redeploy. The fix is permanent. The fix is repeatable. The\nfix is reviewable in a code review.</p>\n<p>If infrastructure is manual, every fix is a one-time click. The next\ndeploy might undo it. You cannot code review a click. You cannot\nversion-control a button press.</p>\n<p>Infrastructure as code is the instruction booklet. It saves you from\nrebuilding the Lego castle by memory every time.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>You write a CDK app.</strong> This is a Python (or\nTypeScript, Java) file that describes what you need. \"I need a DynamoDB\ntable. I need an SQS queue. I need a Lambda function.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You define a stack.</strong> A stack is a box that holds\nrelated infrastructure. One stack might hold the database and the queue\nfor your service. Another stack might hold the monitoring alarms. You\nbuild and tear down a stack as one unit.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You add constructs to the stack.</strong> A construct is\none reusable building block. Like a Lego brick. CDK has constructs for\nDynamoDB, SQS, Lambda, S3, everything. You import the construct library.\nYou create an instance. You pass in the settings (table name, read\ncapacity, encryption on).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You run <code>cdk synth</code>.</strong> This command\ntranslates your code into a CloudFormation template. CloudFormation is\nthe AWS robot that actually builds infrastructure. You do not write\nCloudFormation by hand. CDK writes it for you.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You run <code>cdk deploy</code>.</strong> This command\nsends the CloudFormation template to AWS. CloudFormation reads the\ntemplate. CloudFormation creates the table, the queue, the Lambda. You\nwatch the progress. When it finishes, your infrastructure\nexists.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You change the code and redeploy.</strong> You need to\nadd an attribute to the table. You edit the CDK code. You run\n<code>cdk deploy</code> again. CloudFormation compares the old template\nto the new one. CloudFormation updates only what changed. The table gets\nthe new attribute. Everything else stays the same.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You tear it down.</strong> You run\n<code>cdk destroy</code>. CloudFormation deletes everything in the\nstack. The table, the queue, the Lambda. All gone. You can rebuild it\nlater by running <code>cdk deploy</code> again. Same infrastructure.\nSame code.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>That is the loop. Write code. Synth. Deploy. Change. Redeploy.\nDestroy when done.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CDK</strong></td>\n<td>Cloud Development Kit. Tool to write infrastructure as code.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Stack</strong></td>\n<td>A box of related infrastructure built and torn down together.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Construct</strong></td>\n<td>One reusable building block (a table, a queue, a function). Like a\nLego brick.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CloudFormation</strong></td>\n<td>The AWS robot that reads your CDK output and actually builds the\nstuff.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Synth</strong></td>\n<td>Command that translates your CDK code into CloudFormation. Short for\nsynthesize.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Deploy</strong></td>\n<td>Command that sends the CloudFormation template to AWS and builds the\ninfrastructure.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lambda</strong></td>\n<td>Code that runs without you managing a server. AWS runs it for\nyou.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>a secure infrastructure-as-code construct\nlibrary</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company safer building blocks. Security baked in. Use by\ndefault.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Infrastructure as Code</strong></td>\n<td>Writing the infrastructure instructions in code instead of clicking\nbuttons.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, you will see tickets where a service is broken\nbecause infrastructure is wrong. The queue is missing. The table is too\nsmall. The Lambda timed out.</p>\n<p>If the service uses CDK, you will:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Read the CDK code to understand what infrastructure exists</li>\n<li>Check if the code matches what is actually deployed</li>\n<li>Propose a fix by changing the CDK code</li>\n<li>Test the fix in a lower environment (staging or beta)</li>\n<li>Redeploy the stack to prod</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You will NOT click buttons in the AWS console. You will change the\ncode. The code is the source of truth.</p>\n<p>You might also help a developer onboard to CDK. They wrote a service\nby hand. You help them convert it to CDK so it is repeatable.</p>\n<p>The CDK workshop at your team's internal docs walks you through\nbuilding a stack from zero. You start empty. You add one Lambda. You\nbuild. You check. You add an API. You build. You add a table. You build.\nBy the end you have a working service. All infrastructure is code.</p>\n<p>the internal docs hub your team's internal docs has the CDK docs. a\nsecure infrastructure-as-code construct library docs live there too. You\nwill reference these when you need to add a new construct or\ntroubleshoot a deploy.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>What is a stack? (Hint: a box of related infrastructure.)</li>\n<li>What command translates your CDK code into CloudFormation? (Hint:\nrhymes with \"minth.\")</li>\n<li>Why is infrastructure as code better than clicking buttons? (Hint:\nthink about the Lego instruction booklet.)</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Next:</strong> <a\nhref=\"08-cloudwatch-observability.md\">Module 8 — CloudWatch: seeing what\nyour service is actually doing</a></p>\n","text":"module 7 — cdk: building the ground your code stands on the one line version: cdk lets you write code to describe the infrastructure your service needs, so you can rebuild it exactly the same way every time instead of clicking buttons and forgetting what you did. picture this (the analogy) you built a lego castle. it took three hours. you followed no instructions. you just stacked bricks. the castle is beautiful. your friend loves it. then you have to take it apart and rebuild it tomorrow for a show. you forgot where every brick went. you rebuild it. it looks different. some parts are missing. some are wrong. now imagine you write the instruction booklet while you build the first castle. step one: place the red 2x4 brick here. step two: stack the blue tower on top. when you have to rebuild it tomorrow, you read your instructions. five minutes later, the castle is exactly the same. anyone can build it. you can tear it down and rebuild it a hundred times. same castle. no memory needed. that is cdk. instead of clicking buttons in a web console to create a database or a queue or a place for your code to run, you write the instructions in code. the code remembers. the code is the instruction booklet. you can rebuild the exact same infrastructure whenever you want. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) cdk stands for cloud development kit. it is a tool many companies (and aws) uses to build infrastructure as code. infrastructure means the stuff your code needs to run. your java service needs a database to store data. it needs a compute environment (a machine or container) to run on. it needs a queue to receive messages. it needs a load balancer to distribute traffic. that is infrastructure. the old way: you log into the aws console. you click buttons. you create a dynamodb table. you click more buttons. you create an sqs queue. you write the table name on a sticky note. two weeks later you forget. someone else on your team has to recreate it. they create it slightly different. now prod and staging do not match. that is manual infrastructure. it breaks. the cdk way: you write python code (or typescript, java, etc). the code says \"i need a dynamodb table named schedulestable with these attributes.\" you run the code. cdk translates your code into cloudformation (a language aws understands). cloudformation builds the table. next week you run the same code again. same table. same name. same attributes. you never forget. the code remembers. on the job, we use a secure infrastructure as code construct library by default. a secure infrastructure as code construct library is a collection of safer building blocks. instead of raw cdk, you use a secure infrastructure as code construct library constructs. they have security baked in. encryption on. logs on. access locked down. you start from a safer place. why you should care as a support engineer, you will see tickets where infrastructure is wrong. the queue is missing. the table has the wrong permissions. the lambda function ran out of memory. if infrastructure is code, you can fix it by changing the code and redeploying. you do not have to log into five consoles and click buttons and hope you clicked the right ones. you change one line in the cdk stack. you redeploy. the fix is permanent. the fix is repeatable. the fix is reviewable in a code review. if infrastructure is manual, every fix is a one time click. the next deploy might undo it. you cannot code review a click. you cannot version control a button press. infrastructure as code is the instruction booklet. it saves you from rebuilding the lego castle by memory every time. how it works, step by tiny step 1. you write a cdk app. this is a python (or typescript, java) file that describes what you need. \"i need a dynamodb table. i need an sqs queue. i need a lambda function.\" 2. you define a stack. a stack is a box that holds related infrastructure. one stack might hold the database and the queue for your service. another stack might hold the monitoring alarms. you build and tear down a stack as one unit. 3. you add constructs to the stack. a construct is one reusable building block. like a lego brick. cdk has constructs for dynamodb, sqs, lambda, s3, everything. you import the construct library. you create an instance. you pass in the settings (table name, read capacity, encryption on). 4. you run cdk synth . this command translates your code into a cloudformation template. cloudformation is the aws robot that actually builds infrastructure. you do not write cloudformation by hand. cdk writes it for you. 5. you run cdk deploy . this command sends the cloudformation template to aws. cloudformation reads the template. cloudformation creates the table, the queue, the lambda. you watch the progress. when it finishes, your infrastructure exists. 6. you change the code and redeploy. you need to add an attribute to the table. you edit the cdk code. you run cdk deploy again. cloudformation compares the old template to the new one. cloudformation updates only what changed. the table gets the new attribute. everything else stays the same. 7. you tear it down. you run cdk destroy . cloudformation deletes everything in the stack. the table, the queue, the lambda. all gone. you can rebuild it later by running cdk deploy again. same infrastructure. same code. that is the loop. write code. synth. deploy. change. redeploy. destroy when done. words you will hear term plain meaning cdk cloud development kit. tool to write infrastructure as code. stack a box of related infrastructure built and torn down together. construct one reusable building block (a table, a queue, a function). like a lego brick. cloudformation the aws robot that reads your cdk output and actually builds the stuff. synth command that translates your cdk code into cloudformation. short for synthesize. deploy command that sends the cloudformation template to aws and builds the infrastructure. lambda code that runs without you managing a server. aws runs it for you. a secure infrastructure as code construct library a tech company safer building blocks. security baked in. use by default. infrastructure as code writing the infrastructure instructions in code instead of clicking buttons. what you actually do with this as a support engineer, you will see tickets where a service is broken because infrastructure is wrong. the queue is missing. the table is too small. the lambda timed out. if the service uses cdk, you will: read the cdk code to understand what infrastructure exists check if the code matches what is actually deployed propose a fix by changing the cdk code test the fix in a lower environment (staging or beta) redeploy the stack to prod you will not click buttons in the aws console. you will change the code. the code is the source of truth. you might also help a developer onboard to cdk. they wrote a service by hand. you help them convert it to cdk so it is repeatable. the cdk workshop at your team's internal docs walks you through building a stack from zero. you start empty. you add one lambda. you build. you check. you add an api. you build. you add a table. you build. by the end you have a working service. all infrastructure is code. the internal docs hub your team's internal docs has the cdk docs. a secure infrastructure as code construct library docs live there too. you will reference these when you need to add a new construct or troubleshoot a deploy. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. what is a stack? (hint: a box of related infrastructure.) 2. what command translates your cdk code into cloudformation? (hint: rhymes with \"minth.\") 3. why is infrastructure as code better than clicking buttons? (hint: think about the lego instruction booklet.) next: module 8 — cloudwatch: seeing what your service is actually doing","words":1455},{"id":"course-pipelines-deployment","section":"Course","title":"Pipelines & deployment","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-8--pipelines-and-the-deployment-tool-like-spinnaker-or-argo-cd-how-code-travels-to-real-customers\">Module\n8 — Pipelines and the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD): how\ncode travels to real customers</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> A pipeline is the conveyor\nbelt that carries your code through safety checks (Alpha, Beta, staging)\nuntil it reaches real customers (Prod), and the deployment tool (like\nSpinnaker or Argo CD) is the service that actually puts the code on\nmachines so it can run.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>You wrote a play. Opening night, the theater is full of paying\ncustomers. You do NOT want the first time anyone performs the play to be\nin front of that audience. Too risky. So you run dress rehearsals.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>First rehearsal (Alpha):</strong> just you and the cast in\nan empty room. If someone forgets a line, no problem. Fix it.</li>\n<li><strong>Second rehearsal (Beta):</strong> invite a few friends who\nwill forgive mistakes. If the lighting is wrong, adjust it.</li>\n<li><strong>Third rehearsal (staging):</strong> invite critics and\nindustry people. If they find a problem, you still have time to fix it\nbefore opening night.</li>\n<li><strong>Opening night (Prod):</strong> real customers, paying money.\nEverything must work. No room for \"oops.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A <strong>pipeline</strong> is the rehearsal schedule. It makes sure\nyour play goes through Alpha, Beta, staging in order. It does not let\nyou skip to opening night without passing the earlier checks.\n<strong>the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD)</strong> is the\nstagehands who actually set up the lights, props, and sound system at\neach rehearsal and on opening night. The pipeline decides when to\npromote (move forward). the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD)\ndoes the physical work of getting everything in place.</p>\n<p>If opening night goes wrong, you <strong>rollback</strong> — cancel\nthe show, go back to yesterday's version that worked, stop the bleeding.\nThat is the Support Engineer superpower: knowing how to undo the bad\nchange fast.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p>on the job, when you write code and push a change, it does not go\nstraight to real customers. It travels through a\n<strong>pipeline</strong> — a sequence of <strong>stages</strong> where\nthe change gets tested and verified before reaching production.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Deploy</strong> = the act of putting your code somewhere it\ncan run. Could be on a physical server, a container, a Lambda function,\nanywhere. Deploy is the action. the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or\nArgo CD) is the tool that does it.</li>\n<li><strong>Pipeline</strong> = the automated conveyor belt that moves\nyour code from one stage to the next, running tests and health checks at\neach step.</li>\n<li><strong>Stages</strong> = checkpoints where your code lives\ntemporarily while tests run. The four most common:</li>\n<li><strong>Alpha</strong> — just for you and your team. You can break\nthings here. Nobody else is affected.</li>\n<li><strong>Beta</strong> — internal testers, fake test accounts,\nsynthetic traffic. Still not real customers.</li>\n<li><strong>staging</strong> — almost real. Some real traffic, but\nlimited. The final safety check.</li>\n<li><strong>Prod</strong> — real customers, real money, real\nconsequences. This is the one that matters.</li>\n<li><strong>Promotion</strong> = when the pipeline decides \"this stage\nlooks healthy, move to the next one.\" Promotion is automatic if all the\nchecks pass, but it can be paused or manual if the team wants more\ncontrol.</li>\n<li><strong>Rollback</strong> = undo the last deploy. Go back to the\nversion that worked before. The fastest way to stop an incident. Support\nEngineers learn rollback commands first because that is how you save the\nday when everything is on fire.</li>\n<li><strong>the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD)</strong> = a\ntech company's internal deployment service. It takes your code artifact\n(a compiled package) and puts it on the right machines or containers in\nthe right stage. You tell the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo\nCD) \"deploy version X to Beta,\" and the deployment tool (like Spinnaker\nor Argo CD) makes it happen.</li>\n<li><strong>Self-mutation</strong> = some pipelines can update\nthemselves. If you change the pipeline definition (add a new stage,\nchange a check), the pipeline applies that change to itself. One\nsentence is enough: \"pipelines can self-mutate, so changes to the\npipeline code show up in the next run.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, when an incident starts, the FIRST question\nyou ask is: <strong>\"What changed and which stage is it\nin?\"</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Did a new deploy just finish in Prod? That is your suspect.</li>\n<li>Is the problem only in staging? Good news — it has not reached\ncustomers yet. Stop the promotion.</li>\n<li>Is the problem in Prod but the change is in Beta/staging? That means\nit is NOT the new code. Look elsewhere.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Pipelines and the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) give\nyou the <strong>timeline of changes</strong>. Every incident\ninvestigation starts there. You open the pipeline dashboard, you see the\nlast few deploys, you check the timestamps against when alarms started\nfiring. That narrows the search from \"could be anything\" to \"probably\nthis one deploy.\"</p>\n<p>And when you confirm it is the new deploy, you\n<strong>rollback</strong>. Fast. The pipeline dashboard has a rollback\nbutton. Click it. The bad version disappears, the old working version\ncomes back, the alarms stop. You just saved thousands of customers from\nhitting a broken experience. Then you investigate why it broke, fix it\nin a pull request, and try again.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>You commit code</strong> on your laptop and push to a git\nbranch.</li>\n<li><strong>You create a pull request</strong> (code review). Reviewers\napprove it.</li>\n<li><strong>You merge to mainline</strong> (the main branch). That\ntriggers the pipeline.</li>\n<li><strong>The pipeline wakes up</strong>. It sees a new commit on\nmainline.</li>\n<li><strong>Stage 1 — Build.</strong> The pipeline compiles your code\ninto an artifact (a zip file or Docker image or JAR file, depending on\nthe project). If the build fails, the pipeline stops. You fix it and try\nagain.</li>\n<li><strong>Stage 2 — Unit tests.</strong> The pipeline runs all the\nautomated tests. If any fail, the pipeline stops. You fix them and try\nagain.</li>\n<li><strong>Stage 3 — Deploy to Alpha.</strong> the deployment tool\n(like Spinnaker or Argo CD) takes the artifact and puts it on the Alpha\nmachines. The pipeline waits a few minutes and checks health metrics\n(CPU, memory, error rate). If Alpha looks bad, the pipeline stops.</li>\n<li><strong>Stage 4 — Promote to Beta.</strong> If Alpha is healthy, the\npipeline promotes. the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD)\ndeploys to Beta machines. Same health checks. If Beta looks bad,\nstop.</li>\n<li><strong>Stage 5 — Promote to staging.</strong> If Beta is healthy,\npromote to staging. Real traffic starts hitting the new code, but only a\nsmall percentage. Health checks again. If staging looks bad, stop.</li>\n<li><strong>Stage 6 — Promote to Prod.</strong> If staging is healthy\nfor the configured soak time (maybe 30 minutes, maybe 2 hours, depends\non the team), the pipeline promotes to Prod. the deployment tool (like\nSpinnaker or Argo CD) deploys to all Prod machines. The new code is live\nfor all customers.</li>\n<li><strong>Pipeline finishes.</strong> It stays green on the dashboard.\nYour change is shipped.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If ANY stage fails health checks, the pipeline stops and sends an\nalarm. The on-call engineer (or Support Engineer) investigates. If the\nfailure is in Prod and customers are affected, the SE rolls back\nimmediately, then investigates after customers are safe.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Deploy</strong></td>\n<td>Put code on a machine so it can run. The action of making a code\nchange live.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Pipeline</strong></td>\n<td>The automated conveyor belt that moves code through stages (Alpha,\nBeta, staging, Prod) with health checks.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Stage</strong></td>\n<td>A checkpoint in the pipeline. A place where code lives temporarily\nwhile tests and health checks run.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Alpha</strong></td>\n<td>The first stage. Just for your team. You can break things here.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Beta</strong></td>\n<td>The second stage. Internal testers, synthetic traffic. Still not\nreal customers.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>staging</strong></td>\n<td>The third stage. Almost real. Limited real traffic. The final safety\nnet before Prod.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Prod</strong></td>\n<td>Production. Real customers, real money. The stage that matters.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Promotion</strong></td>\n<td>Moving from one stage to the next. \"Promote to Prod\" means deploy to\nproduction.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Rollback</strong></td>\n<td>Undo the last deploy. Go back to the version that worked before. The\nSE emergency brake.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo\nCD)</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's deployment service. It takes your artifact and puts\nit on machines/containers.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Artifact</strong></td>\n<td>The compiled, packaged version of your code. A zip, JAR, Docker\nimage, etc. The thing the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD)\ndeploys.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Health check</strong></td>\n<td>Automated test at each stage. Does CPU look normal? Error rate low?\nLatency OK? If yes, promote. If no, stop.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Soak time</strong></td>\n<td>How long the pipeline waits in a stage before promoting. Gives time\nfor problems to show up.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Self-mutation</strong></td>\n<td>When a pipeline updates itself. If you change the pipeline\ndefinition, it applies that change to itself.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>On-call</strong></td>\n<td>The engineer responsible for responding to incidents. Carries the\npager. Gets woken up at 3am if Prod breaks.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<h3 id=\"as-a-support-engineer\">As a Support Engineer:</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Incident starts. Alarm fires.</strong> First question: \"What\nchanged?\"</li>\n<li><strong>Open the pipeline dashboard.</strong> Look at the last few\ndeploys. Check timestamps. Did a deploy finish 5 minutes before the\nalarm? That is your prime suspect.</li>\n<li><strong>Check which stage.</strong> Is the problem in staging only?\nStop the promotion. Is it in Prod? Rollback.</li>\n<li><strong>Rollback if needed.</strong> Click the rollback button on\nthe pipeline dashboard OR run the rollback command in the terminal. the\ndeployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) pulls the bad version off\nProd machines and puts the old working version back on.</li>\n<li><strong>Verify the rollback worked.</strong> Check the alarms. Are\nthey clearing? Check the metrics. Is error rate dropping? If yes,\ncustomers are safe. Breathe.</li>\n<li><strong>Investigate the root cause.</strong> Now that customers are\nsafe, figure out WHY the deploy broke. Was it a code bug? A config\nmistake? A dependency upgrade? Write a ticket. The dev team fixes it in\na pull request. The pipeline tries again later with the fix.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"day-to-day\">Day-to-day:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Read pipeline logs</strong> when investigating a ticket.\nLogs show what deployed when, which stage, which version. That is your\ntimeline.</li>\n<li><strong>Know the rollback commands</strong> for the services you\nsupport. Write them on a sticky note. Practice them once so you do not\nfumble in an emergency.</li>\n<li><strong>Understand soak times</strong> for your service. If staging\nsoaks for 1 hour, you know problems show up within an hour. If they do\nnot, Prod is probably safe.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>What are the four pipeline stages in order?</strong>\n(Answer: Alpha, Beta, staging, Prod.)</li>\n<li><strong>What does rollback mean, and why is it the SE\nsuperpower?</strong> (Answer: Rollback = undo the last deploy, go back\nto the working version. It is the superpower because it stops an\nincident fast, before you even know the root cause. Customers are safe\nfirst, investigation comes second.)</li>\n<li><strong>What is the first question you ask when an incident\nstarts?</strong> (Answer: \"What changed and which stage is it in?\")</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you can answer those three, you got it. Pipelines are rehearsals.\nthe deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) is the stagehand.\nRollback is the emergency brake. You are the one who pulls it when the\nshow goes wrong.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Next up:</strong> Module 9 will teach you <strong>Ticketing\nand the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)</strong> — how to\ntrack work, update customers, and close the loop when a problem is\nfixed. Pipelines tell you what changed. Tickets tell you what to do\nabout it.</p>\n","text":"module 8 — pipelines and the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd): how code travels to real customers the one line version: a pipeline is the conveyor belt that carries your code through safety checks (alpha, beta, staging) until it reaches real customers (prod), and the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) is the service that actually puts the code on machines so it can run. picture this (the analogy) you wrote a play. opening night, the theater is full of paying customers. you do not want the first time anyone performs the play to be in front of that audience. too risky. so you run dress rehearsals. first rehearsal (alpha): just you and the cast in an empty room. if someone forgets a line, no problem. fix it. second rehearsal (beta): invite a few friends who will forgive mistakes. if the lighting is wrong, adjust it. third rehearsal (staging): invite critics and industry people. if they find a problem, you still have time to fix it before opening night. opening night (prod): real customers, paying money. everything must work. no room for \"oops.\" a pipeline is the rehearsal schedule. it makes sure your play goes through alpha, beta, staging in order. it does not let you skip to opening night without passing the earlier checks. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) is the stagehands who actually set up the lights, props, and sound system at each rehearsal and on opening night. the pipeline decides when to promote (move forward). the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) does the physical work of getting everything in place. if opening night goes wrong, you rollback — cancel the show, go back to yesterday's version that worked, stop the bleeding. that is the support engineer superpower: knowing how to undo the bad change fast. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) on the job, when you write code and push a change, it does not go straight to real customers. it travels through a pipeline — a sequence of stages where the change gets tested and verified before reaching production. deploy = the act of putting your code somewhere it can run. could be on a physical server, a container, a lambda function, anywhere. deploy is the action. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) is the tool that does it. pipeline = the automated conveyor belt that moves your code from one stage to the next, running tests and health checks at each step. stages = checkpoints where your code lives temporarily while tests run. the four most common: alpha — just for you and your team. you can break things here. nobody else is affected. beta — internal testers, fake test accounts, synthetic traffic. still not real customers. staging — almost real. some real traffic, but limited. the final safety check. prod — real customers, real money, real consequences. this is the one that matters. promotion = when the pipeline decides \"this stage looks healthy, move to the next one.\" promotion is automatic if all the checks pass, but it can be paused or manual if the team wants more control. rollback = undo the last deploy. go back to the version that worked before. the fastest way to stop an incident. support engineers learn rollback commands first because that is how you save the day when everything is on fire. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) = a tech company's internal deployment service. it takes your code artifact (a compiled package) and puts it on the right machines or containers in the right stage. you tell the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) \"deploy version x to beta,\" and the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) makes it happen. self mutation = some pipelines can update themselves. if you change the pipeline definition (add a new stage, change a check), the pipeline applies that change to itself. one sentence is enough: \"pipelines can self mutate, so changes to the pipeline code show up in the next run.\" why you should care as a support engineer, when an incident starts, the first question you ask is: \"what changed and which stage is it in?\" did a new deploy just finish in prod? that is your suspect. is the problem only in staging? good news — it has not reached customers yet. stop the promotion. is the problem in prod but the change is in beta/staging? that means it is not the new code. look elsewhere. pipelines and the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) give you the timeline of changes . every incident investigation starts there. you open the pipeline dashboard, you see the last few deploys, you check the timestamps against when alarms started firing. that narrows the search from \"could be anything\" to \"probably this one deploy.\" and when you confirm it is the new deploy, you rollback . fast. the pipeline dashboard has a rollback button. click it. the bad version disappears, the old working version comes back, the alarms stop. you just saved thousands of customers from hitting a broken experience. then you investigate why it broke, fix it in a pull request, and try again. how it works, step by tiny step 1. you commit code on your laptop and push to a git branch. 2. you create a pull request (code review). reviewers approve it. 3. you merge to mainline (the main branch). that triggers the pipeline. 4. the pipeline wakes up . it sees a new commit on mainline. 5. stage 1 — build. the pipeline compiles your code into an artifact (a zip file or docker image or jar file, depending on the project). if the build fails, the pipeline stops. you fix it and try again. 6. stage 2 — unit tests. the pipeline runs all the automated tests. if any fail, the pipeline stops. you fix them and try again. 7. stage 3 — deploy to alpha. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) takes the artifact and puts it on the alpha machines. the pipeline waits a few minutes and checks health metrics (cpu, memory, error rate). if alpha looks bad, the pipeline stops. 8. stage 4 — promote to beta. if alpha is healthy, the pipeline promotes. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) deploys to beta machines. same health checks. if beta looks bad, stop. 9. stage 5 — promote to staging. if beta is healthy, promote to staging. real traffic starts hitting the new code, but only a small percentage. health checks again. if staging looks bad, stop. 10. stage 6 — promote to prod. if staging is healthy for the configured soak time (maybe 30 minutes, maybe 2 hours, depends on the team), the pipeline promotes to prod. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) deploys to all prod machines. the new code is live for all customers. 11. pipeline finishes. it stays green on the dashboard. your change is shipped. if any stage fails health checks, the pipeline stops and sends an alarm. the on call engineer (or support engineer) investigates. if the failure is in prod and customers are affected, the se rolls back immediately, then investigates after customers are safe. words you will hear term plain meaning deploy put code on a machine so it can run. the action of making a code change live. pipeline the automated conveyor belt that moves code through stages (alpha, beta, staging, prod) with health checks. stage a checkpoint in the pipeline. a place where code lives temporarily while tests and health checks run. alpha the first stage. just for your team. you can break things here. beta the second stage. internal testers, synthetic traffic. still not real customers. staging the third stage. almost real. limited real traffic. the final safety net before prod. prod production. real customers, real money. the stage that matters. promotion moving from one stage to the next. \"promote to prod\" means deploy to production. rollback undo the last deploy. go back to the version that worked before. the se emergency brake. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) a tech company's deployment service. it takes your artifact and puts it on machines/containers. artifact the compiled, packaged version of your code. a zip, jar, docker image, etc. the thing the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) deploys. health check automated test at each stage. does cpu look normal? error rate low? latency ok? if yes, promote. if no, stop. soak time how long the pipeline waits in a stage before promoting. gives time for problems to show up. self mutation when a pipeline updates itself. if you change the pipeline definition, it applies that change to itself. on call the engineer responsible for responding to incidents. carries the pager. gets woken up at 3am if prod breaks. what you actually do with this as a support engineer: 1. incident starts. alarm fires. first question: \"what changed?\" 2. open the pipeline dashboard. look at the last few deploys. check timestamps. did a deploy finish 5 minutes before the alarm? that is your prime suspect. 3. check which stage. is the problem in staging only? stop the promotion. is it in prod? rollback. 4. rollback if needed. click the rollback button on the pipeline dashboard or run the rollback command in the terminal. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) pulls the bad version off prod machines and puts the old working version back on. 5. verify the rollback worked. check the alarms. are they clearing? check the metrics. is error rate dropping? if yes, customers are safe. breathe. 6. investigate the root cause. now that customers are safe, figure out why the deploy broke. was it a code bug? a config mistake? a dependency upgrade? write a ticket. the dev team fixes it in a pull request. the pipeline tries again later with the fix. day to day: read pipeline logs when investigating a ticket. logs show what deployed when, which stage, which version. that is your timeline. know the rollback commands for the services you support. write them on a sticky note. practice them once so you do not fumble in an emergency. understand soak times for your service. if staging soaks for 1 hour, you know problems show up within an hour. if they do not, prod is probably safe. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. what are the four pipeline stages in order? (answer: alpha, beta, staging, prod.) 2. what does rollback mean, and why is it the se superpower? (answer: rollback = undo the last deploy, go back to the working version. it is the superpower because it stops an incident fast, before you even know the root cause. customers are safe first, investigation comes second.) 3. what is the first question you ask when an incident starts? (answer: \"what changed and which stage is it in?\") if you can answer those three, you got it. pipelines are rehearsals. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) is the stagehand. rollback is the emergency brake. you are the one who pulls it when the show goes wrong. next up: module 9 will teach you ticketing and the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) — how to track work, update customers, and close the loop when a problem is fixed. pipelines tell you what changed. tickets tell you what to do about it.","words":2059},{"id":"course-monitoring-alarms","section":"Course","title":"Monitoring & alarms","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-9--cloudwatch-watching-the-machines-and-the-smoke-detectors\">Module\n9 — CloudWatch: Watching the Machines and the Smoke Detectors</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> CloudWatch is how you SEE what\nyour service is doing right now and HEAR the alarm when something goes\nwrong.</p>\n<h3 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h3>\n<p>You have a big fish tank at home. You want the fish to be happy.</p>\n<p><strong>Logs</strong> are like a security camera recording everything\nthat happens. The filter turned on at 9am. A fish ate at 9:15am. The\nheater kicked in at 10am. You can watch the tape later if a fish dies\nand figure out what went wrong.</p>\n<p><strong>Metrics</strong> are like the thermometer stuck on the glass.\nIt shows the water temperature right now. You look at it every hour and\nwrite down the number. Now you have a chart: 72 degrees at 9am, 73 at\n10am, 75 at 11am. That chart is your metric over time.</p>\n<p><strong>Dashboards</strong> are like taping all your charts to the\nwall so you can see temperature, pH level, filter speed, and fish count\nall at once. One glance tells you if the tank is okay.</p>\n<p><strong>Alarms</strong> are like a smoke detector. You tell it: \"if\nthe water goes above 80 degrees, SCREAM at me.\" When it screams, you run\nover and fix the heater before the fish cook.</p>\n<p><strong>CloudWatch Logs Insights</strong> is like asking the security\ncamera: \"show me every time the filter turned off yesterday.\" You type a\nquestion (a query), and the tape rewinds and shows you only those\nmoments.</p>\n<p><strong>the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool</strong> is\nlike a map showing: the heater alarm connects to the thermometer, which\nconnects to the power plug. So when the heater alarm screams, you follow\nthe map backward and realize the power plug is loose. That is the REAL\nproblem. The heater alarm was just the messenger.</p>\n<p><strong>P50, P90, P99</strong> are like: if 100 fish eat, P50 is how\nfast the 50th fish ate (the middle), P90 is the 90th fish (most are\nfaster, but 10 are slower), and P99 is the 99th fish (the slowest 1\npercent, the unhappy ones who had to wait forever). SEs care about P99\nbecause those are the customers yelling.</p>\n<h3 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h3>\n<p>CloudWatch is AWS's monitoring service. Every a tech company service\nsends data to CloudWatch so engineers can see what is happening and get\nwoken up when it breaks.</p>\n<p><strong>Logs</strong> = text lines your service writes every time\nsomething happens. Each line has a timestamp and a message. Example:\n<code>2026-06-03 10:15:32 INFO Employee 12345 requested schedule, returned 10 shifts</code>.\nLogs live in <strong>log groups</strong> (one per service, like\nyour-service-prod-region-ApplicationLogs). Each log group has\n<strong>log streams</strong> (one per instance of your service, so if\nyou have 5 machines running, you have 5 streams all writing to the same\ngroup).</p>\n<p><strong>Metrics</strong> = numbers measured over time. AWS counts\nthem automatically (how many API calls, how many errors, how long each\ncall took). Your service can also send custom metrics (number of\nemployees processed, number of paycodes submitted). A metric is always:\nname + timestamp + number. Example:\n<code>SubmitPaycodeSuccess 2026-06-03T10:15:00Z 1</code> means at\n10:15am, one paycode succeeded. CloudWatch adds them up per minute and\ndraws a graph.</p>\n<p><strong>Dashboards</strong> = a web page full of graphs showing\nmultiple metrics side by side. You pick which metrics matter (error\ncount, latency, API call count) and tile them on one screen. Now you can\nglance at the dashboard and know if the service is healthy.</p>\n<p><strong>Alarms</strong> = rules you set. \"If ErrorCount goes above 10\nin 5 minutes, change state to ALARM and send me a Slack message.\" When\nthe alarm fires, it turns red in the console and notifies the oncall\nengineer. Alarms have three states: OK (green), ALARM (red),\nINSUFFICIENT_DATA (gray, not enough data yet).</p>\n<p><strong>CloudWatch Logs Insights</strong> = a query language for\nsearching logs. You write a query like:\n<code>fields @timestamp, @message | filter @message like /ERROR/ | sort @timestamp desc | limit 20</code>.\nThat means: show me the 20 most recent log lines containing the word\nERROR. The query runs across millions of log lines in seconds.</p>\n<p><strong>the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool</strong> = a\ntech company's internal alarm dependency tool. It shows a tree: which\nalarms trigger other alarms. When 5 alarms fire at once, the alarm\ndependency map in your monitoring tool helps you find the root cause\nalarm (the one at the bottom of the tree). You fix that one, and the\nother 4 stop screaming.</p>\n<p><strong>P50, P90, P99</strong> = percentiles of latency. If you\nmeasure how long 100 API calls took, P50 is the 50th slowest (half were\nfaster, half slower). P90 is the 90th slowest (90 were faster, 10\nslower). P99 is the 99th slowest (99 were faster, 1 slower). SEs care\nabout P99 because even if most requests are fast, the slowest 1 percent\nare the customers calling support to complain.</p>\n<h3 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h3>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, <strong>CloudWatch is your main window into\nthe world</strong>. A customer reports: \"my schedule didn't show up.\"\nYou don't have access to the customer's laptop. You DO have access to\nCloudWatch. You:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Search the logs for that customer's employee ID. Find the API call.\nDid it succeed or fail? What error message?</li>\n<li>Check the metric graph. Was there an error spike at that time? Did\nlatency jump?</li>\n<li>Look at the dashboard. Are other customers also broken right now, or\njust this one?</li>\n<li>Check the alarms. Is anything red? If yes, maybe the whole service\nis down, not just this customer.</li>\n<li>Use the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool to trace the\nred alarm back to the root cause. Maybe the database is slow. Maybe the\nauthentication service is timing out.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Without CloudWatch, you are blind. WITH CloudWatch, you are a\ndetective with a magnifying glass and a wall of evidence.</p>\n<h3 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h3>\n<p><strong>For logs:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Your service runs on a machine (an ECS container, a Lambda, an EC2\ninstance).</li>\n<li>The service writes log lines to stdout (the screen output). Example:\n<code>System.out.println(\"Processing employee 12345\");</code> in\nJava.</li>\n<li>The CloudWatch Logs agent (a tiny program running on the machine)\nwatches stdout, grabs every line, and sends it to AWS.</li>\n<li>AWS stores the log lines in a <strong>log group</strong>. The log\ngroup name usually matches your service:\n<code>your-service-prod-region-ApplicationLogs</code>.</li>\n<li>You open the AWS Console, navigate to CloudWatch Logs, find your log\ngroup, and click. You see the log streams (one per machine). Click a\nstream. You see the log lines, newest at the top.</li>\n<li>If you want to search, click \"Insights\" at the top. Write a query.\nRun it. Results appear in a table.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>For metrics:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Your service makes API calls. AWS automatically records: how many\ncalls per minute, how many errors per minute, how long each call\ntook.</li>\n<li>These numbers become metrics: <code>RequestCount</code>,\n<code>ErrorCount</code>, <code>Latency</code>. AWS stores them in\nCloudWatch Metrics.</li>\n<li>You (or your team) create a <strong>dashboard</strong> that shows\ngraphs of these metrics. The dashboard refreshes every minute.</li>\n<li>You bookmark the dashboard URL. When something breaks, you open the\ndashboard first. If the error graph is spiking, you know it is a real\noutage.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>For alarms:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>You (or your team) create an alarm in CloudWatch. Example: \"If\nErrorCount &gt; 10 for 2 consecutive minutes, go to ALARM state.\"</li>\n<li>You attach a notification: when the alarm goes red, send a message\nto the oncall Slack channel.</li>\n<li>When ErrorCount jumps to 15 at 10:00am and stays there at 10:01am,\nthe alarm fires. Slack pings the oncall engineer.</li>\n<li>The engineer opens the dashboard, sees the error spike, searches the\nlogs, finds the root cause, fixes it.</li>\n<li>ErrorCount drops to 0. After 2 consecutive minutes below 10, the\nalarm goes back to OK (green).</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>For the alarm dependency map in your monitoring\ntool:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Your team has many alarms. Some are high-level (\"Service is down\"),\nsome are low-level (\"Database connection timeout\").</li>\n<li>You configure the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool to\nlink them: \"Service is down\" depends on \"Database connection timeout\".\nSo if the database alarm fires, the alarm dependency map in your\nmonitoring tool shows it as the root cause.</li>\n<li>When 5 alarms fire at once, you open the alarm dependency map in\nyour monitoring tool (your team's internal docs), search for your\nservice, and look at the alarm tree. The one at the BOTTOM (no\ndependencies under it) is the root cause. You fix that one first.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h3>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Log group</strong></td>\n<td>A folder holding all the logs for one service. Example:\n<code>your-service-prod-region-ApplicationLogs</code>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Log stream</strong></td>\n<td>A single file of logs from one machine running your service. If 5\nmachines, 5 streams, all in the same log group.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CloudWatch Logs Insights</strong></td>\n<td>A search tool for logs. You write a query (a question), it scans\nmillions of log lines, returns matches.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Metric</strong></td>\n<td>A number measured over time. Example: ErrorCount = 5 at 10:00am, 3\nat 10:01am, 0 at 10:02am.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dashboard</strong></td>\n<td>A web page showing graphs of multiple metrics side by side. One\nglance = health check.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Alarm</strong></td>\n<td>A rule that screams when a metric goes bad. Example: \"If ErrorCount\n&gt; 10, ALARM.\"</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Percentile (P50, P90, P99)</strong></td>\n<td>A way to describe latency. P50 = half of requests were faster. P99 =\n99% were faster, 1% slower (the unhappy ones).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Latency</strong></td>\n<td>How long something took. Example: API call took 200 milliseconds\n(0.2 seconds).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the alarm dependency map in your monitoring\ntool</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's internal tool that maps which alarms depend on\nwhich. Helps you find the root cause when many alarms fire.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Root cause</strong></td>\n<td>The REAL problem. Other alarms are symptoms. Fix the root cause,\nsymptoms go away.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Insights query</strong></td>\n<td>The question you type into CloudWatch Logs Insights. Example:\n`fields @timestamp, @message</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>EMF (Embedded Metric Format)</strong></td>\n<td>A way to write logs that also count as metrics. The log line\ncontains a number, CloudWatch turns it into a metric automatically.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h3>\n<p><strong>Day 1 SE work:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><p>Customer reports: \"I submitted a paycode but it did not appear in\nmy manager's view.\" You search CloudWatch Logs for that customer's\nemployee ID. Find the API call. See the error message: \"Validation\nfailed: paycode ZZZ does not exist.\" You reply to the customer: \"The\npaycode you used (ZZZ) is not valid for your country. Please use paycode\nABC instead.\" Case closed.</p></li>\n<li><p>Oncall engineer pings you: \"Error alarm firing on the\ntime-tracking service.\" You open the dashboard. Error graph is spiking.\nYou open the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool. The root\ncause alarm is \"Database connection pool exhausted.\" You ping the\ndatabase team. They restart the pool. Errors drop to zero. Alarm goes\ngreen.</p></li>\n<li><p>Your manager asks: \"How many employees used the new schedule API\nlast week?\" You open CloudWatch Metrics. Find the custom metric\n<code>ScheduleAPICallCount</code>. Look at the graph for last week. The\ntotal is 120,000. You reply: \"120K calls last week, trending up from\n100K the week before.\"</p></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>You will:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Search logs when customers report issues (LOGS INSIGHTS).</li>\n<li>Check dashboards when alarms fire (DASHBOARDS).</li>\n<li>Trace alarms back to root causes (the alarm dependency map in your\nmonitoring tool).</li>\n<li>Read P99 latency to know if the slowest customers are suffering\n(METRICS).</li>\n<li>Set up your own alarms for things you care about (ALARMS).</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h3>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h3 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p>If a customer says \"my API call failed at 3pm,\" where do you look\nfirst: logs, metrics, or alarms? <em>(Answer: Logs. Search for the\ncustomer's employee ID + timestamp.)</em></p></li>\n<li><p>If 5 alarms fire at once, which tool helps you find the root\ncause alarm? <em>(Answer: the alarm dependency map in your monitoring\ntool.)</em></p></li>\n<li><p>What does P99 latency mean in plain words? <em>(Answer: The\nslowest 1 percent of requests. If P99 is high, the unhappiest customers\nare waiting too long.)</em></p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Next:</strong> Module 10 will cover <strong>Tickets and\nOncall</strong> (the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty), the\nrequest-tracing tool, how you pick up work, what a Sev-2 looks like, and\nhow you hand off to the next shift).</p>\n","text":"module 9 — cloudwatch: watching the machines and the smoke detectors the one line version: cloudwatch is how you see what your service is doing right now and hear the alarm when something goes wrong. picture this (the analogy) you have a big fish tank at home. you want the fish to be happy. logs are like a security camera recording everything that happens. the filter turned on at 9am. a fish ate at 9:15am. the heater kicked in at 10am. you can watch the tape later if a fish dies and figure out what went wrong. metrics are like the thermometer stuck on the glass. it shows the water temperature right now. you look at it every hour and write down the number. now you have a chart: 72 degrees at 9am, 73 at 10am, 75 at 11am. that chart is your metric over time. dashboards are like taping all your charts to the wall so you can see temperature, ph level, filter speed, and fish count all at once. one glance tells you if the tank is okay. alarms are like a smoke detector. you tell it: \"if the water goes above 80 degrees, scream at me.\" when it screams, you run over and fix the heater before the fish cook. cloudwatch logs insights is like asking the security camera: \"show me every time the filter turned off yesterday.\" you type a question (a query), and the tape rewinds and shows you only those moments. the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool is like a map showing: the heater alarm connects to the thermometer, which connects to the power plug. so when the heater alarm screams, you follow the map backward and realize the power plug is loose. that is the real problem. the heater alarm was just the messenger. p50, p90, p99 are like: if 100 fish eat, p50 is how fast the 50th fish ate (the middle), p90 is the 90th fish (most are faster, but 10 are slower), and p99 is the 99th fish (the slowest 1 percent, the unhappy ones who had to wait forever). ses care about p99 because those are the customers yelling. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) cloudwatch is aws's monitoring service. every a tech company service sends data to cloudwatch so engineers can see what is happening and get woken up when it breaks. logs = text lines your service writes every time something happens. each line has a timestamp and a message. example: 2026 06 03 10:15:32 info employee 12345 requested schedule, returned 10 shifts . logs live in log groups (one per service, like your service prod region applicationlogs). each log group has log streams (one per instance of your service, so if you have 5 machines running, you have 5 streams all writing to the same group). metrics = numbers measured over time. aws counts them automatically (how many api calls, how many errors, how long each call took). your service can also send custom metrics (number of employees processed, number of paycodes submitted). a metric is always: name + timestamp + number. example: submitpaycodesuccess 2026 06 03t10:15:00z 1 means at 10:15am, one paycode succeeded. cloudwatch adds them up per minute and draws a graph. dashboards = a web page full of graphs showing multiple metrics side by side. you pick which metrics matter (error count, latency, api call count) and tile them on one screen. now you can glance at the dashboard and know if the service is healthy. alarms = rules you set. \"if errorcount goes above 10 in 5 minutes, change state to alarm and send me a slack message.\" when the alarm fires, it turns red in the console and notifies the oncall engineer. alarms have three states: ok (green), alarm (red), insufficient data (gray, not enough data yet). cloudwatch logs insights = a query language for searching logs. you write a query like: fields @timestamp, @message filter @message like /error/ sort @timestamp desc limit 20 . that means: show me the 20 most recent log lines containing the word error. the query runs across millions of log lines in seconds. the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool = a tech company's internal alarm dependency tool. it shows a tree: which alarms trigger other alarms. when 5 alarms fire at once, the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool helps you find the root cause alarm (the one at the bottom of the tree). you fix that one, and the other 4 stop screaming. p50, p90, p99 = percentiles of latency. if you measure how long 100 api calls took, p50 is the 50th slowest (half were faster, half slower). p90 is the 90th slowest (90 were faster, 10 slower). p99 is the 99th slowest (99 were faster, 1 slower). ses care about p99 because even if most requests are fast, the slowest 1 percent are the customers calling support to complain. why you should care as a support engineer, cloudwatch is your main window into the world . a customer reports: \"my schedule didn't show up.\" you don't have access to the customer's laptop. you do have access to cloudwatch. you: 1. search the logs for that customer's employee id. find the api call. did it succeed or fail? what error message? 2. check the metric graph. was there an error spike at that time? did latency jump? 3. look at the dashboard. are other customers also broken right now, or just this one? 4. check the alarms. is anything red? if yes, maybe the whole service is down, not just this customer. 5. use the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool to trace the red alarm back to the root cause. maybe the database is slow. maybe the authentication service is timing out. without cloudwatch, you are blind. with cloudwatch, you are a detective with a magnifying glass and a wall of evidence. how it works, step by tiny step for logs: 1. your service runs on a machine (an ecs container, a lambda, an ec2 instance). 2. the service writes log lines to stdout (the screen output). example: system.out.println(\"processing employee 12345\"); in java. 3. the cloudwatch logs agent (a tiny program running on the machine) watches stdout, grabs every line, and sends it to aws. 4. aws stores the log lines in a log group . the log group name usually matches your service: your service prod region applicationlogs . 5. you open the aws console, navigate to cloudwatch logs, find your log group, and click. you see the log streams (one per machine). click a stream. you see the log lines, newest at the top. 6. if you want to search, click \"insights\" at the top. write a query. run it. results appear in a table. for metrics: 1. your service makes api calls. aws automatically records: how many calls per minute, how many errors per minute, how long each call took. 2. these numbers become metrics: requestcount , errorcount , latency . aws stores them in cloudwatch metrics. 3. you (or your team) create a dashboard that shows graphs of these metrics. the dashboard refreshes every minute. 4. you bookmark the dashboard url. when something breaks, you open the dashboard first. if the error graph is spiking, you know it is a real outage. for alarms: 1. you (or your team) create an alarm in cloudwatch. example: \"if errorcount 10 for 2 consecutive minutes, go to alarm state.\" 2. you attach a notification: when the alarm goes red, send a message to the oncall slack channel. 3. when errorcount jumps to 15 at 10:00am and stays there at 10:01am, the alarm fires. slack pings the oncall engineer. 4. the engineer opens the dashboard, sees the error spike, searches the logs, finds the root cause, fixes it. 5. errorcount drops to 0. after 2 consecutive minutes below 10, the alarm goes back to ok (green). for the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool: 1. your team has many alarms. some are high level (\"service is down\"), some are low level (\"database connection timeout\"). 2. you configure the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool to link them: \"service is down\" depends on \"database connection timeout\". so if the database alarm fires, the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool shows it as the root cause. 3. when 5 alarms fire at once, you open the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool (your team's internal docs), search for your service, and look at the alarm tree. the one at the bottom (no dependencies under it) is the root cause. you fix that one first. words you will hear term plain meaning log group a folder holding all the logs for one service. example: your service prod region applicationlogs . log stream a single file of logs from one machine running your service. if 5 machines, 5 streams, all in the same log group. cloudwatch logs insights a search tool for logs. you write a query (a question), it scans millions of log lines, returns matches. metric a number measured over time. example: errorcount = 5 at 10:00am, 3 at 10:01am, 0 at 10:02am. dashboard a web page showing graphs of multiple metrics side by side. one glance = health check. alarm a rule that screams when a metric goes bad. example: \"if errorcount 10, alarm.\" percentile (p50, p90, p99) a way to describe latency. p50 = half of requests were faster. p99 = 99% were faster, 1% slower (the unhappy ones). latency how long something took. example: api call took 200 milliseconds (0.2 seconds). the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool a tech company's internal tool that maps which alarms depend on which. helps you find the root cause when many alarms fire. root cause the real problem. other alarms are symptoms. fix the root cause, symptoms go away. insights query the question you type into cloudwatch logs insights. example: fields @timestamp, @message filter @message like /error/ . emf (embedded metric format) a way to write logs that also count as metrics. the log line contains a number, cloudwatch turns it into a metric automatically. what you actually do with this day 1 se work: customer reports: \"i submitted a paycode but it did not appear in my manager's view.\" you search cloudwatch logs for that customer's employee id. find the api call. see the error message: \"validation failed: paycode zzz does not exist.\" you reply to the customer: \"the paycode you used (zzz) is not valid for your country. please use paycode abc instead.\" case closed. oncall engineer pings you: \"error alarm firing on the time tracking service.\" you open the dashboard. error graph is spiking. you open the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool. the root cause alarm is \"database connection pool exhausted.\" you ping the database team. they restart the pool. errors drop to zero. alarm goes green. your manager asks: \"how many employees used the new schedule api last week?\" you open cloudwatch metrics. find the custom metric scheduleapicallcount . look at the graph for last week. the total is 120,000. you reply: \"120k calls last week, trending up from 100k the week before.\" you will: search logs when customers report issues (logs insights). check dashboards when alarms fire (dashboards). trace alarms back to root causes (the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool). read p99 latency to know if the slowest customers are suffering (metrics). set up your own alarms for things you care about (alarms). how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. if a customer says \"my api call failed at 3pm,\" where do you look first: logs, metrics, or alarms? (answer: logs. search for the customer's employee id + timestamp.) 2. if 5 alarms fire at once, which tool helps you find the root cause alarm? (answer: the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool.) 3. what does p99 latency mean in plain words? (answer: the slowest 1 percent of requests. if p99 is high, the unhappiest customers are waiting too long.) next: module 10 will cover tickets and oncall (the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty), the request tracing tool, how you pick up work, what a sev 2 looks like, and how you hand off to the next shift).","words":2148},{"id":"course-tickets-queues-on-call","section":"Course","title":"Tickets, queues & on-call","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-10--the-ticketing-system-like-jira-or-pagerduty-tickets-queues-and-on-call-the-heart-of-support\">Module\n10 — the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty), tickets, queues, and\non-call: the heart of support</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> Support Engineers live inside\ntickets (help requests), triage them by urgency, and take turns being\non-call (the person who gets paged when things break at 3am).</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h3>\n<p>Imagine a busy restaurant kitchen. Orders keep coming in on a screen.\nSome are simple (side of fries), some are complicated (custom allergy\nmeal), some are URGENT (the VIP table is waiting). The head chef looks\nat the screen and decides what to cook first. That is triage. The chef\nwho is \"on-call\" tonight wears a pager. If the fire alarm goes off or\nthe walk-in freezer breaks, the pager buzzes and that chef has to drop\neverything and run. That is on-call.</p>\n<p>Now imagine a hospital night shift. The ER nurse gets patients in\ndifferent states. One person has a scraped knee (low urgency). One\nperson has chest pain (high urgency, call the doctor NOW). The nurse\ndecides who gets treated first. That is severity. The nurse on the night\nshift is \"on-call\" — they are the one who gets the emergency page if\nsomeone crashes.</p>\n<p>Support Engineers do both. You are the restaurant chef AND the ER\nnurse. Tickets are your orders and your patients. You decide what is\nurgent. You fix what you can. You call for help when you need it. And\nwhen it is your turn to be on-call, you carry the pager (your phone) and\nyou are the first responder when something breaks.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h3>\n<p>A <strong>ticket</strong> is a help request or a problem report. A\ncustomer could not log in. A payroll calculation broke. A metric spiked.\nSomeone filed a ticket describing the problem.</p>\n<p><strong>the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)</strong>\n(Service Issue Management) is a tech company's ticketing system. Think\nof it like Jira but a tech company-built. Every ticket lives in the\nticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty). The web interface is at your\nteam's internal docs When you search for a ticket ID like\n<code>a ticket</code>, you type that into the ticketing system (like\nJira or PagerDuty) and it opens the ticket page.</p>\n<p><strong>the ticketing system</strong> is the newer version of the\nticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) (the \"T\" stands for an\ninternal integration but nobody calls it that). Same idea, cleaner UI.\nthe ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) and the ticketing system\nare the same system, just different generations of the web page.</p>\n<p>A <strong>queue</strong> is the list of tickets waiting for your\nteam. Think of it like the restaurant order screen. New tickets land in\nthe queue. Your team pulls tickets out of the queue and works them.</p>\n<p><strong>Triage</strong> means deciding what order to work the tickets\nin. Not first-in-first-out. You work the MOST URGENT ticket first, even\nif it arrived last. Triage is the art of smart prioritization.</p>\n<p><strong>Severity levels</strong> tell you how urgent the ticket\nis:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sev-1</strong> (Severity 1) = huge fire. Big customer\nimpact. Production is down. Many people cannot work. ALL HANDS. You drop\neverything.</li>\n<li><strong>Sev-2</strong> = serious fire. Some customers impacted.\nRevenue or operations hurt. Work it ASAP.</li>\n<li><strong>Sev-3</strong> = smaller problem. One customer stuck, or a\nnon-critical feature broken. Work it soon, but not emergency-level.</li>\n<li><strong>Sev-5</strong> = tiny issue. Often internal test tickets or\nminor annoyances. Work it when you have time.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>(a tech company skips Sev-4. Just one of those historical quirks. You\nwill see Sev-1, Sev-2, Sev-3, Sev-5. No Sev-4.)</p>\n<p><strong>SLA</strong> (Service Level Agreement) is the promise you\nmade to respond or resolve within a certain time. Example: Sev-2 tickets\nhave a 4-hour response SLA. That means you must post a meaningful update\nwithin 4 hours of the ticket being filed, or you broke your promise. The\nSLA clock is ticking the moment the ticket lands.</p>\n<p><strong>On-call</strong> means it is your turn to be the first\nresponder. You carry your phone (or laptop if working from home). If\nsomething breaks at 3am, the paging system buzzes your phone. You wake\nup, you triage, you mitigate the fire, you loop in help if needed.\nOn-call shifts rotate. One week you are on-call, next week someone else\nis.</p>\n<p><strong>Paging</strong> is the system that buzzes you. A tech company\nuses a tool called <strong>PagerDuty</strong> (or sometimes internal\ntools like <strong>internal paging alarms</strong>). When a critical\nalarm fires, PagerDuty calls your phone. Loudly. You cannot ignore\nit.</p>\n<p><strong>Escalation</strong> means bringing in more help. You do NOT\nhand off the ticket and walk away. You STAY on the ticket as the owner\nand you PULL IN extra people. Escalate UP (to your manager or the senior\nengineer) when the problem is too big for you. Escalate SIDEWAYS (to\nanother team) when the problem is in their domain. But you remain the\nsingle-threaded owner coordinating the response.</p>\n<p><strong>Handoff</strong> means passing the ticket to the next person\ncleanly. You write detailed notes in the ticket: what you found, what\nyou tried, what worked, what did not, what the next step is. You tag the\nnext person. You do NOT just reassign and disappear. Clean handoffs save\nhours of re-investigation.</p>\n<p><strong>Mitigate first, fix root cause second</strong> is the golden\nrule. Mitigate means STOP THE BLEEDING. Turn off the broken feature.\nRoll back the bad deploy. Restore from backup. Get customers unblocked\nNOW. Then, after the fire is out, you investigate the root cause and\nship a real fix. Do not spend 6 hours root-causing while customers are\ndown. Mitigate in 20 minutes, root-cause later.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h3>\n<p>This is the SE job. Tickets are your daily work. Queues are your\nto-do list. On-call is your responsibility (and your growth opportunity\n— you learn the MOST during on-call because you see the real fires).\nTriage is the skill that separates a good SE from a mediocre one. Anyone\ncan work tickets in order. A GOOD SE works tickets in SMART order,\nmitigates fast, escalates when stuck, and keeps customers unblocked.</p>\n<p>SLAs matter because customers trust you to respond on time. Break too\nmany SLAs and customers lose trust. Hit your SLAs consistently and you\nearn trust.</p>\n<p>Handoffs matter because support is a 24-hour job. When your shift\nends, someone else picks up. If you leave messy notes, the next person\nwastes time re-investigating. If you leave CLEAN notes, the next person\nhits the ground running.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h3>\n<h4 id=\"working-a-ticket-the-basic-loop\">Working a ticket (the basic\nloop)</h4>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>A ticket lands in your team queue.</strong> You see it in\nthe ticketing system or you get a notification.</li>\n<li><strong>You open the ticket.</strong> Read the description. What is\nbroken? Who is impacted? When did it start?</li>\n<li><strong>You triage.</strong> Look at severity. Look at SLA clock.\nDecide if this is urgent or can wait.</li>\n<li><strong>You investigate.</strong> Check CloudWatch logs. Check the\nservice metrics. Check recent deploys. Look for clues.</li>\n<li><strong>You mitigate if possible.</strong> If you can stop the\nbleeding NOW, do it. Roll back a deploy. Restart a service. Disable a\nbroken feature.</li>\n<li><strong>You update the ticket.</strong> Post what you found. Post\nwhat you did. Post next steps. This keeps the customer (and your\nmanager) informed.</li>\n<li><strong>You escalate if stuck.</strong> Tag your senior engineer.\nTag the owning team. Stay on the ticket as coordinator.</li>\n<li><strong>You resolve or hand off.</strong> When fixed, mark the\nticket RESOLVED with a summary. If you cannot finish it this shift,\nwrite clean handoff notes and reassign.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4 id=\"on-call-the-emergency-loop\">On-call (the emergency loop)</h4>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>You are on-call this week.</strong> You carry your phone\n24/7. You check it before bed.</li>\n<li><strong>An alarm fires at 3am.</strong> PagerDuty buzzes your phone.\nLoudly.</li>\n<li><strong>You acknowledge the page.</strong> Open PagerDuty app, tap\nACKNOWLEDGE. This tells the system you saw it.</li>\n<li><strong>You triage.</strong> Is this a real fire or a flaky alarm?\nCheck the runbook. Check CloudWatch.</li>\n<li><strong>You mitigate.</strong> If it is a real fire, STOP THE\nBLEEDING. Do not spend an hour root-causing at 3am. Mitigate NOW.</li>\n<li><strong>You escalate if needed.</strong> If you are stuck or it is\ntoo big, page your manager or the senior engineer. Do not struggle alone\nfor 2 hours.</li>\n<li><strong>You update the ticket.</strong> Every on-call incident gets\na ticket. Post what you did, what is stable, what needs follow-up.</li>\n<li><strong>You hand off at shift end.</strong> If the fire is still\nburning when your shift ends, hand off to the next on-call with clean\nnotes.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4\nid=\"escalation-bringing-in-help-without-dropping-the-ball\">Escalation\n(bringing in help without dropping the ball)</h4>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>You are stuck on a ticket.</strong> You tried 3 things, none\nworked, clock is ticking.</li>\n<li><strong>You decide who to escalate to.</strong> Is this a code\nproblem (escalate to dev team)? Is this too hard for you (escalate to\nsenior SE)? Is this cross-team (escalate sideways)?</li>\n<li><strong>You tag them in the ticket.</strong> In the ticketing system\n(like Jira or PagerDuty), add a comment:\n<code>@senior-se-alias — stuck on root cause, need eyes on this CW query.</code>\nInclude your investigation so far. Do NOT make them start from\nzero.</li>\n<li><strong>You STAY on the ticket as owner.</strong> Do not reassign\nand walk away. You are the coordinator. They are the consultant.</li>\n<li><strong>You keep the customer updated.</strong> Post in the ticket:\n<code>Escalated to X team for deeper investigation. Will update within 2 hours.</code>\nCustomers see that you are driving it.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4 id=\"handoff-passing-cleanly-to-the-next-person\">Handoff (passing\ncleanly to the next person)</h4>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Your shift is ending.</strong> You have 3 open tickets.</li>\n<li><strong>For each ticket, you write handoff notes.</strong> Use this\nformat:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>What happened so far:</strong> (timeline)</li>\n<li><strong>What I tried:</strong> (actions taken)</li>\n<li><strong>What worked / did not work:</strong> (results)</li>\n<li><strong>Current state:</strong> (is it mitigated? still\nbroken?)</li>\n<li><strong>Next step:</strong> (exactly what the next person should\ndo)</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>You tag the next on-call.</strong> In the ticketing system\n(like Jira or PagerDuty), add a comment:\n<code>@next-oncall-alias — handing off. See notes above. Next step: check CW for pattern at 10am UTC.</code></li>\n<li><strong>You reassign the ticket.</strong> Change the assignee field\nto the next person.</li>\n<li><strong>You close your laptop.</strong> You did your job. The next\nperson has what they need.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h3>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Ticket</strong></td>\n<td>A help request or problem report. Lives in the ticketing system\n(like Jira or PagerDuty). Has an ID like <code>a ticket</code>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) / the\nticketing system</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's ticketing system. the ticketing system is the newer\nversion. Same system, different UI.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Queue</strong></td>\n<td>The list of tickets waiting for your team. Your to-do list.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Triage</strong></td>\n<td>Deciding what order to work tickets in. Urgent first, not\nfirst-in-first-out.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Severity (Sev)</strong></td>\n<td>How urgent the ticket is. Sev-1 = huge fire. Sev-5 = tiny\nissue.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>SLA</strong></td>\n<td>Service Level Agreement. The promise you made to respond/resolve\nwithin X hours. A clock ticking.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>On-call</strong></td>\n<td>Your turn to be the first responder. You carry the pager (your\nphone).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Paging</strong></td>\n<td>The system buzzing your phone when something breaks. PagerDuty or\ninternal paging alarms.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Escalation</strong></td>\n<td>Bringing in more help. You stay on the ticket as owner, they\nconsult.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Handoff</strong></td>\n<td>Passing a ticket to the next person with clean notes. Do not make\nthem re-investigate.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mitigate</strong></td>\n<td>Stop the bleeding NOW. Roll back, restart, disable. Do not wait to\nroot-cause.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Root cause</strong></td>\n<td>The REAL reason it broke. You investigate this AFTER you\nmitigate.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>PagerDuty</strong></td>\n<td>The tool that buzzes your phone during on-call.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Runbook</strong></td>\n<td>A step-by-step guide for handling a specific alarm or incident. Like\na recipe.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Acknowledge</strong></td>\n<td>Telling the paging system you saw the alert. Stops it from paging\nthe next person.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h3>\n<p><strong>Daily work:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>You open the ticketing system every morning. Check your team queue.\nLook for new tickets.</li>\n<li>You triage. What is Sev-2 and needs attention NOW? What is Sev-3 and\ncan wait?</li>\n<li>You work tickets. Investigate. Mitigate. Update. Resolve or hand\noff.</li>\n<li>You check SLA clocks. If a ticket is near SLA breach, you prioritize\nit.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>On-call rotation:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Once every few weeks (or once a month, depends on team size), it is\nyour turn to be on-call.</li>\n<li>You carry your phone 24/7 that week. You check PagerDuty before\nbed.</li>\n<li>When an alarm fires, you triage and mitigate. You escalate if stuck.\nYou update the ticket.</li>\n<li>At the end of your shift, you hand off any open incidents to the\nnext on-call.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Escalation:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>When you are stuck, you do NOT struggle alone for hours. You tag a\nsenior SE or the dev team in the ticket.</li>\n<li>You stay as the owner. They consult. You drive the resolution.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Handoff:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>When your shift ends, you write clean notes for every open ticket.\nYou tag the next person. You reassign.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h3>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h3 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>A Sev-1 ticket lands in your queue at 2pm. A Sev-3 ticket\nlanded at 10am. Which do you work first?</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Answer: Sev-1. Severity beats arrival time. Sev-1 is a huge fire.\nDrop everything.</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>You are stuck on a ticket. You tried 3 things, none worked,\nSLA clock is at 80%. What do you do?</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Answer: Escalate NOW. Tag a senior SE or the dev team in the ticket.\nStay as owner. Do not wait until SLA breaches.</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Your on-call shift ends at 8am. You have an open incident\nthat is mitigated but not root-caused. What do you do?</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Answer: Write clean handoff notes. State current status (mitigated,\nstable). State next step (root-cause investigation). Tag next on-call.\nReassign ticket. Do not just disappear.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>You have learned:</strong> Tickets are help requests that\nlive in the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty). Queues are your\nto-do list. Triage is working in smart order (urgent first). Severity\ntells you how urgent (Sev-1 huge, Sev-5 tiny). SLA is the response-time\npromise (do not break it). On-call is your turn to carry the pager and\nrespond to fires 24/7. Mitigate first (stop the bleeding), root-cause\nsecond. Escalate when stuck (but stay as owner). Handoff cleanly (clean\nnotes for next person). This is the SE daily loop. You triage, you\nmitigate, you escalate, you hand off. Over and over. You already did\nthis 5 times earlier in your career. Now you do it 50 times a month.</p>\n","text":"module 10 — the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty), tickets, queues, and on call: the heart of support the one line version: support engineers live inside tickets (help requests), triage them by urgency, and take turns being on call (the person who gets paged when things break at 3am). picture this (the analogy) imagine a busy restaurant kitchen. orders keep coming in on a screen. some are simple (side of fries), some are complicated (custom allergy meal), some are urgent (the vip table is waiting). the head chef looks at the screen and decides what to cook first. that is triage. the chef who is \"on call\" tonight wears a pager. if the fire alarm goes off or the walk in freezer breaks, the pager buzzes and that chef has to drop everything and run. that is on call. now imagine a hospital night shift. the er nurse gets patients in different states. one person has a scraped knee (low urgency). one person has chest pain (high urgency, call the doctor now). the nurse decides who gets treated first. that is severity. the nurse on the night shift is \"on call\" — they are the one who gets the emergency page if someone crashes. support engineers do both. you are the restaurant chef and the er nurse. tickets are your orders and your patients. you decide what is urgent. you fix what you can. you call for help when you need it. and when it is your turn to be on call, you carry the pager (your phone) and you are the first responder when something breaks. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) a ticket is a help request or a problem report. a customer could not log in. a payroll calculation broke. a metric spiked. someone filed a ticket describing the problem. the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) (service issue management) is a tech company's ticketing system. think of it like jira but a tech company built. every ticket lives in the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty). the web interface is at your team's internal docs when you search for a ticket id like a ticket , you type that into the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) and it opens the ticket page. the ticketing system is the newer version of the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) (the \"t\" stands for an internal integration but nobody calls it that). same idea, cleaner ui. the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) and the ticketing system are the same system, just different generations of the web page. a queue is the list of tickets waiting for your team. think of it like the restaurant order screen. new tickets land in the queue. your team pulls tickets out of the queue and works them. triage means deciding what order to work the tickets in. not first in first out. you work the most urgent ticket first, even if it arrived last. triage is the art of smart prioritization. severity levels tell you how urgent the ticket is: sev 1 (severity 1) = huge fire. big customer impact. production is down. many people cannot work. all hands. you drop everything. sev 2 = serious fire. some customers impacted. revenue or operations hurt. work it asap. sev 3 = smaller problem. one customer stuck, or a non critical feature broken. work it soon, but not emergency level. sev 5 = tiny issue. often internal test tickets or minor annoyances. work it when you have time. (a tech company skips sev 4. just one of those historical quirks. you will see sev 1, sev 2, sev 3, sev 5. no sev 4.) sla (service level agreement) is the promise you made to respond or resolve within a certain time. example: sev 2 tickets have a 4 hour response sla. that means you must post a meaningful update within 4 hours of the ticket being filed, or you broke your promise. the sla clock is ticking the moment the ticket lands. on call means it is your turn to be the first responder. you carry your phone (or laptop if working from home). if something breaks at 3am, the paging system buzzes your phone. you wake up, you triage, you mitigate the fire, you loop in help if needed. on call shifts rotate. one week you are on call, next week someone else is. paging is the system that buzzes you. a tech company uses a tool called pagerduty (or sometimes internal tools like internal paging alarms ). when a critical alarm fires, pagerduty calls your phone. loudly. you cannot ignore it. escalation means bringing in more help. you do not hand off the ticket and walk away. you stay on the ticket as the owner and you pull in extra people. escalate up (to your manager or the senior engineer) when the problem is too big for you. escalate sideways (to another team) when the problem is in their domain. but you remain the single threaded owner coordinating the response. handoff means passing the ticket to the next person cleanly. you write detailed notes in the ticket: what you found, what you tried, what worked, what did not, what the next step is. you tag the next person. you do not just reassign and disappear. clean handoffs save hours of re investigation. mitigate first, fix root cause second is the golden rule. mitigate means stop the bleeding. turn off the broken feature. roll back the bad deploy. restore from backup. get customers unblocked now. then, after the fire is out, you investigate the root cause and ship a real fix. do not spend 6 hours root causing while customers are down. mitigate in 20 minutes, root cause later. why you should care this is the se job. tickets are your daily work. queues are your to do list. on call is your responsibility (and your growth opportunity — you learn the most during on call because you see the real fires). triage is the skill that separates a good se from a mediocre one. anyone can work tickets in order. a good se works tickets in smart order, mitigates fast, escalates when stuck, and keeps customers unblocked. slas matter because customers trust you to respond on time. break too many slas and customers lose trust. hit your slas consistently and you earn trust. handoffs matter because support is a 24 hour job. when your shift ends, someone else picks up. if you leave messy notes, the next person wastes time re investigating. if you leave clean notes, the next person hits the ground running. how it works, step by tiny step working a ticket (the basic loop) 1. a ticket lands in your team queue. you see it in the ticketing system or you get a notification. 2. you open the ticket. read the description. what is broken? who is impacted? when did it start? 3. you triage. look at severity. look at sla clock. decide if this is urgent or can wait. 4. you investigate. check cloudwatch logs. check the service metrics. check recent deploys. look for clues. 5. you mitigate if possible. if you can stop the bleeding now, do it. roll back a deploy. restart a service. disable a broken feature. 6. you update the ticket. post what you found. post what you did. post next steps. this keeps the customer (and your manager) informed. 7. you escalate if stuck. tag your senior engineer. tag the owning team. stay on the ticket as coordinator. 8. you resolve or hand off. when fixed, mark the ticket resolved with a summary. if you cannot finish it this shift, write clean handoff notes and reassign. on call (the emergency loop) 1. you are on call this week. you carry your phone 24/7. you check it before bed. 2. an alarm fires at 3am. pagerduty buzzes your phone. loudly. 3. you acknowledge the page. open pagerduty app, tap acknowledge. this tells the system you saw it. 4. you triage. is this a real fire or a flaky alarm? check the runbook. check cloudwatch. 5. you mitigate. if it is a real fire, stop the bleeding. do not spend an hour root causing at 3am. mitigate now. 6. you escalate if needed. if you are stuck or it is too big, page your manager or the senior engineer. do not struggle alone for 2 hours. 7. you update the ticket. every on call incident gets a ticket. post what you did, what is stable, what needs follow up. 8. you hand off at shift end. if the fire is still burning when your shift ends, hand off to the next on call with clean notes. escalation (bringing in help without dropping the ball) 1. you are stuck on a ticket. you tried 3 things, none worked, clock is ticking. 2. you decide who to escalate to. is this a code problem (escalate to dev team)? is this too hard for you (escalate to senior se)? is this cross team (escalate sideways)? 3. you tag them in the ticket. in the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty), add a comment: @senior se alias — stuck on root cause, need eyes on this cw query. include your investigation so far. do not make them start from zero. 4. you stay on the ticket as owner. do not reassign and walk away. you are the coordinator. they are the consultant. 5. you keep the customer updated. post in the ticket: escalated to x team for deeper investigation. will update within 2 hours. customers see that you are driving it. handoff (passing cleanly to the next person) 1. your shift is ending. you have 3 open tickets. 2. for each ticket, you write handoff notes. use this format: what happened so far: (timeline) what i tried: (actions taken) what worked / did not work: (results) current state: (is it mitigated? still broken?) next step: (exactly what the next person should do) 3. you tag the next on call. in the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty), add a comment: @next oncall alias — handing off. see notes above. next step: check cw for pattern at 10am utc. 4. you reassign the ticket. change the assignee field to the next person. 5. you close your laptop. you did your job. the next person has what they need. words you will hear term plain meaning ticket a help request or problem report. lives in the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty). has an id like a ticket . the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) / the ticketing system a tech company's ticketing system. the ticketing system is the newer version. same system, different ui. queue the list of tickets waiting for your team. your to do list. triage deciding what order to work tickets in. urgent first, not first in first out. severity (sev) how urgent the ticket is. sev 1 = huge fire. sev 5 = tiny issue. sla service level agreement. the promise you made to respond/resolve within x hours. a clock ticking. on call your turn to be the first responder. you carry the pager (your phone). paging the system buzzing your phone when something breaks. pagerduty or internal paging alarms. escalation bringing in more help. you stay on the ticket as owner, they consult. handoff passing a ticket to the next person with clean notes. do not make them re investigate. mitigate stop the bleeding now. roll back, restart, disable. do not wait to root cause. root cause the real reason it broke. you investigate this after you mitigate. pagerduty the tool that buzzes your phone during on call. runbook a step by step guide for handling a specific alarm or incident. like a recipe. acknowledge telling the paging system you saw the alert. stops it from paging the next person. what you actually do with this daily work: you open the ticketing system every morning. check your team queue. look for new tickets. you triage. what is sev 2 and needs attention now? what is sev 3 and can wait? you work tickets. investigate. mitigate. update. resolve or hand off. you check sla clocks. if a ticket is near sla breach, you prioritize it. on call rotation: once every few weeks (or once a month, depends on team size), it is your turn to be on call. you carry your phone 24/7 that week. you check pagerduty before bed. when an alarm fires, you triage and mitigate. you escalate if stuck. you update the ticket. at the end of your shift, you hand off any open incidents to the next on call. escalation: when you are stuck, you do not struggle alone for hours. you tag a senior se or the dev team in the ticket. you stay as the owner. they consult. you drive the resolution. handoff: when your shift ends, you write clean notes for every open ticket. you tag the next person. you reassign. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. a sev 1 ticket lands in your queue at 2pm. a sev 3 ticket landed at 10am. which do you work first? answer: sev 1. severity beats arrival time. sev 1 is a huge fire. drop everything. 2. you are stuck on a ticket. you tried 3 things, none worked, sla clock is at 80%. what do you do? answer: escalate now. tag a senior se or the dev team in the ticket. stay as owner. do not wait until sla breaches. 3. your on call shift ends at 8am. you have an open incident that is mitigated but not root caused. what do you do? answer: write clean handoff notes. state current status (mitigated, stable). state next step (root cause investigation). tag next on call. reassign ticket. do not just disappear. you have learned: tickets are help requests that live in the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty). queues are your to do list. triage is working in smart order (urgent first). severity tells you how urgent (sev 1 huge, sev 5 tiny). sla is the response time promise (do not break it). on call is your turn to carry the pager and respond to fires 24/7. mitigate first (stop the bleeding), root cause second. escalate when stuck (but stay as owner). handoff cleanly (clean notes for next person). this is the se daily loop. you triage, you mitigate, you escalate, you hand off. over and over. you already did this 5 times earlier in your career. now you do it 50 times a month.","words":2509},{"id":"course-code-review","section":"Course","title":"Code review","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-11--the-code-review-tool-like-github-pull-requests-how-code-gets-checked-before-it-ships\">Module\n11 — the code review tool (like GitHub pull requests): how code gets\nchecked before it ships</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> Before your code becomes real,\na teammate reads it to catch mistakes and teach you the team style.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>You write an essay for school. Before you hand it in, you ask a\nfriend to read it. Your friend finds two spelling mistakes, a confusing\nsentence, and a paragraph that repeats itself. You fix all four things.\nThen you hand in a better essay.</p>\n<p>That is code review. Your friend is the reviewer. The essay is your\ncode change. The fixes you made are the revisions. The spellchecker on\nyour computer is the automated review bot, the robot that finds common\nmistakes automatically.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p>on the job, nobody's code goes live without another engineer reading\nit first. This is called <strong>code review</strong>. The tool a tech\ncompany uses for code review is called <strong>the code review tool\n(like GitHub pull requests)</strong>.</p>\n<p>When you finish writing code, you run a command called\n<code>cr</code>. That creates a <strong>CR</strong> (the code review\nunit). A teammate gets notified. They read your changes. They leave\n<strong>comments</strong> if they see a problem or have a question. You\nfix the issues. You push a new version called a\n<strong>revision</strong>. When the reviewer is happy, they\n<strong>approve</strong>. Then your code can merge and become real.</p>\n<p>Why does this exist? Two reasons. First, two sets of eyes catch what\none misses. Second, it is how you learn your team's style. Every comment\nteaches you something.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, you do two things with code review:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>You create pull requests</strong> when you fix bugs or\nmake small improvements. You want your pull request to land clean and\nfast. That means self-reviewing before you send it out, so the reviewer\nfinds nothing wrong.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You review other people's pull requests</strong>. This is\nhow you learn the codebase. Reading someone else's change forces you to\nunderstand the code they touched. Over time, you become an expert just\nby reviewing.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>If your pull requests always need three revisions before they land,\npeople will think you rush. If your pull requests land clean on revision\n1, people will think you are careful. Reputation builds one CR at a\ntime.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>You write code.</strong> You fix a bug or add a feature.\nYou test it. You commit it to your local git branch.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You run <code>cr -o</code>.</strong> This command creates\na code review. It uploads your changes to the code review tool (like\nGitHub pull requests). It picks a reviewer (usually someone on your\nteam). It sends them a notification.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The reviewer reads your code.</strong> They look at every\nline you changed. They check: does this make sense? Is it safe? Does it\nfollow the team style? Could it break something?</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The reviewer leaves comments.</strong> If they see a\nproblem, they click on the line and type a comment. Examples: \"This\nvariable name is confusing.\" \"What happens if this input is null?\" \"We\nhave a utility function for this already, use that instead.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>You address the comments.</strong> You read each comment.\nYou fix the issue. You run the tests again. You commit the fix. You run\n<code>cr -r</code> to push revision 2.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The reviewer checks revision 2.</strong> If you fixed\neverything, they click <strong>Approve</strong>. If not, they leave more\ncomments. Repeat step 5.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Your CR merges.</strong> Once approved, your change\nbecomes part of the main codebase. Other people can see it and use\nit.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CR</strong></td>\n<td>Code Review. The unit. One change being reviewed. Has an ID like a\npull request.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the code review tool (like GitHub pull\nrequests)</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's code review tool. Like GitHub pull requests.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Reviewer</strong></td>\n<td>The person who reads your code and approves or rejects it.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Revision</strong></td>\n<td>A new version of your pull request after you fix feedback. the first\nrevision is the first version. Rev 2 is after fixes.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Approve</strong></td>\n<td>The reviewer says \"this looks good, it can merge.\"</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Comment</strong></td>\n<td>A note the reviewer leaves on a specific line. You must address\nevery comment.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Self-review</strong></td>\n<td>Reading your own CR before sending it out, to catch mistakes\nearly.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the automated review bot</strong></td>\n<td>A robot reviewer. Checks common issues automatically. Flags things\nlike missing tests or bad variable names.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Merge</strong></td>\n<td>Your change becomes part of the main codebase. Happens after\napproval.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>cr command</strong></td>\n<td>The command-line tool to create and update pull requests.\n<code>cr -o</code> creates. <code>cr -r</code> updates.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<p><strong>When you create a pull request:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Run <code>cr -o</code> after you commit your change.</li>\n<li>Before you send it, do a self-review. Read your own diff. Pretend\nyou are the reviewer. Find issues yourself.</li>\n<li>When the reviewer leaves comments, fix every single one. Reply to\neach comment so they know you read it.</li>\n<li>Aim for revision 1 to be the last revision. Clean pull requests land\nfast. Messy pull requests take three rounds and annoy people.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>When you review someone else's CR:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Read every line they changed. Ask yourself: does this make sense?\nCould it break? Is it simple?</li>\n<li>Leave comments on anything unclear or risky. Be specific. Say what\nis wrong and why.</li>\n<li>If everything looks good, approve.</li>\n<li>Be kind. Your comments teach the other person. Harsh comments make\nthem defensive. Clear helpful comments make them better.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>What is the difference between a pull request and a revision?</li>\n<li>Why do we do code review at all? (Two reasons.)</li>\n<li>You push revision 1 of your pull request. The reviewer leaves five\ncomments. What do you do next?</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Next up:</strong> Module 12 will cover the deployment tool\n(like Spinnaker or Argo CD) and pipelines (how your code actually gets\ndeployed to servers after it merges).</p>\n","text":"module 11 — the code review tool (like github pull requests): how code gets checked before it ships the one line version: before your code becomes real, a teammate reads it to catch mistakes and teach you the team style. picture this (the analogy) you write an essay for school. before you hand it in, you ask a friend to read it. your friend finds two spelling mistakes, a confusing sentence, and a paragraph that repeats itself. you fix all four things. then you hand in a better essay. that is code review. your friend is the reviewer. the essay is your code change. the fixes you made are the revisions. the spellchecker on your computer is the automated review bot, the robot that finds common mistakes automatically. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) on the job, nobody's code goes live without another engineer reading it first. this is called code review . the tool a tech company uses for code review is called the code review tool (like github pull requests) . when you finish writing code, you run a command called cr . that creates a cr (the code review unit). a teammate gets notified. they read your changes. they leave comments if they see a problem or have a question. you fix the issues. you push a new version called a revision . when the reviewer is happy, they approve . then your code can merge and become real. why does this exist? two reasons. first, two sets of eyes catch what one misses. second, it is how you learn your team's style. every comment teaches you something. why you should care as a support engineer, you do two things with code review: 1. you create pull requests when you fix bugs or make small improvements. you want your pull request to land clean and fast. that means self reviewing before you send it out, so the reviewer finds nothing wrong. 2. you review other people's pull requests . this is how you learn the codebase. reading someone else's change forces you to understand the code they touched. over time, you become an expert just by reviewing. if your pull requests always need three revisions before they land, people will think you rush. if your pull requests land clean on revision 1, people will think you are careful. reputation builds one cr at a time. how it works, step by tiny step 1. you write code. you fix a bug or add a feature. you test it. you commit it to your local git branch. 2. you run cr o . this command creates a code review. it uploads your changes to the code review tool (like github pull requests). it picks a reviewer (usually someone on your team). it sends them a notification. 3. the reviewer reads your code. they look at every line you changed. they check: does this make sense? is it safe? does it follow the team style? could it break something? 4. the reviewer leaves comments. if they see a problem, they click on the line and type a comment. examples: \"this variable name is confusing.\" \"what happens if this input is null?\" \"we have a utility function for this already, use that instead.\" 5. you address the comments. you read each comment. you fix the issue. you run the tests again. you commit the fix. you run cr r to push revision 2. 6. the reviewer checks revision 2. if you fixed everything, they click approve . if not, they leave more comments. repeat step 5. 7. your cr merges. once approved, your change becomes part of the main codebase. other people can see it and use it. words you will hear term plain meaning cr code review. the unit. one change being reviewed. has an id like a pull request. the code review tool (like github pull requests) a tech company's code review tool. like github pull requests. reviewer the person who reads your code and approves or rejects it. revision a new version of your pull request after you fix feedback. the first revision is the first version. rev 2 is after fixes. approve the reviewer says \"this looks good, it can merge.\" comment a note the reviewer leaves on a specific line. you must address every comment. self review reading your own cr before sending it out, to catch mistakes early. the automated review bot a robot reviewer. checks common issues automatically. flags things like missing tests or bad variable names. merge your change becomes part of the main codebase. happens after approval. cr command the command line tool to create and update pull requests. cr o creates. cr r updates. what you actually do with this when you create a pull request: 1. run cr o after you commit your change. 2. before you send it, do a self review. read your own diff. pretend you are the reviewer. find issues yourself. 3. when the reviewer leaves comments, fix every single one. reply to each comment so they know you read it. 4. aim for revision 1 to be the last revision. clean pull requests land fast. messy pull requests take three rounds and annoy people. when you review someone else's cr: 1. read every line they changed. ask yourself: does this make sense? could it break? is it simple? 2. leave comments on anything unclear or risky. be specific. say what is wrong and why. 3. if everything looks good, approve. 4. be kind. your comments teach the other person. harsh comments make them defensive. clear helpful comments make them better. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. what is the difference between a pull request and a revision? 2. why do we do code review at all? (two reasons.) 3. you push revision 1 of your pull request. the reviewer leaves five comments. what do you do next? next up: module 12 will cover the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) and pipelines (how your code actually gets deployed to servers after it merges).","words":1120},{"id":"course-the-detective-method-troubleshooting","section":"Course","title":"The detective method: troubleshooting","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-12--the-detective-method-troubleshooting-and-root-cause\">Module\n12 — The detective method: troubleshooting and root cause</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> When something breaks, be a\ndetective who follows clues step-by-step instead of guessing wildly, and\nfind the REAL reason (root cause) not just the symptom you can see.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h3>\n<p>You are a doctor. A patient walks in and says \"my stomach hurts.\"\nThat is the symptom. The hurt is real. But you do not just give them\nstomach medicine and send them home. You ask questions. When did it\nstart? What did you eat today? Have you been sick before? You look at\nevidence (maybe you take their temperature or do a blood test). You make\nONE guess (\"maybe food poisoning from lunch\"). You check if the evidence\nfits that guess. If it does not fit, you make a new guess. You keep\ngoing until you find the ROOT CAUSE (they ate bad chicken). Then you\ntreat the chicken poisoning, not just the stomach ache.</p>\n<p>Or think of a detective solving a crime. The crime is the symptom\n(someone stole the cookies). The detective does not just blame the first\nperson they see. They ask \"what changed today?\" They look at footprints.\nThey follow clues. They try to DISPROVE their own guess (if it was the\ndog, there would be crumbs on the floor, but there are no crumbs, so it\nwas NOT the dog). Eventually they find the real thief (the cat jumped on\nthe counter). That is root cause.</p>\n<p>Troubleshooting in tech is EXACTLY this. A customer says \"the website\nis slow.\" That is the symptom. Your job is detective work to find the\nroot cause.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h3>\n<p>Troubleshooting is the process of finding out WHY something is\nbroken. Root cause is the REAL reason something broke, not just the\nvisible symptom.</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Symptom: website is slow</li>\n<li>Root cause: a database index is missing, so every query scans the\nwhole table</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The symptom is what you see. The root cause is what you fix. If you\nonly treat the symptom (restart the server, it feels faster for 5\nminutes), the problem comes back. If you fix the root cause (add the\nmissing index), the problem is gone forever.</p>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, this is your most important skill. Customers\nreport symptoms. You find root causes. Then you either fix them yourself\n(if it is config or known issue) or you hand the root cause to the dev\nteam with all the evidence so they can fix it fast.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h3>\n<p>Because guessing wastes time and trust.</p>\n<p>If you guess wildly (\"maybe it is DNS, maybe it is the load balancer,\nmaybe it is the moon phase\"), you:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Annoy the customer (they see you flailing)</li>\n<li>Waste hours chasing dead ends</li>\n<li>Never actually fix the problem</li>\n<li>Erode trust (the customer thinks you do not know what you are\ndoing)</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you follow the method, you:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Find the root cause in 20 minutes instead of 3 hours</li>\n<li>Look calm and professional</li>\n<li>Actually fix the thing</li>\n<li>Build trust (the customer sees you are methodical)</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Every senior SE is a detective. Every junior SE who learns this\nmethod BECOMES a senior SE.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h3>\n<p>Here is the method. Use it every single time something breaks.</p>\n<h4 id=\"step-1-understand-the-problem\">Step 1: Understand the\nproblem</h4>\n<p>Ask the customer (or yourself if you are looking at a ticket):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What is broken? (be specific: \"checkout fails\" not \"the site is\nbad\")</li>\n<li>Who is affected? (everyone? one customer? one region?)</li>\n<li>When did it start? (today? last week? always?)</li>\n<li>What changed today? (a deploy? a config change? nothing?)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Write down the answers. Do not skip this. Half the time, \"what\nchanged today\" gives you the root cause immediately.</p>\n<h4 id=\"step-2-make-one-guess-hypothesis\">Step 2: Make ONE guess\n(hypothesis)</h4>\n<p>Based on step 1, make ONE educated guess about the root cause. Not\nfive guesses. One.</p>\n<p>Example: \"I think the deploy that went out this morning broke the\npayment API.\"</p>\n<p>This is your hypothesis. You will test it.</p>\n<h4 id=\"step-3-look-at-evidence\">Step 3: Look at evidence</h4>\n<p>Go find logs, metrics, alarms, anything that can prove or KILL your\nguess.</p>\n<p>For the payment API guess, you would:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Check CloudWatch logs for payment API errors</li>\n<li>Check metrics for latency or error rate spikes</li>\n<li>Check the deploy timeline (did the spike start right after the\ndeploy?)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If the evidence FITS your guess (yes, errors spiked right after the\ndeploy, and the logs show a new exception), your guess is probably\nright. Move to step 4.</p>\n<p>If the evidence does NOT fit (no, errors were happening BEFORE the\ndeploy, or the logs show a totally different error), your guess is\nWRONG. Go back to step 2 and make a new guess.</p>\n<p>The key: try to DISPROVE your own guess. Ask \"if my guess is wrong,\nwhat would I see?\" Look for that. If you find it, your guess is dead.\nMake a new one.</p>\n<h4 id=\"step-4-find-the-real-root-cause\">Step 4: Find the real root\ncause</h4>\n<p>Once you have evidence that fits, dig one level deeper.</p>\n<p>Example: the logs show \"NullPointerException in\nPaymentService.processOrder line 42.\" That is not the root cause yet.\nThat is still a symptom. Go look at line 42. You see the code expects a\ndatabase field that is NULL. Why is it NULL? You check the database. You\nsee a new migration ran today that added a column but did not backfill\nold rows. THAT is the root cause.</p>\n<p>Root cause is the FIRST thing in the chain that went wrong. If you\nfix it, everything downstream is fixed too.</p>\n<h4 id=\"step-5-mitigate-first-stop-the-pain\">Step 5: Mitigate first\n(stop the pain)</h4>\n<p>Before you fix the root cause (which might take hours), STOP THE\nBLEEDING.</p>\n<p>Mitigation means: make the customer pain go away NOW, even if the fix\nis temporary.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Roll back the deploy that broke things</li>\n<li>Restart the stuck service</li>\n<li>Turn off a bad feature flag</li>\n<li>Route traffic to a backup region</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Mitigation is NOT a permanent fix. It is a band-aid. But it stops\ncustomers from screaming while you work on the real fix.</p>\n<h4 id=\"step-6-fix-the-root-cause\">Step 6: Fix the root cause</h4>\n<p>Now fix the REAL problem.</p>\n<p>Example: write a script to backfill the NULL database rows. Deploy\nthe script. Verify the NULLs are gone. The payment API works again.</p>\n<p>This is the permanent fix. Once it is done, you can UNDO the\nmitigation (if you rolled back a deploy, you can re-deploy the new\nversion now that the database is fixed).</p>\n<h4 id=\"step-7-prevent-it-from-happening-again\">Step 7: Prevent it from\nhappening again</h4>\n<p>Add an alarm or update a runbook so next time this breaks, you catch\nit faster.</p>\n<p>Example: add a CloudWatch alarm that fires if payment API error rate\ngoes above 1%. Now if this breaks again, you know in 2 minutes instead\nof 2 hours.</p>\n<p>Or write a runbook that says \"if payment API is down, check for NULL\norder_status in the database first.\" Next time, the on-call person finds\nthe root cause in 5 minutes.</p>\n<p>This is how you turn incidents into learning. The same problem never\nburns you twice.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"a-tiny-worked-example\">A tiny worked example</h3>\n<p>Let me walk you through a real example, smallest steps.</p>\n<p><strong>Symptom:</strong> the time-tracking service website is slow.\nCustomers complain it takes 30 seconds to load their schedule.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 1 - Understand:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>What is broken? Schedule page loads slowly</li>\n<li>Who is affected? Only UK customers</li>\n<li>When did it start? This morning at 9am UTC</li>\n<li>What changed? A deploy went out at 8:45am UTC</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Step 2 - Make a guess:</strong> \"I think the deploy broke\nsomething for UK customers.\"</p>\n<p><strong>Step 3 - Look at evidence:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Check CloudWatch logs for the schedule API, filter by UK region</li>\n<li>See logs show \"TimeoutException: DynamoDB query timed out after\n5000ms\"</li>\n<li>Check CloudWatch metrics: DynamoDB read latency for the UK table\nspiked at 9am, right after the deploy</li>\n<li>Check the deploy diff: a new index was added to the UK table, but\nthe query is NOT using the new index (it is still doing a full table\nscan)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Evidence FITS the guess. The deploy added an index but the code is\nnot using it yet.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 4 - Root cause:</strong> The root cause is: the deploy\nadded a DynamoDB index (which is good) but forgot to update the query\ncode to USE the index. So the query still scans the whole table, which\nis slow.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 5 - Mitigate:</strong> Roll back the deploy. Schedule\npage is fast again. UK customers are happy.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 6 - Fix root:</strong> Update the query code to use the\nnew index. Deploy the fix. Verify the query uses the index and is fast.\nNow re-deploy the original change (with the index AND the query\nfix).</p>\n<p><strong>Step 7 - Prevent:</strong> Add a CloudWatch alarm: if\nDynamoDB read latency for UK table goes above 1000ms, fire an alarm. Add\na runbook note: \"if schedule API is slow, check if queries are using the\nright DynamoDB index.\"</p>\n<p>Done. You followed the method. You found the root cause. You fixed\nit. You prevented it from happening again. That is detective work.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h3>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Symptom</strong></td>\n<td>The visible problem the customer sees (the site is slow, checkout\nfails, page shows error)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Root cause</strong></td>\n<td>The REAL reason something broke (the first domino that fell, the\nbroken database migration, the missing index, the bad config)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Hypothesis</strong></td>\n<td>Your educated guess about the root cause; you test this with\nevidence</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mitigation</strong></td>\n<td>A temporary fix to stop customer pain NOW (rollback, restart, turn\noff feature flag); buys time for permanent fix</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Evidence</strong></td>\n<td>Logs, metrics, alarms, anything concrete that proves or disproves\nyour guess</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Disprove</strong></td>\n<td>Try to prove yourself WRONG; if you cannot disprove your guess, it\nis probably right</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>What changed today</strong></td>\n<td>The single most powerful troubleshooting question; 80% of production\nissues are caused by something that changed today (a deploy, a config, a\ntraffic spike)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Rollback</strong></td>\n<td>Undo a deploy or config change; go back to the previous version that\nwas working</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Runbook</strong></td>\n<td>A step-by-step guide for handling a specific issue; saves time when\nthe same thing breaks again</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h3>\n<p>When a ticket lands on your desk:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Read the symptom from the customer</li>\n<li>Ask \"what changed today?\" (check deploys, configs, traffic\npatterns)</li>\n<li>Make ONE guess about the root cause</li>\n<li>Go look at CloudWatch logs and metrics to test your guess</li>\n<li>If your guess is wrong, make a new guess and test again</li>\n<li>Once you find the root cause, mitigate first (rollback / restart /\nturn off) to stop customer pain</li>\n<li>Then fix the root permanently</li>\n<li>Add an alarm or runbook so next time is faster</li>\n<li>Document the root cause in the ticket so the team learns</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This is the loop. You do this 10 times a day as an SE. It becomes\nmuscle memory.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h3>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h3 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>What is the difference between a symptom and a root cause? (Symptom\nis what you see; root cause is the FIRST thing that went wrong)</li>\n<li>Why do we mitigate BEFORE fixing the root cause? (To stop customer\npain NOW while we work on the permanent fix)</li>\n<li>What is the most powerful question in troubleshooting? (\"What\nchanged today?\" — because most production issues are caused by something\nthat changed today)</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you can answer those, you got it. You are a detective now.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Next up:</strong> Module 13 will teach you how to write a\nrunbook so the NEXT person (or future you) can fix the same issue in 5\nminutes instead of 5 hours.</p>\n","text":"module 12 — the detective method: troubleshooting and root cause the one line version: when something breaks, be a detective who follows clues step by step instead of guessing wildly, and find the real reason (root cause) not just the symptom you can see. picture this (the analogy) you are a doctor. a patient walks in and says \"my stomach hurts.\" that is the symptom. the hurt is real. but you do not just give them stomach medicine and send them home. you ask questions. when did it start? what did you eat today? have you been sick before? you look at evidence (maybe you take their temperature or do a blood test). you make one guess (\"maybe food poisoning from lunch\"). you check if the evidence fits that guess. if it does not fit, you make a new guess. you keep going until you find the root cause (they ate bad chicken). then you treat the chicken poisoning, not just the stomach ache. or think of a detective solving a crime. the crime is the symptom (someone stole the cookies). the detective does not just blame the first person they see. they ask \"what changed today?\" they look at footprints. they follow clues. they try to disprove their own guess (if it was the dog, there would be crumbs on the floor, but there are no crumbs, so it was not the dog). eventually they find the real thief (the cat jumped on the counter). that is root cause. troubleshooting in tech is exactly this. a customer says \"the website is slow.\" that is the symptom. your job is detective work to find the root cause. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) troubleshooting is the process of finding out why something is broken. root cause is the real reason something broke, not just the visible symptom. example: symptom: website is slow root cause: a database index is missing, so every query scans the whole table the symptom is what you see. the root cause is what you fix. if you only treat the symptom (restart the server, it feels faster for 5 minutes), the problem comes back. if you fix the root cause (add the missing index), the problem is gone forever. as a support engineer, this is your most important skill. customers report symptoms. you find root causes. then you either fix them yourself (if it is config or known issue) or you hand the root cause to the dev team with all the evidence so they can fix it fast. why you should care because guessing wastes time and trust. if you guess wildly (\"maybe it is dns, maybe it is the load balancer, maybe it is the moon phase\"), you: 1. annoy the customer (they see you flailing) 2. waste hours chasing dead ends 3. never actually fix the problem 4. erode trust (the customer thinks you do not know what you are doing) if you follow the method, you: 1. find the root cause in 20 minutes instead of 3 hours 2. look calm and professional 3. actually fix the thing 4. build trust (the customer sees you are methodical) every senior se is a detective. every junior se who learns this method becomes a senior se. how it works, step by tiny step here is the method. use it every single time something breaks. step 1: understand the problem ask the customer (or yourself if you are looking at a ticket): what is broken? (be specific: \"checkout fails\" not \"the site is bad\") who is affected? (everyone? one customer? one region?) when did it start? (today? last week? always?) what changed today? (a deploy? a config change? nothing?) write down the answers. do not skip this. half the time, \"what changed today\" gives you the root cause immediately. step 2: make one guess (hypothesis) based on step 1, make one educated guess about the root cause. not five guesses. one. example: \"i think the deploy that went out this morning broke the payment api.\" this is your hypothesis. you will test it. step 3: look at evidence go find logs, metrics, alarms, anything that can prove or kill your guess. for the payment api guess, you would: check cloudwatch logs for payment api errors check metrics for latency or error rate spikes check the deploy timeline (did the spike start right after the deploy?) if the evidence fits your guess (yes, errors spiked right after the deploy, and the logs show a new exception), your guess is probably right. move to step 4. if the evidence does not fit (no, errors were happening before the deploy, or the logs show a totally different error), your guess is wrong. go back to step 2 and make a new guess. the key: try to disprove your own guess. ask \"if my guess is wrong, what would i see?\" look for that. if you find it, your guess is dead. make a new one. step 4: find the real root cause once you have evidence that fits, dig one level deeper. example: the logs show \"nullpointerexception in paymentservice.processorder line 42.\" that is not the root cause yet. that is still a symptom. go look at line 42. you see the code expects a database field that is null. why is it null? you check the database. you see a new migration ran today that added a column but did not backfill old rows. that is the root cause. root cause is the first thing in the chain that went wrong. if you fix it, everything downstream is fixed too. step 5: mitigate first (stop the pain) before you fix the root cause (which might take hours), stop the bleeding. mitigation means: make the customer pain go away now, even if the fix is temporary. examples: roll back the deploy that broke things restart the stuck service turn off a bad feature flag route traffic to a backup region mitigation is not a permanent fix. it is a band aid. but it stops customers from screaming while you work on the real fix. step 6: fix the root cause now fix the real problem. example: write a script to backfill the null database rows. deploy the script. verify the nulls are gone. the payment api works again. this is the permanent fix. once it is done, you can undo the mitigation (if you rolled back a deploy, you can re deploy the new version now that the database is fixed). step 7: prevent it from happening again add an alarm or update a runbook so next time this breaks, you catch it faster. example: add a cloudwatch alarm that fires if payment api error rate goes above 1%. now if this breaks again, you know in 2 minutes instead of 2 hours. or write a runbook that says \"if payment api is down, check for null order status in the database first.\" next time, the on call person finds the root cause in 5 minutes. this is how you turn incidents into learning. the same problem never burns you twice. a tiny worked example let me walk you through a real example, smallest steps. symptom: the time tracking service website is slow. customers complain it takes 30 seconds to load their schedule. step 1 understand: what is broken? schedule page loads slowly who is affected? only uk customers when did it start? this morning at 9am utc what changed? a deploy went out at 8:45am utc step 2 make a guess: \"i think the deploy broke something for uk customers.\" step 3 look at evidence: check cloudwatch logs for the schedule api, filter by uk region see logs show \"timeoutexception: dynamodb query timed out after 5000ms\" check cloudwatch metrics: dynamodb read latency for the uk table spiked at 9am, right after the deploy check the deploy diff: a new index was added to the uk table, but the query is not using the new index (it is still doing a full table scan) evidence fits the guess. the deploy added an index but the code is not using it yet. step 4 root cause: the root cause is: the deploy added a dynamodb index (which is good) but forgot to update the query code to use the index. so the query still scans the whole table, which is slow. step 5 mitigate: roll back the deploy. schedule page is fast again. uk customers are happy. step 6 fix root: update the query code to use the new index. deploy the fix. verify the query uses the index and is fast. now re deploy the original change (with the index and the query fix). step 7 prevent: add a cloudwatch alarm: if dynamodb read latency for uk table goes above 1000ms, fire an alarm. add a runbook note: \"if schedule api is slow, check if queries are using the right dynamodb index.\" done. you followed the method. you found the root cause. you fixed it. you prevented it from happening again. that is detective work. words you will hear term plain meaning symptom the visible problem the customer sees (the site is slow, checkout fails, page shows error) root cause the real reason something broke (the first domino that fell, the broken database migration, the missing index, the bad config) hypothesis your educated guess about the root cause; you test this with evidence mitigation a temporary fix to stop customer pain now (rollback, restart, turn off feature flag); buys time for permanent fix evidence logs, metrics, alarms, anything concrete that proves or disproves your guess disprove try to prove yourself wrong; if you cannot disprove your guess, it is probably right what changed today the single most powerful troubleshooting question; 80% of production issues are caused by something that changed today (a deploy, a config, a traffic spike) rollback undo a deploy or config change; go back to the previous version that was working runbook a step by step guide for handling a specific issue; saves time when the same thing breaks again what you actually do with this when a ticket lands on your desk: 1. read the symptom from the customer 2. ask \"what changed today?\" (check deploys, configs, traffic patterns) 3. make one guess about the root cause 4. go look at cloudwatch logs and metrics to test your guess 5. if your guess is wrong, make a new guess and test again 6. once you find the root cause, mitigate first (rollback / restart / turn off) to stop customer pain 7. then fix the root permanently 8. add an alarm or runbook so next time is faster 9. document the root cause in the ticket so the team learns this is the loop. you do this 10 times a day as an se. it becomes muscle memory. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. what is the difference between a symptom and a root cause? (symptom is what you see; root cause is the first thing that went wrong) 2. why do we mitigate before fixing the root cause? (to stop customer pain now while we work on the permanent fix) 3. what is the most powerful question in troubleshooting? (\"what changed today?\" — because most production issues are caused by something that changed today) if you can answer those, you got it. you are a detective now. next up: module 13 will teach you how to write a runbook so the next person (or future you) can fix the same issue in 5 minutes instead of 5 hours.","words":2071},{"id":"course-writing-coes-runbooks","section":"Course","title":"Writing: COEs & runbooks","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-13--writing-like-a-tech-company-coes-runbooks-and-clear-words\">Module\n13 — Writing like a tech company: COEs, runbooks, and clear words</h1>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> A tech company runs on\ndocuments, not slides. The two you will write most are runbooks\n(step-by-step fix recipes) and COEs (blame-free reports after something\nbroke).</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>Your home router stops working at midnight. You are tired. You walk\nto the box on the wall. Taped to it is a laminated card that says:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Unplug the black cable</li>\n<li>Wait 30 seconds</li>\n<li>Plug it back in</li>\n<li>Green light means good. Red light? Call this number.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>That card is a runbook. Someone who fixed this 100 times wrote it so\nyou, tired and frustrated, can fix it without thinking.</p>\n<p>Now imagine a plane nearly crashes. The investigation team writes a\ncareful report. What happened minute by minute. Why the warning light\ndid not work. What the pilot did. What the airline will change so this\nnever happens again. No one gets blamed. The system gets fixed.</p>\n<p>That report is a COE.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p>A tech company runs on writing. No PowerPoint. Documents. Clear,\nshort, data-heavy documents.</p>\n<p>A <strong>runbook</strong> is a step-by-step guide for fixing a known\nproblem. It assumes you are tired, maybe on call at 2am, maybe new to\nthe system. It holds your hand. It gives you the exact commands to type.\nIt tells you what output means good and what means bad. It does the\nthinking for you.</p>\n<p>A <strong>COE</strong> (Correction of Errors) is the official report\nafter a serious incident. A service went down. Customers could not buy\nthings. An alarm did not fire. The COE answers: what broke, when, why,\nwhat we are changing so it never breaks that way again. It is BLAMELESS.\nYou blame the process, not the person. If someone made a mistake, you\nask why the system let them make it.</p>\n<p>Both follow a tech company's core writing rules:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Clear beats clever</li>\n<li>Data beats adjectives (say \"dropped from 800ms to 420ms\", not \"got\nway faster\")</li>\n<li>Active voice (say \"the alarm fired\", not \"the alarm was fired\")</li>\n<li>Short sentences</li>\n<li>Say it once and stop</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, you will write runbooks for every repeating\nproblem you solve. If you fix the same thing twice, the second time you\nwrite the runbook so the next person (or you in six months) can fix it\nin three minutes instead of three hours.</p>\n<p>You will read COEs when trying to understand why something broke. You\nmay help write a COE after a Sev-2 incident. The COE is how the team\nlearns. It is how a tech company turns pain into process.</p>\n<p>Writing clear documents is how you show Earn Trust. A good runbook\nsaves the on-call engineer's night. A good COE prevents the next\noutage.</p>\n<p>A tech company promotes people who write well. The six-pager matters\nmore than the code sometimes.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<h3 id=\"writing-a-runbook-8-steps\">Writing a runbook (8 steps)</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>Pick the problem.</strong> Something that repeats. Not a\none-time weird thing. Example: \"Pipeline stuck in staging for 2+\nhours.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Write the title.</strong> Clear. \"How to unblock staging\ndeploy after timeout.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Write the symptoms.</strong> What does the on-call person\nsee? \"Pipeline shows BLOCKED. Alarm StageFailed fires. CloudWatch logs\nshow SocketTimeoutException.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Write the fix steps.</strong> Numbered. Exact commands.\nExample output after each step. \"1. Open pipeline console. 2. Click\nRetry Stage. 3. If it works, green light appears in 5 min. If it fails\nagain, go to step 5.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Add decision points.</strong> What if step 3 fails? Give\nthem the next path. Never leave them stuck.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Link to context.</strong> Where are the logs? What wiki\nexplains the pipeline? Give URLs.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Test it.</strong> Have someone who has never seen this\nproblem try to follow your runbook. If they get confused, rewrite that\nstep.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Keep it updated.</strong> When the system changes, update\nthe runbook the same day.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"writing-a-coe-6-steps\">Writing a COE (6 steps)</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>State what broke.</strong> One sentence. \"On May 15,\n2026, customers in UK could not submit time-off requests for 47\nminutes.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Write the timeline.</strong> Minute by minute. What\nhappened when. Use UTC timestamps. Be factual, not dramatic. \"14:32 UTC:\ndeployment started. 14:38 UTC: first customer error logged. 14:41 UTC:\nalarm fired. 14:50 UTC: rollback initiated.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Find the root cause.</strong> Use the 5 Whys. Keep asking\nwhy until you hit the real system failure. Example: \"Why did it break?\nDatabase timed out. Why? New query had no index. Why? Code reviewer\nmissed it. Why? Review checklist does not include query performance\ncheck. Why? We added the query type last month and did not update the\nchecklist.\" The root cause: outdated checklist. Not the developer who\nwrote the query.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>List action items.</strong> Concrete changes. Who owns\neach. Deadline. Example: \"Add query review to checklist. Owner: Alice.\nDone by: June 1.\" \"Add alarm for query latency &gt;500ms. Owner: Bob.\nDone by: June 5.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Mark it blameless.</strong> No person names in the \"what\nwent wrong\" section. Say \"the deployment process lacked a rollback\ngate\", not \"Alice deployed without checking.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Get it reviewed.</strong> Your manager reads it. The team\nreads it. If there is a better root cause, they will catch it.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Runbook</strong></td>\n<td>Step-by-step recipe for fixing a known problem, written for a tired\nperson at 2am</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>COE</strong> (Correction of Errors)</td>\n<td>Official blame-free report after an incident: what broke, why, how\nwe prevent it next time</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Blameless</strong></td>\n<td>You blame the system or process, never the person. \"The checklist\nwas missing X\" not \"Alice forgot X\"</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Root cause</strong></td>\n<td>The real underlying reason, found by asking \"why\" 5+ times until you\ncannot go deeper</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>5 Whys</strong></td>\n<td>Keep asking \"why did that happen\" until you reach the system\nfailure, not the symptom</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Active voice</strong></td>\n<td>Subject does the action. \"The alarm fired\" not \"The alarm was\nfired\"</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Working Backwards</strong></td>\n<td>Start from what the customer/reader needs, then write the doc to\nserve that need</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>PR/FAQ</strong> (Press Release / FAQ)</td>\n<td>A document format used early in product design. You rarely write\nthis as an SE, but you may read one</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Six-pager</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's standard long-form narrative document, max 6 pages.\nUsed for proposals, deep dives, reviews</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Writing Hub</strong></td>\n<td>Internal wiki with writing guides: your team's internal docs</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<p><strong>Week 1 on the job:</strong> Read 3 runbooks for common issues\non your team. Notice the pattern. Clear title. Symptoms. Numbered steps.\nLinks.</p>\n<p><strong>First repeating problem you solve:</strong> Write the runbook\nsame day. Paste it in your team wiki. Link it in the ticket. Ask your\nmanager to review it.</p>\n<p><strong>First Sev-2 you participate in:</strong> You may be asked to\nhelp write the timeline section of the COE. Practice being factual and\nblameless.</p>\n<p><strong>Every document you write:</strong> Use short sentences. Use\ndata not adjectives. Active voice. Read it out loud. If it sounds like a\nrobot, rewrite it.</p>\n<p><strong>When you need help:</strong> your team's internal docs has\ntemplates, examples, and rules. your team's internal docs explains the\n\"start from the customer\" philosophy.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>You are on call. A pipeline breaks. You follow a runbook.\nStep 4 says \"click Retry\" but the button is grayed out. The runbook has\nno \"what if the button is gray\" path. What do you do?</strong> Escalate\nto your manager or the next on-call tier. Then, after the incident,\nupdate the runbook to add the missing decision branch.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>A COE draft says \"The outage happened because Sarah\ndeployed without running tests.\" Is this blameless? How would you\nrewrite it?</strong> Not blameless. Rewrite: \"The outage happened\nbecause the deployment pipeline did not enforce a test-passing gate.\"\nFocus on the missing process, not the person.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>What is the 5 Whys technique, and when do you use\nit?</strong> Keep asking \"why did that happen\" until you reach the real\nsystem failure. Use it when writing the root cause section of a\nCOE.</p></li>\n</ol>\n","text":"module 13 — writing like a tech company: coes, runbooks, and clear words the one line version: a tech company runs on documents, not slides. the two you will write most are runbooks (step by step fix recipes) and coes (blame free reports after something broke). picture this (the analogy) your home router stops working at midnight. you are tired. you walk to the box on the wall. taped to it is a laminated card that says: 1. unplug the black cable 2. wait 30 seconds 3. plug it back in 4. green light means good. red light? call this number. that card is a runbook. someone who fixed this 100 times wrote it so you, tired and frustrated, can fix it without thinking. now imagine a plane nearly crashes. the investigation team writes a careful report. what happened minute by minute. why the warning light did not work. what the pilot did. what the airline will change so this never happens again. no one gets blamed. the system gets fixed. that report is a coe. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) a tech company runs on writing. no powerpoint. documents. clear, short, data heavy documents. a runbook is a step by step guide for fixing a known problem. it assumes you are tired, maybe on call at 2am, maybe new to the system. it holds your hand. it gives you the exact commands to type. it tells you what output means good and what means bad. it does the thinking for you. a coe (correction of errors) is the official report after a serious incident. a service went down. customers could not buy things. an alarm did not fire. the coe answers: what broke, when, why, what we are changing so it never breaks that way again. it is blameless. you blame the process, not the person. if someone made a mistake, you ask why the system let them make it. both follow a tech company's core writing rules: clear beats clever data beats adjectives (say \"dropped from 800ms to 420ms\", not \"got way faster\") active voice (say \"the alarm fired\", not \"the alarm was fired\") short sentences say it once and stop why you should care as a support engineer, you will write runbooks for every repeating problem you solve. if you fix the same thing twice, the second time you write the runbook so the next person (or you in six months) can fix it in three minutes instead of three hours. you will read coes when trying to understand why something broke. you may help write a coe after a sev 2 incident. the coe is how the team learns. it is how a tech company turns pain into process. writing clear documents is how you show earn trust. a good runbook saves the on call engineer's night. a good coe prevents the next outage. a tech company promotes people who write well. the six pager matters more than the code sometimes. how it works, step by tiny step writing a runbook (8 steps) 1. pick the problem. something that repeats. not a one time weird thing. example: \"pipeline stuck in staging for 2+ hours.\" 2. write the title. clear. \"how to unblock staging deploy after timeout.\" 3. write the symptoms. what does the on call person see? \"pipeline shows blocked. alarm stagefailed fires. cloudwatch logs show sockettimeoutexception.\" 4. write the fix steps. numbered. exact commands. example output after each step. \"1. open pipeline console. 2. click retry stage. 3. if it works, green light appears in 5 min. if it fails again, go to step 5.\" 5. add decision points. what if step 3 fails? give them the next path. never leave them stuck. 6. link to context. where are the logs? what wiki explains the pipeline? give urls. 7. test it. have someone who has never seen this problem try to follow your runbook. if they get confused, rewrite that step. 8. keep it updated. when the system changes, update the runbook the same day. writing a coe (6 steps) 1. state what broke. one sentence. \"on may 15, 2026, customers in uk could not submit time off requests for 47 minutes.\" 2. write the timeline. minute by minute. what happened when. use utc timestamps. be factual, not dramatic. \"14:32 utc: deployment started. 14:38 utc: first customer error logged. 14:41 utc: alarm fired. 14:50 utc: rollback initiated.\" 3. find the root cause. use the 5 whys. keep asking why until you hit the real system failure. example: \"why did it break? database timed out. why? new query had no index. why? code reviewer missed it. why? review checklist does not include query performance check. why? we added the query type last month and did not update the checklist.\" the root cause: outdated checklist. not the developer who wrote the query. 4. list action items. concrete changes. who owns each. deadline. example: \"add query review to checklist. owner: alice. done by: june 1.\" \"add alarm for query latency 500ms. owner: bob. done by: june 5.\" 5. mark it blameless. no person names in the \"what went wrong\" section. say \"the deployment process lacked a rollback gate\", not \"alice deployed without checking.\" 6. get it reviewed. your manager reads it. the team reads it. if there is a better root cause, they will catch it. words you will hear term plain meaning runbook step by step recipe for fixing a known problem, written for a tired person at 2am coe (correction of errors) official blame free report after an incident: what broke, why, how we prevent it next time blameless you blame the system or process, never the person. \"the checklist was missing x\" not \"alice forgot x\" root cause the real underlying reason, found by asking \"why\" 5+ times until you cannot go deeper 5 whys keep asking \"why did that happen\" until you reach the system failure, not the symptom active voice subject does the action. \"the alarm fired\" not \"the alarm was fired\" working backwards start from what the customer/reader needs, then write the doc to serve that need pr/faq (press release / faq) a document format used early in product design. you rarely write this as an se, but you may read one six pager a tech company's standard long form narrative document, max 6 pages. used for proposals, deep dives, reviews writing hub internal wiki with writing guides: your team's internal docs what you actually do with this week 1 on the job: read 3 runbooks for common issues on your team. notice the pattern. clear title. symptoms. numbered steps. links. first repeating problem you solve: write the runbook same day. paste it in your team wiki. link it in the ticket. ask your manager to review it. first sev 2 you participate in: you may be asked to help write the timeline section of the coe. practice being factual and blameless. every document you write: use short sentences. use data not adjectives. active voice. read it out loud. if it sounds like a robot, rewrite it. when you need help: your team's internal docs has templates, examples, and rules. your team's internal docs explains the \"start from the customer\" philosophy. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. you are on call. a pipeline breaks. you follow a runbook. step 4 says \"click retry\" but the button is grayed out. the runbook has no \"what if the button is gray\" path. what do you do? escalate to your manager or the next on call tier. then, after the incident, update the runbook to add the missing decision branch. 2. a coe draft says \"the outage happened because sarah deployed without running tests.\" is this blameless? how would you rewrite it? not blameless. rewrite: \"the outage happened because the deployment pipeline did not enforce a test passing gate.\" focus on the missing process, not the person. 3. what is the 5 whys technique, and when do you use it? keep asking \"why did that happen\" until you reach the real system failure. use it when writing the root cause section of a coe.","words":1459},{"id":"course-leadership-principles","section":"Course","title":"Leadership Principles","html":"<h2 id=\"module-14--the-house-rules-leadership-principles\">Module 14 —\nThe house rules: Leadership Principles</h2>\n<p><strong>The one-line version:</strong> A tech company's Leadership\nPrinciples are the shared behavior rules everyone actually uses, not\njust a poster on the wall.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h3>\n<p>Imagine a big family house with 10 people living in it. The house has\nrules: clean up your own mess, help anyone who needs it, fix things when\nthey break instead of walking past them, speak up if something looks\nwrong. These rules are written down. But more important, everyone USES\nthem. When someone leaves dirty dishes, another person says \"hey, we\nagreed to clean up.\" When a pipe leaks, people do not say \"that is not\nmy room,\" they grab a bucket and call a plumber.</p>\n<p>A tech company's Leadership Principles are like those house rules.\nThey tell you what good behavior looks like. Everyone knows them. People\nuse them in hiring, in reviews, and when they decide what to do every\nday.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h3>\n<p>A tech company has 16 Leadership Principles, but you call them LPs\nfor short. They are statements like \"Customer Obsession\" and \"Ownership\"\nand \"Dive Deep.\" Each one describes a way to think or act that a tech\ncompany values.</p>\n<p>When you interview on the job, interviewers ask you questions that\nmap to specific LPs. When your manager writes your review, they cite\nwhich LPs you showed. When you are deciding how to handle a ticket, you\nuse the LPs to guide you. For example, if a customer is stuck, you think\n\"Customer Obsession says I put the customer pain first,\" and you\nprioritize that ticket over something less urgent.</p>\n<p>The LPs are not just corporate fluff. People really use them. You\nwill hear coworkers say things like \"that is very Ownership\" or \"let us\nDive Deep on this.\"</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h3>\n<p>As a Support Engineer, you will be judged on how well you demonstrate\nthe LPs. Your manager will look for LP evidence in your work. Your\nteammates will respect you more if you act like the LPs say. Your own\ndecisions get easier when you have a shared framework.</p>\n<p>Also, when you interview for your next role (SE2, SE3, maybe to a\ndevelopment role), the interviewer will ask for STAR stories that show\nLPs. If you do not know the LPs, you cannot tell those stories well.</p>\n<p>The LPs are the common language. Learn them now, practice them every\nday, and your career moves faster.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h3>\n<p>There are 16 total LPs. As an SE, you care MOST about these six:</p>\n<p><strong>1. Customer Obsession</strong> Start with the customer and\nwork backwards. Always think: what is the customer feeling right now? If\na ticket says \"this has been broken for 3 days,\" that customer is\nfrustrated. You put that ticket high on your list because the customer\npain is high. You do not say \"well, it is just a config issue, no big\ndeal.\" To the customer, it IS a big deal.</p>\n<p><strong>2. Ownership</strong> Act like the problem is yours until it\nis solved, even if someone else code broke. You do not say \"that is not\nmy team\" and close the ticket. You find the right owner, hand it off\ncleanly, and check back to make sure it closed. If the customer is still\nstuck, it is still your problem.</p>\n<p><strong>3. Dive Deep</strong> Dig past the surface to find the real\ncause. A ticket says \"API times out.\" You do not just restart the\nservice and close. You look at logs, check metrics, find the slow query,\nunderstand WHY it slowed down. The surface symptom is the timeout. The\nroot cause might be a missing index or a bad config or a code bug. You\nfind the root.</p>\n<p><strong>4. Bias for Action</strong> When there is a fire, act fast\nwith the info you have. Do not freeze waiting for perfect data. If a\nprod alarm is firing and you see the service is down, you restart it\nNOW, then you investigate why. Speed matters. Reversible decisions are\ncheap. If you can undo it, just do it.</p>\n<p><strong>5. Insist on Highest Standards</strong> Keep things clean.\nFix the root, do not accept \"it has always been broken.\" If you see a\nrecurring ticket pattern, you file a bug to fix it permanently instead\nof manually solving it every week. High standards means you do not let\njank pile up.</p>\n<p><strong>6. Earn Trust</strong> Be honest. Admit when you do not know.\nFollow through on what you promise. If you tell a customer \"I will\nupdate you by end of day,\" you do it. Trust is built in small actions\nover time.</p>\n<p>The other 10 LPs matter too, but less directly for an SE role. You\nwill hear: Are Right A Lot (make good calls, seek diverse input), Learn\nand Be Curious (always learning), Invent and Simplify (make things\neasier), Frugality (do more with less), Deliver Results (ship on time).\nKnow they exist. Focus your daily energy on the top 6.</p>\n<p><strong>7. How to tell LP stories: STAR</strong></p>\n<p>When you interview or write a self-review, you tell work stories in\nSTAR format:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>S</strong>ituation: what was the context?</li>\n<li><strong>T</strong>ask: what did you need to do?</li>\n<li><strong>A</strong>ction: what did YOU do? (This is the LP\nproof.)</li>\n<li><strong>R</strong>esult: what happened because of your action?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Example STAR for Dive Deep: <strong>Situation:</strong> A customer\nticket said their cron job failed every morning. <strong>Task:</strong>\nI needed to figure out why. <strong>Action:</strong> I pulled logs,\nfound a timeout on a downstream API, checked that API CloudWatch\nmetrics, discovered the database was hitting max connections at 6 AM\nevery day. <strong>Result:</strong> I worked with the DB team to\nincrease the connection pool. The cron job has run clean for 2\nweeks.</p>\n<p>That story shows Dive Deep because you went deeper than \"cron job\nfails\" to find the actual root cause. You do the work first. Then you\ntell the story in STAR shape later.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h3>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>LP</strong></td>\n<td>Leadership Principle, one of the 16 house rules</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Customer Obsession</strong></td>\n<td>Always put the customer pain first</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Ownership</strong></td>\n<td>It is your problem until solved, even if not your code</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dive Deep</strong></td>\n<td>Dig to the real cause, not just the surface symptom</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Bias for Action</strong></td>\n<td>Act fast when needed, do not freeze</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Highest Standards</strong></td>\n<td>Fix the root, do not accept jank</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Earn Trust</strong></td>\n<td>Be honest, follow through, admit mistakes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>STAR</strong></td>\n<td>Situation Task Action Result, the shape of a work story</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>LP signal</strong></td>\n<td>Evidence that you showed a specific LP</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Demonstrate an LP</strong></td>\n<td>You DO the behavior, then you tell the story</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h3>\n<p><strong>Every day:</strong> When you pick up a ticket, ask: what does\nCustomer Obsession say? Put yourself in the customer shoes. When you\nclose a ticket, ask: did I fix the root (Highest Standards) or just the\nsymptom? When you are stuck, ask: Bias for Action says act, Dive Deep\nsays investigate. Which matters more right now?</p>\n<p><strong>In reviews:</strong> Your manager will look for LP evidence.\nWrite your accomplishments in STAR format with the LP named. Example:\n\"Demonstrated Ownership by taking over ticket a ticket even though it\nwas filed against another team, found the right owner, and verified the\nfix deployed.\"</p>\n<p><strong>In interviews:</strong> Prepare 2-3 STAR stories per LP. The\ninterviewer will say \"tell me about a time you showed Ownership.\" You\ntell your STAR. Short situation, clear task, detailed action (you did X,\nyou did Y), concrete result (the customer was unblocked, the issue\nstopped recurring).</p>\n<p><strong>Daily habit:</strong> After you close a big ticket, write\ndown the STAR in a notes file. Do not wait until review time to\nremember. You will forget details. Capture it fresh.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h3>\n<p>If you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel\nfamiliar. You have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped\ncode through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. What\nshifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features,\nmore time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. You are\nbuilding on a foundation, not starting from zero.</p>\n<h3 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p>A ticket says \"my report is wrong.\" You restart the service and\nthe report looks better. The customer closes the ticket. Did you\ndemonstrate Highest Standards? (Answer: No. You fixed the symptom, not\nthe root. Highest Standards says find WHY the report was wrong, fix\nthat, so it does not break again.)</p></li>\n<li><p>You are writing your self-review. You want to show Dive Deep. You\nwrite \"I investigated many tickets.\" Is that a STAR story? (Answer: No.\nThat is too vague. STAR needs a specific situation, a specific task,\nspecific actions you took, and a concrete result.)</p></li>\n<li><p>A customer ticket lands in your queue, but the broken service is\nowned by another team. What does Ownership say you do? (Answer: You do\nnot close it with \"not my team.\" You find the right owner, hand it off\nwith full context, check back to make sure it closes. It is your problem\nuntil the customer is unblocked.)</p></li>\n</ol>\n","text":"module 14 — the house rules: leadership principles the one line version: a tech company's leadership principles are the shared behavior rules everyone actually uses, not just a poster on the wall. picture this (the analogy) imagine a big family house with 10 people living in it. the house has rules: clean up your own mess, help anyone who needs it, fix things when they break instead of walking past them, speak up if something looks wrong. these rules are written down. but more important, everyone uses them. when someone leaves dirty dishes, another person says \"hey, we agreed to clean up.\" when a pipe leaks, people do not say \"that is not my room,\" they grab a bucket and call a plumber. a tech company's leadership principles are like those house rules. they tell you what good behavior looks like. everyone knows them. people use them in hiring, in reviews, and when they decide what to do every day. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) a tech company has 16 leadership principles, but you call them lps for short. they are statements like \"customer obsession\" and \"ownership\" and \"dive deep.\" each one describes a way to think or act that a tech company values. when you interview on the job, interviewers ask you questions that map to specific lps. when your manager writes your review, they cite which lps you showed. when you are deciding how to handle a ticket, you use the lps to guide you. for example, if a customer is stuck, you think \"customer obsession says i put the customer pain first,\" and you prioritize that ticket over something less urgent. the lps are not just corporate fluff. people really use them. you will hear coworkers say things like \"that is very ownership\" or \"let us dive deep on this.\" why you should care as a support engineer, you will be judged on how well you demonstrate the lps. your manager will look for lp evidence in your work. your teammates will respect you more if you act like the lps say. your own decisions get easier when you have a shared framework. also, when you interview for your next role (se2, se3, maybe to a development role), the interviewer will ask for star stories that show lps. if you do not know the lps, you cannot tell those stories well. the lps are the common language. learn them now, practice them every day, and your career moves faster. how it works, step by tiny step there are 16 total lps. as an se, you care most about these six: 1. customer obsession start with the customer and work backwards. always think: what is the customer feeling right now? if a ticket says \"this has been broken for 3 days,\" that customer is frustrated. you put that ticket high on your list because the customer pain is high. you do not say \"well, it is just a config issue, no big deal.\" to the customer, it is a big deal. 2. ownership act like the problem is yours until it is solved, even if someone else code broke. you do not say \"that is not my team\" and close the ticket. you find the right owner, hand it off cleanly, and check back to make sure it closed. if the customer is still stuck, it is still your problem. 3. dive deep dig past the surface to find the real cause. a ticket says \"api times out.\" you do not just restart the service and close. you look at logs, check metrics, find the slow query, understand why it slowed down. the surface symptom is the timeout. the root cause might be a missing index or a bad config or a code bug. you find the root. 4. bias for action when there is a fire, act fast with the info you have. do not freeze waiting for perfect data. if a prod alarm is firing and you see the service is down, you restart it now, then you investigate why. speed matters. reversible decisions are cheap. if you can undo it, just do it. 5. insist on highest standards keep things clean. fix the root, do not accept \"it has always been broken.\" if you see a recurring ticket pattern, you file a bug to fix it permanently instead of manually solving it every week. high standards means you do not let jank pile up. 6. earn trust be honest. admit when you do not know. follow through on what you promise. if you tell a customer \"i will update you by end of day,\" you do it. trust is built in small actions over time. the other 10 lps matter too, but less directly for an se role. you will hear: are right a lot (make good calls, seek diverse input), learn and be curious (always learning), invent and simplify (make things easier), frugality (do more with less), deliver results (ship on time). know they exist. focus your daily energy on the top 6. 7. how to tell lp stories: star when you interview or write a self review, you tell work stories in star format: s ituation: what was the context? t ask: what did you need to do? a ction: what did you do? (this is the lp proof.) r esult: what happened because of your action? example star for dive deep: situation: a customer ticket said their cron job failed every morning. task: i needed to figure out why. action: i pulled logs, found a timeout on a downstream api, checked that api cloudwatch metrics, discovered the database was hitting max connections at 6 am every day. result: i worked with the db team to increase the connection pool. the cron job has run clean for 2 weeks. that story shows dive deep because you went deeper than \"cron job fails\" to find the actual root cause. you do the work first. then you tell the story in star shape later. words you will hear term plain meaning lp leadership principle, one of the 16 house rules customer obsession always put the customer pain first ownership it is your problem until solved, even if not your code dive deep dig to the real cause, not just the surface symptom bias for action act fast when needed, do not freeze highest standards fix the root, do not accept jank earn trust be honest, follow through, admit mistakes star situation task action result, the shape of a work story lp signal evidence that you showed a specific lp demonstrate an lp you do the behavior, then you tell the story what you actually do with this every day: when you pick up a ticket, ask: what does customer obsession say? put yourself in the customer shoes. when you close a ticket, ask: did i fix the root (highest standards) or just the symptom? when you are stuck, ask: bias for action says act, dive deep says investigate. which matters more right now? in reviews: your manager will look for lp evidence. write your accomplishments in star format with the lp named. example: \"demonstrated ownership by taking over ticket a ticket even though it was filed against another team, found the right owner, and verified the fix deployed.\" in interviews: prepare 2 3 star stories per lp. the interviewer will say \"tell me about a time you showed ownership.\" you tell your star. short situation, clear task, detailed action (you did x, you did y), concrete result (the customer was unblocked, the issue stopped recurring). daily habit: after you close a big ticket, write down the star in a notes file. do not wait until review time to remember. you will forget details. capture it fresh. how this connects to your background if you have prior engineering experience, a lot of this will feel familiar. you have probably read logs, used version control, and shipped code through reviews before, and the tools and habits carry over. what shifts in a support role is the focus: less time writing new features, more time keeping services healthy and investigating problems. you are building on a foundation, not starting from zero. check yourself 1. a ticket says \"my report is wrong.\" you restart the service and the report looks better. the customer closes the ticket. did you demonstrate highest standards? (answer: no. you fixed the symptom, not the root. highest standards says find why the report was wrong, fix that, so it does not break again.) 2. you are writing your self review. you want to show dive deep. you write \"i investigated many tickets.\" is that a star story? (answer: no. that is too vague. star needs a specific situation, a specific task, specific actions you took, and a concrete result.) 3. a customer ticket lands in your queue, but the broken service is owned by another team. what does ownership say you do? (answer: you do not close it with \"not my team.\" you find the right owner, hand it off with full context, check back to make sure it closes. it is your problem until the customer is unblocked.)","words":1575},{"id":"course-capstone-30-60-90-plan","section":"Course","title":"Capstone & 30/60/90 plan","html":"<h1\nid=\"module-15--becoming-the-hero-your-plan-and-the-victory-lap\">Module\n15 — Becoming the hero: your plan and the victory lap</h1>\n<h2 id=\"the-one-line-version\">The one-line version</h2>\n<p>You learned the map, the tools, the rules, the fix loop. Now you tie\nit all together with a real practice run, a ladder plan, and the path\nfrom watching to leading.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"picture-this-the-analogy\">Picture this (the analogy)</h2>\n<p>You finished driving school. You know the pedals, the signs, the\nrules. You passed the test.</p>\n<p>Now you get the keys to your own car.</p>\n<p>You start on quiet streets. A buddy rides with you. You build hours.\nYou learn every street in your neighborhood. Then you drive alone. Then\nother people ask you for directions.</p>\n<p>That is the hero journey.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-it-really-is-the-grown-up-truth-still-simple\">What it\nreally is (the grown-up truth, still simple)</h2>\n<p>You learned 14 modules. You know the landscape (company single\nsign-on (SSO), a tech company portal, a tech company AI assistant, the\ninternal docs hub). You know Git and the build system. You know how\nservices talk. You know how CDK builds the ground. You know how code\nships through pipelines. You know how CloudWatch watches it. You know\nhow the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) tickets get triaged.\nYou know how the code review tool (like GitHub pull requests) reviews\nhappen. You know how to run the fix loop. You know how to write a COE.\nYou know the house rules.</p>\n<p>That was the classroom.</p>\n<p>Now you do it for real.</p>\n<p>You do a full hands-on training from zero (build a toy service). You\nmap out your first 90 days. You climb the ladder one rung at a time.</p>\n<p>By the end, other people come to you with questions. You are the\nhero.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"why-you-should-care\">Why you should care</h2>\n<p>Your earlier experience gave you one path (a backend platform). You\nsaw the big picture from that window.</p>\n<p>Support Engineer means you see ALL the windows. Every team. Every\nservice. Every fire. You become the go-to person for the whole org.</p>\n<p>This module shows you the plan.</p>\n<p>It ties the 14 lessons into one roadmap.</p>\n<p>It gives you the next concrete step (the hands-on onboarding workshop\ntraining).</p>\n<p>It gives you the 30/60/90 day plan (what to do your first three\nmonths).</p>\n<p>It reminds you where the ladder goes (L3 SE1 → L4 SE2 → L4 SE3 → L5\nSE4).</p>\n<p>It defines \"hero\" so you know what good looks like.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-it-works-step-by-tiny-step\">How it works, step by tiny\nstep</h2>\n<h3 id=\"step-1-retrace-the-journey-what-you-already-learned\">Step 1:\nRetrace the journey (what you already learned)</h3>\n<p>You covered 14 modules. Here is the summary.</p>\n<p><strong>Modules 1-2 (the map):</strong> company single sign-on (SSO)\nis the front door. A tech company portal is the employee portal. A tech\ncompany AI assistant is IT. the internal docs hub is the dev library.\nthe company directory is the people search.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 3 (the workshop):</strong> a cloud dev machine is your\nvirtual computer. Terminal is the command window. Git is the version\ncontrol. the build system is the build tool. Your workspace is your\nworking folder.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 4 (how code lives):</strong> Git tracks every change.\nCommit is a snapshot. Branch is a parallel timeline. Mainline is the\ntruth. the central Git server is the server.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 5 (how code builds):</strong> the build system\npackages are folders with code. A version set pins every package\nversion. Build compiles code into a runnable program.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 6 (how services talk):</strong> the service framework\n(like gRPC or Spring Boot) is the framework. API is the menu. Request is\nthe order. Response is the food. Activity/Component/Builder/Accessor are\nthe layers.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 7 (how the ground is built):</strong> CDK writes\ninfrastructure as code. Stack is the full definition. Construct is one\nbuilding block. CloudFormation is the AWS deployer. Lambda is the\nserverless function. a secure infrastructure-as-code construct library\nadds safety guardrails.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 8 (how code ships):</strong> Deploy means launch.\nPipeline is the assembly line. Stages are Alpha/Beta/staging/Prod.\nRollback is undo. the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) is the\ndeployer tool.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 9 (how you watch it):</strong> CloudWatch is the\nmonitor. Logs are the journal. Metrics are the measurements. Alarms ring\nwhen thresholds break. Dashboard is the live view. Logs Insights\nsearches logs. the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool links\nalarms to services.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 10 (how you support it):</strong> the ticketing system\n(like Jira or PagerDuty) is the ticketing system. Queue is the inbox.\nTriage means sorting by urgency. Severity is Sev-1 (emergency) to Sev-5\n(question). SLA is the response time promise. On-call means you are the\none who answers. Paging means the alarm calls you. Escalation means you\ncall backup. Handoff means you pass the ticket.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 11 (how it gets checked):</strong> the code review\ntool (like GitHub pull requests) is the code review system. CR is one\nreview. Reviewer reads the code. Revision is version 2. the automated\nreview bot flags common mistakes.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 12 (how you fix it):</strong> Runbook is the playbook.\nCOE is the incident report. 5 Whys digs to root cause. Mitigate means\ntemporary fix. Root cause fix means permanent fix.</p>\n<p><strong>Module 13 (how you write about it):</strong> Working\nBackwards starts with the customer problem. PR/FAQ is the press release\nformat. Leadership Principles are a tech company values. STAR is the\nstory format (Situation Task Action Result).</p>\n<p><strong>Module 14 (the house rules):</strong> Write understandable\ncode. Test before you ship. Document what you do. Ask questions early.\nCheck twice before touching prod.</p>\n<p>That is the full loop.</p>\n<h3\nid=\"step-2-do-the-practice-run-the-hands-on-onboarding-workshop\">Step 2:\nDo the practice run (the hands-on onboarding workshop)</h3>\n<p>the hands-on onboarding workshop is a hands-on course. You build a\ntoy service from scratch. You write the code. You write the CDK stack.\nYou deploy it through a pipeline. You watch the logs. You break it on\npurpose. You fix it. You write the runbook.</p>\n<p>It takes maybe 8 hours spread over a few days.</p>\n<p>Link: your team's internal docs</p>\n<p>Do this FIRST. It cements everything.</p>\n<p>After the hands-on onboarding workshop, do the CDK workshop. That\ngoes deeper on infrastructure.</p>\n<p>Link: your team's internal docs</p>\n<p>Those two together make the abstract real.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step-3-understand-the-se-ladder\">Step 3: Understand the SE\nladder</h3>\n<p>Support Engineer has levels.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>L3 SE1:</strong> new to the role. You follow runbooks. A\nbuddy checks your work.</li>\n<li><strong>L4 SE2:</strong> early L4. You handle common tickets solo.\nYou improve runbooks.</li>\n<li><strong>L4 SE3:</strong> senior L4. You handle hard tickets. You\ndebug without the runbook. Other people ask you for help. This is the\ngo-to rung.</li>\n<li><strong>L5 SE4:</strong> you write the runbooks. You train others.\nYou own the on-call process.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>your earlier experience gives you credit. You saw production. You\nhandled tickets. You shipped code. L4 SE3 (senior L4) is a fair ask.</p>\n<p>But most people start at SE2 and climb to SE3 in 6-12 months.</p>\n<p>The difference between SE2 and SE3 is not time. It is confidence. SE3\nmeans other people come to you.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step-4-map-out-your-first-90-days\">Step 4: Map out your first 90\ndays</h3>\n<p><strong>First 30 days (watch and learn):</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Shadow an SE3 or SE4. Watch how they triage. Watch how they\ndebug.</li>\n<li>Handle small tickets with a buddy. Low severity. Clear runbook.</li>\n<li>Read every runbook in your queue. Run through the steps on\nAlpha.</li>\n<li>Join the on-call rotation as shadow (you watch, someone else\ndrives).</li>\n<li>Write down every question. Ask them all.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Next 30 days (do with backup):</strong></p>\n<ol start=\"6\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Handle medium tickets solo. Buddy is on Slack if you get stuck.</li>\n<li>Start improving runbooks. Add screenshots. Add troubleshooting\nsteps.</li>\n<li>Shadow on-call for one full week (24/7). You see the fire\ndrill.</li>\n<li>Write your first COE for a ticket you handled.</li>\n<li>Join a Working Backwards session for a new feature.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>By day 90 (do solo):</strong></p>\n<ol start=\"11\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Handle on-call shifts solo. Backup is available but you drive.</li>\n<li>Write one new runbook for a gap you found.</li>\n<li>Train a new person on a runbook you know well.</li>\n<li>Present one COE to the team (what broke, why, how you fixed it for\ngood).</li>\n</ol>\n<p>By day 90, you are SE3. Other people come to you.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step-5-define-hero-so-you-know-what-good-looks-like\">Step 5:\nDefine \"hero\" so you know what good looks like</h3>\n<p>A hero is not the person who works the most hours.</p>\n<p>A hero is not the person who fixes fires fastest.</p>\n<p>A hero is the person other people come to with questions.</p>\n<p>A hero fixes the root, not just the symptom.</p>\n<p>A hero leaves the runbooks better than they found them.</p>\n<p>A hero trains the next person.</p>\n<p>That is the goal.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"words-you-will-hear\">Words you will hear</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the hands-on onboarding workshop</strong></td>\n<td>the hands-on onboarding workshop, the hands-on toy service\ncourse</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CDK workshop</strong></td>\n<td>The deeper infrastructure training after the hands-on onboarding\nworkshop</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>SE1 / SE2 / SE3 / SE4</strong></td>\n<td>Support Engineer ladder (L3, early L4, senior L4, L5)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shadow</strong></td>\n<td>You watch someone else do the work, you learn by watching</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Go-to person</strong></td>\n<td>The one other people ask when stuck, the local expert</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>First 90 days</strong></td>\n<td>Your first three months in a new role, the learning window</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>COE presentation</strong></td>\n<td>You tell the team what broke and how you fixed it for good</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Root cause fix</strong></td>\n<td>The permanent fix that stops the problem from coming back</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Runbook gap</strong></td>\n<td>A scenario the runbook does not cover yet, a hole you fill</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-you-actually-do-with-this\">What YOU actually do with\nthis</h2>\n<p><strong>Right now (before you start the SE role):</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Do the hands-on onboarding workshop end to end. Build the toy\nservice. Ship it. Break it. Fix it. Write the runbook.</li>\n<li>Do the CDK workshop. Build a stack. Deploy it. Tear it down.</li>\n<li>Read the full cheat sheet below. Every term should click.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>First week on the job:</strong></p>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Ask your manager who your shadow buddy is. Stick to them.</li>\n<li>Read every runbook in your queue. Run through the steps on Alpha or\nyour laptop.</li>\n<li>Join the team Slack channel. Read the last 30 days of messages.\nLearn the rhythm.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>First month:</strong></p>\n<ol start=\"7\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Handle 5 small tickets with your buddy watching.</li>\n<li>Improve 1 runbook (add a screenshot, clarify a step, add a\ntroubleshooting branch).</li>\n<li>Shadow on-call for 2 shifts.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>By day 90:</strong></p>\n<ol start=\"10\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Do on-call solo for 1 full week.</li>\n<li>Write 1 new runbook for a gap.</li>\n<li>Present 1 COE to the team.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>That is the plan.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"check-yourself\">Check yourself</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>What are the two best practice runs to do before day 1 of SE? (the\nhands-on onboarding workshop + CDK workshop)</li>\n<li>What is the difference between SE2 and SE3? (SE3 is the go-to\nperson, others come to you for help)</li>\n<li>What does \"hero\" mean in this context? (The person who fixes roots,\nimproves runbooks, and trains others)</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"the-full-course-cheat-sheet-every-key-term-from-zero-to-hero\">The\nfull course cheat sheet (every key term from zero to hero)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>company single sign-on (SSO)</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's internal front page, the starting point every\nday</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>A tech company portal</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company employee portal, your pay/benefits/time off hub</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>A tech company AI assistant</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company IT self-service, your laptop/VPN/access requests</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the internal docs hub</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company dev documentation library, the how-to manual</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Terminal</strong></td>\n<td>The command window on your computer, the text interface</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>a cloud dev machine</strong></td>\n<td>Your virtual work computer in AWS, lives in the cloud</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Git</strong></td>\n<td>Version control system, tracks every change to code</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Commit</strong></td>\n<td>One saved snapshot of your code, a checkpoint in Git</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Branch</strong></td>\n<td>A parallel timeline in Git, your sandbox</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mainline</strong></td>\n<td>The main branch in Git, the single source of truth</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the central Git server</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's internal Git server, where code lives</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the build system</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's build tool, turns code into runnable programs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Package</strong></td>\n<td>One folder of code in the build system, the unit of work</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Workspace</strong></td>\n<td>Your local working folder where you edit code</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Version set</strong></td>\n<td>The list of every package version pinned together</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Build</strong></td>\n<td>The process that compiles code and runs tests</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the service framework (like gRPC or Spring\nBoot)</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's service framework, how services talk</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API</strong></td>\n<td>Application Programming Interface, the menu of operations</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Request</strong></td>\n<td>The call a client makes to a service, the order</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Response</strong></td>\n<td>The data the service sends back, the food</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Activity</strong></td>\n<td>the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot) layer 1, handles\nincoming requests and validation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Component</strong></td>\n<td>the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot) layer 2, the\nbusiness logic brain</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Builder</strong></td>\n<td>the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot) layer 3, constructs\ndata objects</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Accessor</strong></td>\n<td>the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot) layer 4, talks to\ndatabases and other services</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Exception</strong></td>\n<td>An error object, signals something went wrong</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CDK</strong></td>\n<td>Cloud Development Kit, writes infrastructure as code</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Stack</strong></td>\n<td>The full infrastructure definition in CDK</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Construct</strong></td>\n<td>One building block in a CDK stack (one Lambda, one table)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CloudFormation</strong></td>\n<td>AWS tool that reads CDK output and builds resources</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lambda</strong></td>\n<td>AWS serverless function, code that runs on demand</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>a secure infrastructure-as-code construct\nlibrary</strong></td>\n<td>CDK with built-in security guardrails, safer defaults</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Deploy</strong></td>\n<td>Launch new code or infrastructure to a stage</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Pipeline</strong></td>\n<td>The assembly line that builds, tests, and ships code</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Stage</strong></td>\n<td>One environment in the pipeline (Alpha, Beta, staging, Prod)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Alpha</strong></td>\n<td>First test stage, team only, breaks often</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Beta</strong></td>\n<td>Second test stage, small real traffic</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>staging</strong></td>\n<td>Third test stage, bigger real traffic, last check</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Prod</strong></td>\n<td>Production, the real customer-facing environment</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Rollback</strong></td>\n<td>Undo a bad deploy, go back to the last good version</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo\nCD)</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's deploy tool, ships code to stages</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CloudWatch</strong></td>\n<td>AWS monitoring service, the security camera system</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Logs</strong></td>\n<td>Text records of what happened, the journal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Metrics</strong></td>\n<td>Measurements of system health (latency, errors, requests)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Alarm</strong></td>\n<td>A CloudWatch alert that fires when a threshold breaks</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dashboard</strong></td>\n<td>A live view of metrics and alarms in one screen</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Logs Insights</strong></td>\n<td>CloudWatch search tool, grep for logs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the alarm dependency map in your monitoring\ntool</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company alarm manager, links alarms to services</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)</strong></td>\n<td>Service Incident Management, a tech company's ticketing system</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Ticket</strong></td>\n<td>One support request or bug report in the ticketing system (like Jira\nor PagerDuty)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Queue</strong></td>\n<td>The inbox of tickets waiting to be handled</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Triage</strong></td>\n<td>Sorting tickets by urgency, deciding what to do first</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Severity Sev-1</strong></td>\n<td>Emergency, customer impact right now, all hands on deck</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Severity Sev-2</strong></td>\n<td>High priority, fix today, some customer impact</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Severity Sev-3</strong></td>\n<td>Medium priority, fix this week, internal issue</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Severity Sev-4</strong></td>\n<td>Low priority, fix when you can, cosmetic problem</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Severity Sev-5</strong></td>\n<td>Question or feature request, not a bug</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>SLA</strong></td>\n<td>Service Level Agreement, the promise for response time</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>On-call</strong></td>\n<td>You are the one who gets paged when alarms fire</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Paging</strong></td>\n<td>The system calls you (phone, Slack, email) for an alarm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Escalation</strong></td>\n<td>You call backup (senior engineer, manager) for help</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Handoff</strong></td>\n<td>You pass the ticket to someone else with full context</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the code review tool (like GitHub pull\nrequests)</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's code review system, where reviews happen</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CR</strong></td>\n<td>Code Review, one review request in the code review tool (like GitHub\npull requests)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Reviewer</strong></td>\n<td>The person who reads and approves your code</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Revision</strong></td>\n<td>Version 2 (or 3) of your pull request after changes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the automated review bot</strong></td>\n<td>Automated code analyzer, flags common mistakes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Runbook</strong></td>\n<td>Step-by-step instructions for fixing a known problem</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>COE</strong></td>\n<td>Correction of Errors, the incident report you write after a\nfire</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>5 Whys</strong></td>\n<td>Root cause technique, ask \"why\" five times to dig deep</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Working Backwards</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company planning method, starts with customer need</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>PR/FAQ</strong></td>\n<td>Press Release and Frequently Asked Questions, the design doc\nformat</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Leadership Principles</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's 16 core values, the house rules</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>STAR</strong></td>\n<td>Story format (Situation Task Action Result), for interviews and\nself-reviews</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Root cause</strong></td>\n<td>The original reason something broke, the true source</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mitigate</strong></td>\n<td>Temporary fix to stop the bleeding while you find root cause</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"you-are-ready\">You are ready</h2>\n<p>You learned the map. You learned the tools. You learned the rules.\nYou learned the fix loop.</p>\n<p>You know what good looks like.</p>\n<p>You have the practice runs (the hands-on onboarding workshop, CDK\nworkshop).</p>\n<p>You have the 30/60/90 plan.</p>\n<p>You have the ladder (SE2 to SE3 to SE4).</p>\n<p>You know what hero means (the go-to person who fixes roots and trains\nothers).</p>\n<p>Your earlier experience gave you the foundation. You saw production.\nYou handled tickets. You shipped code.</p>\n<p>Now you tie it together.</p>\n<p>Do the practice runs. Shadow your buddy. Handle small tickets.\nImprove runbooks. Do on-call. Write COEs. Train the next person.</p>\n<p>By day 90, other people come to you.</p>\n<p>That is the victory lap.</p>\n<p>You are the hero.</p>\n<p>Go.</p>\n","text":"module 15 — becoming the hero: your plan and the victory lap the one line version you learned the map, the tools, the rules, the fix loop. now you tie it all together with a real practice run, a ladder plan, and the path from watching to leading. picture this (the analogy) you finished driving school. you know the pedals, the signs, the rules. you passed the test. now you get the keys to your own car. you start on quiet streets. a buddy rides with you. you build hours. you learn every street in your neighborhood. then you drive alone. then other people ask you for directions. that is the hero journey. what it really is (the grown up truth, still simple) you learned 14 modules. you know the landscape (company single sign on (sso), a tech company portal, a tech company ai assistant, the internal docs hub). you know git and the build system. you know how services talk. you know how cdk builds the ground. you know how code ships through pipelines. you know how cloudwatch watches it. you know how the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) tickets get triaged. you know how the code review tool (like github pull requests) reviews happen. you know how to run the fix loop. you know how to write a coe. you know the house rules. that was the classroom. now you do it for real. you do a full hands on training from zero (build a toy service). you map out your first 90 days. you climb the ladder one rung at a time. by the end, other people come to you with questions. you are the hero. why you should care your earlier experience gave you one path (a backend platform). you saw the big picture from that window. support engineer means you see all the windows. every team. every service. every fire. you become the go to person for the whole org. this module shows you the plan. it ties the 14 lessons into one roadmap. it gives you the next concrete step (the hands on onboarding workshop training). it gives you the 30/60/90 day plan (what to do your first three months). it reminds you where the ladder goes (l3 se1 → l4 se2 → l4 se3 → l5 se4). it defines \"hero\" so you know what good looks like. how it works, step by tiny step step 1: retrace the journey (what you already learned) you covered 14 modules. here is the summary. modules 1 2 (the map): company single sign on (sso) is the front door. a tech company portal is the employee portal. a tech company ai assistant is it. the internal docs hub is the dev library. the company directory is the people search. module 3 (the workshop): a cloud dev machine is your virtual computer. terminal is the command window. git is the version control. the build system is the build tool. your workspace is your working folder. module 4 (how code lives): git tracks every change. commit is a snapshot. branch is a parallel timeline. mainline is the truth. the central git server is the server. module 5 (how code builds): the build system packages are folders with code. a version set pins every package version. build compiles code into a runnable program. module 6 (how services talk): the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) is the framework. api is the menu. request is the order. response is the food. activity/component/builder/accessor are the layers. module 7 (how the ground is built): cdk writes infrastructure as code. stack is the full definition. construct is one building block. cloudformation is the aws deployer. lambda is the serverless function. a secure infrastructure as code construct library adds safety guardrails. module 8 (how code ships): deploy means launch. pipeline is the assembly line. stages are alpha/beta/staging/prod. rollback is undo. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) is the deployer tool. module 9 (how you watch it): cloudwatch is the monitor. logs are the journal. metrics are the measurements. alarms ring when thresholds break. dashboard is the live view. logs insights searches logs. the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool links alarms to services. module 10 (how you support it): the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) is the ticketing system. queue is the inbox. triage means sorting by urgency. severity is sev 1 (emergency) to sev 5 (question). sla is the response time promise. on call means you are the one who answers. paging means the alarm calls you. escalation means you call backup. handoff means you pass the ticket. module 11 (how it gets checked): the code review tool (like github pull requests) is the code review system. cr is one review. reviewer reads the code. revision is version 2. the automated review bot flags common mistakes. module 12 (how you fix it): runbook is the playbook. coe is the incident report. 5 whys digs to root cause. mitigate means temporary fix. root cause fix means permanent fix. module 13 (how you write about it): working backwards starts with the customer problem. pr/faq is the press release format. leadership principles are a tech company values. star is the story format (situation task action result). module 14 (the house rules): write understandable code. test before you ship. document what you do. ask questions early. check twice before touching prod. that is the full loop. step 2: do the practice run (the hands on onboarding workshop) the hands on onboarding workshop is a hands on course. you build a toy service from scratch. you write the code. you write the cdk stack. you deploy it through a pipeline. you watch the logs. you break it on purpose. you fix it. you write the runbook. it takes maybe 8 hours spread over a few days. link: your team's internal docs do this first. it cements everything. after the hands on onboarding workshop, do the cdk workshop. that goes deeper on infrastructure. link: your team's internal docs those two together make the abstract real. step 3: understand the se ladder support engineer has levels. l3 se1: new to the role. you follow runbooks. a buddy checks your work. l4 se2: early l4. you handle common tickets solo. you improve runbooks. l4 se3: senior l4. you handle hard tickets. you debug without the runbook. other people ask you for help. this is the go to rung. l5 se4: you write the runbooks. you train others. you own the on call process. your earlier experience gives you credit. you saw production. you handled tickets. you shipped code. l4 se3 (senior l4) is a fair ask. but most people start at se2 and climb to se3 in 6 12 months. the difference between se2 and se3 is not time. it is confidence. se3 means other people come to you. step 4: map out your first 90 days first 30 days (watch and learn): 1. shadow an se3 or se4. watch how they triage. watch how they debug. 2. handle small tickets with a buddy. low severity. clear runbook. 3. read every runbook in your queue. run through the steps on alpha. 4. join the on call rotation as shadow (you watch, someone else drives). 5. write down every question. ask them all. next 30 days (do with backup): 6. handle medium tickets solo. buddy is on slack if you get stuck. 7. start improving runbooks. add screenshots. add troubleshooting steps. 8. shadow on call for one full week (24/7). you see the fire drill. 9. write your first coe for a ticket you handled. 10. join a working backwards session for a new feature. by day 90 (do solo): 11. handle on call shifts solo. backup is available but you drive. 12. write one new runbook for a gap you found. 13. train a new person on a runbook you know well. 14. present one coe to the team (what broke, why, how you fixed it for good). by day 90, you are se3. other people come to you. step 5: define \"hero\" so you know what good looks like a hero is not the person who works the most hours. a hero is not the person who fixes fires fastest. a hero is the person other people come to with questions. a hero fixes the root, not just the symptom. a hero leaves the runbooks better than they found them. a hero trains the next person. that is the goal. words you will hear term plain meaning the hands on onboarding workshop the hands on onboarding workshop, the hands on toy service course cdk workshop the deeper infrastructure training after the hands on onboarding workshop se1 / se2 / se3 / se4 support engineer ladder (l3, early l4, senior l4, l5) shadow you watch someone else do the work, you learn by watching go to person the one other people ask when stuck, the local expert first 90 days your first three months in a new role, the learning window coe presentation you tell the team what broke and how you fixed it for good root cause fix the permanent fix that stops the problem from coming back runbook gap a scenario the runbook does not cover yet, a hole you fill what you actually do with this right now (before you start the se role): 1. do the hands on onboarding workshop end to end. build the toy service. ship it. break it. fix it. write the runbook. 2. do the cdk workshop. build a stack. deploy it. tear it down. 3. read the full cheat sheet below. every term should click. first week on the job: 4. ask your manager who your shadow buddy is. stick to them. 5. read every runbook in your queue. run through the steps on alpha or your laptop. 6. join the team slack channel. read the last 30 days of messages. learn the rhythm. first month: 7. handle 5 small tickets with your buddy watching. 8. improve 1 runbook (add a screenshot, clarify a step, add a troubleshooting branch). 9. shadow on call for 2 shifts. by day 90: 10. do on call solo for 1 full week. 11. write 1 new runbook for a gap. 12. present 1 coe to the team. that is the plan. check yourself 1. what are the two best practice runs to do before day 1 of se? (the hands on onboarding workshop + cdk workshop) 2. what is the difference between se2 and se3? (se3 is the go to person, others come to you for help) 3. what does \"hero\" mean in this context? (the person who fixes roots, improves runbooks, and trains others) the full course cheat sheet (every key term from zero to hero) term plain meaning company single sign on (sso) a tech company's internal front page, the starting point every day a tech company portal a tech company employee portal, your pay/benefits/time off hub a tech company ai assistant a tech company it self service, your laptop/vpn/access requests the internal docs hub a tech company dev documentation library, the how to manual terminal the command window on your computer, the text interface a cloud dev machine your virtual work computer in aws, lives in the cloud git version control system, tracks every change to code commit one saved snapshot of your code, a checkpoint in git branch a parallel timeline in git, your sandbox mainline the main branch in git, the single source of truth the central git server a tech company's internal git server, where code lives the build system a tech company's build tool, turns code into runnable programs package one folder of code in the build system, the unit of work workspace your local working folder where you edit code version set the list of every package version pinned together build the process that compiles code and runs tests the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) a tech company's service framework, how services talk api application programming interface, the menu of operations request the call a client makes to a service, the order response the data the service sends back, the food activity the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) layer 1, handles incoming requests and validation component the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) layer 2, the business logic brain builder the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) layer 3, constructs data objects accessor the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) layer 4, talks to databases and other services exception an error object, signals something went wrong cdk cloud development kit, writes infrastructure as code stack the full infrastructure definition in cdk construct one building block in a cdk stack (one lambda, one table) cloudformation aws tool that reads cdk output and builds resources lambda aws serverless function, code that runs on demand a secure infrastructure as code construct library cdk with built in security guardrails, safer defaults deploy launch new code or infrastructure to a stage pipeline the assembly line that builds, tests, and ships code stage one environment in the pipeline (alpha, beta, staging, prod) alpha first test stage, team only, breaks often beta second test stage, small real traffic staging third test stage, bigger real traffic, last check prod production, the real customer facing environment rollback undo a bad deploy, go back to the last good version the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) a tech company's deploy tool, ships code to stages cloudwatch aws monitoring service, the security camera system logs text records of what happened, the journal metrics measurements of system health (latency, errors, requests) alarm a cloudwatch alert that fires when a threshold breaks dashboard a live view of metrics and alarms in one screen logs insights cloudwatch search tool, grep for logs the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool a tech company alarm manager, links alarms to services the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) service incident management, a tech company's ticketing system ticket one support request or bug report in the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) queue the inbox of tickets waiting to be handled triage sorting tickets by urgency, deciding what to do first severity sev 1 emergency, customer impact right now, all hands on deck severity sev 2 high priority, fix today, some customer impact severity sev 3 medium priority, fix this week, internal issue severity sev 4 low priority, fix when you can, cosmetic problem severity sev 5 question or feature request, not a bug sla service level agreement, the promise for response time on call you are the one who gets paged when alarms fire paging the system calls you (phone, slack, email) for an alarm escalation you call backup (senior engineer, manager) for help handoff you pass the ticket to someone else with full context the code review tool (like github pull requests) a tech company's code review system, where reviews happen cr code review, one review request in the code review tool (like github pull requests) reviewer the person who reads and approves your code revision version 2 (or 3) of your pull request after changes the automated review bot automated code analyzer, flags common mistakes runbook step by step instructions for fixing a known problem coe correction of errors, the incident report you write after a fire 5 whys root cause technique, ask \"why\" five times to dig deep working backwards a tech company planning method, starts with customer need pr/faq press release and frequently asked questions, the design doc format leadership principles a tech company's 16 core values, the house rules star story format (situation task action result), for interviews and self reviews root cause the original reason something broke, the true source mitigate temporary fix to stop the bleeding while you find root cause you are ready you learned the map. you learned the tools. you learned the rules. you learned the fix loop. you know what good looks like. you have the practice runs (the hands on onboarding workshop, cdk workshop). you have the 30/60/90 plan. you have the ladder (se2 to se3 to se4). you know what hero means (the go to person who fixes roots and trains others). your earlier experience gave you the foundation. you saw production. you handled tickets. you shipped code. now you tie it together. do the practice runs. shadow your buddy. handle small tickets. improve runbooks. do on call. write coes. train the next person. by day 90, other people come to you. that is the victory lap. you are the hero. go.","words":3002},{"id":"training-troubleshooting-drills","section":"Training","title":"Troubleshooting drills","html":"<h1 id=\"troubleshooting-drills--the-core-se-muscle\">Troubleshooting\nDrills — The Core SE Muscle</h1>\n<p><strong>What this trains:</strong> The 7-step troubleshooting reflex\nthat turns \"something's broken\" into \"here's the root cause, here's the\nfix, here's how we prevent it\" — the core SE skill that runs underneath\nevery ticket, every alarm, every prod incident.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-7-step-method-your-north-star\">The 7-Step Method (Your North\nStar)</h2>\n<p>Every SE troubleshooting session follows this path, in this\norder:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand</strong> — What broke? Who's affected? When did\nit start? What changed recently?</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis</strong> — One clear guess at the root cause.\nState it out loud.</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence</strong> — Pull logs, metrics, stack traces to\nprove OR KILL your hypothesis. Killing bad hypotheses is progress.</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause</strong> — Once evidence confirms, name the\nactual thing that broke (not just symptoms).</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate</strong> — Stop the bleeding. Often this means\nrollback. Get customers unstuck first.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> — Code change, config update, or operational\nfix that solves the root cause.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent</strong> — Alarm that would catch this earlier next\ntime. Runbook update. Test that would have caught it pre-deploy.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The habit is: always understand before you hypothesize, always gather\nevidence before you act, always mitigate before you chase the perfect\nfix, always prevent after you close.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-1--web-app-slow-starter\">Drill 1 — Web App Slow\n(Starter)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Users report your web app is \"slow to\nload\" starting about 30 minutes ago. Nothing deployed today. Load is\nnormal.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> What's your first hypothesis? What\nevidence do you need?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> Slow to load = response time spike.\nStarted 30 min ago. No deploy, load normal. Affects all users or\nsubset?</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> Downstream dependency (database, API,\ncache) is slow or timing out.</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> Check CloudWatch metrics — p99 latency on\nyour service. Check dependency call durations (DDB, external API\ntimeouts). Check logs for timeout exceptions in the last 30 min.</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Say evidence shows DDB read latency\nspiked 30 min ago — something changed in DDB load or capacity.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> If DDB, can you increase provisioned\nthroughput? Can you fail fast with cached stale data? Is there a circuit\nbreaker you can temporarily open to shed load?</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> If DDB autoscaling wasn't working, fix the\nscaling config. If a bad query pattern started, fix the query or add an\nindex.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Alarm on p99 DDB latency. Runbook for \"web\napp slow\" that checks dependencies first.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"Did downstream dependency latency change 30 minutes\nago?\" (Check your dependencies before you dig into your own code.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-2--api-5xx-spike-intermediate\">Drill 2 — API 5xx Spike\n(Intermediate)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Your API starts returning 500 errors at\n10:00 AM. Error rate jumps from 0.1% to 5%. Alarm fires. No deploy since\nyesterday.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> What's your hypothesis? What's the\nfirst log line you grep for?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> 500 errors = server-side failure.\nStarted 10 AM sharp. No recent deploy. Alarm threshold crossed.</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> A dependency started failing (external\nservice, database, auth service), OR something in the environment\nchanged (cert expired, network partition, fleet capacity\nexhausted).</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> Grep logs for stack traces with \"500\" or\n\"InternalServiceException\" timestamp 10:00 AM onward. Check exception\ntype — is it timeout, connection refused, null pointer, dependency\nfailure?</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Say logs show\n<code>SSLHandshakeException</code> — cert expired at 10 AM.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Rotate the cert immediately. Restart\naffected hosts if needed.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> Update cert rotation automation to renew 7\ndays before expiry, not same-day.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Alarm on cert expiry &lt; 7 days. Runbook\nfor \"API 5xx spike\" that checks certs + dependencies.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"What's the exception type in the 500 errors?\" (The\nstack trace tells you what broke — connection, timeout, null, auth —\nbefore you guess.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-3--batch-job-stuck\">Drill 3 — Batch Job Stuck</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> A nightly batch job that processes\npaycodes normally finishes in 20 minutes. Tonight it's been running for\n3 hours and still not done. Logs show it's processing rows but very\nslowly. This is the first run of the month.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> First-run-of-month is a clue. What's\nyour hypothesis?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> Batch job slow, not failing. First run\nof new month. Normally 20 min, now 3 hrs. Processing continues.</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> Data volume spiked (cross-month\npaycodes doubled), OR a code path that only fires at month boundaries is\ninefficient, OR database query performance degraded with larger\ndataset.</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> Check row count being processed — is it\n2x normal? Check database query duration — are scans taking longer?\nCheck logs for any \"duplicate row\" handling or retries.</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Say logs show duplicate paycode rows\nbeing written for employees crossing month boundary. Deduplication logic\nis quadratic — checking every new row against all previous rows. With 2x\nrows, runtime becomes 4x.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Kill the current run if it's producing\nbad data. If data is correct but slow, let it finish + add capacity for\nnext run.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> Fix the root cause that creates duplicate rows\n(date-handling bug at month boundary). Add unique constraint or\nidempotency key so duplicates can't be written. Optimize dedup logic to\nO(1) with a set instead of O(n²).</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Alarm on batch job duration &gt; 30 min.\nAdd a test case that runs the batch job on cross-month data. Add a DDB\nunique constraint or conditional write to catch duplicates before they\nslow you down.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"Is the row count being processed larger than usual?\"\n(Volume spike is the simplest hypothesis for 'same code suddenly\nslow'.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-4--queue-backing-up-intermediate\">Drill 4 — Queue Backing\nUp (Intermediate)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Your SQS queue depth is climbing. Normally\nit stays under 100 messages. Now it's at 5000 and growing. Messages are\nbeing enqueued but not processed fast enough.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> Is the problem on the producer side\nor consumer side? What's your hypothesis?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> Queue depth climbing = producers faster\nthan consumers, OR consumers stuck/slow. Normally balanced. Started\nwhen?</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> Consumers are slow (processing time\nincreased), OR consumers are failing/crashing and restarting, OR\nproducer traffic spiked.</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> Check consumer fleet size (autoscaling\nworking?). Check consumer processing time per message (CloudWatch\nmetric). Check producer message rate (did traffic spike?). Check\nconsumer logs for errors or timeouts.</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Say evidence shows consumer processing\ntime jumped from 100ms to 5 seconds per message because a downstream\ndependency (DDB, API) is slow.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Scale up consumer fleet manually to drain\nthe queue faster. If dependency is broken, can you fail fast or use\ncached data to speed up processing?</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> Fix the slow dependency. If DDB, add capacity\nor optimize the query. If API, fix the timeout or add circuit\nbreaker.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Alarm on queue depth &gt; 1000. Alarm on\nconsumer processing time &gt; 1 second. Runbook for \"queue backing up\"\nthat checks consumer health + dependency latency first.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"Did consumer processing time per message change?\" (If\nprocessing is slow, scaling consumers helps. If processing is broken,\nscaling makes it worse.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-5--latency-only-in-one-region-tricky\">Drill 5 — Latency\nOnly in One Region (Tricky)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> API latency is normal in us-west-2 and\neu-west-1, but p99 latency in ap-southeast-1 is 5x higher. Started an\nhour ago. No regional deploy differences.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> Regional difference = regional\nresource or network issue. What's your hypothesis?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> One region slow, others fine. Started 1\nhour ago. Same code deployed everywhere.</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> Regional resource exhausted (DDB\ncapacity, Lambda concurrency, NAT gateway bandwidth), OR network issue\n(cross-AZ latency, internet gateway), OR regional dependency failing\n(cache, database replica lag).</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> Check regional DDB consumed capacity vs\nprovisioned. Check Lambda throttles in that region. Check VPC flow logs\nfor packet loss or retransmits. Check if the region calls a different\ndependency endpoint (regional cache, regional DDB replica).</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Say evidence shows DDB autoscaling in\nap-southeast-1 lagged behind traffic spike — capacity didn't scale fast\nenough, reads are throttled.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Manually increase DDB capacity in\nap-southeast-1 to match traffic.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> Adjust DDB autoscaling policy to scale faster\n(lower target utilization or faster cooldown). Investigate why traffic\nspiked in that region only.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Alarm on DDB throttled requests per\nregion. Runbook for \"latency spike in one region\" that checks regional\nresource limits first.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"Is a regional resource (DDB, Lambda, NAT) throttling or\nexhausted in the slow region?\" (Regional problems = regional resource or\nnetwork first.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-6--intermittent-timeouts-hard\">Drill 6 — Intermittent\nTimeouts (Hard)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Your API randomly times out 1-2% of\nrequests. No pattern by time of day or endpoint. Logs show timeout after\n3 seconds on calls to a downstream service. That downstream service's\nown metrics show p99 latency is only 200ms.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> Downstream says they're fast, but\nyou're timing out. What gives?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> 1-2% random timeouts. Downstream claims\nfast. Your timeout is 3 seconds.</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> Downstream has a tail latency problem\n(p99 is fine but p99.9 is bad), OR network issue between you and them\n(packet loss, retries), OR your connection pool is exhausted and new\nconnections are slow, OR your retry logic is broken (retry on timeout\ncreates more timeouts).</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> Check your p99.9 latency to downstream\n(not just p99). Check connection pool metrics (active connections, wait\ntime). Check network metrics (packet retransmits, connection resets).\nCheck if timeouts cluster by host or by downstream endpoint.</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Say evidence shows your connection pool\nis size 10, and under load all 10 are busy. New requests wait for a free\nconnection, timeout after 3 seconds. Downstream is actually fast, but\nyour connection reuse is broken.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Increase connection pool size to 50.\nRestart hosts to clear any stuck connections.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> Set connection pool size based on expected\nconcurrency (not a magic number). Add connection pool health checks. Fix\nany connection leak in your code.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Alarm on connection pool exhaustion\n(active connections = max pool size). Runbook for \"intermittent\ntimeouts\" that checks connection pool + network first.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"What's our p99.9 latency to the downstream, not just\np99?\" (Tail latency kills. P99 = 200ms doesn't tell you p99.9 might be\n10 seconds.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-7--deploy-this-morning-common-se-scenario\">Drill 7 —\nDeploy This Morning (Common SE Scenario)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> A new version deployed to production at 9\nAM. At 10 AM, alarms fire for increased 4xx errors (from 0.5% to 3%).\nLogs show\n<code>ValidationException: missing required field 'employeeId'</code>.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> Deploy this morning + new errors =\nwhat's your hypothesis?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> New deploy at 9 AM. Errors started 10\nAM (1 hour later, likely phased rollout). 4xx = client error (your API\nrejecting requests). ValidationException = your code.</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> New deploy introduced stricter\nvalidation or changed the API contract. Clients that worked yesterday\nare now being rejected.</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> Check the diff in the deploy — was there\na schema change, a new required field, or stricter validation logic?\nCheck which clients are failing (old version, specific integration,\nmobile app). Check if the API docs were updated or if this was a\nbreaking change.</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Deploy added <code>employeeId</code> as\na required field. Existing clients don't send it. Breaking change\nshipped without backward compatibility.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Rollback the deploy immediately to\nunblock clients. OR make <code>employeeId</code> optional in the current\ncode, validate it only if present.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> Make the field optional with a default, OR\nversion the API so new clients use v2 with the required field, old\nclients stay on v1.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Backward compatibility check in pre-deploy\ntesting. Canary deploy with alarm on 4xx rate increase. API contract\nreview in CR process.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"What changed in the deploy that could cause\nValidationException?\" (Deploy + new error = code diff first.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-8--downstream-dependency-failing\">Drill 8 — Downstream\nDependency Failing</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Your service calls the downstream routing\nAPI (a scheduling API) to fetch schedule data. Suddenly 30% of calls\nreturn <code>a routing-not-found error</code>. the downstream routing\nAPI team says their service is healthy. Alarm fires. Logs show the\nexception started 2 hours ago.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> the downstream routing API says\nthey're healthy but you're getting exceptions. What's your\nhypothesis?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> 30% failure rate calling the downstream\nrouting API. Exception = <code>a routing-not-found error</code>. the\ndownstream routing API team claims healthy. Started 2 hours ago.</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> Routing issue in the downstream routing\nAPI's gateway (profile mismatch, missing route for a subset of\nemployees), OR your request format changed and the downstream routing\nAPI can't route it, OR network/DNS issue between you and the downstream\nrouting API.</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> Check which employees are failing — is\nthere a pattern (country, hire date, employee type)? Check the\ndownstream routing API logs for the same employeeIds — do they see the\nrequests? Check your request payload — did you change the operation name\nor profile routing parameters? Check the downstream routing API's\nrouting cascade (operation ID profile, domain profile, default).</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Say evidence shows failing employees\nare missing an employee-data profiles assignment. the downstream routing\nAPI's routing cascade tries operation profile (miss), domain profile\n(miss), default profile (miss) → <code>a routing-not-found error</code>.\nNot the downstream routing API's fault, not your fault — data gap in the\nemployee data source.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Get the employee-data team to backfill\nmissing profiles for affected employees. OR add a fallback in your code\nto handle <code>a routing-not-found error</code> gracefully (use cached\ndata, skip enrichment, log and continue).</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> Work with the employee-data team to ensure all\nemployees get profile assignments at hire. Add a validation step in your\nonboarding flow to catch missing profiles early.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Alarm on\n<code>a routing-not-found error</code> rate &gt; 1%. Runbook for the\ndownstream routing API failures that checks employee profile assignment\nfirst. Add a pre-call validation (if profile missing, don't call the\ndownstream routing API).</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"Which employees are failing — is there a common\nattribute?\" (Pattern in failures = data-driven root cause, not\ncode.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-9--disk-filling-on-a-host-operational-se-task\">Drill 9 —\nDisk Filling on a Host (Operational SE Task)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Alarm fires: disk utilization on one host\nin your fleet is at 85%, climbing. Normally hosts stay under 40%. The\nhost is still serving traffic.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> One host, not the whole fleet =\nhost-specific issue. What's your hypothesis?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> Disk filling on one host. Others fine.\nStill serving traffic. Started when?</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> Log rotation broken on that host, OR a\nbatch job writing temp files and not cleaning up, OR a memory leak\ncausing core dumps or heap dumps to pile up.</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> SSH to the host. Run <code>df -h</code>\nto see which partition is full. Run <code>du -sh /*</code> to see which\ndirectory is eating space. Check <code>/var/log</code> size,\n<code>/tmp</code> size, application log directory size.</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Say evidence shows\n<code>/var/log/application.log</code> is 50 GB. Log rotation config is\nbroken or not applied to this host.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Manually rotate or compress old logs to\nfree space immediately. If needed, terminate and replace the host (since\nit's in an ASG).</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> Fix log rotation config fleet-wide\n(logrotate.d or CloudWatch Logs agent config). Verify all hosts have the\ncorrect config deployed.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Alarm on disk utilization per host &gt;\n70%. Runbook for \"disk full\" that checks log rotation + temp file\ncleanup first. Fleet health check that validates log rotation config on\nall hosts.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"Which directory on the host is consuming the most disk\nspace?\" (<code>du -sh /*</code> tells you where to look — logs, temp\nfiles, core dumps, or application data.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-10--cert-expired-classic-ops-failure\">Drill 10 — Cert\nExpired (Classic Ops Failure)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> At 3 AM, alarms fire for 100% 5xx errors\non your API. Logs show <code>SSLHandshakeException</code> on every\nrequest. The service was healthy at 2 AM. On-call wakes up.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP and think.</strong> Sudden 100% failure at 3 AM sharp =\nsomething expired or rotated. What's your hypothesis?</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Understand:</strong> 100% 5xx, every request.\n<code>SSLHandshakeException</code> = SSL/TLS failure. Happened at 3 AM\nsharp. Service was fine 1 hour ago.</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> SSL cert expired at 3 AM, OR cert\nrotation job ran and broke something, OR a dependency's cert expired and\nyou can't connect to them.</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> Check your cert expiry date (openssl or\nACM console). Check logs for which cert is failing (your own or a\ndownstream). Check if a cert rotation job ran at 3 AM.</li>\n<li><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Your own cert expired at 3 AM. Cert\nrotation automation didn't run or failed silently.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Manually renew the cert and deploy it\nimmediately. Restart hosts to pick up new cert. If you can't renew fast\nenough, failover to a secondary cert or endpoint.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix:</strong> Fix cert rotation automation to renew 7 days\nbefore expiry. Add retries and alerting to the rotation job. If manual\ncert, replace with ACM auto-renewal.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> Alarm on cert expiry &lt; 7 days. Alarm if\ncert rotation job fails. Runbook for \"SSL failures\" that checks cert\nexpiry first.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Most Important Question You Should Have Asked\nFirst:</strong> \"When does our SSL cert expire?\" (Exact-time failures =\nexpiry or scheduled job. Check the cert date before you dig deeper.)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"symptom-vs-root-cause--matching-drill\">Symptom vs Root Cause —\nMatching Drill</h2>\n<p><strong>Instructions:</strong> For each symptom, pick the most likely\nroot cause from the list. Then check the answer key.</p>\n<p><strong>Symptoms:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>API latency spikes every day at 3 PM for 10 minutes.</li>\n<li>Random 500 errors, no pattern by time or endpoint, &lt;1% of\nrequests.</li>\n<li>Queue depth grows slowly over hours, then drops to zero\novernight.</li>\n<li>One host in the fleet shows high CPU, others normal.</li>\n<li>4xx errors spike immediately after a deploy.</li>\n<li>Logs show \"Connection refused\" to a downstream service starting at\nmidnight.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Possible Root Causes:</strong></p>\n<p>A. Cert expired at midnight. B. Breaking API change deployed without\nbackward compatibility. C. Memory leak on one host (GC thrashing or\nprocess restart loop). D. Scheduled batch job runs at 3 PM and\noverwhelms the database. E. Consumer fleet undersized, can't keep up\nduring business hours. F. Tail latency issue (p99.9 bad even though p99\nis fine), causing random timeouts that surface as 500s.</p>\n<p><strong>Answer Key:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>→ D (scheduled batch job)</li>\n<li>→ F (tail latency)</li>\n<li>→ E (undersized consumer fleet during day, catches up at night when\ntraffic drops)</li>\n<li>→ C (memory leak on that host)</li>\n<li>→ B (breaking change deployed)</li>\n<li>→ A (cert expired at midnight)</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-changed-today--reflex-drill\">\"What Changed Today?\" — Reflex\nDrill</h2>\n<p><strong>The Reflex:</strong> When anything breaks, the first question\nis \"what changed?\" 80% of prod issues trace to a recent change. Train\nyourself to ask this before you dig into logs.</p>\n<p><strong>Drill:</strong> For each scenario, list the 3 things you'd\ncheck first to answer \"what changed?\"</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario A:</strong> API 5xx spike at 10:15 AM.</p>\n<p><strong>Your Answer:</strong> (Think before scrolling.)</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Was there a deploy between 10:00 and 10:15?</li>\n<li>Did a dependency deploy or have an incident at that time?</li>\n<li>Did traffic pattern change (marketing email, batch job kicked\noff)?</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Scenario B:</strong> Database write throughput drops by 50%\nstarting at 8 AM, no code deploy.</p>\n<p><strong>Your Answer:</strong> (Think before scrolling.)</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Did database capacity (provisioned throughput, autoscaling) get\nchanged?</li>\n<li>Did a schema change or index change deploy overnight?</li>\n<li>Did a scheduled backup or maintenance window start at 8 AM?</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Scenario C:</strong> Your service starts getting \"Access\nDenied\" errors calling S3 at 2 PM, no deploy.</p>\n<p><strong>Your Answer:</strong> (Think before scrolling.)</p>\n<p><strong>Model Answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Did IAM role permissions change?</li>\n<li>Did S3 bucket policy change?</li>\n<li>Did service credentials (assumed role, instance profile) rotate or\nexpire?</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-maps-to-real-work\">How this maps to real work</h2>\n<p>These drills mirror the investigations support engineers run every\nweek: a symptom comes in, you ask what changed, you form one hypothesis,\nyou pull evidence to prove or kill it, you find the root cause, you\nmitigate first and fix second. If you have done production debugging\nbefore, you have already run this loop. Now you drill it until the steps\nare automatic.</p>\n<h2 id=\"rapid-fire-self-test-5-questions\">Rapid-Fire Self-Test (5\nQuestions)</h2>\n<p>Answer in your head, then check below.</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>API 5xx spike + no deploy + started at 10 AM sharp → first thing to\ncheck?</li>\n<li>Queue backing up + consumer logs show no errors + processing time\nnormal → most likely cause?</li>\n<li>One region slow, others fine → where do you look first?</li>\n<li>Random intermittent timeouts to a downstream that claims fast p99 →\nwhat metric do you check?</li>\n<li>Deploy this morning + 4xx spike 1 hour later → first\nhypothesis?</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Answers:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Dependency status or cert expiry (something external changed at 10\nAM).</li>\n<li>Consumer fleet undersized or autoscaling not keeping up with traffic\n(producers faster than consumers).</li>\n<li>Regional resource limits (DDB capacity, Lambda concurrency, NAT\nbandwidth in that region).</li>\n<li>Your p99.9 latency (or connection pool health) — p99 hides tail\nlatency.</li>\n<li>Breaking change in the deploy (API contract changed, stricter\nvalidation, required field added).</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-takeaway\">The Takeaway</h2>\n<p>Troubleshooting is not magic. It's:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Ask \"what changed?\"</li>\n<li>Form one clear hypothesis.</li>\n<li>Gather evidence to prove or kill it.</li>\n<li>Name the root cause.</li>\n<li>Mitigate first (often rollback).</li>\n<li>Fix the root.</li>\n<li>Prevent with alarms + runbooks + tests.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>You've already done this loop a dozen times in your earlier\nexperience. Now drill it until it's automatic. The SE role is 80%\nrunning this loop on different symptoms, 20% operational toil (fleet\nhealth, security patches, pipeline unblocks). Master the loop and the\nrole is yours.</p>\n","text":"troubleshooting drills — the core se muscle what this trains: the 7 step troubleshooting reflex that turns \"something's broken\" into \"here's the root cause, here's the fix, here's how we prevent it\" — the core se skill that runs underneath every ticket, every alarm, every prod incident. the 7 step method (your north star) every se troubleshooting session follows this path, in this order: 1. understand — what broke? who's affected? when did it start? what changed recently? 2. hypothesis — one clear guess at the root cause. state it out loud. 3. evidence — pull logs, metrics, stack traces to prove or kill your hypothesis. killing bad hypotheses is progress. 4. root cause — once evidence confirms, name the actual thing that broke (not just symptoms). 5. mitigate — stop the bleeding. often this means rollback. get customers unstuck first. 6. fix — code change, config update, or operational fix that solves the root cause. 7. prevent — alarm that would catch this earlier next time. runbook update. test that would have caught it pre deploy. the habit is: always understand before you hypothesize, always gather evidence before you act, always mitigate before you chase the perfect fix, always prevent after you close. drill 1 — web app slow (starter) scenario: users report your web app is \"slow to load\" starting about 30 minutes ago. nothing deployed today. load is normal. stop and think. what's your first hypothesis? what evidence do you need? model answer: 1. understand: slow to load = response time spike. started 30 min ago. no deploy, load normal. affects all users or subset? 2. hypothesis: downstream dependency (database, api, cache) is slow or timing out. 3. evidence: check cloudwatch metrics — p99 latency on your service. check dependency call durations (ddb, external api timeouts). check logs for timeout exceptions in the last 30 min. 4. root cause: say evidence shows ddb read latency spiked 30 min ago — something changed in ddb load or capacity. 5. mitigate: if ddb, can you increase provisioned throughput? can you fail fast with cached stale data? is there a circuit breaker you can temporarily open to shed load? 6. fix: if ddb autoscaling wasn't working, fix the scaling config. if a bad query pattern started, fix the query or add an index. 7. prevent: alarm on p99 ddb latency. runbook for \"web app slow\" that checks dependencies first. the most important question you should have asked first: \"did downstream dependency latency change 30 minutes ago?\" (check your dependencies before you dig into your own code.) drill 2 — api 5xx spike (intermediate) scenario: your api starts returning 500 errors at 10:00 am. error rate jumps from 0.1% to 5%. alarm fires. no deploy since yesterday. stop and think. what's your hypothesis? what's the first log line you grep for? model answer: 1. understand: 500 errors = server side failure. started 10 am sharp. no recent deploy. alarm threshold crossed. 2. hypothesis: a dependency started failing (external service, database, auth service), or something in the environment changed (cert expired, network partition, fleet capacity exhausted). 3. evidence: grep logs for stack traces with \"500\" or \"internalserviceexception\" timestamp 10:00 am onward. check exception type — is it timeout, connection refused, null pointer, dependency failure? 4. root cause: say logs show sslhandshakeexception — cert expired at 10 am. 5. mitigate: rotate the cert immediately. restart affected hosts if needed. 6. fix: update cert rotation automation to renew 7 days before expiry, not same day. 7. prevent: alarm on cert expiry < 7 days. runbook for \"api 5xx spike\" that checks certs + dependencies. the most important question you should have asked first: \"what's the exception type in the 500 errors?\" (the stack trace tells you what broke — connection, timeout, null, auth — before you guess.) drill 3 — batch job stuck scenario: a nightly batch job that processes paycodes normally finishes in 20 minutes. tonight it's been running for 3 hours and still not done. logs show it's processing rows but very slowly. this is the first run of the month. stop and think. first run of month is a clue. what's your hypothesis? model answer: 1. understand: batch job slow, not failing. first run of new month. normally 20 min, now 3 hrs. processing continues. 2. hypothesis: data volume spiked (cross month paycodes doubled), or a code path that only fires at month boundaries is inefficient, or database query performance degraded with larger dataset. 3. evidence: check row count being processed — is it 2x normal? check database query duration — are scans taking longer? check logs for any \"duplicate row\" handling or retries. 4. root cause: say logs show duplicate paycode rows being written for employees crossing month boundary. deduplication logic is quadratic — checking every new row against all previous rows. with 2x rows, runtime becomes 4x. 5. mitigate: kill the current run if it's producing bad data. if data is correct but slow, let it finish + add capacity for next run. 6. fix: fix the root cause that creates duplicate rows (date handling bug at month boundary). add unique constraint or idempotency key so duplicates can't be written. optimize dedup logic to o(1) with a set instead of o(n²). 7. prevent: alarm on batch job duration 30 min. add a test case that runs the batch job on cross month data. add a ddb unique constraint or conditional write to catch duplicates before they slow you down. the most important question you should have asked first: \"is the row count being processed larger than usual?\" (volume spike is the simplest hypothesis for 'same code suddenly slow'.) drill 4 — queue backing up (intermediate) scenario: your sqs queue depth is climbing. normally it stays under 100 messages. now it's at 5000 and growing. messages are being enqueued but not processed fast enough. stop and think. is the problem on the producer side or consumer side? what's your hypothesis? model answer: 1. understand: queue depth climbing = producers faster than consumers, or consumers stuck/slow. normally balanced. started when? 2. hypothesis: consumers are slow (processing time increased), or consumers are failing/crashing and restarting, or producer traffic spiked. 3. evidence: check consumer fleet size (autoscaling working?). check consumer processing time per message (cloudwatch metric). check producer message rate (did traffic spike?). check consumer logs for errors or timeouts. 4. root cause: say evidence shows consumer processing time jumped from 100ms to 5 seconds per message because a downstream dependency (ddb, api) is slow. 5. mitigate: scale up consumer fleet manually to drain the queue faster. if dependency is broken, can you fail fast or use cached data to speed up processing? 6. fix: fix the slow dependency. if ddb, add capacity or optimize the query. if api, fix the timeout or add circuit breaker. 7. prevent: alarm on queue depth 1000. alarm on consumer processing time 1 second. runbook for \"queue backing up\" that checks consumer health + dependency latency first. the most important question you should have asked first: \"did consumer processing time per message change?\" (if processing is slow, scaling consumers helps. if processing is broken, scaling makes it worse.) drill 5 — latency only in one region (tricky) scenario: api latency is normal in us west 2 and eu west 1, but p99 latency in ap southeast 1 is 5x higher. started an hour ago. no regional deploy differences. stop and think. regional difference = regional resource or network issue. what's your hypothesis? model answer: 1. understand: one region slow, others fine. started 1 hour ago. same code deployed everywhere. 2. hypothesis: regional resource exhausted (ddb capacity, lambda concurrency, nat gateway bandwidth), or network issue (cross az latency, internet gateway), or regional dependency failing (cache, database replica lag). 3. evidence: check regional ddb consumed capacity vs provisioned. check lambda throttles in that region. check vpc flow logs for packet loss or retransmits. check if the region calls a different dependency endpoint (regional cache, regional ddb replica). 4. root cause: say evidence shows ddb autoscaling in ap southeast 1 lagged behind traffic spike — capacity didn't scale fast enough, reads are throttled. 5. mitigate: manually increase ddb capacity in ap southeast 1 to match traffic. 6. fix: adjust ddb autoscaling policy to scale faster (lower target utilization or faster cooldown). investigate why traffic spiked in that region only. 7. prevent: alarm on ddb throttled requests per region. runbook for \"latency spike in one region\" that checks regional resource limits first. the most important question you should have asked first: \"is a regional resource (ddb, lambda, nat) throttling or exhausted in the slow region?\" (regional problems = regional resource or network first.) drill 6 — intermittent timeouts (hard) scenario: your api randomly times out 1 2% of requests. no pattern by time of day or endpoint. logs show timeout after 3 seconds on calls to a downstream service. that downstream service's own metrics show p99 latency is only 200ms. stop and think. downstream says they're fast, but you're timing out. what gives? model answer: 1. understand: 1 2% random timeouts. downstream claims fast. your timeout is 3 seconds. 2. hypothesis: downstream has a tail latency problem (p99 is fine but p99.9 is bad), or network issue between you and them (packet loss, retries), or your connection pool is exhausted and new connections are slow, or your retry logic is broken (retry on timeout creates more timeouts). 3. evidence: check your p99.9 latency to downstream (not just p99). check connection pool metrics (active connections, wait time). check network metrics (packet retransmits, connection resets). check if timeouts cluster by host or by downstream endpoint. 4. root cause: say evidence shows your connection pool is size 10, and under load all 10 are busy. new requests wait for a free connection, timeout after 3 seconds. downstream is actually fast, but your connection reuse is broken. 5. mitigate: increase connection pool size to 50. restart hosts to clear any stuck connections. 6. fix: set connection pool size based on expected concurrency (not a magic number). add connection pool health checks. fix any connection leak in your code. 7. prevent: alarm on connection pool exhaustion (active connections = max pool size). runbook for \"intermittent timeouts\" that checks connection pool + network first. the most important question you should have asked first: \"what's our p99.9 latency to the downstream, not just p99?\" (tail latency kills. p99 = 200ms doesn't tell you p99.9 might be 10 seconds.) drill 7 — deploy this morning (common se scenario) scenario: a new version deployed to production at 9 am. at 10 am, alarms fire for increased 4xx errors (from 0.5% to 3%). logs show validationexception: missing required field 'employeeid' . stop and think. deploy this morning + new errors = what's your hypothesis? model answer: 1. understand: new deploy at 9 am. errors started 10 am (1 hour later, likely phased rollout). 4xx = client error (your api rejecting requests). validationexception = your code. 2. hypothesis: new deploy introduced stricter validation or changed the api contract. clients that worked yesterday are now being rejected. 3. evidence: check the diff in the deploy — was there a schema change, a new required field, or stricter validation logic? check which clients are failing (old version, specific integration, mobile app). check if the api docs were updated or if this was a breaking change. 4. root cause: deploy added employeeid as a required field. existing clients don't send it. breaking change shipped without backward compatibility. 5. mitigate: rollback the deploy immediately to unblock clients. or make employeeid optional in the current code, validate it only if present. 6. fix: make the field optional with a default, or version the api so new clients use v2 with the required field, old clients stay on v1. 7. prevent: backward compatibility check in pre deploy testing. canary deploy with alarm on 4xx rate increase. api contract review in cr process. the most important question you should have asked first: \"what changed in the deploy that could cause validationexception?\" (deploy + new error = code diff first.) drill 8 — downstream dependency failing scenario: your service calls the downstream routing api (a scheduling api) to fetch schedule data. suddenly 30% of calls return a routing not found error . the downstream routing api team says their service is healthy. alarm fires. logs show the exception started 2 hours ago. stop and think. the downstream routing api says they're healthy but you're getting exceptions. what's your hypothesis? model answer: 1. understand: 30% failure rate calling the downstream routing api. exception = a routing not found error . the downstream routing api team claims healthy. started 2 hours ago. 2. hypothesis: routing issue in the downstream routing api's gateway (profile mismatch, missing route for a subset of employees), or your request format changed and the downstream routing api can't route it, or network/dns issue between you and the downstream routing api. 3. evidence: check which employees are failing — is there a pattern (country, hire date, employee type)? check the downstream routing api logs for the same employeeids — do they see the requests? check your request payload — did you change the operation name or profile routing parameters? check the downstream routing api's routing cascade (operation id profile, domain profile, default). 4. root cause: say evidence shows failing employees are missing an employee data profiles assignment. the downstream routing api's routing cascade tries operation profile (miss), domain profile (miss), default profile (miss) → a routing not found error . not the downstream routing api's fault, not your fault — data gap in the employee data source. 5. mitigate: get the employee data team to backfill missing profiles for affected employees. or add a fallback in your code to handle a routing not found error gracefully (use cached data, skip enrichment, log and continue). 6. fix: work with the employee data team to ensure all employees get profile assignments at hire. add a validation step in your onboarding flow to catch missing profiles early. 7. prevent: alarm on a routing not found error rate 1%. runbook for the downstream routing api failures that checks employee profile assignment first. add a pre call validation (if profile missing, don't call the downstream routing api). the most important question you should have asked first: \"which employees are failing — is there a common attribute?\" (pattern in failures = data driven root cause, not code.) drill 9 — disk filling on a host (operational se task) scenario: alarm fires: disk utilization on one host in your fleet is at 85%, climbing. normally hosts stay under 40%. the host is still serving traffic. stop and think. one host, not the whole fleet = host specific issue. what's your hypothesis? model answer: 1. understand: disk filling on one host. others fine. still serving traffic. started when? 2. hypothesis: log rotation broken on that host, or a batch job writing temp files and not cleaning up, or a memory leak causing core dumps or heap dumps to pile up. 3. evidence: ssh to the host. run df h to see which partition is full. run du sh / to see which directory is eating space. check /var/log size, /tmp size, application log directory size. 4. root cause: say evidence shows /var/log/application.log is 50 gb. log rotation config is broken or not applied to this host. 5. mitigate: manually rotate or compress old logs to free space immediately. if needed, terminate and replace the host (since it's in an asg). 6. fix: fix log rotation config fleet wide (logrotate.d or cloudwatch logs agent config). verify all hosts have the correct config deployed. 7. prevent: alarm on disk utilization per host 70%. runbook for \"disk full\" that checks log rotation + temp file cleanup first. fleet health check that validates log rotation config on all hosts. the most important question you should have asked first: \"which directory on the host is consuming the most disk space?\" ( du sh / tells you where to look — logs, temp files, core dumps, or application data.) drill 10 — cert expired (classic ops failure) scenario: at 3 am, alarms fire for 100% 5xx errors on your api. logs show sslhandshakeexception on every request. the service was healthy at 2 am. on call wakes up. stop and think. sudden 100% failure at 3 am sharp = something expired or rotated. what's your hypothesis? model answer: 1. understand: 100% 5xx, every request. sslhandshakeexception = ssl/tls failure. happened at 3 am sharp. service was fine 1 hour ago. 2. hypothesis: ssl cert expired at 3 am, or cert rotation job ran and broke something, or a dependency's cert expired and you can't connect to them. 3. evidence: check your cert expiry date (openssl or acm console). check logs for which cert is failing (your own or a downstream). check if a cert rotation job ran at 3 am. 4. root cause: your own cert expired at 3 am. cert rotation automation didn't run or failed silently. 5. mitigate: manually renew the cert and deploy it immediately. restart hosts to pick up new cert. if you can't renew fast enough, failover to a secondary cert or endpoint. 6. fix: fix cert rotation automation to renew 7 days before expiry. add retries and alerting to the rotation job. if manual cert, replace with acm auto renewal. 7. prevent: alarm on cert expiry < 7 days. alarm if cert rotation job fails. runbook for \"ssl failures\" that checks cert expiry first. the most important question you should have asked first: \"when does our ssl cert expire?\" (exact time failures = expiry or scheduled job. check the cert date before you dig deeper.) symptom vs root cause — matching drill instructions: for each symptom, pick the most likely root cause from the list. then check the answer key. symptoms: 1. api latency spikes every day at 3 pm for 10 minutes. 2. random 500 errors, no pattern by time or endpoint, <1% of requests. 3. queue depth grows slowly over hours, then drops to zero overnight. 4. one host in the fleet shows high cpu, others normal. 5. 4xx errors spike immediately after a deploy. 6. logs show \"connection refused\" to a downstream service starting at midnight. possible root causes: a. cert expired at midnight. b. breaking api change deployed without backward compatibility. c. memory leak on one host (gc thrashing or process restart loop). d. scheduled batch job runs at 3 pm and overwhelms the database. e. consumer fleet undersized, can't keep up during business hours. f. tail latency issue (p99.9 bad even though p99 is fine), causing random timeouts that surface as 500s. answer key: 1. → d (scheduled batch job) 2. → f (tail latency) 3. → e (undersized consumer fleet during day, catches up at night when traffic drops) 4. → c (memory leak on that host) 5. → b (breaking change deployed) 6. → a (cert expired at midnight) \"what changed today?\" — reflex drill the reflex: when anything breaks, the first question is \"what changed?\" 80% of prod issues trace to a recent change. train yourself to ask this before you dig into logs. drill: for each scenario, list the 3 things you'd check first to answer \"what changed?\" scenario a: api 5xx spike at 10:15 am. your answer: (think before scrolling.) model answer: 1. was there a deploy between 10:00 and 10:15? 2. did a dependency deploy or have an incident at that time? 3. did traffic pattern change (marketing email, batch job kicked off)? scenario b: database write throughput drops by 50% starting at 8 am, no code deploy. your answer: (think before scrolling.) model answer: 1. did database capacity (provisioned throughput, autoscaling) get changed? 2. did a schema change or index change deploy overnight? 3. did a scheduled backup or maintenance window start at 8 am? scenario c: your service starts getting \"access denied\" errors calling s3 at 2 pm, no deploy. your answer: (think before scrolling.) model answer: 1. did iam role permissions change? 2. did s3 bucket policy change? 3. did service credentials (assumed role, instance profile) rotate or expire? how this maps to real work these drills mirror the investigations support engineers run every week: a symptom comes in, you ask what changed, you form one hypothesis, you pull evidence to prove or kill it, you find the root cause, you mitigate first and fix second. if you have done production debugging before, you have already run this loop. now you drill it until the steps are automatic. rapid fire self test (5 questions) answer in your head, then check below. 1. api 5xx spike + no deploy + started at 10 am sharp → first thing to check? 2. queue backing up + consumer logs show no errors + processing time normal → most likely cause? 3. one region slow, others fine → where do you look first? 4. random intermittent timeouts to a downstream that claims fast p99 → what metric do you check? 5. deploy this morning + 4xx spike 1 hour later → first hypothesis? answers: 1. dependency status or cert expiry (something external changed at 10 am). 2. consumer fleet undersized or autoscaling not keeping up with traffic (producers faster than consumers). 3. regional resource limits (ddb capacity, lambda concurrency, nat bandwidth in that region). 4. your p99.9 latency (or connection pool health) — p99 hides tail latency. 5. breaking change in the deploy (api contract changed, stricter validation, required field added). the takeaway troubleshooting is not magic. it's: 1. ask \"what changed?\" 2. form one clear hypothesis. 3. gather evidence to prove or kill it. 4. name the root cause. 5. mitigate first (often rollback). 6. fix the root. 7. prevent with alarms + runbooks + tests. you've already done this loop a dozen times in your earlier experience. now drill it until it's automatic. the se role is 80% running this loop on different symptoms, 20% operational toil (fleet health, security patches, pipeline unblocks). master the loop and the role is yours.","words":3661},{"id":"training-on-call-incident-drills","section":"Training","title":"On-call & incident drills","html":"<h1 id=\"on-call-and-incident-management-drills\">On-Call and\nIncident-Management Drills</h1>\n<p><strong>What this trains:</strong> The reflexes you need when a page\nfires — triage severity, quantify impact, pull the right evidence, post\nupdates, escalate at the right time, and ship customer-facing summaries\nthat read like a human wrote them at 3am.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-basics--severities-sla-escalation-handoff\">The Basics —\nSeverities, SLA, Escalation, Handoff</h2>\n<p><strong>Severities (a tech company standard):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sev-1:</strong> Huge customer impact. Revenue down, site\ncan't load, data breach. All hands. Rare.</li>\n<li><strong>Sev-2:</strong> Serious customer impact. Feature broken for\na region, orders failing for a category, login issues for a segment. You\npage people. Common enough.</li>\n<li><strong>Sev-3:</strong> Smaller customer impact. Single feature\ndegraded, one workflow slow, edge case broken. Fix during business\nhours.</li>\n<li><strong>Sev-5:</strong> Tiny or test-only. No customer sees it. Log\nit, fix when convenient.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>SLA = the clock.</strong> Sev-2 might have a 30-min ack SLA\n(you must acknowledge the page within 30 min) and a 4-hour resolution\ntarget. Miss it and the ticket escalates automatically or your manager\ngets pinged. The SLA is not a suggestion — it's the contract with the\ncustomer.</p>\n<p><strong>Escalation = bringing help, NOT handing off.</strong> You\nstay on the ticket. You pull in another SE, a dev, an oncall from the\ndownstream team. You're coordinating, they're investigating in parallel.\nEscalation is a team sport, not a relay race.</p>\n<p><strong>Handoff = when your shift ends or you physically can't\ncontinue.</strong> Write a full summary in the ticket (what you found,\nwhat you tried, what's still unknown, next step), assign to the next\noncall, ping them on Slack. No handoff without a summary. No summary =\nthe next person starts from zero and you just burned 2 hours of their\nlife.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-first-60-seconds--reflex-protocol\">The First 60 Seconds —\nReflex Protocol</h2>\n<p>A page fires. Your phone buzzes. Alarm shows in the ticketing system\n(like Jira or PagerDuty) dashboard. Here's what you do in the first\nminute, every time:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Acknowledge the page.</strong> Click \"ack\" in the ticketing\nsystem (like Jira or PagerDuty) app or reply to the Slack bot. This\nstops the escalation timer.</li>\n<li><strong>Read the alarm description.</strong> What metric fired? What\nthreshold? What region/stage?</li>\n<li><strong>Quantify impact.</strong> Open CloudWatch. How many errors\nin the last 5 min? How many customers hit this API in the last hour? Is\nit 10 errors or 10,000?</li>\n<li><strong>Post an initial update in the ticket.</strong> Template:\n\"Acknowledged. [Metric X] fired at [time]. Investigating. Will update in\n15 min.\" This buys you time and signals to the customer (and your\nmanager, who might be watching) that you're on it.</li>\n<li><strong>Pull the runbook.</strong> Every alarm should link to a\nrunbook. If it doesn't, you're writing one after this incident\ncloses.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>That's 60 seconds. After that, you're into investigation mode\n(understand → hypothesis → evidence → root cause → mitigate → fix →\nprevent). But the first 60 is pure reflex. Ack, quantify, post, runbook.\nEvery time.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"scenario-drill-1--the-triple-ticket-collision\">Scenario Drill 1\n— The Triple-Ticket Collision</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> You're on-call. You already have 3 open\nSev-3 tickets (a timeout issue you're tracing, a config question from a\nPM, a log-noise cleanup request). A Sev-2 page fires: API latency spiked\nto 8 seconds, 200 customers affected in the last 10 minutes.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP. What do you do first?</strong></p>\n<p>Think: priority, not sequence. The Sev-2 is the new top of the stack.\nThe Sev-3s don't go away, but they pause.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk-through:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Ack the Sev-2 page immediately.</li>\n<li>Post a holding update on each of the 3 Sev-3 tickets: \"Sev-2 came\nin, pausing this for [X hours]. Will resume once the customer-impacting\nissue is mitigated.\"</li>\n<li>Quantify the Sev-2 impact in CloudWatch. 200 customers, 8-sec\nlatency, started 10 min ago. That's real and recent.</li>\n<li>Open the latency runbook. Step 1: check downstream dependencies.\nStep 2: check recent deploys. Step 3: check DB query times.</li>\n<li>Mitigate first (rollback if there was a deploy, throttle if it's a\ntraffic spike, kill the slow query if it's a DB issue). Fix root cause\nsecond.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>LP shown:</strong> Customer Obsession (drop lower-priority\nwork to handle customer impact), Bias for Action (mitigate before you\nhave the full root cause), Ownership (you don't hand off the Sev-3s, you\njust pause them with clear communication).</p>\n<p><strong>Trade-off reasoned:</strong> You can't work 4 tickets in\nparallel. Severity decides the order. The Sev-3s wait. If one of them\nwas actually urgent, it would have been filed as a higher sev.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"scenario-drill-2--the-2am-non-reproducible\">Scenario Drill 2 —\nThe 2am Non-Reproducible</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> 2:47am. Sev-2 page: \"OrderSubmit API\nreturning 500s.\" You roll out of bed, ack the page, check CloudWatch.\nThe alarm fired at 2:42am. But when you hit the API in staging or prod\n(via Postman or curl), it returns 200. Metrics show 3 errors in the last\nhour, all at 2:42am. Now it's silent.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP. What do you do?</strong></p>\n<p>Think: transient vs persistent. If the error isn't happening now, you\ncan't fix it live. But you still need to find the cause so it doesn't\nhappen again.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk-through:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Post an update: \"Acknowledged. Metrics show 3 errors at 2:42am. API\nresponding normally now. Investigating logs for the failure\nwindow.\"</li>\n<li>Pull CloudWatch Logs Insights for the 2:40-2:45am window. Filter by\n<code>level=ERROR</code> or <code>status=500</code>. Look for stack\ntraces, exception types, employee IDs.</li>\n<li>Check for a deploy or config change around that time. Was there a\nrollout between 2:30-2:45? A pipeline stage promotion? An a runtime\nconfig service flag flip?</li>\n<li>Check downstream service health. Did a dependency (DynamoDB, S3,\nanother internal API) have a blip at 2:42am? Cross-reference their\nCloudWatch metrics.</li>\n<li>If you find the cause (e.g., DDB throttle, transient network error,\nbrief Lambda cold-start surge), document it in the ticket. If it's a\none-off transient, close with \"Mitigated by [dependency recovery].\nMonitoring for recurrence. Runbook updated to check [X] during future\nnon-reproducibles.\"</li>\n<li>If you can't find the cause after 90 min, escalate to a dev who owns\nthat API. Attach your investigation (CW log snippets, the exact 2:42am\nerror stack, what you ruled out).</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>LP shown:</strong> Dive Deep (you didn't just close the\nticket when the error stopped, you pulled logs and traced the timeline),\nLearn and Be Curious (you updated the runbook so the next oncall has a\nbetter checklist), Insist on Highest Standards (you didn't accept \"it\nwent away\" as an answer).</p>\n<p><strong>Trade-off reasoned:</strong> At 2am with a transient issue,\nthe choice is: burn 4 hours chasing a ghost vs document what you know\nand escalate if you're stuck. 90 min is the cutoff. After that, bring\nhelp.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"scenario-drill-3--the-alarm-firing-no-customer-complaint\">Scenario\nDrill 3 — The Alarm Firing, No Customer Complaint</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Sev-3 alarm fires: \"DDB read throttle on\nEmployeeTable exceeds 10/min for 5 consecutive minutes.\" You check the\nticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) queue. No customer tickets. No\nSlack pings from PMs. Metrics show the throttle started 20 min ago and\nis still happening. The API using that table is still returning 200s (it\nhas retry logic).</p>\n<p><strong>STOP. What do you do?</strong></p>\n<p>Think: no customer impact YET doesn't mean no problem. The alarm\nfired for a reason. This is proactive vs reactive.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk-through:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Ack the alarm. Post an update: \"DDB throttle detected on\nEmployeeTable. No customer tickets yet. API retries are succeeding.\nInvestigating to prevent customer-visible impact.\"</li>\n<li>Check DDB CloudWatch metrics. What's the actual RCU consumption vs\nprovisioned capacity? Is this a traffic spike or a slow query?</li>\n<li>Check the API code. Is there a new query pattern that's reading more\nrows than it should? Did a recent deploy add a scan where there used to\nbe a get-item?</li>\n<li>If it's a traffic spike: check if today is a peak day (payroll\ncutoff, open enrollment, Prime Day). If yes, scale up the DDB table or\nswitch to on-demand billing temporarily.</li>\n<li>If it's a slow query: file a ticket to optimize the query (add a\nGSI, batch the reads, cache the result). Meanwhile, monitor. If the\nthrottle starts causing API timeouts, escalate to Sev-2.</li>\n<li>Close the Sev-3 with \"Throttle mitigated by [scaling / caching].\nRoot cause: [traffic spike / slow query]. Preventive action: [filed\nticket to optimize query / set up auto-scaling].\"</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>LP shown:</strong> Ownership (you didn't wait for a customer\nto complain, you acted on the alarm), Insist on Highest Standards (you\ntreated \"no impact yet\" as \"opportunity to prevent impact\"), Bias for\nAction (you scaled or filed a ticket instead of just monitoring).</p>\n<p><strong>Trade-off reasoned:</strong> An alarm with no customer\ncomplaint is still an alarm. Silence it by fixing the root cause, not by\nignoring it.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"scenario-drill-4--the-screaming-customer-calm-metrics\">Scenario\nDrill 4 — The Screaming Customer, Calm Metrics</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Sev-2 ticket lands from a PM: \"Customer\nreports OrderSubmit API is down. They've tried 10 times in the last 5\nminutes, all failed. Urgent.\" You check CloudWatch. API error rate:\n0.01% (baseline noise). Latency: p99 200ms (normal). No alarms. No spike\nin 500s.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP. What do you do?</strong></p>\n<p>Think: the customer's reality is the only reality that matters, even\nif your metrics disagree. Either your metrics are missing something, or\nthe customer hit an edge case.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk-through:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Ack the ticket. Post an update: \"Acknowledged. API metrics look\nnormal globally. Investigating customer-specific failure. Need customer\ndetails: employee ID, timestamp of one failed attempt, any error message\nthey saw.\"</li>\n<li>Reply to the PM: \"Can you get the customer's employee ID and the\nexact time of one failed request? That'll let me pull their specific\nlogs.\"</li>\n<li>Once you have the employee ID + timestamp, run a CloudWatch Logs\nInsights query filtered by\n<code>employeeId=X AND timestamp BETWEEN [Y] AND [Z]</code>. Look for\ntheir request in the logs.</li>\n<li>Common findings:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Customer in a region you didn't monitor.</strong> Your alarm\nonly tracks <code>us-east-1</code>, they're in <code>eu-west-1</code>\nand that stage is broken.</li>\n<li><strong>Customer has a specific data pattern that triggers a\nvalidation bug.</strong> Their employee record has a null field your\ncode doesn't handle.</li>\n<li><strong>Customer's client is sending a malformed request.</strong>\nThey're on an old version of the mobile app that sends a deprecated\nfield.</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"5\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Once you find the root cause, mitigate it (fix the region, deploy a\nnull-check, ask the PM to tell the customer to update their app).</li>\n<li>Update your alarms to cover the gap. If this was a regional miss,\nadd alarms for all regions. If this was a validation edge case, add a\nmetric for that specific error type.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>LP shown:</strong> Customer Obsession (you believed the\ncustomer even when your metrics didn't, and you dug until you found\ntheir specific failure), Dive Deep (you didn't stop at \"metrics look\nfine,\" you went customer-by-customer), Earn Trust (you responded with\n\"I'll investigate\" not \"the API is fine, must be user error\").</p>\n<p><strong>Trade-off reasoned:</strong> Global metrics hide individual\nfailures. When a customer says it's broken, it's broken for them, even\nif it's not broken for everyone.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"scenario-drill-5--the-downstream-blame-game\">Scenario Drill 5 —\nThe Downstream Blame Game</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Sev-2: \"GetEmployeeSchedule API timing out\nfor 50% of requests.\" You check your service. Your code is fine. Logs\nshow your API calls the downstream <code>ScheduleDataService</code>\n(owned by another team) and waits forever. You check their CloudWatch.\nTheir API is returning 200s but latency is 30 seconds (normally 200ms).\nNo alarm on their side because their p99 latency alarm is set to 60\nseconds.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP. What do you do?</strong></p>\n<p>Think: the customer doesn't care whose fault it is. Your API is\ntiming out, so it's your problem to fix, even if the root cause is\ndownstream.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk-through:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Ack the Sev-2. Post an update: \"Acknowledged. Root cause: downstream\nScheduleDataService latency spiked to 30s. Engaging their oncall.\nMitigating by [reducing timeout / returning cached data / failing fast\nwith a clear error].\"</li>\n<li>Ping the downstream team's oncall on Slack or via their the\nticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) page-bot. Include the data:\n\"Your API latency is 30s since [time]. Our API is timing out waiting for\nyou. Can you investigate?\"</li>\n<li><strong>While you wait for them, mitigate on your side.</strong>\nOptions:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Lower your timeout from 60s to 5s so your API fails fast instead of\nhanging.</li>\n<li>Return cached schedule data if you have it (stale data &gt; no data\nfor some use cases).</li>\n<li>Return a 503 with a clear error message: \"Schedule service\ntemporarily unavailable. Try again in 5 minutes.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Once the downstream team fixes their latency, verify your API\nrecovers. Close your Sev-2 with \"Mitigated by [failing fast]. Root\ncause: downstream ScheduleDataService latency. Resolved by their team at\n[time]. Preventive action: added alarm for downstream API latency.\"</li>\n<li>After the incident, file a ticket with the downstream team: \"Your\np99 latency alarm is set too high. 30s latency breaks our SLA. Can you\nlower it to 5s so your oncall catches this before it cascades?\"</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>LP shown:</strong> Ownership (you didn't just blame the\ndownstream team, you mitigated on your side while they investigated),\nBias for Action (you failed fast instead of waiting for them to fix it),\nEarn Trust (you documented the root cause clearly so there's no\nfinger-pointing later).</p>\n<p><strong>Trade-off reasoned:</strong> When a downstream dependency is\nslow, you have two jobs: 1) mitigate the impact on your customers, 2)\nhelp the downstream team fix their root cause. Both jobs are yours, not\njust #2.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"scenario-drill-6--the-90-minute-stuck-point\">Scenario Drill 6 —\nThe 90-Minute Stuck Point</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Sev-2: \"SubmitPaycode API returning 500s\nfor another region employees.\" You've been investigating for 90 minutes.\nYou found the error in the logs:\n<code>NullPointerException in PaycodeValidator line 127</code>. You\ntraced it to a recent deploy 3 hours ago. But you can't figure out WHY\nthe deploy broke another region specifically — the code looks the same\nfor all countries. You've tried rolling back in staging, but the\nrollback didn't help (the bug might have been latent for longer). You've\npulled 3 sample employee IDs and their data looks normal. You're\nstuck.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP. What do you do?</strong></p>\n<p>Think: 90 minutes is the cutoff. After that, you're burning time\nwithout progress. Escalation = bringing help, not handing off.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk-through:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Post an update in the ticket: \"90 min in. Root cause narrowed to NPE\nin PaycodeValidator line 127, another region-specific. Attempted\nrollback in staging, issue persists. Escalating to dev oncall for\ncode-path review. Staying on ticket.\"</li>\n<li>Page the dev oncall (or Slack the team's oncall channel if they have\none). Message: \"Sev-2 in prod, another region paycode 500s, 90 min\nstuck. NPE in PaycodeValidator line 127. I've pulled logs [link], tried\nrollback [result]. Need help tracing why another region is different.\nCan you pair with me?\"</li>\n<li><strong>You stay on the ticket.</strong> You're the context-keeper.\nThe dev is the code expert. You show them the logs, the error line, the\nsample employee data. They spot the pattern (maybe another region\nemployees have a <code>null</code> paycode field that other countries\ndon't, and the recent deploy removed a null-check).</li>\n<li>Once they identify the fix, you coordinate the deploy. They push the\npull request, you verify it in staging, you approve the prod rollout,\nyou monitor the metrics post-deploy.</li>\n<li>Close the ticket with \"Mitigated by [re-adding null-check]. Root\ncause: recent deploy removed validation for null paycode field, another\nregion employees hit this edge case. Escalated at 90-min mark, resolved\nwith dev oncall assistance.\"</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>LP shown:</strong> Bias for Action (you escalated at the\nright time instead of spinning for 3 hours), Earn Trust (you stayed on\nthe ticket and coordinated the fix instead of handing it off), Learn and\nBe Curious (you'll document this pattern so the next oncall knows\n\"another region-specific bug = check for null fields in employee\ndata\").</p>\n<p><strong>Trade-off reasoned:</strong> The 90-120 min mark is the\nescalation window. Before that, you're expected to exhaust the runbook.\nAfter that, you're expected to bring help. Escalation is not failure —\nit's the protocol.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"scenario-drill-7--the-peak-day-surge-prime-day-black-friday\">Scenario\nDrill 7 — The Peak-Day Surge (Prime Day, Black Friday)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> It's Prime Day. 10am PST. Traffic is 10x\nnormal. Your <code>GetEmployeeSchedule</code> API is handling the load\nfine (you scaled up the fleet yesterday). But at 10:47am, a Sev-2 alarm\nfires: \"DDB write throttle on ScheduleTable exceeds 100/min.\" The API\nthat WRITES schedules (used by managers updating shifts) is now timing\nout. You check the fleet: all instances are healthy. You check DDB:\nwrite capacity is provisioned at 1000 WCU, but actual consumption is\n1200 WCU.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP. What do you do?</strong></p>\n<p>Think: peak day = every decision is high-stakes. Scaling up is safe\nif you do it incrementally. Scaling down is dangerous if you do it\nduring the surge.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk-through:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Ack the alarm. Post an update: \"Acknowledged. Prime Day traffic\nsurge. DDB write throttle on ScheduleTable. Scaling up write capacity\nnow. ETA 5 min.\"</li>\n<li>Open the DDB console. Increase write capacity from 1000 WCU to 2000\nWCU. (On-demand billing is safer for peak days if your service supports\nit, but if you're on provisioned, double the capacity as a first\nstep.)</li>\n<li>Monitor for 5 minutes. Did the throttle stop? Did the write API\nlatency drop? If yes, you're good. If no, scale again to 3000 WCU.</li>\n<li>Post a follow-up update in the ticket: \"Write capacity scaled to\n2000 WCU. Throttle resolved. API latency back to normal. Monitoring for\nremainder of Prime Day.\"</li>\n<li><strong>Do NOT scale back down until Prime Day ends.</strong>\nScaling down mid-surge can cause another throttle. Wait until traffic\ndrops to baseline (usually 24 hours after the event).</li>\n<li>After Prime Day, write a post-mortem: \"Prime Day traffic was 10x\nbaseline. DDB write throttle at 1000 WCU, scaled to 2000.\nRecommendation: pre-scale to 2000 WCU before next Prime Day, or switch\nto on-demand billing.\"</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>LP shown:</strong> Bias for Action (you scaled immediately\ninstead of waiting to see if the throttle would resolve itself), Insist\non Highest Standards (you monitored after scaling to confirm it worked),\nCustomer Obsession (you kept the write API available for managers who\nneeded to update schedules during the surge).</p>\n<p><strong>Trade-off reasoned:</strong> Peak days are not the time to\nexperiment. Scale up conservatively, monitor, and don't scale down until\nthe event is over. The cost of over-provisioning for 24 hours is tiny\ncompared to the cost of another outage.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"scenario-drill-8--the-bad-deploy-mid-rollout\">Scenario Drill 8 —\nThe Bad Deploy Mid-Rollout</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> You're monitoring a deploy of\n<code>the time-tracking service</code> rolling out to prod. Stage 1 (1%\nof fleet): green. Stage 2 (10% of fleet): green. Stage 3 (50% of fleet):\nalarm fires. <code>the GetEmployeeBalance API</code> API error rate\nspiked from 0% to 5% in the last 5 minutes. The alarm is only firing on\nthe 50% of instances running the new version. The other 50% (old\nversion) are fine.</p>\n<p><strong>STOP. What do you do?</strong></p>\n<p>Think: a deploy that breaks at 50% is a code bug in the new version.\nRollback immediately. Root cause investigation happens after.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk-through:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Ack the alarm. Post an update: \"Acknowledged. the GetEmployeeBalance\nAPI error rate spike during prod deploy. Rolling back now.\"</li>\n<li>Open the pipeline. Click \"Rollback\" on Stage 3. This reverts the 50%\nof instances to the previous version.</li>\n<li>Monitor for 5 minutes. Did the error rate drop back to 0%? If yes,\nrollback succeeded.</li>\n<li>Post a follow-up update: \"Rollback complete. Error rate back to 0%.\nInvestigating root cause in new version. Deploy paused.\"</li>\n<li>Pull the logs from the 50% that had the new version. Filter by\n<code>level=ERROR AND version=[new-version-number]</code>. Look for the\nstack trace.</li>\n<li>Open the pull request for the deploy. Check what changed in the\nGetEmployeeBalance API code path. Did someone add a new dependency?\nChange a query? Remove a null-check?</li>\n<li>Once you find the bug, file a ticket with the dev team. Attach the\nlogs, the stack trace, the pull request link. Mark the deploy as\n\"blocked until [ticket] is resolved.\"</li>\n<li>Close the Sev-2 with \"Mitigated by rollback. Root cause: [bug in new\nversion]. Deploy paused. Dev team notified via [ticket link].\"</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>LP shown:</strong> Bias for Action (you rolled back\nimmediately when the alarm fired, you didn't wait to investigate first),\nCustomer Obsession (you prioritized stopping the customer impact over\nfiguring out the root cause), Ownership (you paused the deploy and\ncoordinated with the dev team to fix the bug before retrying).</p>\n<p><strong>Trade-off reasoned:</strong> When a deploy breaks, rollback\nfirst, investigate second. The faster you rollback, the fewer customers\nare affected.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-escalate-vs-keep-going-decision-rule\">The\nEscalate-vs-Keep-Going Decision Rule</h2>\n<p><strong>Escalate (bring help) when:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>You've been stuck for 90-120 minutes with no progress.</li>\n<li>You've exhausted the runbook and don't know the next step.</li>\n<li>The issue requires code changes and you're not a dev.</li>\n<li>The root cause is in a service you don't own.</li>\n<li>You're drowning in multiple Sev-2s at once.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Keep going when:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>You're making progress (each step is ruling out a hypothesis or\nnarrowing the root cause).</li>\n<li>The runbook has more steps you haven't tried yet.</li>\n<li>You have a clear next action (e.g., \"try rolling back,\" \"scale up\nDDB,\" \"check downstream service health\").</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Escalation is bringing help, not handing off.</strong> You\nstay on the ticket. You coordinate. The person you escalate to\ninvestigates in parallel. You're the context-keeper, they're the\nspecialist.</p>\n<p><strong>Example escalation message (Slack):</strong></p>\n<pre><code>Sev-2 in prod, GetEmployeeSchedule timeouts, 90 min stuck.\nRoot cause: downstream ScheduleDataService latency 30s (normally 200ms).\nI&#39;ve mitigated by lowering our timeout to 5s.\nCan your oncall investigate why your API is slow?\nLogs: [CW link]\nTicket: [the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) link]</code></pre>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"write-the-customer-update--mini-drill\">Write the Customer Update\n— Mini-Drill</h2>\n<p><strong>Raw technical incident:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Alarm: DDB write throttle on\n<code>PaycodeSubmissionTable</code></li>\n<li>Impact: 200 customers unable to submit paycodes for 15 minutes\n(10:30am-10:45am PST)</li>\n<li>Root cause: traffic surge from a bulk paycode upload job running\nduring peak hours</li>\n<li>Mitigation: scaled DDB write capacity from 500 WCU to 1500 WCU</li>\n<li>Prevention: scheduled bulk jobs to run during off-peak hours\n(1am-5am PST)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Your task:</strong> Write a 3-sentence customer-facing update\n(what broke / what we did / what prevents recurrence). Non-technical\nlanguage. No jargon. Reads like a human wrote it at 3am.</p>\n<p><strong>Model answer:</strong></p>\n<pre><code>Between 10:30am and 10:45am PST today, the paycode submission feature was unavailable for approximately 200 employees due to a traffic surge from a scheduled background job. We mitigated the issue by increasing system capacity, and the feature is now fully operational. We&#39;ve rescheduled background jobs to run during off-peak hours to prevent recurrence.</code></pre>\n<p><strong>What makes this good:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Plain words (no \"DDB,\" no \"WCU,\" no \"throttle\").</li>\n<li>Honest about the window (15 min, 200 employees).</li>\n<li>Action-focused (\"we increased capacity,\" \"we rescheduled\njobs\").</li>\n<li>Forward-looking (\"to prevent recurrence\").</li>\n<li>Reads like a tired human wrote it, not a press release.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"rapid-fire-severity-triage-quiz\">Rapid-Fire Severity-Triage\nQuiz</h2>\n<p>For each mini-case, pick the severity (Sev-1, Sev-2, Sev-3, or Sev-5)\nand justify in one sentence. Answers at the end.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 1:</strong> The login page is down for all users in all\nregions. Nobody can access the site.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 2:</strong> A single API endpoint is returning 500s for\n10% of requests. The other 90% succeed. No customer complaints yet.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 3:</strong> A typo in the footer of the website\n(\"Contcat Us\" instead of \"Contact Us\"). No functional impact.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 4:</strong> A batch job that runs nightly failed last\nnight. It processes payroll data. Payroll is due in 3 days.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 5:</strong> An alarm fired in the test environment. Prod\nis unaffected.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 6:</strong> A customer reports they can't upload a file\nbecause the upload button is grayed out. You reproduce it in prod. The\nbutton works for other customers.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Answers:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Case 1: Sev-1.</strong> Total site unavailability = revenue\ndown, all customers blocked. All hands.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 2: Sev-2.</strong> 10% error rate with no complaints yet\nis still customer-impacting. Fix proactively before the complaints\narrive.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 3: Sev-5.</strong> Cosmetic issue, no functional impact.\nLog it, fix when convenient.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 4: Sev-2 or Sev-3, depending on the deadline.</strong>\nIf payroll is due in 3 days and the job takes 1 day to fix + 1 day to\nre-run, this is Sev-2 (tight timeline). If there's slack, Sev-3.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 5: Sev-5.</strong> Test environment issue = no customer\nimpact. Close it or fix it during the next deploy cycle.</p>\n<p><strong>Case 6: Sev-3.</strong> Single customer blocked on a specific\nworkflow = smaller impact than an API-wide failure. Investigate during\nbusiness hours, but don't page people at 2am.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>End of drill bank.</strong> These 8 scenarios + the\nescalation rule + the customer-update mini-drill + the rapid-fire quiz\nare the reflexes you drill until they're muscle memory. When a real page\nfires, you won't be thinking \"what's the protocol?\" — you'll be\nexecuting.</p>\n","text":"on call and incident management drills what this trains: the reflexes you need when a page fires — triage severity, quantify impact, pull the right evidence, post updates, escalate at the right time, and ship customer facing summaries that read like a human wrote them at 3am. the basics — severities, sla, escalation, handoff severities (a tech company standard): sev 1: huge customer impact. revenue down, site can't load, data breach. all hands. rare. sev 2: serious customer impact. feature broken for a region, orders failing for a category, login issues for a segment. you page people. common enough. sev 3: smaller customer impact. single feature degraded, one workflow slow, edge case broken. fix during business hours. sev 5: tiny or test only. no customer sees it. log it, fix when convenient. sla = the clock. sev 2 might have a 30 min ack sla (you must acknowledge the page within 30 min) and a 4 hour resolution target. miss it and the ticket escalates automatically or your manager gets pinged. the sla is not a suggestion — it's the contract with the customer. escalation = bringing help, not handing off. you stay on the ticket. you pull in another se, a dev, an oncall from the downstream team. you're coordinating, they're investigating in parallel. escalation is a team sport, not a relay race. handoff = when your shift ends or you physically can't continue. write a full summary in the ticket (what you found, what you tried, what's still unknown, next step), assign to the next oncall, ping them on slack. no handoff without a summary. no summary = the next person starts from zero and you just burned 2 hours of their life. the first 60 seconds — reflex protocol a page fires. your phone buzzes. alarm shows in the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) dashboard. here's what you do in the first minute, every time: 1. acknowledge the page. click \"ack\" in the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) app or reply to the slack bot. this stops the escalation timer. 2. read the alarm description. what metric fired? what threshold? what region/stage? 3. quantify impact. open cloudwatch. how many errors in the last 5 min? how many customers hit this api in the last hour? is it 10 errors or 10,000? 4. post an initial update in the ticket. template: \"acknowledged. [metric x] fired at [time]. investigating. will update in 15 min.\" this buys you time and signals to the customer (and your manager, who might be watching) that you're on it. 5. pull the runbook. every alarm should link to a runbook. if it doesn't, you're writing one after this incident closes. that's 60 seconds. after that, you're into investigation mode (understand → hypothesis → evidence → root cause → mitigate → fix → prevent). but the first 60 is pure reflex. ack, quantify, post, runbook. every time. scenario drill 1 — the triple ticket collision scenario: you're on call. you already have 3 open sev 3 tickets (a timeout issue you're tracing, a config question from a pm, a log noise cleanup request). a sev 2 page fires: api latency spiked to 8 seconds, 200 customers affected in the last 10 minutes. stop. what do you do first? think: priority, not sequence. the sev 2 is the new top of the stack. the sev 3s don't go away, but they pause. model walk through: 1. ack the sev 2 page immediately. 2. post a holding update on each of the 3 sev 3 tickets: \"sev 2 came in, pausing this for [x hours]. will resume once the customer impacting issue is mitigated.\" 3. quantify the sev 2 impact in cloudwatch. 200 customers, 8 sec latency, started 10 min ago. that's real and recent. 4. open the latency runbook. step 1: check downstream dependencies. step 2: check recent deploys. step 3: check db query times. 5. mitigate first (rollback if there was a deploy, throttle if it's a traffic spike, kill the slow query if it's a db issue). fix root cause second. lp shown: customer obsession (drop lower priority work to handle customer impact), bias for action (mitigate before you have the full root cause), ownership (you don't hand off the sev 3s, you just pause them with clear communication). trade off reasoned: you can't work 4 tickets in parallel. severity decides the order. the sev 3s wait. if one of them was actually urgent, it would have been filed as a higher sev. scenario drill 2 — the 2am non reproducible scenario: 2:47am. sev 2 page: \"ordersubmit api returning 500s.\" you roll out of bed, ack the page, check cloudwatch. the alarm fired at 2:42am. but when you hit the api in staging or prod (via postman or curl), it returns 200. metrics show 3 errors in the last hour, all at 2:42am. now it's silent. stop. what do you do? think: transient vs persistent. if the error isn't happening now, you can't fix it live. but you still need to find the cause so it doesn't happen again. model walk through: 1. post an update: \"acknowledged. metrics show 3 errors at 2:42am. api responding normally now. investigating logs for the failure window.\" 2. pull cloudwatch logs insights for the 2:40 2:45am window. filter by level=error or status=500 . look for stack traces, exception types, employee ids. 3. check for a deploy or config change around that time. was there a rollout between 2:30 2:45? a pipeline stage promotion? an a runtime config service flag flip? 4. check downstream service health. did a dependency (dynamodb, s3, another internal api) have a blip at 2:42am? cross reference their cloudwatch metrics. 5. if you find the cause (e.g., ddb throttle, transient network error, brief lambda cold start surge), document it in the ticket. if it's a one off transient, close with \"mitigated by [dependency recovery]. monitoring for recurrence. runbook updated to check [x] during future non reproducibles.\" 6. if you can't find the cause after 90 min, escalate to a dev who owns that api. attach your investigation (cw log snippets, the exact 2:42am error stack, what you ruled out). lp shown: dive deep (you didn't just close the ticket when the error stopped, you pulled logs and traced the timeline), learn and be curious (you updated the runbook so the next oncall has a better checklist), insist on highest standards (you didn't accept \"it went away\" as an answer). trade off reasoned: at 2am with a transient issue, the choice is: burn 4 hours chasing a ghost vs document what you know and escalate if you're stuck. 90 min is the cutoff. after that, bring help. scenario drill 3 — the alarm firing, no customer complaint scenario: sev 3 alarm fires: \"ddb read throttle on employeetable exceeds 10/min for 5 consecutive minutes.\" you check the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) queue. no customer tickets. no slack pings from pms. metrics show the throttle started 20 min ago and is still happening. the api using that table is still returning 200s (it has retry logic). stop. what do you do? think: no customer impact yet doesn't mean no problem. the alarm fired for a reason. this is proactive vs reactive. model walk through: 1. ack the alarm. post an update: \"ddb throttle detected on employeetable. no customer tickets yet. api retries are succeeding. investigating to prevent customer visible impact.\" 2. check ddb cloudwatch metrics. what's the actual rcu consumption vs provisioned capacity? is this a traffic spike or a slow query? 3. check the api code. is there a new query pattern that's reading more rows than it should? did a recent deploy add a scan where there used to be a get item? 4. if it's a traffic spike: check if today is a peak day (payroll cutoff, open enrollment, prime day). if yes, scale up the ddb table or switch to on demand billing temporarily. 5. if it's a slow query: file a ticket to optimize the query (add a gsi, batch the reads, cache the result). meanwhile, monitor. if the throttle starts causing api timeouts, escalate to sev 2. 6. close the sev 3 with \"throttle mitigated by [scaling / caching]. root cause: [traffic spike / slow query]. preventive action: [filed ticket to optimize query / set up auto scaling].\" lp shown: ownership (you didn't wait for a customer to complain, you acted on the alarm), insist on highest standards (you treated \"no impact yet\" as \"opportunity to prevent impact\"), bias for action (you scaled or filed a ticket instead of just monitoring). trade off reasoned: an alarm with no customer complaint is still an alarm. silence it by fixing the root cause, not by ignoring it. scenario drill 4 — the screaming customer, calm metrics scenario: sev 2 ticket lands from a pm: \"customer reports ordersubmit api is down. they've tried 10 times in the last 5 minutes, all failed. urgent.\" you check cloudwatch. api error rate: 0.01% (baseline noise). latency: p99 200ms (normal). no alarms. no spike in 500s. stop. what do you do? think: the customer's reality is the only reality that matters, even if your metrics disagree. either your metrics are missing something, or the customer hit an edge case. model walk through: 1. ack the ticket. post an update: \"acknowledged. api metrics look normal globally. investigating customer specific failure. need customer details: employee id, timestamp of one failed attempt, any error message they saw.\" 2. reply to the pm: \"can you get the customer's employee id and the exact time of one failed request? that'll let me pull their specific logs.\" 3. once you have the employee id + timestamp, run a cloudwatch logs insights query filtered by employeeid=x and timestamp between [y] and [z] . look for their request in the logs. 4. common findings: customer in a region you didn't monitor. your alarm only tracks us east 1 , they're in eu west 1 and that stage is broken. customer has a specific data pattern that triggers a validation bug. their employee record has a null field your code doesn't handle. customer's client is sending a malformed request. they're on an old version of the mobile app that sends a deprecated field. 5. once you find the root cause, mitigate it (fix the region, deploy a null check, ask the pm to tell the customer to update their app). 6. update your alarms to cover the gap. if this was a regional miss, add alarms for all regions. if this was a validation edge case, add a metric for that specific error type. lp shown: customer obsession (you believed the customer even when your metrics didn't, and you dug until you found their specific failure), dive deep (you didn't stop at \"metrics look fine,\" you went customer by customer), earn trust (you responded with \"i'll investigate\" not \"the api is fine, must be user error\"). trade off reasoned: global metrics hide individual failures. when a customer says it's broken, it's broken for them, even if it's not broken for everyone. scenario drill 5 — the downstream blame game scenario: sev 2: \"getemployeeschedule api timing out for 50% of requests.\" you check your service. your code is fine. logs show your api calls the downstream scheduledataservice (owned by another team) and waits forever. you check their cloudwatch. their api is returning 200s but latency is 30 seconds (normally 200ms). no alarm on their side because their p99 latency alarm is set to 60 seconds. stop. what do you do? think: the customer doesn't care whose fault it is. your api is timing out, so it's your problem to fix, even if the root cause is downstream. model walk through: 1. ack the sev 2. post an update: \"acknowledged. root cause: downstream scheduledataservice latency spiked to 30s. engaging their oncall. mitigating by [reducing timeout / returning cached data / failing fast with a clear error].\" 2. ping the downstream team's oncall on slack or via their the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) page bot. include the data: \"your api latency is 30s since [time]. our api is timing out waiting for you. can you investigate?\" 3. while you wait for them, mitigate on your side. options: lower your timeout from 60s to 5s so your api fails fast instead of hanging. return cached schedule data if you have it (stale data no data for some use cases). return a 503 with a clear error message: \"schedule service temporarily unavailable. try again in 5 minutes.\" 4. once the downstream team fixes their latency, verify your api recovers. close your sev 2 with \"mitigated by [failing fast]. root cause: downstream scheduledataservice latency. resolved by their team at [time]. preventive action: added alarm for downstream api latency.\" 5. after the incident, file a ticket with the downstream team: \"your p99 latency alarm is set too high. 30s latency breaks our sla. can you lower it to 5s so your oncall catches this before it cascades?\" lp shown: ownership (you didn't just blame the downstream team, you mitigated on your side while they investigated), bias for action (you failed fast instead of waiting for them to fix it), earn trust (you documented the root cause clearly so there's no finger pointing later). trade off reasoned: when a downstream dependency is slow, you have two jobs: 1) mitigate the impact on your customers, 2) help the downstream team fix their root cause. both jobs are yours, not just 2. scenario drill 6 — the 90 minute stuck point scenario: sev 2: \"submitpaycode api returning 500s for another region employees.\" you've been investigating for 90 minutes. you found the error in the logs: nullpointerexception in paycodevalidator line 127 . you traced it to a recent deploy 3 hours ago. but you can't figure out why the deploy broke another region specifically — the code looks the same for all countries. you've tried rolling back in staging, but the rollback didn't help (the bug might have been latent for longer). you've pulled 3 sample employee ids and their data looks normal. you're stuck. stop. what do you do? think: 90 minutes is the cutoff. after that, you're burning time without progress. escalation = bringing help, not handing off. model walk through: 1. post an update in the ticket: \"90 min in. root cause narrowed to npe in paycodevalidator line 127, another region specific. attempted rollback in staging, issue persists. escalating to dev oncall for code path review. staying on ticket.\" 2. page the dev oncall (or slack the team's oncall channel if they have one). message: \"sev 2 in prod, another region paycode 500s, 90 min stuck. npe in paycodevalidator line 127. i've pulled logs [link], tried rollback [result]. need help tracing why another region is different. can you pair with me?\" 3. you stay on the ticket. you're the context keeper. the dev is the code expert. you show them the logs, the error line, the sample employee data. they spot the pattern (maybe another region employees have a null paycode field that other countries don't, and the recent deploy removed a null check). 4. once they identify the fix, you coordinate the deploy. they push the pull request, you verify it in staging, you approve the prod rollout, you monitor the metrics post deploy. 5. close the ticket with \"mitigated by [re adding null check]. root cause: recent deploy removed validation for null paycode field, another region employees hit this edge case. escalated at 90 min mark, resolved with dev oncall assistance.\" lp shown: bias for action (you escalated at the right time instead of spinning for 3 hours), earn trust (you stayed on the ticket and coordinated the fix instead of handing it off), learn and be curious (you'll document this pattern so the next oncall knows \"another region specific bug = check for null fields in employee data\"). trade off reasoned: the 90 120 min mark is the escalation window. before that, you're expected to exhaust the runbook. after that, you're expected to bring help. escalation is not failure — it's the protocol. scenario drill 7 — the peak day surge (prime day, black friday) scenario: it's prime day. 10am pst. traffic is 10x normal. your getemployeeschedule api is handling the load fine (you scaled up the fleet yesterday). but at 10:47am, a sev 2 alarm fires: \"ddb write throttle on scheduletable exceeds 100/min.\" the api that writes schedules (used by managers updating shifts) is now timing out. you check the fleet: all instances are healthy. you check ddb: write capacity is provisioned at 1000 wcu, but actual consumption is 1200 wcu. stop. what do you do? think: peak day = every decision is high stakes. scaling up is safe if you do it incrementally. scaling down is dangerous if you do it during the surge. model walk through: 1. ack the alarm. post an update: \"acknowledged. prime day traffic surge. ddb write throttle on scheduletable. scaling up write capacity now. eta 5 min.\" 2. open the ddb console. increase write capacity from 1000 wcu to 2000 wcu. (on demand billing is safer for peak days if your service supports it, but if you're on provisioned, double the capacity as a first step.) 3. monitor for 5 minutes. did the throttle stop? did the write api latency drop? if yes, you're good. if no, scale again to 3000 wcu. 4. post a follow up update in the ticket: \"write capacity scaled to 2000 wcu. throttle resolved. api latency back to normal. monitoring for remainder of prime day.\" 5. do not scale back down until prime day ends. scaling down mid surge can cause another throttle. wait until traffic drops to baseline (usually 24 hours after the event). 6. after prime day, write a post mortem: \"prime day traffic was 10x baseline. ddb write throttle at 1000 wcu, scaled to 2000. recommendation: pre scale to 2000 wcu before next prime day, or switch to on demand billing.\" lp shown: bias for action (you scaled immediately instead of waiting to see if the throttle would resolve itself), insist on highest standards (you monitored after scaling to confirm it worked), customer obsession (you kept the write api available for managers who needed to update schedules during the surge). trade off reasoned: peak days are not the time to experiment. scale up conservatively, monitor, and don't scale down until the event is over. the cost of over provisioning for 24 hours is tiny compared to the cost of another outage. scenario drill 8 — the bad deploy mid rollout scenario: you're monitoring a deploy of the time tracking service rolling out to prod. stage 1 (1% of fleet): green. stage 2 (10% of fleet): green. stage 3 (50% of fleet): alarm fires. the getemployeebalance api api error rate spiked from 0% to 5% in the last 5 minutes. the alarm is only firing on the 50% of instances running the new version. the other 50% (old version) are fine. stop. what do you do? think: a deploy that breaks at 50% is a code bug in the new version. rollback immediately. root cause investigation happens after. model walk through: 1. ack the alarm. post an update: \"acknowledged. the getemployeebalance api error rate spike during prod deploy. rolling back now.\" 2. open the pipeline. click \"rollback\" on stage 3. this reverts the 50% of instances to the previous version. 3. monitor for 5 minutes. did the error rate drop back to 0%? if yes, rollback succeeded. 4. post a follow up update: \"rollback complete. error rate back to 0%. investigating root cause in new version. deploy paused.\" 5. pull the logs from the 50% that had the new version. filter by level=error and version=[new version number] . look for the stack trace. 6. open the pull request for the deploy. check what changed in the getemployeebalance api code path. did someone add a new dependency? change a query? remove a null check? 7. once you find the bug, file a ticket with the dev team. attach the logs, the stack trace, the pull request link. mark the deploy as \"blocked until [ticket] is resolved.\" 8. close the sev 2 with \"mitigated by rollback. root cause: [bug in new version]. deploy paused. dev team notified via [ticket link].\" lp shown: bias for action (you rolled back immediately when the alarm fired, you didn't wait to investigate first), customer obsession (you prioritized stopping the customer impact over figuring out the root cause), ownership (you paused the deploy and coordinated with the dev team to fix the bug before retrying). trade off reasoned: when a deploy breaks, rollback first, investigate second. the faster you rollback, the fewer customers are affected. the escalate vs keep going decision rule escalate (bring help) when: you've been stuck for 90 120 minutes with no progress. you've exhausted the runbook and don't know the next step. the issue requires code changes and you're not a dev. the root cause is in a service you don't own. you're drowning in multiple sev 2s at once. keep going when: you're making progress (each step is ruling out a hypothesis or narrowing the root cause). the runbook has more steps you haven't tried yet. you have a clear next action (e.g., \"try rolling back,\" \"scale up ddb,\" \"check downstream service health\"). escalation is bringing help, not handing off. you stay on the ticket. you coordinate. the person you escalate to investigates in parallel. you're the context keeper, they're the specialist. example escalation message (slack): write the customer update — mini drill raw technical incident: alarm: ddb write throttle on paycodesubmissiontable impact: 200 customers unable to submit paycodes for 15 minutes (10:30am 10:45am pst) root cause: traffic surge from a bulk paycode upload job running during peak hours mitigation: scaled ddb write capacity from 500 wcu to 1500 wcu prevention: scheduled bulk jobs to run during off peak hours (1am 5am pst) your task: write a 3 sentence customer facing update (what broke / what we did / what prevents recurrence). non technical language. no jargon. reads like a human wrote it at 3am. model answer: what makes this good: plain words (no \"ddb,\" no \"wcu,\" no \"throttle\"). honest about the window (15 min, 200 employees). action focused (\"we increased capacity,\" \"we rescheduled jobs\"). forward looking (\"to prevent recurrence\"). reads like a tired human wrote it, not a press release. rapid fire severity triage quiz for each mini case, pick the severity (sev 1, sev 2, sev 3, or sev 5) and justify in one sentence. answers at the end. case 1: the login page is down for all users in all regions. nobody can access the site. case 2: a single api endpoint is returning 500s for 10% of requests. the other 90% succeed. no customer complaints yet. case 3: a typo in the footer of the website (\"contcat us\" instead of \"contact us\"). no functional impact. case 4: a batch job that runs nightly failed last night. it processes payroll data. payroll is due in 3 days. case 5: an alarm fired in the test environment. prod is unaffected. case 6: a customer reports they can't upload a file because the upload button is grayed out. you reproduce it in prod. the button works for other customers. answers: case 1: sev 1. total site unavailability = revenue down, all customers blocked. all hands. case 2: sev 2. 10% error rate with no complaints yet is still customer impacting. fix proactively before the complaints arrive. case 3: sev 5. cosmetic issue, no functional impact. log it, fix when convenient. case 4: sev 2 or sev 3, depending on the deadline. if payroll is due in 3 days and the job takes 1 day to fix + 1 day to re run, this is sev 2 (tight timeline). if there's slack, sev 3. case 5: sev 5. test environment issue = no customer impact. close it or fix it during the next deploy cycle. case 6: sev 3. single customer blocked on a specific workflow = smaller impact than an api wide failure. investigate during business hours, but don't page people at 2am. end of drill bank. these 8 scenarios + the escalation rule + the customer update mini drill + the rapid fire quiz are the reflexes you drill until they're muscle memory. when a real page fires, you won't be thinking \"what's the protocol?\" — you'll be executing.","words":4093},{"id":"training-tools-fluency-drills","section":"Training","title":"Tools fluency drills","html":"<h1\nid=\"tools-fluency-drills--cloudwatch-the-ticketing-system-like-jira-or-pagerduty-pipelines-the-deployment-tool-like-spinnaker-or-argo-cd-your-host-access-and-log-tooling\">Tools\nFluency Drills — CloudWatch, the ticketing system (like Jira or\nPagerDuty), Pipelines, the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD),\nyour host access and log tooling</h1>\n<p><em>What this trains:</em> hands-on proficiency with the SE daily\ntoolchain through \"what would you click/type\" drills</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-each-tool-is-quick-reference\">What Each Tool Is (quick\nreference)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Tool</th>\n<th>What it is</th>\n<th>SE daily use</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CloudWatch Logs Insights</strong></td>\n<td>AWS log query engine (SQL-like syntax)</td>\n<td>Find errors, trace request flows, measure latency, count by\npattern</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CloudWatch Metrics</strong></td>\n<td>Time-series data + graphing</td>\n<td>Spot spikes, compare to baseline, measure SLA</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CloudWatch Alarms</strong></td>\n<td>Threshold + SNS notification</td>\n<td>Root cause for Sev2 pages, tune thresholds to prevent noise</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) / the\nticketing system</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company internal ticketing (the ticketing system (like Jira\nor PagerDuty) = customer-visible, the ticketing system = internal\nops)</td>\n<td>Queue triage, assign/close/escalate, track RCAs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Pipelines</strong></td>\n<td>a tech company's CICD orchestration (beta → staging → prod)</td>\n<td>Unblock stages, rollback, check a production change approval, push\ndeploys</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo\nCD)</strong></td>\n<td>Deployment system (hosts, containers, Lambda, versions)</td>\n<td>Verify deploy state, read env logs, rollback if needed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>the alarm dependency map in your monitoring\ntool</strong></td>\n<td>Alarm aggregation + dependency tree</td>\n<td>Trace root alarm from leaf symptom, understand blast radius</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>your host access and log tooling</strong></td>\n<td>Host-level ops tooling (grep logs, restart, describe fleet)</td>\n<td>Manual log grep when CW query times out, host diagnostics</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"day-1-access-checklist-what-to-request\">Day 1 Access Checklist\n(what to request)</h2>\n<p>Before you can do SE work, you need:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>AWS account access</strong> (prod + staging) — via the cloud\naccess tool, role = ReadOnly or a limited-admin role (ask team\nwhich)</li>\n<li><strong>the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) queue\nmembership</strong> — ask manager for your team's queue name (like\n<code>YourTeam-OPS</code> or <code>a real SE team-Support</code>), file\naccess via the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) Portal</li>\n<li><strong>Pipelines permissions</strong> — usually auto-granted if you\nown the service in IAM, verify you can see your team's pipeline in\npipelines your company.dev</li>\n<li><strong>the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) read\naccess</strong> — tied to Pipelines, verify you can click through to env\nlogs</li>\n<li><strong>CloudWatch cross-account role</strong> (if multi-account) —\nsome teams need a separate assume-role for prod CW read</li>\n<li><strong>your host access and log tooling permissions</strong> — file\nvia your host access and log tooling portal, scope = your service's host\nfleet</li>\n<li><strong>the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool dashboard\nlink</strong> — ask team for the bookmark (usually team wiki has\nit)</li>\n<li><strong>On-call schedule</strong> — a published SE interview guide\nsays you shadow 2 weeks before first solo shift; confirm with\nmanager</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Most of this lands in the first week. If day 3 you still can't open\nCloudWatch prod logs, escalate.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"cloudwatch-logs-insights-5-query-reading-drills\">CloudWatch Logs\nInsights: 5 Query-Reading Drills</h2>\n<p>For each, a small query is shown. Your job: <strong>what does this\nquery return?</strong> Then read the explanation.</p>\n<h3 id=\"drill-1\">Drill 1</h3>\n<pre><code>fields @timestamp, @message\n| filter @message like /ERROR/\n| sort @timestamp desc\n| limit 50</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Your answer (before scrolling):</strong> ___</p>\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Returns the 50 most recent log lines\ncontaining the word ERROR, newest first. The <code>fields</code> line\npicks which columns to show (timestamp + full message). The\n<code>filter</code> line keeps only rows matching the pattern. The\n<code>sort</code> orders by time descending (newest on top). The\n<code>limit</code> caps output at 50 rows so the query doesn't time out\non massive logs.</p>\n<p><strong>When you'd use it:</strong> First move on a Sev2 page: \"show\nme the most recent errors in the last 15 minutes.\" You'd add\n<code>| filter @timestamp &gt; ago(15m)</code> before the sort if the\nlog group is huge.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"drill-2\">Drill 2</h3>\n<pre><code>fields @timestamp\n| filter requestId = &quot;abc-123-def&quot;\n| sort @timestamp asc</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Your answer:</strong> ___</p>\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Returns all log lines for a single\nrequest (identified by <code>requestId = \"abc-123-def\"</code>), sorted\nchronologically (oldest first). This traces the full lifecycle of one\nAPI call: ingress → validation → downstream calls → response. You see\nevery log the service emitted for that request.</p>\n<p><strong>When you'd use it:</strong> A customer reports \"my API call\nfailed at 9:43am, here's the request ID.\" You paste that ID into this\nquery to see the full error stack + which downstream call timed out.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"drill-3\">Drill 3</h3>\n<pre><code>fields @timestamp, latency\n| filter endpoint = &quot;/api/balances&quot;\n| stats avg(latency) as avg_latency by bin(5m)</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Your answer:</strong> ___</p>\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Returns the average latency for the\n<code>/api/balances</code> endpoint, grouped into 5-minute buckets. The\n<code>stats</code> clause aggregates: <code>avg(latency)</code>\ncalculates the mean, <code>by bin(5m)</code> groups rows into 5-minute\ntime windows. Output is a time-series table (time bucket,\navg_latency).</p>\n<p><strong>When you'd use it:</strong> A Sev2 alarm fires for \"P99\nlatency spiked.\" You run this to see if the spike affects all endpoints\nor just one. Then you zoom in on the spike's time window and add more\nfilters (like <code>| filter latency &gt; 1000</code> to find the slow\noutliers).</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"drill-4\">Drill 4</h3>\n<pre><code>fields @message\n| parse @message &quot;employeeId=* action=*&quot; as empId, action\n| filter action = &quot;SUBMIT&quot;\n| stats count() by empId\n| sort count desc\n| limit 10</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Your answer:</strong> ___</p>\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Returns the top 10 employees (by\nemployeeId) who triggered the most SUBMIT actions, ordered by count\ndescending. The <code>parse</code> line extracts two fields from the log\nmessage using a pattern (<code>employeeId=X action=Y</code>). The\n<code>filter</code> keeps only SUBMIT rows. The\n<code>stats count()</code> groups by employee and counts how many times\neach appears. The <code>sort</code> orders by count (highest first), and\n<code>limit 10</code> caps output.</p>\n<p><strong>When you'd use it:</strong> A team reports \"someone is\nspamming the API, our queue is backed up.\" You run this to find the\nemployeeId responsible, then check if it's a legit spike (like a manager\nbulk-approving timecards) or an automation loop gone wrong.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"drill-5\">Drill 5</h3>\n<pre><code>fields @timestamp, statusCode\n| filter statusCode &gt;= 500\n| stats count() by statusCode, bin(1h)</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Your answer:</strong> ___</p>\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Returns the count of 5xx errors\n(server-side failures) grouped by status code (500, 502, 503, etc.) and\nby 1-hour time buckets. This shows you when errors spiked and which type\n(500 = internal bug, 502 = downstream timeout, 503 = service\noverloaded).</p>\n<p><strong>When you'd use it:</strong> A Sev2 fires for \"elevated 5xx\nrate.\" You run this to see the error distribution over time. If all 502s\nstarted at 3pm, you check what downstream service deployed at 3pm. If\nall 503s, you check fleet capacity + autoscaling.</p>\n<p><strong>Common mistake:</strong> Forgetting the\n<code>filter statusCode &gt;= 500</code> means you'd count 200s and 400s\ntoo, drowning the signal in noise.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"which-tool-for-which-question-matching-drill\">Which Tool For\nWhich Question? (matching drill)</h2>\n<p>For each question, write which tool you'd use first. Then check the\nanswers.</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Is the prod deploy stuck at beta stage?</li>\n<li>What did host i-0abc123 log at 9:15am?</li>\n<li>Who owns the \"HighErrorRate\" alarm that just paged me?</li>\n<li>How many the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) tickets are\nin our queue right now?</li>\n<li>What version is currently deployed to prod?</li>\n<li>Why did the last staging deploy rollback automatically?</li>\n<li>What's the P99 latency for the <code>/submit</code> endpoint over\nthe last hour?</li>\n<li>Which alarm triggered the Sev2 page at 2am?</li>\n<li>The pipeline says \"waiting on a production change approval\" —\nwhere's the a production change approval?</li>\n<li>A host is throwing <code>OutOfMemoryError</code> — how do I SSH to\nit?</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Answers:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Pipelines</strong> — open pipelines your company.dev, find\nyour pipeline, check the beta stage status. If red, click for logs. If\nyellow, it's waiting (possibly a production change approval).</li>\n<li><strong>CloudWatch Logs Insights</strong> (or your host access and\nlog tooling if CW times out) — query:\n<code>filter @timestamp &gt; ago(1h) and @timestamp &lt; ago(50m) | fields @message</code>\n(adjust the time window to 9:15am's epoch or use a timestamp filter).\nyour host access and log tooling alternative:\n<code>host-cli logs --host i-0abc123 --since 9:00 --until 9:30</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool</strong> —\nsearch for \"HighErrorRate\" in the alarm tree. the alarm dependency map\nin your monitoring tool shows you the dependency graph: which metrics\nfeed the alarm, which teams own the upstream/downstream alarms.</li>\n<li><strong>the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)</strong> —\nopen your ticketing system, navigate to your queue (like\n<code>YourTeam-OPS</code>), filter by status=OPEN. The count is right\nthere. Or use <code>ticket-cli queue-stats</code> if your team has a\nCLI.</li>\n<li><strong>the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD)</strong> (or\nPipelines) — the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) shows the\ncurrent deployed version per environment. Pipelines also shows it in the\nstage cards (\"prod: version X.Y.Z, deployed 2h ago\").</li>\n<li><strong>Pipelines</strong> — click the staging stage, check the\n\"History\" or \"Rollback\" tab. Pipelines logs why: usually a canary metric\nbreached threshold (like error rate &gt; 5% for 10 min) or a manual\nabort.</li>\n<li><strong>CloudWatch Metrics</strong> (or Logs Insights if latency is\nlogged) — if your service emits a <code>Latency</code> metric, graph it\nwith statistic=p99. If latency is only in logs, run a Logs Insights\nquery:\n<code>filter endpoint = \"/submit\" | stats percentile(latency, 99) by bin(5m)</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool</strong>\n(or the page itself) — the page email/Slack usually names the alarm.\nSearch the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool for that alarm\nto see the dependency tree. Or check your on-call dashboard if your team\nuses one.</li>\n<li><strong>Pipelines</strong> — the stage card shows \"waiting on a\nchange-approval ticket.\" Click that link to see the a production change\napproval status in the a production change approval portal\n(approved/pending/rejected). If rejected, you fix the issue and\nresubmit.</li>\n<li><strong>your host access and log tooling</strong> (or the deployment\ntool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD), or SSH directly if you have\ncredentials) — your host access and log tooling:\n<code>host-cli ssh i-0abc123</code>. the deployment tool (like Spinnaker\nor Argo CD): click the host in the env view, then \"SSH\" button if your\nteam has it wired. Direct SSH: <code>ssh host-01.internal</code> if you\nhave the VPN + key.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Scoring:</strong> 8+ correct = solid. 6-7 = good, keep\ndrilling. &lt;6 = review the tools table at the top again.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"drill-youre-on-call-a-sev2-fires-walk-me-through-your-first-5-minutes\">Drill:\nYou're on-call, a Sev2 fires. Walk me through your first 5 minutes.</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> 3:17am, you get paged: \"ALARM:\nHighAPIErrorRate in us-west-2 breached threshold (&gt;5% for 10 min).\"\nThe alarm is for your team's service. You wake up, open your laptop.\nWhat do you do, in order?</p>\n<p><strong>Your answer (before scrolling):</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><hr /></li>\n<li><hr /></li>\n<li><hr /></li>\n<li><hr /></li>\n<li><hr /></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Model answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Acknowledge the page</strong> (in PagerDuty or whatever your\nteam uses). This stops re-pages and signals you're awake.</li>\n<li><strong>Open the alarm dependency map in your monitoring\ntool</strong>, search for \"HighAPIErrorRate.\" Check the alarm tree to\nsee if this is a root alarm or a symptom of an upstream failure (like a\ndownstream service is down, so your API calls are failing). If upstream\nalarm exists and someone else is on it, you coordinate. If you're the\nroot, you own it.</li>\n<li><strong>Open CloudWatch Logs Insights</strong> for your service's\nprod log group. Run:\n<code>fields @timestamp, @message | filter @message like /ERROR/ and @timestamp &gt; ago(15m) | sort @timestamp desc | limit 100</code>.\nThis shows you the most recent errors. Scan for patterns: same error\nmessage repeating? Same endpoint failing? Same downstream service timing\nout?</li>\n<li><strong>Open CloudWatch Metrics</strong>, graph your service's error\nrate + request count + latency over the last 30 min. Check if the spike\ncorrelates with a deploy (look at the Pipelines timeline) or a traffic\nspike (request count graph).</li>\n<li><strong>Check Pipelines</strong> — did a deploy just finish? If the\nspike started right after a prod push, you prepare to rollback. If no\nrecent deploy, you start deeper investigation (logs + metrics +\nhypothesis).</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Time check:</strong> if you're still investigating at 10\nminutes with no mitigation, you escalate (page your manager or the\non-call senior). Sev2 rule: mitigate first (often = rollback),\nroot-cause later.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-reading-a-pipelines-stage\">Drill: Reading a Pipelines\nstage</h2>\n<p>You open your service's pipeline (pipelines your company.dev). You\nsee:</p>\n<pre><code>Beta: GREEN (deployed 2h ago, version 1.2.3)\nstaging: YELLOW (waiting, a change-approval ticket pending)\nProd: GREEN (version 1.2.2, deployed 5d ago)</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Questions:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Can you push to prod right now?</li>\n<li>What's blocking staging?</li>\n<li>If you need to rollback prod, what version would you roll back\nto?</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Answers:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>No.</strong> Prod deploys require staging soak (usually 24h\ngreen). staging is yellow (blocked), so the pipeline won't let you\npromote. You need to unblock staging first.</li>\n<li><strong>a change-approval ticket is pending approval.</strong>\nproduction change approvals (production change approval) are required\nfor prod-adjacent deploys (staging counts as prod-adjacent at many\nteams). You check the a production change approval portal: if it's\nwaiting on approval, you ping the approver. If it's rejected, you fix\nthe issue (like missing rollback plan or incomplete testing evidence)\nand resubmit.</li>\n<li><strong>Version 1.2.1</strong> (the version before 1.2.2). Pipelines\nkeeps a rollback history. You'd click \"Rollback\" on the prod stage,\nselect 1.2.1, confirm. The rollback usually takes 10-20 min (deploy the\nold version, health-check, done).</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"drill-the-deployment-tool-like-spinnaker-or-argo-cd-environment-view\">Drill:\nthe deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) environment view</h2>\n<p>You open the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD), navigate to\nyour service's prod environment. You see:</p>\n<pre><code>Environment: prod-us-west-2\nHosts: 12 (target: 12, healthy: 11, unhealthy: 1)\nVersion: 1.2.2 (deployed 5d ago)\nLast deploy: SUCCESS\nUnhealthy host: i-0abc123 (failing health check: /ping timeout)</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Questions:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>What do you do about the unhealthy host?</li>\n<li>How do you check the host's logs?</li>\n<li>If you rollback, what happens to the unhealthy host?</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Answers:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Investigate first, replace if needed.</strong> Click the\nhost details to see why <code>/ping</code> is timing out. Common causes:\nhost is CPU-pegged (check CloudWatch host metrics), disk full (SSH +\n<code>df -h</code>), or a bug in the <code>/ping</code> handler (check\nlogs). If logs show <code>OutOfMemoryError</code>, you restart the host\n(your host access and log tooling or the deployment tool (like Spinnaker\nor Argo CD) \"restart\" button). If restart fails, you terminate the host\nand let autoscaling replace it.</li>\n<li><strong>CloudWatch or your host access and log tooling.</strong> the\ndeployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) usually links to the host's\nlog stream in CloudWatch (click \"Logs\" on the host detail page). Or your\nhost access and log tooling:\n<code>host-cli logs --host i-0abc123 --since 1h</code>. Or SSH:\n<code>ssh host-01.internal</code>, then\n<code>tail /var/log/service.log</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>The unhealthy host gets the rollback version too.</strong>\nRollback redeploys the old version to ALL hosts (healthy + unhealthy).\nIf the unhealthy host is so broken it can't receive the deploy, the\ndeployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) marks it failed and\nautoscaling replaces it. Either way, rollback doesn't skip hosts.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-which-tool-speed-round\">Drill: \"Which tool?\" speed\nround</h2>\n<p>30 seconds each. Which tool?</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>\"Show me all 500 errors from the last hour.\"</li>\n<li>\"Who's on-call for the upstream service that's timing out?\"</li>\n<li>\"Is the current prod version the same as what's in mainline?\"</li>\n<li>\"What's the P99 latency for our API in the last 30 days?\"</li>\n<li>\"The deploy to staging failed — what's the error?\"</li>\n<li>\"A customer filed a the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)\nticket 3 hours ago and nobody picked it up — why?\"</li>\n<li>\"I need to grep the prod logs for a specific employeeId, but\nCloudWatch times out.\"</li>\n<li>\"The alarm 'HighCPU' fired — what hosts are affected?\"</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Answers:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>CloudWatch Logs Insights</strong> — query:\n<code>filter statusCode = 500 | filter @timestamp &gt; ago(1h)</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>On-call schedule tool</strong> (PagerDuty / Splunk On-Call /\nyour team's wiki). Or ask in Slack if it's urgent.</li>\n<li><strong>Pipelines</strong> (compare prod version to mainline tip) or\n<strong>git</strong> (<code>git log</code> in your the build system\npackage, compare deployed commit to HEAD).</li>\n<li><strong>CloudWatch Metrics</strong> — graph your\n<code>Latency</code> metric with statistic=p99, time range=30d.</li>\n<li><strong>Pipelines</strong> — click the staging stage, check the\n\"Logs\" or \"History\" tab for the failure reason.</li>\n<li><strong>the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)</strong> —\nopen the queue, check the ticket state. Common reasons: ticket got\nassigned to the wrong queue (reroute it), or the assignee is OOO\n(manually reassign).</li>\n<li><strong>your host access and log tooling</strong> —\n<code>host-cli logs --grep \"employeeId=12345\"</code> (adjust the\npattern). your host access and log tooling searches raw log files on\ndisk, no query timeout.</li>\n<li><strong>CloudWatch Alarms</strong> (click the alarm to see which\nhosts breached) + <strong>the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo\nCD)</strong> (check the host list for CPU metrics). Or <strong>your host\naccess and log tooling</strong> (<code>host-cli describe-fleet</code> to\nsee CPU by host).</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-day-1-se-workflow-walkthrough\">Drill: Day-1 SE workflow\nwalkthrough</h2>\n<p>Imagine it's your first day as SE2. Your manager says: \"Shadow the\non-call today. A Sev3 ticket just came in: 'Customer reports their API\ncall returned 502, request ID xyz-123.' Walk me through how you'd\ninvestigate.\"</p>\n<p><strong>Your answer (step by step):</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><hr /></li>\n<li><hr /></li>\n<li><hr /></li>\n<li><hr /></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Model answer:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Open the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)</strong>,\nfind the ticket. Read the customer description: \"I called GET\n/api/balances at 10:43am, got 502 Bad Gateway. Request ID: xyz-123.\"\nNote the time (10:43am), endpoint, and request ID.</li>\n<li><strong>Open CloudWatch Logs Insights</strong>, query the request\nID: <code>filter requestId = \"xyz-123\" | sort @timestamp asc</code>.\nThis shows the full request trace. Scan for errors. Common 502 causes:\ndownstream service timed out (you'd see a <code>TimeoutException</code>\nlog), or your service threw an unhandled exception (you'd see a stack\ntrace).</li>\n<li><strong>Hypothesis:</strong> Let's say the logs show\n<code>TimeoutException: call to the time-tracking service API timed out after 30s</code>.\nYour hypothesis: the downstream the time-tracking service service was\nslow or down at 10:43am.</li>\n<li><strong>Verify:</strong> Check the time-tracking service's\nCloudWatch metrics around 10:43am (if you have cross-account access) or\ncheck their public status page. If the time-tracking service had a\nspike, that's your root cause. If the time-tracking service was fine,\ndig deeper: maybe your retry logic is broken, or the 30s timeout is too\nshort.</li>\n<li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> If the time-tracking service was\ntemporarily down and recovered, no action needed (transient issue). If\nit's still slow, you coordinate with the time-tracking service's\non-call. If your timeout is wrong, you file a ticket to tune it.</li>\n<li><strong>Update the ticketing system (like Jira or\nPagerDuty):</strong> Post a worklog: \"Investigated. Root cause:\ndownstream the time-tracking service service had elevated latency at\n10:43am (their P99 spiked to 45s, our timeout is 30s). the time-tracking\nservice's incident resolved at 10:50am. This was a transient issue. No\naction needed. Closing ticket.\" Then close.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Time:</strong> This investigation should take 15-30 min. If\nyou're stuck after 30 min, escalate to the senior on-call.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"how-this-connects-to-your-background\">How this connects to your\nbackground</h2>\n<p>If you have used a log query tool, a ticketing system, a CI/CD\npipeline, and a deployment tool before, the daily SE toolchain will feel\nfamiliar. What is new is the operational layer: alarm-dependency\ntracing, host-level debugging, production change approvals, and the\non-call tooling your team uses. Your manager walks you through those in\nweek one.</p>\n<h2 id=\"next-steps-after-drilling\">Next Steps (after drilling)</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Bookmark these URLs</strong> (ask your team for exact\nlinks):</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Your service's CloudWatch log group (prod + staging)</li>\n<li>Your service's Pipelines page</li>\n<li>Your service's the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD) prod\nenvironment</li>\n<li>Your team's the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) queue</li>\n<li>Your team's the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool\ndashboard</li>\n<li>Your on-call schedule</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>Request day-1 access</strong> (see checklist at top). If\nyou don't have prod CloudWatch read by day 3, escalate.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Shadow on-call for 2 weeks</strong> before your first\nsolo shift (standard per a published SE interview guide). Ask to pair on\n2-3 Sev2/Sev3 tickets. Watch the full investigation flow.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Drill the CloudWatch queries</strong> — pick 5 from this\ndoc, run them against your service's logs (use staging if you don't have\nprod yet). Get comfortable with the syntax.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Read your team's runbooks</strong> (usually in wiki or\ngit). Every team has a \"what to do when X alarm fires\" doc. Memorize the\ntop 3 alarms for your service.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>By end of week 2, you should be able to triage a Sev3 ticket solo\n(with a senior shadowing you). By end of week 4, you should be\ncomfortable with the tools to handle most tickets without asking.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"common-mistakes-avoid-these\">Common Mistakes (avoid these)</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Querying the wrong time window</strong> — if the customer\nsays \"failed at 10:43am\" and you query the last 15 minutes when it's now\n11:30am, you'll see nothing. Always adjust <code>@timestamp</code>\nfilters to match the reported time.</li>\n<li><strong>Forgetting to check Pipelines before investigating</strong>\n— if a deploy just finished and errors spiked, rollback is usually\nfaster than debugging. Check the deploy timeline first.</li>\n<li><strong>Not escalating after 30 min</strong> — Sev2 = 10 min\nmitigation, Sev3 = 30 min. If you're stuck, escalate. Asking for help is\nOwnership, not weakness.</li>\n<li><strong>Fixing symptoms instead of root cause</strong> — restarting\na host that's OOMing every hour just delays the next page. Find why it's\nOOMing (memory leak? traffic spike? config issue?) and fix that.</li>\n<li><strong>Not updating the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)\nticket</strong> — the customer is waiting. Even if you're still\ninvestigating, post a worklog every 30 min: \"still investigating, found\nX, checking Y next.\" Radio silence is worse than \"I don't know\nyet.\"</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"final-check-are-you-ready\">Final Check: Are You Ready?</h2>\n<p>Answer these 3 questions:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>A Sev2 alarm fires at 2am for \"HighAPIErrorRate.\" You open Pipelines\nand see a prod deploy finished 10 minutes ago. What's your first\naction?</li>\n<li>A customer reports \"my API call failed, request ID abc-123.\" You\nquery CloudWatch Logs Insights for that request ID and see 0 results.\nWhat are 3 possible reasons?</li>\n<li>You're investigating a ticket and the logs show \"TimeoutException:\ndownstream service X timed out.\" What's your next step?</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Answers:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Rollback.</strong> The deploy timing matches the error\nspike. Mitigation first (rollback), root-cause later (check the diff for\nwhat changed).</li>\n<li>(a) The request ID is wrong (typo, or customer gave you the wrong\none). (b) The logs aged out (CloudWatch default retention is 30 days; if\nthe call was 2 months ago, it's gone). (c) You're querying the wrong log\ngroup (maybe customer hit a different service or environment).</li>\n<li><strong>Check downstream service X's health.</strong> Open their\nCloudWatch metrics / Pipelines / the alarm dependency map in your\nmonitoring tool to see if they had an incident at the same time. If they\nwere down, coordinate with their team. If they were fine, your timeout\nconfig might be wrong.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you got all 3, you're ready for the real drills. If you missed\nany, reread the relevant section above.</p>\n","text":"tools fluency drills — cloudwatch, the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty), pipelines, the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd), your host access and log tooling what this trains: hands on proficiency with the se daily toolchain through \"what would you click/type\" drills what each tool is (quick reference) tool what it is se daily use cloudwatch logs insights aws log query engine (sql like syntax) find errors, trace request flows, measure latency, count by pattern cloudwatch metrics time series data + graphing spot spikes, compare to baseline, measure sla cloudwatch alarms threshold + sns notification root cause for sev2 pages, tune thresholds to prevent noise the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) / the ticketing system a tech company internal ticketing (the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) = customer visible, the ticketing system = internal ops) queue triage, assign/close/escalate, track rcas pipelines a tech company's cicd orchestration (beta → staging → prod) unblock stages, rollback, check a production change approval, push deploys the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) deployment system (hosts, containers, lambda, versions) verify deploy state, read env logs, rollback if needed the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool alarm aggregation + dependency tree trace root alarm from leaf symptom, understand blast radius your host access and log tooling host level ops tooling (grep logs, restart, describe fleet) manual log grep when cw query times out, host diagnostics day 1 access checklist (what to request) before you can do se work, you need: 1. aws account access (prod + staging) — via the cloud access tool, role = readonly or a limited admin role (ask team which) 2. the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) queue membership — ask manager for your team's queue name (like yourteam ops or a real se team support ), file access via the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) portal 3. pipelines permissions — usually auto granted if you own the service in iam, verify you can see your team's pipeline in pipelines your company.dev 4. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) read access — tied to pipelines, verify you can click through to env logs 5. cloudwatch cross account role (if multi account) — some teams need a separate assume role for prod cw read 6. your host access and log tooling permissions — file via your host access and log tooling portal, scope = your service's host fleet 7. the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool dashboard link — ask team for the bookmark (usually team wiki has it) 8. on call schedule — a published se interview guide says you shadow 2 weeks before first solo shift; confirm with manager most of this lands in the first week. if day 3 you still can't open cloudwatch prod logs, escalate. cloudwatch logs insights: 5 query reading drills for each, a small query is shown. your job: what does this query return? then read the explanation. drill 1 your answer (before scrolling): explanation: returns the 50 most recent log lines containing the word error, newest first. the fields line picks which columns to show (timestamp + full message). the filter line keeps only rows matching the pattern. the sort orders by time descending (newest on top). the limit caps output at 50 rows so the query doesn't time out on massive logs. when you'd use it: first move on a sev2 page: \"show me the most recent errors in the last 15 minutes.\" you'd add filter @timestamp ago(15m) before the sort if the log group is huge. drill 2 your answer: explanation: returns all log lines for a single request (identified by requestid = \"abc 123 def\" ), sorted chronologically (oldest first). this traces the full lifecycle of one api call: ingress → validation → downstream calls → response. you see every log the service emitted for that request. when you'd use it: a customer reports \"my api call failed at 9:43am, here's the request id.\" you paste that id into this query to see the full error stack + which downstream call timed out. drill 3 your answer: explanation: returns the average latency for the /api/balances endpoint, grouped into 5 minute buckets. the stats clause aggregates: avg(latency) calculates the mean, by bin(5m) groups rows into 5 minute time windows. output is a time series table (time bucket, avg latency). when you'd use it: a sev2 alarm fires for \"p99 latency spiked.\" you run this to see if the spike affects all endpoints or just one. then you zoom in on the spike's time window and add more filters (like filter latency 1000 to find the slow outliers). drill 4 your answer: explanation: returns the top 10 employees (by employeeid) who triggered the most submit actions, ordered by count descending. the parse line extracts two fields from the log message using a pattern ( employeeid=x action=y ). the filter keeps only submit rows. the stats count() groups by employee and counts how many times each appears. the sort orders by count (highest first), and limit 10 caps output. when you'd use it: a team reports \"someone is spamming the api, our queue is backed up.\" you run this to find the employeeid responsible, then check if it's a legit spike (like a manager bulk approving timecards) or an automation loop gone wrong. drill 5 your answer: explanation: returns the count of 5xx errors (server side failures) grouped by status code (500, 502, 503, etc.) and by 1 hour time buckets. this shows you when errors spiked and which type (500 = internal bug, 502 = downstream timeout, 503 = service overloaded). when you'd use it: a sev2 fires for \"elevated 5xx rate.\" you run this to see the error distribution over time. if all 502s started at 3pm, you check what downstream service deployed at 3pm. if all 503s, you check fleet capacity + autoscaling. common mistake: forgetting the filter statuscode = 500 means you'd count 200s and 400s too, drowning the signal in noise. which tool for which question? (matching drill) for each question, write which tool you'd use first. then check the answers. 1. is the prod deploy stuck at beta stage? 2. what did host i 0abc123 log at 9:15am? 3. who owns the \"higherrorrate\" alarm that just paged me? 4. how many the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) tickets are in our queue right now? 5. what version is currently deployed to prod? 6. why did the last staging deploy rollback automatically? 7. what's the p99 latency for the /submit endpoint over the last hour? 8. which alarm triggered the sev2 page at 2am? 9. the pipeline says \"waiting on a production change approval\" — where's the a production change approval? 10. a host is throwing outofmemoryerror — how do i ssh to it? answers: 1. pipelines — open pipelines your company.dev, find your pipeline, check the beta stage status. if red, click for logs. if yellow, it's waiting (possibly a production change approval). 2. cloudwatch logs insights (or your host access and log tooling if cw times out) — query: filter @timestamp ago(1h) and @timestamp < ago(50m) fields @message (adjust the time window to 9:15am's epoch or use a timestamp filter). your host access and log tooling alternative: host cli logs host i 0abc123 since 9:00 until 9:30 . 3. the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool — search for \"higherrorrate\" in the alarm tree. the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool shows you the dependency graph: which metrics feed the alarm, which teams own the upstream/downstream alarms. 4. the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) — open your ticketing system, navigate to your queue (like yourteam ops ), filter by status=open. the count is right there. or use ticket cli queue stats if your team has a cli. 5. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) (or pipelines) — the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) shows the current deployed version per environment. pipelines also shows it in the stage cards (\"prod: version x.y.z, deployed 2h ago\"). 6. pipelines — click the staging stage, check the \"history\" or \"rollback\" tab. pipelines logs why: usually a canary metric breached threshold (like error rate 5% for 10 min) or a manual abort. 7. cloudwatch metrics (or logs insights if latency is logged) — if your service emits a latency metric, graph it with statistic=p99. if latency is only in logs, run a logs insights query: filter endpoint = \"/submit\" stats percentile(latency, 99) by bin(5m) . 8. the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool (or the page itself) — the page email/slack usually names the alarm. search the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool for that alarm to see the dependency tree. or check your on call dashboard if your team uses one. 9. pipelines — the stage card shows \"waiting on a change approval ticket.\" click that link to see the a production change approval status in the a production change approval portal (approved/pending/rejected). if rejected, you fix the issue and resubmit. 10. your host access and log tooling (or the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd), or ssh directly if you have credentials) — your host access and log tooling: host cli ssh i 0abc123 . the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd): click the host in the env view, then \"ssh\" button if your team has it wired. direct ssh: ssh host 01.internal if you have the vpn + key. scoring: 8+ correct = solid. 6 7 = good, keep drilling. <6 = review the tools table at the top again. drill: you're on call, a sev2 fires. walk me through your first 5 minutes. scenario: 3:17am, you get paged: \"alarm: highapierrorrate in us west 2 breached threshold ( 5% for 10 min).\" the alarm is for your team's service. you wake up, open your laptop. what do you do, in order? your answer (before scrolling): 1. 2. 3. 4. 5. model answer: 1. acknowledge the page (in pagerduty or whatever your team uses). this stops re pages and signals you're awake. 2. open the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool , search for \"highapierrorrate.\" check the alarm tree to see if this is a root alarm or a symptom of an upstream failure (like a downstream service is down, so your api calls are failing). if upstream alarm exists and someone else is on it, you coordinate. if you're the root, you own it. 3. open cloudwatch logs insights for your service's prod log group. run: fields @timestamp, @message filter @message like /error/ and @timestamp ago(15m) sort @timestamp desc limit 100 . this shows you the most recent errors. scan for patterns: same error message repeating? same endpoint failing? same downstream service timing out? 4. open cloudwatch metrics , graph your service's error rate + request count + latency over the last 30 min. check if the spike correlates with a deploy (look at the pipelines timeline) or a traffic spike (request count graph). 5. check pipelines — did a deploy just finish? if the spike started right after a prod push, you prepare to rollback. if no recent deploy, you start deeper investigation (logs + metrics + hypothesis). time check: if you're still investigating at 10 minutes with no mitigation, you escalate (page your manager or the on call senior). sev2 rule: mitigate first (often = rollback), root cause later. drill: reading a pipelines stage you open your service's pipeline (pipelines your company.dev). you see: questions: 1. can you push to prod right now? 2. what's blocking staging? 3. if you need to rollback prod, what version would you roll back to? answers: 1. no. prod deploys require staging soak (usually 24h green). staging is yellow (blocked), so the pipeline won't let you promote. you need to unblock staging first. 2. a change approval ticket is pending approval. production change approvals (production change approval) are required for prod adjacent deploys (staging counts as prod adjacent at many teams). you check the a production change approval portal: if it's waiting on approval, you ping the approver. if it's rejected, you fix the issue (like missing rollback plan or incomplete testing evidence) and resubmit. 3. version 1.2.1 (the version before 1.2.2). pipelines keeps a rollback history. you'd click \"rollback\" on the prod stage, select 1.2.1, confirm. the rollback usually takes 10 20 min (deploy the old version, health check, done). drill: the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) environment view you open the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd), navigate to your service's prod environment. you see: questions: 1. what do you do about the unhealthy host? 2. how do you check the host's logs? 3. if you rollback, what happens to the unhealthy host? answers: 1. investigate first, replace if needed. click the host details to see why /ping is timing out. common causes: host is cpu pegged (check cloudwatch host metrics), disk full (ssh + df h ), or a bug in the /ping handler (check logs). if logs show outofmemoryerror , you restart the host (your host access and log tooling or the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) \"restart\" button). if restart fails, you terminate the host and let autoscaling replace it. 2. cloudwatch or your host access and log tooling. the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) usually links to the host's log stream in cloudwatch (click \"logs\" on the host detail page). or your host access and log tooling: host cli logs host i 0abc123 since 1h . or ssh: ssh host 01.internal , then tail /var/log/service.log . 3. the unhealthy host gets the rollback version too. rollback redeploys the old version to all hosts (healthy + unhealthy). if the unhealthy host is so broken it can't receive the deploy, the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) marks it failed and autoscaling replaces it. either way, rollback doesn't skip hosts. drill: \"which tool?\" speed round 30 seconds each. which tool? 1. \"show me all 500 errors from the last hour.\" 2. \"who's on call for the upstream service that's timing out?\" 3. \"is the current prod version the same as what's in mainline?\" 4. \"what's the p99 latency for our api in the last 30 days?\" 5. \"the deploy to staging failed — what's the error?\" 6. \"a customer filed a the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) ticket 3 hours ago and nobody picked it up — why?\" 7. \"i need to grep the prod logs for a specific employeeid, but cloudwatch times out.\" 8. \"the alarm 'highcpu' fired — what hosts are affected?\" answers: 1. cloudwatch logs insights — query: filter statuscode = 500 filter @timestamp ago(1h) . 2. on call schedule tool (pagerduty / splunk on call / your team's wiki). or ask in slack if it's urgent. 3. pipelines (compare prod version to mainline tip) or git ( git log in your the build system package, compare deployed commit to head). 4. cloudwatch metrics — graph your latency metric with statistic=p99, time range=30d. 5. pipelines — click the staging stage, check the \"logs\" or \"history\" tab for the failure reason. 6. the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) — open the queue, check the ticket state. common reasons: ticket got assigned to the wrong queue (reroute it), or the assignee is ooo (manually reassign). 7. your host access and log tooling — host cli logs grep \"employeeid=12345\" (adjust the pattern). your host access and log tooling searches raw log files on disk, no query timeout. 8. cloudwatch alarms (click the alarm to see which hosts breached) + the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) (check the host list for cpu metrics). or your host access and log tooling ( host cli describe fleet to see cpu by host). drill: day 1 se workflow walkthrough imagine it's your first day as se2. your manager says: \"shadow the on call today. a sev3 ticket just came in: 'customer reports their api call returned 502, request id xyz 123.' walk me through how you'd investigate.\" your answer (step by step): 1. 2. 3. 4. model answer: 1. open the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) , find the ticket. read the customer description: \"i called get /api/balances at 10:43am, got 502 bad gateway. request id: xyz 123.\" note the time (10:43am), endpoint, and request id. 2. open cloudwatch logs insights , query the request id: filter requestid = \"xyz 123\" sort @timestamp asc . this shows the full request trace. scan for errors. common 502 causes: downstream service timed out (you'd see a timeoutexception log), or your service threw an unhandled exception (you'd see a stack trace). 3. hypothesis: let's say the logs show timeoutexception: call to the time tracking service api timed out after 30s . your hypothesis: the downstream the time tracking service service was slow or down at 10:43am. 4. verify: check the time tracking service's cloudwatch metrics around 10:43am (if you have cross account access) or check their public status page. if the time tracking service had a spike, that's your root cause. if the time tracking service was fine, dig deeper: maybe your retry logic is broken, or the 30s timeout is too short. 5. mitigate: if the time tracking service was temporarily down and recovered, no action needed (transient issue). if it's still slow, you coordinate with the time tracking service's on call. if your timeout is wrong, you file a ticket to tune it. 6. update the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty): post a worklog: \"investigated. root cause: downstream the time tracking service service had elevated latency at 10:43am (their p99 spiked to 45s, our timeout is 30s). the time tracking service's incident resolved at 10:50am. this was a transient issue. no action needed. closing ticket.\" then close. time: this investigation should take 15 30 min. if you're stuck after 30 min, escalate to the senior on call. how this connects to your background if you have used a log query tool, a ticketing system, a ci/cd pipeline, and a deployment tool before, the daily se toolchain will feel familiar. what is new is the operational layer: alarm dependency tracing, host level debugging, production change approvals, and the on call tooling your team uses. your manager walks you through those in week one. next steps (after drilling) 1. bookmark these urls (ask your team for exact links): your service's cloudwatch log group (prod + staging) your service's pipelines page your service's the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd) prod environment your team's the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) queue your team's the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool dashboard your on call schedule 2. request day 1 access (see checklist at top). if you don't have prod cloudwatch read by day 3, escalate. 3. shadow on call for 2 weeks before your first solo shift (standard per a published se interview guide). ask to pair on 2 3 sev2/sev3 tickets. watch the full investigation flow. 4. drill the cloudwatch queries — pick 5 from this doc, run them against your service's logs (use staging if you don't have prod yet). get comfortable with the syntax. 5. read your team's runbooks (usually in wiki or git). every team has a \"what to do when x alarm fires\" doc. memorize the top 3 alarms for your service. by end of week 2, you should be able to triage a sev3 ticket solo (with a senior shadowing you). by end of week 4, you should be comfortable with the tools to handle most tickets without asking. common mistakes (avoid these) 1. querying the wrong time window — if the customer says \"failed at 10:43am\" and you query the last 15 minutes when it's now 11:30am, you'll see nothing. always adjust @timestamp filters to match the reported time. 2. forgetting to check pipelines before investigating — if a deploy just finished and errors spiked, rollback is usually faster than debugging. check the deploy timeline first. 3. not escalating after 30 min — sev2 = 10 min mitigation, sev3 = 30 min. if you're stuck, escalate. asking for help is ownership, not weakness. 4. fixing symptoms instead of root cause — restarting a host that's ooming every hour just delays the next page. find why it's ooming (memory leak? traffic spike? config issue?) and fix that. 5. not updating the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) ticket — the customer is waiting. even if you're still investigating, post a worklog every 30 min: \"still investigating, found x, checking y next.\" radio silence is worse than \"i don't know yet.\" final check: are you ready? answer these 3 questions: 1. a sev2 alarm fires at 2am for \"highapierrorrate.\" you open pipelines and see a prod deploy finished 10 minutes ago. what's your first action? 2. a customer reports \"my api call failed, request id abc 123.\" you query cloudwatch logs insights for that request id and see 0 results. what are 3 possible reasons? 3. you're investigating a ticket and the logs show \"timeoutexception: downstream service x timed out.\" what's your next step? answers: 1. rollback. the deploy timing matches the error spike. mitigation first (rollback), root cause later (check the diff for what changed). 2. (a) the request id is wrong (typo, or customer gave you the wrong one). (b) the logs aged out (cloudwatch default retention is 30 days; if the call was 2 months ago, it's gone). (c) you're querying the wrong log group (maybe customer hit a different service or environment). 3. check downstream service x's health. open their cloudwatch metrics / pipelines / the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool to see if they had an incident at the same time. if they were down, coordinate with their team. if they were fine, your timeout config might be wrong. if you got all 3, you're ready for the real drills. if you missed any, reread the relevant section above.","words":3810},{"id":"training-behavioral-lp-star-drills","section":"Training","title":"Behavioral / LP / STAR drills","html":"<h1\nid=\"behavioral--leadership-principle--star-interview-drills\">Behavioral\n/ Leadership Principle / STAR Interview Drills</h1>\n<p><strong>What this trains:</strong> Tell your earlier experience\nstories in STAR shape against the 8 SE-weighted LPs so interviewers see\nthe operational-excellence mindset behind every decision.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-star-is-and-why-interviewers-want-it\">What STAR Is (and Why\nInterviewers Want It)</h2>\n<p><strong>STAR = Situation, Task, Action, Result.</strong></p>\n<p>Interviewers aren't testing if you succeeded. They're testing:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Can you isolate the problem (Situation + Task)?</li>\n<li>Did you own the decision or just follow orders (Action)?</li>\n<li>Did you measure the outcome or just claim success (Result)?</li>\n<li>Do you show the trade-off reasoning (why you picked this path over\nthat one)?</li>\n</ol>\n<p>A complete answer has all four. A weak answer skips Task (so the\ninterviewer doesn't know what you were trying to solve) or Result (so\nthey can't tell if it worked). A strong answer shows the alternatives\nyou ruled out and the metric that proved you were right.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-se-weighted-lp-list-what-they-look-for\">The SE-Weighted LP\nList (What They Look For)</h2>\n<h3 id=\"core-5-these-show-up-in-every-se-story\">Core 5 (these show up in\nEVERY SE story)</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Customer Obsession</strong> — you put the customer (internal\nor external) first, not the easy path for you. Showed urgency when\ncustomers were blocked.</li>\n<li><strong>Ownership</strong> — you acted like it was your system even\nwhen it wasn't your code. Didn't wait for someone else to unblock\nyou.</li>\n<li><strong>Dive Deep</strong> — you traced to root cause, not symptom.\nRead logs, metrics, code. Didn't stop at the surface answer.</li>\n<li><strong>Bias for Action</strong> — you moved fast with 70% data.\nRolled back first, fixed root later. Didn't wait for perfect info.</li>\n<li><strong>Insist on Highest Standards</strong> — you held the bar on\nops (pull requests that land clean on first review, zero-alarm-noise\ntuning, runbook clarity). Raised the bar for the team, not just\nyourself.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"strong-secondary-3-show-these-when-the-story-fits\">Strong\nSecondary 3 (show these when the story fits)</h3>\n<ol start=\"6\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Earn Trust</strong> — you were transparent about mistakes,\nshared context early, didn't hide bad news.</li>\n<li><strong>Are Right A Lot</strong> — you made a call that teammates\ndoubted, turned out correct, data proved it.</li>\n<li><strong>Learn and Be Curious</strong> — you picked up a new\ntool/system/domain fast because the problem required it.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-12-core-se-behavioral-questions\">The 12 Core SE Behavioral\nQuestions</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>owned a production problem that\nwasn't in your code</strong>.</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>dug to root cause</strong> when\nothers wanted to move on.</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>acted fast with incomplete\ninformation</strong>.</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>raised the bar on operational\nhealth</strong> (metrics, alarms, runbooks).</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>disagreed with a teammate or\nmanager</strong> on the right fix.</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>failed</strong> (missed a root\ncause, caused an outage, misjudged priority).</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>handled an unhappy\ncustomer</strong> (internal team or external user blocked by your\nsystem).</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>simplified a painful operational\nprocess</strong>.</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you had to <strong>learn a new system\nfast</strong> to unblock a ticket.</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you were <strong>right when others doubted\nyou</strong>.</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>missed something</strong> in your\ninvestigation and had to go back.</li>\n<li>Tell me about a time you <strong>improved a key metric</strong>\n(MTTR, ticket backlog, alarm noise).</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"building-your-star-stories\">Building Your STAR Stories</h2>\n<p>Pick real situations from your own experience and write each in STAR\nshape. Aim for eight that cover the eight SE-weighted LPs. For each:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Situation:</strong> the context. What system, what\ncustomers, why it mattered.</li>\n<li><strong>Task:</strong> what you needed to do, and any disagreement\nor constraint you faced.</li>\n<li><strong>Action:</strong> what YOU did, step by step. This is the LP\nproof. Show the investigation, the evidence, the decision.</li>\n<li><strong>Result:</strong> the concrete outcome, with a number where\nyou can (tickets dropped, latency improved, customer unblocked in X\nhours).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Strong stories show the trade-off you reasoned through and a metric\nthat proves the outcome. Weak stories skip the Task or the Result.</p>\n<h2 id=\"weak-answer-vs-strong-answer-2-examples\">Weak Answer vs Strong\nAnswer (2 Examples)</h2>\n<h3 id=\"example-1-tell-me-about-a-time-you-dug-to-root-cause\">Example 1:\n\"Tell me about a time you dug to root cause.\"</h3>\n<p><strong>WEAK ANSWER (what NOT to say):</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"We had a bug where duplicate paycodes were showing up. I looked at\nthe code and found the issue was in the eventId generation. I fixed it\nand the bug went away.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Why it's weak:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>No Situation context (which system? which customers affected? why\ndid it matter?).</li>\n<li>No Task (what was the goal? who wanted a quick fix? why did you push\nfor root cause?).</li>\n<li>Action is vague (\"looked at the code\" — how? CW logs? code trace?\nteammate pairing?).</li>\n<li>No Result metric (how do you know it worked? ticket count\nbefore/after? alarm data?).</li>\n<li>No trade-off reasoning (why not just add dedup logic like the\nteammate suggested?).</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>STRONG ANSWER (the Q2 skeleton above, filled\nin):</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"a past cross-month data bug was creating duplicate paycode rows for\ncross-month shifts. A teammate proposed adding dedup logic in the\nsubmission layer to skip the duplicate. I disagreed — that's a band-aid.\nI traced the code and found the root cause: eventId generation happened\nonce per shift instead of once per output row, so when the shift split\nacross months, both rows inherited the same eventId. I grepped callers\nto confirm eventId format had no downstream parsing risk, proposed\nfixing the generation logic, and the teammate agreed after seeing the\ndata. We shipped a 30-line fix instead of adding a dedup layer. Result:\nduplicate-row tickets dropped from 8/month to zero, and the fix was\ncleaner and safer long-term.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Why it's strong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Situation: system + customer impact clear.</li>\n<li>Task: the disagreement (dedup vs root-cause fix) is explicit.</li>\n<li>Action: trace → evidence → grep → proposal, shows Dive Deep.</li>\n<li>Result: metric (8/month → 0) + engineering quality win (no tech debt\nadded).</li>\n<li>Trade-off reasoning: band-aid vs root cause, why root cause\nwon.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"example-2-tell-me-about-a-time-you-failed\">Example 2: \"Tell me\nabout a time you failed.\"</h3>\n<p><strong>WEAK ANSWER (what NOT to say):</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"I once missed a bug in a pull request and it caused a Sev-2. I felt\nbad about it. I learned to be more careful next time.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Why it's weak:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>No details (what was the bug? what broke? why didn't you catch\nit?).</li>\n<li>No ownership language (\"it caused\" — passive, sounds like you're\ndeflecting).</li>\n<li>Vague learning (\"be more careful\" — how? what specific gate did you\nadd?).</li>\n<li>No Result showing you fixed the gap (did you add a test? update the\nchecklist? catch similar bugs later?).</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>STRONG ANSWER (craft one from a real miss if you have one, or\na near-miss):</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"I once raised a pull request that passed build and tests locally but\nfailed the pipeline's <strong>cross-package integration test</strong> in\nalpha. Root cause: I added a new exception type in a shared utility, and\na downstream Lambda test in another package expected the old exception\ntype. My local build didn't catch it because I only ran tests in my\npackage. I should have run <code>the build command</code> in the\ndownstream package too, or used <code>cr -i</code> to include both\npackages in one CR. Mitigation: I reverted immediately, then re-raised a\npull request with both packages included and all integration tests\ngreen. Permanent fix: I added a pre-CR checklist item: 'grep for callers\nin other packages, run their tests too.' Result: I haven't missed a\ncross-package integration failure since, and I shared the checklist with\nthe team so they don't hit the same gap.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Why it's strong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Specific failure (cross-package integration miss).</li>\n<li>Ownership (\"I should have\" — no blame-shifting).</li>\n<li>Concrete learning (pre-CR checklist, grep for callers).</li>\n<li>Result showing the learning stuck (zero cross-package misses\nsince).</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"common-star-traps-and-how-to-avoid-them\">Common STAR Traps (and\nHow to Avoid Them)</h2>\n<h3 id=\"trap-1-telling-we-stories\">Trap 1: Telling \"We\" Stories</h3>\n<p><strong>Problem:</strong> \"We investigated the logs and we found the\nbug.\" <strong>Fix:</strong> Say <strong>\"I\"</strong> for your actions,\n<strong>\"we\"</strong> only when it's genuinely a team effort where you\ncan't separate your contribution. <strong>Example:</strong> \"I pulled\nthe CW logs. The team brainstormed hypotheses on a call, but I traced\nthe code path solo and found the root cause in the eventId logic.\"</p>\n<h3 id=\"trap-2-no-result--no-metric\">Trap 2: No Result / No Metric</h3>\n<p><strong>Problem:</strong> \"I fixed the bug and it worked.\"\n<strong>Fix:</strong> Always include a <strong>before/after\nnumber</strong> (ticket count, alarm frequency, MTTR, customer impact,\ncall success rate). <strong>Example:</strong> \"Duplicate-row tickets\ndropped from 8/month to 0 after the fix deployed.\"</p>\n<h3 id=\"trap-3-rambling-no-structure\">Trap 3: Rambling (No\nStructure)</h3>\n<p><strong>Problem:</strong> You tell a 5-minute story that jumps around\n(logs → code → logs → meeting → code → fix → oh wait I forgot to mention\nthe customer was blocked...). <strong>Fix:</strong> Stick to STAR order.\nWrite it down before the interview if you need to. Practice out\nloud.</p>\n<h3 id=\"trap-4-hiding-the-failure\">Trap 4: Hiding the Failure</h3>\n<p><strong>Problem:</strong> When asked about a time you failed, you\npick something trivial or frame it so you still look perfect.\n<strong>Fix:</strong> Pick a <strong>real failure</strong> (missed a\nroot cause, caused a Sev-2, misjudged priority). Show what you learned\nand how you closed the gap. Interviewers trust people who own\nmistakes.</p>\n<h3 id=\"trap-5-no-trade-off-reasoning\">Trap 5: No Trade-Off\nReasoning</h3>\n<p><strong>Problem:</strong> \"I chose approach A.\" (Interviewer: why not\nB?) <strong>Fix:</strong> Proactively show the alternatives. \"I chose A\nover B because [evidence/constraint]. The trade-off: A was faster but B\nwould've been cleaner long-term. Given customers were blocked, I\nprioritized unblock speed.\"</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"prep-checklist-run-this-before-your-interview\">Prep Checklist\n(Run This Before Your Interview)</h2>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>Pick 8 stories</strong> that cover the 8 SE-weighted LPs.\nWrite each in STAR format (1 page max per story). Practice out loud.\nTime yourself (aim for 2-3 minutes per story).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Memorize your metrics.</strong> For each story, know the\nbefore/after number (ticket count, alarm rate, MTTR, customer unblock\ntime, CR revision count).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Anticipate the follow-up.</strong> After every STAR, the\ninterviewer will ask: \"What would you do differently?\" or \"What did you\nlearn?\" Have the answer ready.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Use your real work.</strong> a past routing\ninvestigation, a past cross-month bug, a past API migration, a\ncode-standards effort, clean-first-review discipline, any triage call.\nThese are YOUR stories. You lived them. They're more believable than\ngeneric examples.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Practice the failure question.</strong> Pick a real miss\n(cross-package integration test, stale workspace false-green, anything\nwhere you caused a Sev-2 or shipped a bug). Own it, show the learning,\nprove the gap is closed.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Read your own self-review.</strong> Your STAR skeletons\nare already written there. Just adapt the language for a verbal answer\n(shorter, conversational, still metric-backed).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Script the \"Tell me about yourself\" opener.</strong> 90\nseconds. Current role (your transition into the SE role). Internship\nhighlight (a backend platform, payroll systems, on-call-adjacent work).\nWhy SE (operations excites you, you like the troubleshooting +\nroot-cause + proactive-health mix). One sentence on what you bring (Dive\nDeep, Ownership, Bias for Action from real incidents).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Prepare 3 questions to ask them.</strong> (1) What's the\nsplit between reactive tickets and proactive ops work on this team? (2)\nHow does the team handle knowledge transfer when a long-running incident\ncloses? (3) What's one operational improvement this team shipped in the\nlast quarter that you're proud of?</p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p>You've built the stories during your earlier experience. Now drill\nthem until the STAR structure is automatic and the metrics are on the\ntip of your tongue. Interviewers aren't testing if you succeeded —\nthey're testing if you can <strong>isolate the problem, own the\ndecision, measure the outcome, and show the trade-off\nreasoning</strong>. That's the SE mindset. You have it. Now prove it in\nSTAR shape.</p>\n","text":"behavioral / leadership principle / star interview drills what this trains: tell your earlier experience stories in star shape against the 8 se weighted lps so interviewers see the operational excellence mindset behind every decision. what star is (and why interviewers want it) star = situation, task, action, result. interviewers aren't testing if you succeeded. they're testing: 1. can you isolate the problem (situation + task)? 2. did you own the decision or just follow orders (action)? 3. did you measure the outcome or just claim success (result)? 4. do you show the trade off reasoning (why you picked this path over that one)? a complete answer has all four. a weak answer skips task (so the interviewer doesn't know what you were trying to solve) or result (so they can't tell if it worked). a strong answer shows the alternatives you ruled out and the metric that proved you were right. the se weighted lp list (what they look for) core 5 (these show up in every se story) 1. customer obsession — you put the customer (internal or external) first, not the easy path for you. showed urgency when customers were blocked. 2. ownership — you acted like it was your system even when it wasn't your code. didn't wait for someone else to unblock you. 3. dive deep — you traced to root cause, not symptom. read logs, metrics, code. didn't stop at the surface answer. 4. bias for action — you moved fast with 70% data. rolled back first, fixed root later. didn't wait for perfect info. 5. insist on highest standards — you held the bar on ops (pull requests that land clean on first review, zero alarm noise tuning, runbook clarity). raised the bar for the team, not just yourself. strong secondary 3 (show these when the story fits) 6. earn trust — you were transparent about mistakes, shared context early, didn't hide bad news. 7. are right a lot — you made a call that teammates doubted, turned out correct, data proved it. 8. learn and be curious — you picked up a new tool/system/domain fast because the problem required it. the 12 core se behavioral questions 1. tell me about a time you owned a production problem that wasn't in your code . 2. tell me about a time you dug to root cause when others wanted to move on. 3. tell me about a time you acted fast with incomplete information . 4. tell me about a time you raised the bar on operational health (metrics, alarms, runbooks). 5. tell me about a time you disagreed with a teammate or manager on the right fix. 6. tell me about a time you failed (missed a root cause, caused an outage, misjudged priority). 7. tell me about a time you handled an unhappy customer (internal team or external user blocked by your system). 8. tell me about a time you simplified a painful operational process . 9. tell me about a time you had to learn a new system fast to unblock a ticket. 10. tell me about a time you were right when others doubted you . 11. tell me about a time you missed something in your investigation and had to go back. 12. tell me about a time you improved a key metric (mttr, ticket backlog, alarm noise). building your star stories pick real situations from your own experience and write each in star shape. aim for eight that cover the eight se weighted lps. for each: situation: the context. what system, what customers, why it mattered. task: what you needed to do, and any disagreement or constraint you faced. action: what you did, step by step. this is the lp proof. show the investigation, the evidence, the decision. result: the concrete outcome, with a number where you can (tickets dropped, latency improved, customer unblocked in x hours). strong stories show the trade off you reasoned through and a metric that proves the outcome. weak stories skip the task or the result. weak answer vs strong answer (2 examples) example 1: \"tell me about a time you dug to root cause.\" weak answer (what not to say): \"we had a bug where duplicate paycodes were showing up. i looked at the code and found the issue was in the eventid generation. i fixed it and the bug went away.\" why it's weak: no situation context (which system? which customers affected? why did it matter?). no task (what was the goal? who wanted a quick fix? why did you push for root cause?). action is vague (\"looked at the code\" — how? cw logs? code trace? teammate pairing?). no result metric (how do you know it worked? ticket count before/after? alarm data?). no trade off reasoning (why not just add dedup logic like the teammate suggested?). strong answer (the q2 skeleton above, filled in): \"a past cross month data bug was creating duplicate paycode rows for cross month shifts. a teammate proposed adding dedup logic in the submission layer to skip the duplicate. i disagreed — that's a band aid. i traced the code and found the root cause: eventid generation happened once per shift instead of once per output row, so when the shift split across months, both rows inherited the same eventid. i grepped callers to confirm eventid format had no downstream parsing risk, proposed fixing the generation logic, and the teammate agreed after seeing the data. we shipped a 30 line fix instead of adding a dedup layer. result: duplicate row tickets dropped from 8/month to zero, and the fix was cleaner and safer long term.\" why it's strong: situation: system + customer impact clear. task: the disagreement (dedup vs root cause fix) is explicit. action: trace → evidence → grep → proposal, shows dive deep. result: metric (8/month → 0) + engineering quality win (no tech debt added). trade off reasoning: band aid vs root cause, why root cause won. example 2: \"tell me about a time you failed.\" weak answer (what not to say): \"i once missed a bug in a pull request and it caused a sev 2. i felt bad about it. i learned to be more careful next time.\" why it's weak: no details (what was the bug? what broke? why didn't you catch it?). no ownership language (\"it caused\" — passive, sounds like you're deflecting). vague learning (\"be more careful\" — how? what specific gate did you add?). no result showing you fixed the gap (did you add a test? update the checklist? catch similar bugs later?). strong answer (craft one from a real miss if you have one, or a near miss): \"i once raised a pull request that passed build and tests locally but failed the pipeline's cross package integration test in alpha. root cause: i added a new exception type in a shared utility, and a downstream lambda test in another package expected the old exception type. my local build didn't catch it because i only ran tests in my package. i should have run the build command in the downstream package too, or used cr i to include both packages in one cr. mitigation: i reverted immediately, then re raised a pull request with both packages included and all integration tests green. permanent fix: i added a pre cr checklist item: 'grep for callers in other packages, run their tests too.' result: i haven't missed a cross package integration failure since, and i shared the checklist with the team so they don't hit the same gap.\" why it's strong: specific failure (cross package integration miss). ownership (\"i should have\" — no blame shifting). concrete learning (pre cr checklist, grep for callers). result showing the learning stuck (zero cross package misses since). common star traps (and how to avoid them) trap 1: telling \"we\" stories problem: \"we investigated the logs and we found the bug.\" fix: say \"i\" for your actions, \"we\" only when it's genuinely a team effort where you can't separate your contribution. example: \"i pulled the cw logs. the team brainstormed hypotheses on a call, but i traced the code path solo and found the root cause in the eventid logic.\" trap 2: no result / no metric problem: \"i fixed the bug and it worked.\" fix: always include a before/after number (ticket count, alarm frequency, mttr, customer impact, call success rate). example: \"duplicate row tickets dropped from 8/month to 0 after the fix deployed.\" trap 3: rambling (no structure) problem: you tell a 5 minute story that jumps around (logs → code → logs → meeting → code → fix → oh wait i forgot to mention the customer was blocked...). fix: stick to star order. write it down before the interview if you need to. practice out loud. trap 4: hiding the failure problem: when asked about a time you failed, you pick something trivial or frame it so you still look perfect. fix: pick a real failure (missed a root cause, caused a sev 2, misjudged priority). show what you learned and how you closed the gap. interviewers trust people who own mistakes. trap 5: no trade off reasoning problem: \"i chose approach a.\" (interviewer: why not b?) fix: proactively show the alternatives. \"i chose a over b because [evidence/constraint]. the trade off: a was faster but b would've been cleaner long term. given customers were blocked, i prioritized unblock speed.\" prep checklist (run this before your interview) 1. pick 8 stories that cover the 8 se weighted lps. write each in star format (1 page max per story). practice out loud. time yourself (aim for 2 3 minutes per story). 2. memorize your metrics. for each story, know the before/after number (ticket count, alarm rate, mttr, customer unblock time, cr revision count). 3. anticipate the follow up. after every star, the interviewer will ask: \"what would you do differently?\" or \"what did you learn?\" have the answer ready. 4. use your real work. a past routing investigation, a past cross month bug, a past api migration, a code standards effort, clean first review discipline, any triage call. these are your stories. you lived them. they're more believable than generic examples. 5. practice the failure question. pick a real miss (cross package integration test, stale workspace false green, anything where you caused a sev 2 or shipped a bug). own it, show the learning, prove the gap is closed. 6. read your own self review. your star skeletons are already written there. just adapt the language for a verbal answer (shorter, conversational, still metric backed). 7. script the \"tell me about yourself\" opener. 90 seconds. current role (your transition into the se role). internship highlight (a backend platform, payroll systems, on call adjacent work). why se (operations excites you, you like the troubleshooting + root cause + proactive health mix). one sentence on what you bring (dive deep, ownership, bias for action from real incidents). 8. prepare 3 questions to ask them. (1) what's the split between reactive tickets and proactive ops work on this team? (2) how does the team handle knowledge transfer when a long running incident closes? (3) what's one operational improvement this team shipped in the last quarter that you're proud of? you've built the stories during your earlier experience. now drill them until the star structure is automatic and the metrics are on the tip of your tongue. interviewers aren't testing if you succeeded — they're testing if you can isolate the problem, own the decision, measure the outcome, and show the trade off reasoning . that's the se mindset. you have it. now prove it in star shape.","words":1937},{"id":"training-coding-scripting-drills","section":"Training","title":"Coding & scripting drills","html":"<h1 id=\"coding-and-scripting-drills-python-first-for-se\">Coding and\nScripting Drills (Python-first for SE)</h1>\n<p><strong>What this trains:</strong> the SE coding bar — small scripts,\nread-and-fix, log parsing, data wrangling, and talk-out-loud problem\nsolving.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-se-coding-bar-plain-words\">The SE Coding Bar (Plain\nWords)</h2>\n<p>The SE coding interview is <strong>not</strong> algorithms and data\nstructures. It's lighter. The bar:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Ask clarifying questions</strong> — what format is the\ninput? what counts as a match? what should the output look like?</li>\n<li><strong>Break into parts</strong> — \"first I'll parse the lines,\nthen I'll filter, then I'll sort.\"</li>\n<li><strong>Working-not-optimal solution</strong> — code that works\nbeats code that's fast. If you solve it in O(n²) and it works, you pass.\nOptimization is bonus.</li>\n<li><strong>Handle one edge case</strong> — empty input, missing field,\nbad data. Pick one, show you thought about it.</li>\n<li><strong>Talk out loud</strong> — narrate your plan before coding,\nexplain as you write, walk through your solution at the end.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Python is the SE scripting default (quick automation, log parsing,\nsimple data wrangling). Bash is second (grep/tail/pipe/find). You\nalready code in Java — this is just showing you can write quick scripts,\nnot proving you're an algorithms wizard.</p>\n<p>Your strong coding already covers this. These drills make sure you're\nloose on the day.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"from-scratch-small-problems-model-solutions\">From-Scratch Small\nProblems (Model Solutions)</h2>\n<h3\nid=\"problem-1-find-words-in-a-string-case-insensitive-whole-word\">Problem\n1: Find Words in a String (Case-Insensitive Whole-Word)</h3>\n<p><strong>Task:</strong> Given a string and a target word, return how\nmany times the word appears as a whole word, case-insensitive.</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Input: <code>\"Error 500 occurred. error on line 500.\"</code>, target\n<code>\"error\"</code></li>\n<li>Output: <code>2</code> (the \"500\" does not count)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Model Solution (Python):</strong></p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>def count_word(text, word):\n # Split on whitespace and punctuation, convert to lowercase\n import re\n words = re.findall(r&#39;\\b\\w+\\b&#39;, text.lower())\n target = word.lower()\n return words.count(target)\n\n# Test\ntext = &quot;Error 500 occurred. error on line 500.&quot;\nprint(count_word(text, &quot;error&quot;)) # Output: 2</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Line-by-line explanation:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>import re</code> — we use regex to find word boundaries</li>\n<li><code>re.findall(r'\\b\\w+\\b', text.lower())</code> — <code>\\b</code>\nis word boundary, <code>\\w+</code> is one-or-more word characters. This\nsplits on spaces and punctuation, returns a list of words in\nlowercase.</li>\n<li><code>target = word.lower()</code> — normalize the target to\nlowercase</li>\n<li><code>words.count(target)</code> — count how many times the target\nappears in the list</li>\n<li>The \"500\" doesn't match \"error\" because we're splitting on word\nboundaries, so numbers stay separate.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Edge case you could mention:</strong> What if the text is\nempty? The list would be empty, count returns 0. Works fine.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"problem-2-parse-a-log-and-find-slow-requests\">Problem 2: Parse a\nLog and Find Slow Requests</h3>\n<p><strong>Task:</strong> Given a log file where each line is\n<code>timestamp request_id duration_ms</code>, find all requests slower\nthan N ms and return them sorted by duration descending.</p>\n<p>Example input (file <code>log.txt</code>):</p>\n<pre><code>2024-01-01T10:00:00 req1 120\n2024-01-01T10:00:01 req2 3500\n2024-01-01T10:00:02 req3 50\n2024-01-01T10:00:03 req4 4200</code></pre>\n<p>N = 1000. Expected output:\n<code>[('req4', 4200), ('req2', 3500)]</code></p>\n<p><strong>Model Solution (Python):</strong></p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>def find_slow_requests(log_file, threshold_ms):\n slow = []\n with open(log_file, &#39;r&#39;) as f:\n for line in f:\n parts = line.strip().split()\n if len(parts) &lt; 3:\n continue # skip malformed lines\n request_id = parts[1]\n duration = int(parts[2])\n if duration &gt; threshold_ms:\n slow.append((request_id, duration))\n # Sort by duration descending\n slow.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)\n return slow\n\n# Test\nresult = find_slow_requests(&#39;log.txt&#39;, 1000)\nprint(result) # [(&#39;req4&#39;, 4200), (&#39;req2&#39;, 3500)]</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Line-by-line:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>with open(log_file, 'r') as f:</code> — open the file safely\n(auto-closes)</li>\n<li><code>line.strip().split()</code> — remove trailing newline, split\non whitespace</li>\n<li><code>if len(parts) &lt; 3: continue</code> — handle edge case:\nmalformed line (missing fields)</li>\n<li><code>int(parts[2])</code> — parse duration as integer</li>\n<li><code>if duration &gt; threshold_ms:</code> — filter</li>\n<li><code>slow.append((request_id, duration))</code> — collect as\ntuple</li>\n<li><code>slow.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)</code> — sort by\nthe second element (duration) descending</li>\n<li>Return the sorted list</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Edge case:</strong> What if the file is empty? Loop doesn't\nrun, slow stays <code>[]</code>, function returns empty list. Works.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"problem-3-count-error-codes-in-a-log\">Problem 3: Count Error\nCodes in a Log</h3>\n<p><strong>Task:</strong> Given a log file where each line contains an\nHTTP status code somewhere in it, count how many times each error code\n(4xx, 5xx) appears.</p>\n<p>Example input:</p>\n<pre><code>INFO 200 OK\nERROR 500 Internal\nWARN 404 Not Found\nERROR 500 Timeout\nINFO 201 Created</code></pre>\n<p>Expected output: <code>{'500': 2, '404': 1}</code></p>\n<p><strong>Model Solution (Python):</strong></p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>def count_error_codes(log_file):\n from collections import defaultdict\n counts = defaultdict(int)\n \n with open(log_file, &#39;r&#39;) as f:\n for line in f:\n parts = line.split()\n for word in parts:\n if word.isdigit():\n code = int(word)\n if 400 &lt;= code &lt; 600: # 4xx or 5xx\n counts[word] += 1\n return dict(counts)\n\n# Test\nresult = count_error_codes(&#39;error_log.txt&#39;)\nprint(result) # {&#39;500&#39;: 2, &#39;404&#39;: 1}</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Line-by-line:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>from collections import defaultdict</code> — makes counting\neasier (auto-initializes to 0)</li>\n<li><code>counts = defaultdict(int)</code> — dictionary that starts keys\nat 0</li>\n<li><code>parts = line.split()</code> — split on whitespace</li>\n<li><code>if word.isdigit():</code> — check if the word is all\ndigits</li>\n<li><code>code = int(word)</code> — convert to int to do range\ncheck</li>\n<li><code>if 400 &lt;= code &lt; 600:</code> — 4xx and 5xx range</li>\n<li><code>counts[word] += 1</code> — increment count (we use\n<code>word</code> as key so it stays a string)</li>\n<li><code>return dict(counts)</code> — convert defaultdict back to\nnormal dict for cleaner output</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Edge case:</strong> What if there's a line with \"4500\" (a\nnumber but not a status code)? It's &gt; 600 so the range check skips\nit. Good.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"problem-4-find-the-most-frequent-value\">Problem 4: Find the Most\nFrequent Value</h3>\n<p><strong>Task:</strong> Given a list of strings, return the one that\nappears most often. If tie, return any.</p>\n<p>Example:\n<code>['apple', 'banana', 'apple', 'orange', 'banana', 'apple']</code> →\n<code>'apple'</code></p>\n<p><strong>Model Solution (Python):</strong></p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>def most_frequent(items):\n from collections import Counter\n if not items:\n return None # edge case: empty list\n counts = Counter(items)\n return counts.most_common(1)[0][0]\n\n# Test\nitems = [&#39;apple&#39;, &#39;banana&#39;, &#39;apple&#39;, &#39;orange&#39;, &#39;banana&#39;, &#39;apple&#39;]\nprint(most_frequent(items)) # &#39;apple&#39;</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Line-by-line:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>from collections import Counter</code> — built-in frequency\ncounter</li>\n<li><code>if not items: return None</code> — handle empty list edge\ncase</li>\n<li><code>counts = Counter(items)</code> — counts each item, returns a\ndict-like object</li>\n<li><code>counts.most_common(1)</code> — returns a list of the top 1\nitem as <code>[(item, count)]</code></li>\n<li><code>[0][0]</code> — first tuple, first element = the item</li>\n<li>Return it</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Edge case covered:</strong> empty list returns None. If you\nwanted to return empty string or raise an error instead, clarify with\nthe interviewer.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"problem-5-reduce-prices-by-a-percent\">Problem 5: Reduce Prices\nby a Percent</h3>\n<p><strong>Task:</strong> Given a string like\n<code>\"Item costs $120.50\"</code>, reduce the price by a given percent\nand return the updated string.</p>\n<p>Example: <code>\"Item costs $120.50\"</code>, reduce by 10% →\n<code>\"Item costs $108.45\"</code></p>\n<p><strong>Model Solution (Python):</strong></p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>import re\n\ndef reduce_price(text, percent):\n def replace_price(match):\n price = float(match.group(1))\n new_price = price * (1 - percent / 100)\n return f&quot;${new_price:.2f}&quot;\n \n # Find all dollar amounts ($X.XX)\n return re.sub(r&#39;\\$(\\d+\\.\\d+)&#39;, replace_price, text)\n\n# Test\ntext = &quot;Item costs $120.50&quot;\nprint(reduce_price(text, 10)) # &quot;Item costs $108.45&quot;</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Line-by-line:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>import re</code> — regex for finding dollar amounts</li>\n<li><code>def replace_price(match):</code> — callback function for each\nmatch</li>\n<li><code>match.group(1)</code> — captures the numeric part (the\n<code>\\d+\\.\\d+</code>)</li>\n<li><code>price * (1 - percent / 100)</code> — reduce by percent (10%\noff = multiply by 0.9)</li>\n<li><code>f\"${new_price:.2f}\"</code> — format back to two decimals</li>\n<li><code>re.sub(r'\\$(\\d+\\.\\d+)', replace_price, text)</code> — find all\n<code>$X.XX</code>, replace each with the callback result</li>\n<li>Return the updated string</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Edge case:</strong> What if there's no dollar sign? The regex\nwon't match, text stays unchanged. Fine.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"problem-6-dedupe-and-sort\">Problem 6: Dedupe and Sort</h3>\n<p><strong>Task:</strong> Given a list of strings with duplicates,\nreturn a sorted list of unique values.</p>\n<p>Example:\n<code>['banana', 'apple', 'banana', 'cherry', 'apple']</code> →\n<code>['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']</code></p>\n<p><strong>Model Solution (Python):</strong></p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>def dedupe_and_sort(items):\n return sorted(set(items))\n\n# Test\nitems = [&#39;banana&#39;, &#39;apple&#39;, &#39;banana&#39;, &#39;cherry&#39;, &#39;apple&#39;]\nprint(dedupe_and_sort(items)) # [&#39;apple&#39;, &#39;banana&#39;, &#39;cherry&#39;]</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Line-by-line:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>set(items)</code> — convert list to set, removes\nduplicates</li>\n<li><code>sorted(...)</code> — convert set back to list and sort\nalphabetically</li>\n<li>Return it</li>\n</ul>\n<p>One line does it. SE coding isn't about showing off, it's about\nsolving the problem.</p>\n<p><strong>Edge case:</strong> Empty list? <code>sorted(set([]))</code>\n→ <code>[]</code>. Works.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"read-and-fix-drills-spot-the-bugs\">Read-and-Fix Drills (Spot the\nBugs)</h2>\n<h3 id=\"drill-1-buggy-python-script\">Drill 1: Buggy Python Script</h3>\n<p><strong>Task:</strong> This script is supposed to create a directory,\nwrite a list of error codes to a file, and print the count. Find\n<strong>all</strong> the bugs.</p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>import os\n\ndef write_errors(error_codes, output_file):\n os.mkdir(&#39;logs&#39;) # Bug 1\n \n # Bug 2: unused import at top (not critical but sloppy)\n import sys\n \n with open(output_file, &#39;w&#39;) as f:\n for code in error_codes:\n f.write(code + &#39;\\n&#39;)\n \n # Bug 3: undefined variable\n print(f&quot;Wrote {count} errors&quot;)\n \n # Bug 4: string matching will match &#39;4500&#39; as containing &#39;500&#39;\n if &#39;500&#39; in error_codes:\n print(&quot;Found 500 error&quot;)\n \n # Bug 5: writing to the same file again overwrites\n with open(output_file, &#39;w&#39;) as f:\n f.write(&quot;Done\\n&quot;)\n\n# Test\nwrite_errors([&#39;404&#39;, &#39;500&#39;, &#39;500&#39;], &#39;errors.txt&#39;)</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Bugs:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong><code>os.mkdir('logs')</code> fails if directory already\nexists.</strong> Fix:\n<code>os.makedirs('logs', exist_ok=True)</code>.</li>\n<li><strong><code>import sys</code> is unused.</strong> Not a runtime\nbug but sloppy. Remove it or use it.</li>\n<li><strong><code>count</code> is never defined.</strong> Fix:\n<code>count = len(error_codes)</code> before the print.</li>\n<li><strong><code>if '500' in error_codes:</code> checks if the string\n'500' is an element. If error_codes is <code>['404', '500']</code>, this\nworks. But if it's a single string <code>'4500'</code>,\n<code>'500' in '4500'</code> is True (substring match). Clarify: are\nerror_codes a list of strings or one string? If list, this is fine. If\nstring, bug. Interviewer might say \"assume list\" — then this is OK.\nMention the ambiguity.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Second <code>with open(output_file, 'w')</code> overwrites\nthe file.</strong> Fix: use <code>'a'</code> (append) or don't write\nagain, or write to a different file.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Model fix:</strong></p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>import os\n\ndef write_errors(error_codes, output_file):\n os.makedirs(&#39;logs&#39;, exist_ok=True)\n \n with open(output_file, &#39;w&#39;) as f:\n for code in error_codes:\n f.write(code + &#39;\\n&#39;)\n \n count = len(error_codes)\n print(f&quot;Wrote {count} errors&quot;)\n \n if &#39;500&#39; in error_codes:\n print(&quot;Found 500 error&quot;)\n \n # Don&#39;t overwrite — if you need to append, use &#39;a&#39;\n with open(output_file, &#39;a&#39;) as f:\n f.write(&quot;Done\\n&quot;)</code></pre>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"drill-2-bash-gotcha--vs-\">Drill 2: Bash Gotcha (&gt; vs\n&gt;&gt;)</h3>\n<p><strong>Task:</strong> This script appends log entries to a file.\nWhat's the bug?</p>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>#!/bin/bash\nLOG_FILE=&quot;app.log&quot;\n\necho &quot;Starting service&quot; &gt; $LOG_FILE\necho &quot;Service started&quot; &gt; $LOG_FILE\necho &quot;Request handled&quot; &gt; $LOG_FILE</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Bug:</strong> <code>&gt;</code> <strong>overwrites</strong>\nthe file each time. Only the last line ends up in the file.</p>\n<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Use <code>&gt;&gt;</code> (append):</p>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>echo &quot;Starting service&quot; &gt;&gt; $LOG_FILE\necho &quot;Service started&quot; &gt;&gt; $LOG_FILE\necho &quot;Request handled&quot; &gt;&gt; $LOG_FILE</code></pre>\n<p>Or use <code>&gt;</code> once for the first line,\n<code>&gt;&gt;</code> for the rest:</p>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>echo &quot;Starting service&quot; &gt; $LOG_FILE\necho &quot;Service started&quot; &gt;&gt; $LOG_FILE\necho &quot;Request handled&quot; &gt;&gt; $LOG_FILE</code></pre>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"drill-3-off-by-one-in-a-loop\">Drill 3: Off-by-One in a Loop</h3>\n<p><strong>Task:</strong> This script processes a list of files. Find\nthe bug.</p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>files = [&#39;file1.txt&#39;, &#39;file2.txt&#39;, &#39;file3.txt&#39;]\n\nfor i in range(len(files) + 1):\n print(f&quot;Processing {files[i]}&quot;)</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Bug:</strong> <code>range(len(files) + 1)</code> goes from 0\nto 3 (since len is 3). Index 3 is out of bounds. Crashes with\n<code>IndexError</code>.</p>\n<p><strong>Fix:</strong> <code>range(len(files))</code> (or just\n<code>for file in files:</code> — no index needed).</p>\n<pre class=\"python\"><code>for file in files:\n print(f&quot;Processing {file}&quot;)</code></pre>\n<p>Simpler and no index math.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"bash-mini-cheatsheet-for-se-with-tiny-drills\">Bash\nMini-Cheatsheet for SE (with Tiny Drills)</h2>\n<h3 id=\"grep--search-for-patterns\">grep — search for patterns</h3>\n<p><strong>Usage:</strong> <code>grep \"pattern\" file.txt</code> or\n<code>command | grep \"pattern\"</code></p>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong> Find all lines with \"ERROR\":</p>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>grep &quot;ERROR&quot; app.log</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Drill:</strong> You have a log <code>app.log</code>. How do\nyou count how many lines contain \"500\"?</p>\n<p><strong>Answer:</strong> <code>grep \"500\" app.log | wc -l</code>\n(grep finds lines, wc -l counts lines)</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"tail--f--follow-a-log-in-real-time\">tail -f — follow a log in\nreal time</h3>\n<p><strong>Usage:</strong> <code>tail -f app.log</code></p>\n<p><strong>Why:</strong> Watch new log lines appear as the service\nwrites them. Cancel with Ctrl+C.</p>\n<p><strong>Drill:</strong> How do you watch only ERROR lines in real\ntime?</p>\n<p><strong>Answer:</strong>\n<code>tail -f app.log | grep \"ERROR\"</code></p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"-vs---write-vs-append\">&gt; vs &gt;&gt; — write vs append</h3>\n<p><strong>Usage:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>command &gt; file</code> — overwrite file</li>\n<li><code>command &gt;&gt; file</code> — append to file</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Drill:</strong> You want to collect 10 separate command\noutputs into one file. Which do you use?</p>\n<p><strong>Answer:</strong> <code>&gt;&gt;</code> (append). If you used\n<code>&gt;</code>, only the last command's output would remain.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"pipe---chain-commands\">pipe (|) — chain commands</h3>\n<p><strong>Usage:</strong> <code>command1 | command2</code> — output of\ncommand1 becomes input to command2</p>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong>\n<code>cat app.log | grep \"ERROR\" | wc -l</code> (count ERROR lines)</p>\n<p><strong>Drill:</strong> How do you find the 5 most recent ERROR lines\nin a log?</p>\n<p><strong>Answer:</strong>\n<code>grep \"ERROR\" app.log | tail -5</code></p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"find--locate-files\">find — locate files</h3>\n<p><strong>Usage:</strong> <code>find /path -name \"pattern\"</code></p>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong> Find all <code>.log</code> files:</p>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>find /var/logs -name &quot;*.log&quot;</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Drill:</strong> How do you find all files modified in the\nlast day?</p>\n<p><strong>Answer:</strong> <code>find /var/logs -mtime -1</code> (mtime\n-1 = modified within last 24 hours)</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"wc--l--count-lines\">wc -l — count lines</h3>\n<p><strong>Usage:</strong> <code>wc -l file.txt</code> or\n<code>command | wc -l</code></p>\n<p><strong>Drill:</strong> How many files are in a directory?</p>\n<p><strong>Answer:</strong> <code>ls | wc -l</code></p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"awk-basics--extract-columns\">awk basics — extract columns</h3>\n<p><strong>Usage:</strong> <code>awk '{print $N}' file</code> — print\ncolumn N (space-separated by default)</p>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong> Log format:\n<code>timestamp level message</code>. Print only the level:</p>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>awk &#39;{print $2}&#39; app.log</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Drill:</strong> Log lines: <code>2024-01-01 ERROR msg</code>,\n<code>2024-01-02 INFO msg</code>. Count ERROR lines.</p>\n<p><strong>Answer:</strong>\n<code>awk '$2 == \"ERROR\"' app.log | wc -l</code> (awk filters, wc\ncounts)</p>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"encouragement-per-the-a-published-se-interview-guide\">Encouragement\n(Per the a published SE interview guide)</h2>\n<p>Your strong coding from the an earlier engineering role already\ncovers this. The a published SE interview guide says: \"Candidates with\nprior coding experience typically do well — the bar is lighter than SDE,\nfocused on scripting and problem-solving, not algorithms.\"</p>\n<p>You've written production Java pull requests, investigated the\ndownstream routing API routing bugs, parsed CloudWatch logs for past\non-call tickets, automated deployment scripts. This drill bank is just\nwarming up your Python and bash muscle memory so you can talk out loud\nsmoothly on the day.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"practice-plan\">Practice Plan</h2>\n<p>Before any SE screen that includes coding:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Do 3 of the from-scratch problems out loud</strong> (pick\ndifferent ones each time). Narrate your plan before coding. Walk through\nyour solution at the end.</li>\n<li><strong>Do 2 of the buggy-script drills.</strong> Spot bugs, explain\nthe fix.</li>\n<li><strong>Run the bash cheatsheet commands</strong> in a terminal once\n(grep a file, tail -f a log, pipe two commands). Muscle memory.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Total time: 30-40 minutes. Do this the morning of the interview or\nthe night before. You'll be loose.</p>\n<p><strong>You've got this.</strong> Your SDE coding background puts you\nahead. These drills just make sure you're ready to show it in the SE\nformat.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>End of drill bank.</strong></p>\n","text":"coding and scripting drills (python first for se) what this trains: the se coding bar — small scripts, read and fix, log parsing, data wrangling, and talk out loud problem solving. the se coding bar (plain words) the se coding interview is not algorithms and data structures. it's lighter. the bar: 1. ask clarifying questions — what format is the input? what counts as a match? what should the output look like? 2. break into parts — \"first i'll parse the lines, then i'll filter, then i'll sort.\" 3. working not optimal solution — code that works beats code that's fast. if you solve it in o(n²) and it works, you pass. optimization is bonus. 4. handle one edge case — empty input, missing field, bad data. pick one, show you thought about it. 5. talk out loud — narrate your plan before coding, explain as you write, walk through your solution at the end. python is the se scripting default (quick automation, log parsing, simple data wrangling). bash is second (grep/tail/pipe/find). you already code in java — this is just showing you can write quick scripts, not proving you're an algorithms wizard. your strong coding already covers this. these drills make sure you're loose on the day. from scratch small problems (model solutions) problem 1: find words in a string (case insensitive whole word) task: given a string and a target word, return how many times the word appears as a whole word, case insensitive. example: input: \"error 500 occurred. error on line 500.\" , target \"error\" output: 2 (the \"500\" does not count) model solution (python): line by line explanation: import re — we use regex to find word boundaries re.findall(r'\\b\\w+\\b', text.lower()) — \\b is word boundary, \\w+ is one or more word characters. this splits on spaces and punctuation, returns a list of words in lowercase. target = word.lower() — normalize the target to lowercase words.count(target) — count how many times the target appears in the list the \"500\" doesn't match \"error\" because we're splitting on word boundaries, so numbers stay separate. edge case you could mention: what if the text is empty? the list would be empty, count returns 0. works fine. problem 2: parse a log and find slow requests task: given a log file where each line is timestamp request id duration ms , find all requests slower than n ms and return them sorted by duration descending. example input (file log.txt ): n = 1000. expected output: [('req4', 4200), ('req2', 3500)] model solution (python): line by line: with open(log file, 'r') as f: — open the file safely (auto closes) line.strip().split() — remove trailing newline, split on whitespace if len(parts) < 3: continue — handle edge case: malformed line (missing fields) int(parts[2]) — parse duration as integer if duration threshold ms: — filter slow.append((request id, duration)) — collect as tuple slow.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=true) — sort by the second element (duration) descending return the sorted list edge case: what if the file is empty? loop doesn't run, slow stays [] , function returns empty list. works. problem 3: count error codes in a log task: given a log file where each line contains an http status code somewhere in it, count how many times each error code (4xx, 5xx) appears. example input: expected output: {'500': 2, '404': 1} model solution (python): line by line: from collections import defaultdict — makes counting easier (auto initializes to 0) counts = defaultdict(int) — dictionary that starts keys at 0 parts = line.split() — split on whitespace if word.isdigit(): — check if the word is all digits code = int(word) — convert to int to do range check if 400 <= code < 600: — 4xx and 5xx range counts[word] += 1 — increment count (we use word as key so it stays a string) return dict(counts) — convert defaultdict back to normal dict for cleaner output edge case: what if there's a line with \"4500\" (a number but not a status code)? it's 600 so the range check skips it. good. problem 4: find the most frequent value task: given a list of strings, return the one that appears most often. if tie, return any. example: ['apple', 'banana', 'apple', 'orange', 'banana', 'apple'] → 'apple' model solution (python): line by line: from collections import counter — built in frequency counter if not items: return none — handle empty list edge case counts = counter(items) — counts each item, returns a dict like object counts.most common(1) — returns a list of the top 1 item as [(item, count)] [0][0] — first tuple, first element = the item return it edge case covered: empty list returns none. if you wanted to return empty string or raise an error instead, clarify with the interviewer. problem 5: reduce prices by a percent task: given a string like \"item costs $120.50\" , reduce the price by a given percent and return the updated string. example: \"item costs $120.50\" , reduce by 10% → \"item costs $108.45\" model solution (python): line by line: import re — regex for finding dollar amounts def replace price(match): — callback function for each match match.group(1) — captures the numeric part (the \\d+\\.\\d+ ) price (1 percent / 100) — reduce by percent (10% off = multiply by 0.9) f\"${new price:.2f}\" — format back to two decimals re.sub(r'\\$(\\d+\\.\\d+)', replace price, text) — find all $x.xx , replace each with the callback result return the updated string edge case: what if there's no dollar sign? the regex won't match, text stays unchanged. fine. problem 6: dedupe and sort task: given a list of strings with duplicates, return a sorted list of unique values. example: ['banana', 'apple', 'banana', 'cherry', 'apple'] → ['apple', 'banana', 'cherry'] model solution (python): line by line: set(items) — convert list to set, removes duplicates sorted(...) — convert set back to list and sort alphabetically return it one line does it. se coding isn't about showing off, it's about solving the problem. edge case: empty list? sorted(set([])) → [] . works. read and fix drills (spot the bugs) drill 1: buggy python script task: this script is supposed to create a directory, write a list of error codes to a file, and print the count. find all the bugs. bugs: 1. os.mkdir('logs') fails if directory already exists. fix: os.makedirs('logs', exist ok=true) . 2. import sys is unused. not a runtime bug but sloppy. remove it or use it. 3. count is never defined. fix: count = len(error codes) before the print. 4. if '500' in error codes: checks if the string '500' is an element. if error codes is ['404', '500'] , this works. but if it's a single string '4500' , '500' in '4500' is true (substring match). clarify: are error codes a list of strings or one string? if list, this is fine. if string, bug. interviewer might say \"assume list\" — then this is ok. mention the ambiguity. 5. second with open(output file, 'w') overwrites the file. fix: use 'a' (append) or don't write again, or write to a different file. model fix: drill 2: bash gotcha ( vs ) task: this script appends log entries to a file. what's the bug? bug: overwrites the file each time. only the last line ends up in the file. fix: use (append): or use once for the first line, for the rest: drill 3: off by one in a loop task: this script processes a list of files. find the bug. bug: range(len(files) + 1) goes from 0 to 3 (since len is 3). index 3 is out of bounds. crashes with indexerror . fix: range(len(files)) (or just for file in files: — no index needed). simpler and no index math. bash mini cheatsheet for se (with tiny drills) grep — search for patterns usage: grep \"pattern\" file.txt or command grep \"pattern\" example: find all lines with \"error\": drill: you have a log app.log . how do you count how many lines contain \"500\"? answer: grep \"500\" app.log wc l (grep finds lines, wc l counts lines) tail f — follow a log in real time usage: tail f app.log why: watch new log lines appear as the service writes them. cancel with ctrl+c. drill: how do you watch only error lines in real time? answer: tail f app.log grep \"error\" vs — write vs append usage: command file — overwrite file command file — append to file drill: you want to collect 10 separate command outputs into one file. which do you use? answer: (append). if you used , only the last command's output would remain. pipe ( ) — chain commands usage: command1 command2 — output of command1 becomes input to command2 example: cat app.log grep \"error\" wc l (count error lines) drill: how do you find the 5 most recent error lines in a log? answer: grep \"error\" app.log tail 5 find — locate files usage: find /path name \"pattern\" example: find all .log files: drill: how do you find all files modified in the last day? answer: find /var/logs mtime 1 (mtime 1 = modified within last 24 hours) wc l — count lines usage: wc l file.txt or command wc l drill: how many files are in a directory? answer: ls wc l awk basics — extract columns usage: awk '{print $n}' file — print column n (space separated by default) example: log format: timestamp level message . print only the level: drill: log lines: 2024 01 01 error msg , 2024 01 02 info msg . count error lines. answer: awk '$2 == \"error\"' app.log wc l (awk filters, wc counts) encouragement (per the a published se interview guide) your strong coding from the an earlier engineering role already covers this. the a published se interview guide says: \"candidates with prior coding experience typically do well — the bar is lighter than sde, focused on scripting and problem solving, not algorithms.\" you've written production java pull requests, investigated the downstream routing api routing bugs, parsed cloudwatch logs for past on call tickets, automated deployment scripts. this drill bank is just warming up your python and bash muscle memory so you can talk out loud smoothly on the day. practice plan before any se screen that includes coding: 1. do 3 of the from scratch problems out loud (pick different ones each time). narrate your plan before coding. walk through your solution at the end. 2. do 2 of the buggy script drills. spot bugs, explain the fix. 3. run the bash cheatsheet commands in a terminal once (grep a file, tail f a log, pipe two commands). muscle memory. total time: 30 40 minutes. do this the morning of the interview or the night before. you'll be loose. you've got this. your sde coding background puts you ahead. these drills just make sure you're ready to show it in the se format. end of drill bank.","words":2372},{"id":"training-operational-excellence-drills","section":"Training","title":"Operational excellence drills","html":"<h1\nid=\"operational-excellence-drills--the-proactive-half-of-the-job\">Operational\nExcellence Drills — The Proactive Half of the Job</h1>\n<p><strong>What this trains:</strong> The daily/weekly/monthly rhythm\nthat separates a reactive SE2 from a proactive SE3 \"go-to person\" —\nalarm quality, metrics literacy, security hygiene, deployment health,\nfleet/capacity, ticket analysis.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-se2-vs-se3-frame\">The SE2 vs SE3 Frame</h2>\n<p><strong>SE2</strong> responds. Sev2 fires, you investigate. Ticket\nlands, you triage. Pipeline breaks, you unblock.</p>\n<p><strong>SE3</strong> anticipates. You tune alarms so they fire at the\nright time, not 3 hours late or 50 false positives a day. You scan the\nsecurity-vulnerability scanner risks every Monday before they hit 20\ndays old. You know Prime Day is next week so you verify ASG scaling\nrules today. You see 12 tickets about the same timeout and file one CR\nto fix the root cause.</p>\n<p>Reactive is baseline. Proactive is the promotion case.</p>\n<p>This drill bank trains the proactive behaviors a real SE team's\nactual SE role page calls out: alarm quality, metrics literacy,\nsecurity/risk hygiene, deployment health, fleet/capacity, ticket\nanalysis. Master these and you own the operational health of a\nservice.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"drill-1--alarm-quality-monitor-the-right-things-and-monitor-things-right\">Drill\n1 — Alarm Quality: Monitor the Right Things AND Monitor Things\nRight</h2>\n<p>Two dimensions. <strong>Monitor the right things</strong> = you have\nalarms on your critical APIs, error rates, latency SLAs, DDB throttles,\nLambda timeouts. <strong>Monitor things right</strong> = your thresholds\nare tuned so alarms fire when there's a real problem, not 50 false Sev2s\na day or 3 hours too late.</p>\n<h3 id=\"scenario-set-5-alarms-whats-wrong-with-each\">Scenario Set (5\nalarms, what's wrong with each?)</h3>\n<p><strong>Alarm A:</strong> \"DDBReadThrottleCount &gt; 10 for 1\ndatapoint within 5 minutes\" Fires 20 times a day. Ops team ignores it\nbecause it's always noise.</p>\n<p><strong>Alarm B:</strong> \"APIErrorRate &gt; 0.5% for 1 datapoint\nwithin 5 minutes\" Your API serves 10,000 requests/hour. This alarm fires\nwhen 50 requests fail. Customers are angry, but by the time you see it\nthe blast radius is 200 failed requests.</p>\n<p><strong>Alarm C:</strong> \"Lambda FunctionErrors &gt; 0\" Fires every\ntime a single Lambda invocation fails, even expected validation errors.\nYou get 30 Sev2 pages a day.</p>\n<p><strong>Alarm D:</strong> \"GetEmployeeBalance P99 latency &gt; 2000ms\nfor 3 datapoints within 15 minutes\" No runbook. No owner. Fires once a\nweek, someone investigates for 2 hours, finds nothing, closes the\nSev2.</p>\n<p><strong>Alarm E:</strong> Your service has 6 core APIs. You have\nalarms on 4 of them. The other 2 APIs silently degraded last month and\nnobody noticed until a customer filed a Sev2.</p>\n<h3 id=\"your-task\">Your Task</h3>\n<p>For each alarm, name the problem category (threshold too loose, too\naggressive, missing alarm, no runbook, nobody owns it) and write one\nsentence fixing it.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"model-answers\">Model Answers</h3>\n<p><strong>Alarm A</strong> — threshold too aggressive + alarm fatigue.\nFix: increase threshold to 50 throttles sustained for 2 consecutive\n5-min periods. Add context: \"DDB capacity = X WCU, throttle at Y traffic\nis expected under burst.\"</p>\n<p><strong>Alarm B</strong> — threshold too loose + detection too slow.\nFix: lower threshold to 0.2% for 2 consecutive datapoints. Add a second\nalarm at 1% for 1 datapoint to catch spikes faster. Runbook: rollback\ndecision tree.</p>\n<p><strong>Alarm C</strong> — every error is not a Sev2. Fix: exclude\nexpected validation errors (400s from bad client input). Alarm only on\n5xx server errors &gt; 10/min sustained for 5 minutes. Add a weekly\nreport tracking all errors so you can spot trends without paging.</p>\n<p><strong>Alarm D</strong> — no runbook, no owner. Fix: write a 10-line\nrunbook: \"check CW Insights for slow queries, check downstream the\ndownstream routing API latency, check DDB read capacity, escalate to\non-call if none of those\". Assign ownership to the team that owns\nGetEmployeeBalance.</p>\n<p><strong>Alarm E</strong> — missing alarms. Fix: audit all 6 APIs, add\nP99 latency + error rate alarms for the 2 uncovered. Checklist: every\ncustomer-facing API gets 2 alarms minimum (latency + errors).</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-2--metrics-literacy-reading-graphs-like-a-pro\">Drill 2 —\nMetrics Literacy: Reading Graphs Like a Pro</h2>\n<p>Three concepts you need cold:</p>\n<p><strong>P50 / P90 / P99 (percentiles):</strong> If P99 latency =\n800ms, that means 99% of requests finish in 800ms or less. The 1%\noutliers might be 3 seconds. P50 (median) hides outliers. P99 catches\nthe worst customer experience. Always look at P99.</p>\n<p><strong>Latency vs error rate vs saturation:</strong> Latency = how\nlong requests take. Error rate = % of requests failing. Saturation = how\nclose you are to capacity (CPU 90%, DDB throttles, Lambda concurrency\n950/1000). High latency + low errors = downstream slowness or DB\ncontention. High errors + normal latency = bad deploy or dependency\nfailure. High saturation = you're about to fall over.</p>\n<p><strong>Reading a spike:</strong> Spike at 3am every night = batch\njob. Spike on Monday 9am = weekly load. Spike that starts at deploy time\n+ stays elevated = bad code. Spike during a known event (Prime Day) =\nexpected load.</p>\n<h3\nid=\"scenario-set-3-graphs-describe-what-you-see-and-what-to-check\">Scenario\nSet (3 graphs, describe what you see and what to check)</h3>\n<p><strong>Graph A:</strong> GetEmployeeBalance P99 latency. Flat at\n200ms for 3 weeks. At 2pm today it jumps to 1200ms and stays there.\nError rate is 0.1% (normal). Traffic volume unchanged.</p>\n<p><strong>Graph B:</strong> SubmitTimeOff error rate. Flat at 0.05% for\n2 months. At 10am today it spikes to 5% for 1 hour, then drops back to\n0.05%. Latency unchanged. Traffic unchanged. No deploy at 10am.</p>\n<p><strong>Graph C:</strong> Lambda GetShiftDetails invocations.\n1000/hour baseline. At midnight every night it spikes to 8000/hour for\n15 minutes. No corresponding spike in API traffic. No alarms.</p>\n<h3 id=\"your-task-1\">Your Task</h3>\n<p>For each graph, write 2 sentences: what's happening, and what's the\nfirst thing you check.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"model-answers-1\">Model Answers</h3>\n<p><strong>Graph A</strong> — sustained latency increase with no error\nspike or traffic change = downstream dependency got slow or DB\ncontention. First check: CW Insights query for GetEmployeeBalance calls,\nfilter by duration &gt; 1000ms, see if they're all calling the same\ndownstream service (the downstream routing API? DDB?). Second check: DDB\nread capacity metrics — are you throttling?</p>\n<p><strong>Graph B</strong> — 1-hour error spike with no deploy or\ntraffic change = transient downstream failure. First check: CW logs for\nSubmitTimeOff errors during 10-11am, grep for exception types. Second\ncheck: the downstream routing API or downstream service latency graphs\nat 10am — did a dependency have a blip?</p>\n<p><strong>Graph C</strong> — nightly batch spike. Midnight = scheduled\njob. First check: grep your codebase for cron jobs or EventBridge rules\nthat run at midnight. Second check: is this expected load? If yes,\ndocument it in your runbook so on-call doesn't panic. If no, file a\nticket to understand why 8x traffic happens nightly.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"drill-3--weekly-securityrisk-hygiene-the-dashboards-you-own\">Drill 3\n— Weekly Security/Risk Hygiene: The Dashboards You Own</h2>\n<p>A tech company SEs own 5 recurring security/availability checks. You\nrun these weekly (or daily for high-risk services). The rule:\n<strong>address risks older than 20 days</strong>. If a the\nsecurity-vulnerability scanner risk sits for 3 weeks, your SDM will ask\nwhy.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-5-dashboards\">The 5 Dashboards</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>the security-vulnerability scanner</strong> — scans your\npackages for known CVEs (security vulnerabilities). Shows risk count,\nseverity, age. You fix high-severity risks first, then medium.\nLow-severity risks you accept or fix in batches.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>the dependency-compliance scanner</strong> — software\ncompliance. Checks if your dependencies have licenses a tech company can\nuse, if you're using deprecated packages, if you need security\napprovals.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Vulnerabilities dashboard</strong> (part of the\nsecurity-vulnerability scanner) — CVE details. Click through to see\nwhich package version is affected, which version fixes it, and the blast\nradius.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Patching cadence</strong> — are your hosts/containers\nrunning the latest AMI with security patches? If you're on ECS Fargate,\na tech company patches for you. If you're on EC2, you own the patching\nschedule.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>the cloud policy scanner risks</strong> — checks your IAM\npolicies, S3 bucket permissions, DDB encryption, logging config. Flags\nthings like \"S3 bucket is public\" or \"IAM role has *\npermissions.\"</p></li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"drill-prioritizing-5-risks\">Drill: Prioritizing 5 Risks</h3>\n<p>You're the SE for the time-tracking service. It's Monday morning. You\nopen the security-vulnerability scanner and see 5 risks:</p>\n<p><strong>Risk 1:</strong> High-severity CVE in log4j (dependency in\nyour Java package). Age: 35 days. Exploit allows remote code\nexecution.</p>\n<p><strong>Risk 2:</strong> Medium-severity CVE in a test-only\ndependency (JUnit). Age: 10 days. No production impact.</p>\n<p><strong>Risk 3:</strong> Low-severity license issue with a frontend\nnpm package. Age: 50 days. Legal team flagged it but said \"fix when\nconvenient.\"</p>\n<p><strong>Risk 4:</strong> the cloud policy scanner risk: DDB table\ndoesn't have point-in-time recovery enabled. Age: 25 days. No\nencryption-at-rest issue.</p>\n<p><strong>Risk 5:</strong> the dependency-compliance scanner:\ndeprecated the build system package (old the service framework (like\ngRPC or Spring Boot) version). Age: 5 days. Upgrade path documented.</p>\n<h3 id=\"your-task-2\">Your Task</h3>\n<p>Rank 1-5 by urgency. For the top 2, write one sentence explaining why\nyou're prioritizing them and what you'll do this week.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"model-answer\">Model Answer</h3>\n<p><strong>Rank:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Risk 1 (log4j CVE, 35 days old, high severity, remote code\nexec)</li>\n<li>Risk 4 (DDB point-in-time recovery, 25 days old, approaching 30-day\nSLA)</li>\n<li>Risk 5 (deprecated the service framework (like gRPC or Spring Boot),\nrecent, documented upgrade)</li>\n<li>Risk 2 (test-only, medium severity, 10 days is fine)</li>\n<li>Risk 3 (legal said \"when convenient,\" 50 days but low blast\nradius)</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Top 2 actions:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Risk 1:</strong> High-severity CVE past 20 days = top\npriority. This week: file a pull request upgrading log4j to the patched\nversion, test in alpha, push to beta by Friday. If the upgrade is\nbreaking, file a Sev2 and get help from the service framework (like gRPC\nor Spring Boot) team.</p>\n<p><strong>Risk 4:</strong> the cloud policy scanner risks over 20 days\nget flagged in ops review. This week: file a simple CR enabling\npoint-in-time recovery on the DDB table (one line of CDK), deploy to\nprod. Takes 30 minutes, clears the risk.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-4--deployment-health-rollback-hotfix-or-wait\">Drill 4 —\nDeployment Health: Rollback, Hotfix, or Wait?</h2>\n<p>Your pipeline breaks or your service degrades post-deploy. You have 3\noptions:</p>\n<p><strong>Rollback</strong> — revert to the last known good version.\nFastest fix, safest move. Do this when the new deploy is clearly broken\nand the old version was stable.</p>\n<p><strong>Hotfix</strong> — deploy a small fix on top of the broken\nversion. Use this when rollback isn't possible (e.g., you ran a one-way\nDB migration) or when the fix is a 1-line config change.</p>\n<p><strong>Wait</strong> — sometimes a transient issue (downstream\nservice blip, DNS propagation) looks like a deploy problem but isn't.\nWait 15 minutes, check metrics again.</p>\n<h3 id=\"when-you-need-a-production-change-approval\">When You Need a\nproduction change approval</h3>\n<p><strong>a production change approval (production change\napproval)</strong> = approval from a senior engineer or manager to push\na high-risk change to production. You need one when:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Deploying during a freeze window (code freeze before Prime Day,\nBlack Friday)</li>\n<li>Deploying a rollback during an active Sev2</li>\n<li>Deploying a hotfix that bypasses normal testing (alpha/beta\nskipped)</li>\n<li>Making infrastructure changes (DDB capacity bump, ASG scaling rule\nchange)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Your pipeline may require a production change approval approval at\nthe prod stage. Don't skip it. If you push without an approved a\nproduction change approval, your SDM will hear about it.</p>\n<h3 id=\"drill-3-scenarios-what-do-you-do\">Drill: 3 Scenarios, What Do\nYou Do?</h3>\n<p><strong>Scenario A:</strong> You deploy the time-tracking service rev\n47 to prod at 2pm. At 2:05pm, the GetEmployeeBalance API error rate\njumps from 0.1% to 8%. Latency unchanged. Rev 46 was stable for 2 weeks.\nNo DB migration in rev 47.</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario B:</strong> You deploy a DB schema change (new DDB\nGSI) at 10am. At 10:15am, writes to the table start failing with\n\"ResourceNotFoundException.\" Rollback would delete the GSI, but you need\nit for the new feature launching tomorrow.</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario C:</strong> At 3pm, SubmitTimeOff P99 latency jumps\nfrom 300ms to 2000ms. No deploy in the last 6 hours. Your last deploy\nwas yesterday and it's been stable. CW logs show the downstream routing\nAPI downstream is returning 503s.</p>\n<h3 id=\"your-task-3\">Your Task</h3>\n<p>For each scenario, choose rollback / hotfix / wait and write one\nsentence justifying it.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"model-answers-2\">Model Answers</h3>\n<p><strong>Scenario A</strong> — rollback. Error rate spiked immediately\npost-deploy, rev 46 was stable, no migration blocker. Rollback to rev 46\nnow, investigate rev 47 offline, re-deploy after fix.</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario B</strong> — hotfix. Rollback would delete the GSI\nand you need it tomorrow. File a 1-line CR fixing the\nResourceNotFoundException (probably a missing IAM permission or a typo\nin the GSI name). Deploy the hotfix with a production change approval\napproval (Sev2 active, prod hotfix).</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario C</strong> — wait (and monitor). No recent deploy,\ndownstream the downstream routing API is the culprit. Check the\ndownstream routing API's status page or Slack channel. If the downstream\nrouting API recovers in 15 minutes, your service will too. If it\ndoesn't, escalate to the downstream routing API's on-call. Don't\nrollback your own deploy when the problem is external.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"drill-5--fleetcapacity-prime-day-is-next-week-what-do-you-check\">Drill\n5 — Fleet/Capacity: Prime Day is Next Week, What Do You Check?</h2>\n<p><strong>Fleet = your service's compute capacity.</strong> ECS tasks,\nLambda concurrency, EC2 instances. <strong>Capacity planning = making\nsure you have enough fleet to handle peak traffic without throttling or\ntiming out.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Peak / HVE (High Volume Event) days</strong> = Prime Day,\nBlack Friday, Cyber Monday, back-to-school in some regions. Traffic can\n5x your normal baseline. If you don't scale your fleet in advance, your\nservice will fall over.</p>\n<h3 id=\"what-an-se-checks-before-prime-day\">What an SE Checks Before\nPrime Day</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>ASG (Auto Scaling Group) rules:</strong> Are your\nmin/max/desired instance counts set for peak load? If your normal fleet\nis 10 tasks and Prime Day will 5x traffic, bump desired to 50 and max to\n75.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>DDB capacity:</strong> Read/write capacity units\n(RCU/WCU). If you're on-demand, you're auto-scaled. If you're on\nprovisioned, check your current utilization and bump capacity\n3-5x.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Lambda concurrency limits:</strong> Your account has a\nregional limit (default 1000 concurrent invocations). If your function\nhits 1000 during peak, new invocations get throttled. Request a limit\nincrease or reserve concurrency for critical functions.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Downstream dependencies:</strong> Does your service call\nthe downstream routing API, a downstream classification service, another\ninternal service? Ping their on-call to confirm they're scaled for Prime\nDay too.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Alarms and dashboards:</strong> Create a Prime Day\ndashboard with your top 5 metrics (traffic, error rate, latency, DDB\nthrottles, Lambda errors). Share it with your SDM and on-call.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Dry run:</strong> Deploy your capacity changes to beta 3\ndays before Prime Day. Run a load test (if possible) or at least verify\nthe fleet scales up correctly.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"drill-5-things-to-check\">Drill: 5 Things to Check</h3>\n<p>You're the SE for the GetEmployeeBalance API. Your SDM says \"Prime\nDay is June 15, traffic will 5x, make sure we're ready.\" Today is June\n8. List 5 things you check this week and what \"good\" looks like for\neach.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"model-answer-1\">Model Answer</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>ASG desired/max counts:</strong> Current: 8 ECS tasks.\nPrime Day estimate: 40 tasks. Action: bump desired to 40, max to 60.\nDeploy to beta June 10, verify tasks launch. Deploy to prod June 12.\nGood = all 40 tasks healthy in beta.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>DDB read capacity (the GetEmployeeBalance API\ntable):</strong> Current: 100 RCU, 60% utilized at peak. Prime Day 5x =\n300 RCU needed. Action: bump to 500 RCU (buffer). Deploy June 12. Good =\nno throttles in beta dry run.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Lambda concurrency (if the GetEmployeeBalance API calls a\nLambda):</strong> Current limit: 1000 concurrent in account, the\nGetEmployeeBalance API uses ~50 at peak. Prime Day = 250 concurrent.\nAction: reserve 300 concurrency for the GetEmployeeBalance API Lambda.\nGood = no throttles.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>the downstream routing API dependency:</strong> the\nGetEmployeeBalance API calls the downstream routing API searchBalances.\nAction: ping the downstream routing API on-call (the dependency team's\non-call), confirm they're scaled. Good = they reply \"yes, scaled to 10K\nTPS.\"</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Prime Day dashboard:</strong> Metrics = the\nGetEmployeeBalance API traffic, error rate, P99 latency, DDB throttles,\nthe downstream routing API call latency. Action: create dashboard, share\nlink in team Slack. Good = SDM can watch live on Prime Day.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-6--ticket-kpis-spot-the-systemic-problem\">Drill 6 — Ticket\nKPIs: Spot the Systemic Problem</h2>\n<p>Every SE team tracks ticket metrics monthly: volume, time-to-resolve,\nrepeat issues, category breakdown. These metrics tell you if you're\nreacting well (time-to-resolve is low) and if you're preventing well\n(repeat issues are dropping because you fixed root causes).</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-metrics-you-track\">The Metrics You Track</h3>\n<p><strong>Volume:</strong> How many tickets this month? Trend up/down\nvs last 3 months? If volume is climbing, why? New feature launched? More\ncustomers? Or a new recurring bug?</p>\n<p><strong>Time-to-resolve (TTR):</strong> Median hours from ticket open\nto close. If TTR spikes, you're either short-staffed or hitting complex\nissues. Break it down by priority (Sev2 vs Sev3).</p>\n<p><strong>Repeat issues:</strong> Same root cause, multiple tickets.\nExample: 8 tickets about \"GetShiftDetails timeout\" in 2 weeks. If you\nsee a cluster, file one CR to fix the root cause.</p>\n<p><strong>Category breakdown:</strong> What % of tickets are config\nissues, code bugs, user errors, dependencies? If 40% are \"the downstream\nrouting API returned 503,\" you have a dependency reliability problem,\nnot a your-service problem.</p>\n<p><strong>Top 3 issues:</strong> Every month, call out the top 3 most\nfrequent issues. Propose fixes or mitigations for each.</p>\n<h3 id=\"drill-analyze-this-months-tickets\">Drill: Analyze This Month's\nTickets</h3>\n<p>You're the SE for SubmitTimeOff API. Here's April's ticket data:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Volume:</strong> 32 tickets (up from 22 in March)</li>\n<li><strong>TTR median:</strong> 4 hours (same as March)</li>\n<li><strong>Repeat issues:</strong> 9 tickets about \"validation error:\nemployeeId not found\" (all from India contingent workers). 6 tickets\nabout \"the downstream routing API timeout.\" 4 tickets about \"duplicate\nsubmission blocked.\"</li>\n<li><strong>Category breakdown:</strong> 50% code bugs, 30% downstream\ndependency, 20% user error.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"your-task-4\">Your Task</h3>\n<p>Write 3 bullets: (1) what's the biggest problem, (2) what's the root\ncause hypothesis, (3) what do you do this month to fix it.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3 id=\"model-answer-2\">Model Answer</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>Biggest problem:</strong> 9 tickets in one month about\n\"employeeId not found\" for India contingent workers. That's 28% of all\ntickets, all the same failure mode.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Root cause hypothesis:</strong> SubmitTimeOff validates\nemployeeId by calling the downstream routing API or checking a local\ncache. India contingent workers (yellow/green badge) might not be in the\ncache or the downstream routing API might not have them indexed yet.\nAlternatively, there's a data sync delay between the HR data feed (the\nthird-party payroll vendor India feed) and the downstream routing\nAPI.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Action this month:</strong> File one CR to improve the\nerror message (\"employeeId X not found in the downstream routing API,\ncheck the HR data feed ingestion status\") AND add a fallback: if the\ndownstream routing API returns 404, call a secondary lookup (the\ninternal schedule store or the HR data feed direct). This fixes the\ncustomer experience and reduces repeat tickets. Also: ping the HR data\nfeed pipeline owner (check a reference doc) to confirm the the\nvendor-to-internal pipeline is healthy.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-7--weekly-rhythm-checklist-the-se3-cadence\">Drill 7 —\nWeekly Rhythm Checklist (The SE3 Cadence)</h2>\n<p>Proactive SEs run on a rhythm. Here's the weekly/monthly checklist\nthat separates an SE3 from an SE2.</p>\n<h3 id=\"daily-15-min\">Daily (15 min)</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Scan your service dashboard: traffic, error rate, latency. Any\nanomalies? If yes, investigate.</li>\n<li>Check open Sev2s / Sev3s. Any stuck for &gt;1 day? Unblock or\nescalate.</li>\n<li>Glance at pipeline: any stages red? Any deploy waiting on\napproval?</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"weekly-1-2-hours\">Weekly (1-2 hours)</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Monday morning:</strong> the security-vulnerability scanner\nrisks. Fix anything &gt;20 days old. File pull requests for\nhigh-severity CVEs.</li>\n<li><strong>Wednesday:</strong> Deployment health. Review last week's\ndeploys. Any rollbacks? Any post-deploy issues? Document in your ops\nlog.</li>\n<li><strong>Thursday:</strong> Alarm audit. Did any alarms fire this\nweek? Were they real issues or false positives? Tune thresholds if\nneeded.</li>\n<li><strong>Friday:</strong> Ticket analysis. Count repeat issues. If 3+\ntickets on the same topic, file a pull request to fix the root\ncause.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"monthly-half-day\">Monthly (half day)</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ticket KPIs report:</strong> Volume, TTR, repeat issues, top\n3 problems. Share with SDM.</li>\n<li><strong>Security dashboard deep dive:</strong> the\nsecurity-vulnerability scanner + the dependency-compliance scanner + the\ncloud policy scanner. Close out risks older than 30 days.</li>\n<li><strong>Capacity planning:</strong> Look ahead 2 months. Any peak\nevents (Prime Day, Black Friday)? Any new features launching that will\nincrease traffic? File capacity increase requests now.</li>\n<li><strong>Fleet/IMR review:</strong> Are your ASGs / ECS services\nscaled correctly? Any cost optimization opportunities\n(over-provisioned)?</li>\n<li><strong>Ops review prep:</strong> Most teams have a weekly or\nmonthly ops meeting. Bring your top 3 operational wins (fixed a\nrecurring issue, tuned an alarm, scaled for peak) and top 3 risks (aging\nthe security-vulnerability scanner CVE, upcoming capacity crunch,\nbrittle deployment).</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-big-picture\">The Big Picture</h2>\n<p>All of this — alarms, metrics, security hygiene, deployment health,\nfleet/capacity, ticket analysis — is the <strong>proactive half of the\nSE job</strong>. The reactive half (troubleshooting Sev2s) gets you\nbaseline competence. The proactive half gets you promoted.</p>\n<p><strong>SE2 behavior:</strong> Wait for the alarm to fire, then\ninvestigate. <strong>SE3 behavior:</strong> Tune the alarm so it fires\nat the right time. Fix the root cause so the alarm stops firing.</p>\n<p><strong>SE2 behavior:</strong> Clear the security-vulnerability\nscanner risks when your SDM asks about them. <strong>SE3\nbehavior:</strong> Check the security-vulnerability scanner every\nMonday, clear risks before they hit 20 days.</p>\n<p><strong>SE2 behavior:</strong> Deploy when the pipeline is green,\nrollback when it's red. <strong>SE3 behavior:</strong> Pre-scale your\nfleet for Prime Day 1 week in advance. Create a dashboard. Dry-run the\ncapacity bump. Write the rollback runbook before you need it.</p>\n<p>Master the drills in this file and you'll own the operational health\nof your service. That's the SE3 signal.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"next-steps\">Next Steps</h2>\n<p>You've now trained: troubleshooting (01), AWS/tools (02), RCA (03),\nSE interview (04), daily SE work (05), this one (06 operational\nexcellence). The 7th and final drill bank will be: \"Career growth + SE3\nsignal\" — how to demonstrate SE3 behaviors in your first 90 days, how to\nwrite your self-review showing operational impact, and how to frame your\nwork for promotion. That one ties it all together.</p>\n<p>After that, you'll have a complete SE1 → SE2 → SE3 training corpus.\nRun these drills until the moves are muscle memory. Then you'll walk\ninto your SE role and own it from day 1.</p>\n","text":"operational excellence drills — the proactive half of the job what this trains: the daily/weekly/monthly rhythm that separates a reactive se2 from a proactive se3 \"go to person\" — alarm quality, metrics literacy, security hygiene, deployment health, fleet/capacity, ticket analysis. the se2 vs se3 frame se2 responds. sev2 fires, you investigate. ticket lands, you triage. pipeline breaks, you unblock. se3 anticipates. you tune alarms so they fire at the right time, not 3 hours late or 50 false positives a day. you scan the security vulnerability scanner risks every monday before they hit 20 days old. you know prime day is next week so you verify asg scaling rules today. you see 12 tickets about the same timeout and file one cr to fix the root cause. reactive is baseline. proactive is the promotion case. this drill bank trains the proactive behaviors a real se team's actual se role page calls out: alarm quality, metrics literacy, security/risk hygiene, deployment health, fleet/capacity, ticket analysis. master these and you own the operational health of a service. drill 1 — alarm quality: monitor the right things and monitor things right two dimensions. monitor the right things = you have alarms on your critical apis, error rates, latency slas, ddb throttles, lambda timeouts. monitor things right = your thresholds are tuned so alarms fire when there's a real problem, not 50 false sev2s a day or 3 hours too late. scenario set (5 alarms, what's wrong with each?) alarm a: \"ddbreadthrottlecount 10 for 1 datapoint within 5 minutes\" fires 20 times a day. ops team ignores it because it's always noise. alarm b: \"apierrorrate 0.5% for 1 datapoint within 5 minutes\" your api serves 10,000 requests/hour. this alarm fires when 50 requests fail. customers are angry, but by the time you see it the blast radius is 200 failed requests. alarm c: \"lambda functionerrors 0\" fires every time a single lambda invocation fails, even expected validation errors. you get 30 sev2 pages a day. alarm d: \"getemployeebalance p99 latency 2000ms for 3 datapoints within 15 minutes\" no runbook. no owner. fires once a week, someone investigates for 2 hours, finds nothing, closes the sev2. alarm e: your service has 6 core apis. you have alarms on 4 of them. the other 2 apis silently degraded last month and nobody noticed until a customer filed a sev2. your task for each alarm, name the problem category (threshold too loose, too aggressive, missing alarm, no runbook, nobody owns it) and write one sentence fixing it. model answers alarm a — threshold too aggressive + alarm fatigue. fix: increase threshold to 50 throttles sustained for 2 consecutive 5 min periods. add context: \"ddb capacity = x wcu, throttle at y traffic is expected under burst.\" alarm b — threshold too loose + detection too slow. fix: lower threshold to 0.2% for 2 consecutive datapoints. add a second alarm at 1% for 1 datapoint to catch spikes faster. runbook: rollback decision tree. alarm c — every error is not a sev2. fix: exclude expected validation errors (400s from bad client input). alarm only on 5xx server errors 10/min sustained for 5 minutes. add a weekly report tracking all errors so you can spot trends without paging. alarm d — no runbook, no owner. fix: write a 10 line runbook: \"check cw insights for slow queries, check downstream the downstream routing api latency, check ddb read capacity, escalate to on call if none of those\". assign ownership to the team that owns getemployeebalance. alarm e — missing alarms. fix: audit all 6 apis, add p99 latency + error rate alarms for the 2 uncovered. checklist: every customer facing api gets 2 alarms minimum (latency + errors). drill 2 — metrics literacy: reading graphs like a pro three concepts you need cold: p50 / p90 / p99 (percentiles): if p99 latency = 800ms, that means 99% of requests finish in 800ms or less. the 1% outliers might be 3 seconds. p50 (median) hides outliers. p99 catches the worst customer experience. always look at p99. latency vs error rate vs saturation: latency = how long requests take. error rate = % of requests failing. saturation = how close you are to capacity (cpu 90%, ddb throttles, lambda concurrency 950/1000). high latency + low errors = downstream slowness or db contention. high errors + normal latency = bad deploy or dependency failure. high saturation = you're about to fall over. reading a spike: spike at 3am every night = batch job. spike on monday 9am = weekly load. spike that starts at deploy time + stays elevated = bad code. spike during a known event (prime day) = expected load. scenario set (3 graphs, describe what you see and what to check) graph a: getemployeebalance p99 latency. flat at 200ms for 3 weeks. at 2pm today it jumps to 1200ms and stays there. error rate is 0.1% (normal). traffic volume unchanged. graph b: submittimeoff error rate. flat at 0.05% for 2 months. at 10am today it spikes to 5% for 1 hour, then drops back to 0.05%. latency unchanged. traffic unchanged. no deploy at 10am. graph c: lambda getshiftdetails invocations. 1000/hour baseline. at midnight every night it spikes to 8000/hour for 15 minutes. no corresponding spike in api traffic. no alarms. your task for each graph, write 2 sentences: what's happening, and what's the first thing you check. model answers graph a — sustained latency increase with no error spike or traffic change = downstream dependency got slow or db contention. first check: cw insights query for getemployeebalance calls, filter by duration 1000ms, see if they're all calling the same downstream service (the downstream routing api? ddb?). second check: ddb read capacity metrics — are you throttling? graph b — 1 hour error spike with no deploy or traffic change = transient downstream failure. first check: cw logs for submittimeoff errors during 10 11am, grep for exception types. second check: the downstream routing api or downstream service latency graphs at 10am — did a dependency have a blip? graph c — nightly batch spike. midnight = scheduled job. first check: grep your codebase for cron jobs or eventbridge rules that run at midnight. second check: is this expected load? if yes, document it in your runbook so on call doesn't panic. if no, file a ticket to understand why 8x traffic happens nightly. drill 3 — weekly security/risk hygiene: the dashboards you own a tech company ses own 5 recurring security/availability checks. you run these weekly (or daily for high risk services). the rule: address risks older than 20 days . if a the security vulnerability scanner risk sits for 3 weeks, your sdm will ask why. the 5 dashboards 1. the security vulnerability scanner — scans your packages for known cves (security vulnerabilities). shows risk count, severity, age. you fix high severity risks first, then medium. low severity risks you accept or fix in batches. 2. the dependency compliance scanner — software compliance. checks if your dependencies have licenses a tech company can use, if you're using deprecated packages, if you need security approvals. 3. vulnerabilities dashboard (part of the security vulnerability scanner) — cve details. click through to see which package version is affected, which version fixes it, and the blast radius. 4. patching cadence — are your hosts/containers running the latest ami with security patches? if you're on ecs fargate, a tech company patches for you. if you're on ec2, you own the patching schedule. 5. the cloud policy scanner risks — checks your iam policies, s3 bucket permissions, ddb encryption, logging config. flags things like \"s3 bucket is public\" or \"iam role has permissions.\" drill: prioritizing 5 risks you're the se for the time tracking service. it's monday morning. you open the security vulnerability scanner and see 5 risks: risk 1: high severity cve in log4j (dependency in your java package). age: 35 days. exploit allows remote code execution. risk 2: medium severity cve in a test only dependency (junit). age: 10 days. no production impact. risk 3: low severity license issue with a frontend npm package. age: 50 days. legal team flagged it but said \"fix when convenient.\" risk 4: the cloud policy scanner risk: ddb table doesn't have point in time recovery enabled. age: 25 days. no encryption at rest issue. risk 5: the dependency compliance scanner: deprecated the build system package (old the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) version). age: 5 days. upgrade path documented. your task rank 1 5 by urgency. for the top 2, write one sentence explaining why you're prioritizing them and what you'll do this week. model answer rank: 1. risk 1 (log4j cve, 35 days old, high severity, remote code exec) 2. risk 4 (ddb point in time recovery, 25 days old, approaching 30 day sla) 3. risk 5 (deprecated the service framework (like grpc or spring boot), recent, documented upgrade) 4. risk 2 (test only, medium severity, 10 days is fine) 5. risk 3 (legal said \"when convenient,\" 50 days but low blast radius) top 2 actions: risk 1: high severity cve past 20 days = top priority. this week: file a pull request upgrading log4j to the patched version, test in alpha, push to beta by friday. if the upgrade is breaking, file a sev2 and get help from the service framework (like grpc or spring boot) team. risk 4: the cloud policy scanner risks over 20 days get flagged in ops review. this week: file a simple cr enabling point in time recovery on the ddb table (one line of cdk), deploy to prod. takes 30 minutes, clears the risk. drill 4 — deployment health: rollback, hotfix, or wait? your pipeline breaks or your service degrades post deploy. you have 3 options: rollback — revert to the last known good version. fastest fix, safest move. do this when the new deploy is clearly broken and the old version was stable. hotfix — deploy a small fix on top of the broken version. use this when rollback isn't possible (e.g., you ran a one way db migration) or when the fix is a 1 line config change. wait — sometimes a transient issue (downstream service blip, dns propagation) looks like a deploy problem but isn't. wait 15 minutes, check metrics again. when you need a production change approval a production change approval (production change approval) = approval from a senior engineer or manager to push a high risk change to production. you need one when: deploying during a freeze window (code freeze before prime day, black friday) deploying a rollback during an active sev2 deploying a hotfix that bypasses normal testing (alpha/beta skipped) making infrastructure changes (ddb capacity bump, asg scaling rule change) your pipeline may require a production change approval approval at the prod stage. don't skip it. if you push without an approved a production change approval, your sdm will hear about it. drill: 3 scenarios, what do you do? scenario a: you deploy the time tracking service rev 47 to prod at 2pm. at 2:05pm, the getemployeebalance api error rate jumps from 0.1% to 8%. latency unchanged. rev 46 was stable for 2 weeks. no db migration in rev 47. scenario b: you deploy a db schema change (new ddb gsi) at 10am. at 10:15am, writes to the table start failing with \"resourcenotfoundexception.\" rollback would delete the gsi, but you need it for the new feature launching tomorrow. scenario c: at 3pm, submittimeoff p99 latency jumps from 300ms to 2000ms. no deploy in the last 6 hours. your last deploy was yesterday and it's been stable. cw logs show the downstream routing api downstream is returning 503s. your task for each scenario, choose rollback / hotfix / wait and write one sentence justifying it. model answers scenario a — rollback. error rate spiked immediately post deploy, rev 46 was stable, no migration blocker. rollback to rev 46 now, investigate rev 47 offline, re deploy after fix. scenario b — hotfix. rollback would delete the gsi and you need it tomorrow. file a 1 line cr fixing the resourcenotfoundexception (probably a missing iam permission or a typo in the gsi name). deploy the hotfix with a production change approval approval (sev2 active, prod hotfix). scenario c — wait (and monitor). no recent deploy, downstream the downstream routing api is the culprit. check the downstream routing api's status page or slack channel. if the downstream routing api recovers in 15 minutes, your service will too. if it doesn't, escalate to the downstream routing api's on call. don't rollback your own deploy when the problem is external. drill 5 — fleet/capacity: prime day is next week, what do you check? fleet = your service's compute capacity. ecs tasks, lambda concurrency, ec2 instances. capacity planning = making sure you have enough fleet to handle peak traffic without throttling or timing out. peak / hve (high volume event) days = prime day, black friday, cyber monday, back to school in some regions. traffic can 5x your normal baseline. if you don't scale your fleet in advance, your service will fall over. what an se checks before prime day 1. asg (auto scaling group) rules: are your min/max/desired instance counts set for peak load? if your normal fleet is 10 tasks and prime day will 5x traffic, bump desired to 50 and max to 75. 2. ddb capacity: read/write capacity units (rcu/wcu). if you're on demand, you're auto scaled. if you're on provisioned, check your current utilization and bump capacity 3 5x. 3. lambda concurrency limits: your account has a regional limit (default 1000 concurrent invocations). if your function hits 1000 during peak, new invocations get throttled. request a limit increase or reserve concurrency for critical functions. 4. downstream dependencies: does your service call the downstream routing api, a downstream classification service, another internal service? ping their on call to confirm they're scaled for prime day too. 5. alarms and dashboards: create a prime day dashboard with your top 5 metrics (traffic, error rate, latency, ddb throttles, lambda errors). share it with your sdm and on call. 6. dry run: deploy your capacity changes to beta 3 days before prime day. run a load test (if possible) or at least verify the fleet scales up correctly. drill: 5 things to check you're the se for the getemployeebalance api. your sdm says \"prime day is june 15, traffic will 5x, make sure we're ready.\" today is june 8. list 5 things you check this week and what \"good\" looks like for each. model answer 1. asg desired/max counts: current: 8 ecs tasks. prime day estimate: 40 tasks. action: bump desired to 40, max to 60. deploy to beta june 10, verify tasks launch. deploy to prod june 12. good = all 40 tasks healthy in beta. 2. ddb read capacity (the getemployeebalance api table): current: 100 rcu, 60% utilized at peak. prime day 5x = 300 rcu needed. action: bump to 500 rcu (buffer). deploy june 12. good = no throttles in beta dry run. 3. lambda concurrency (if the getemployeebalance api calls a lambda): current limit: 1000 concurrent in account, the getemployeebalance api uses ~50 at peak. prime day = 250 concurrent. action: reserve 300 concurrency for the getemployeebalance api lambda. good = no throttles. 4. the downstream routing api dependency: the getemployeebalance api calls the downstream routing api searchbalances. action: ping the downstream routing api on call (the dependency team's on call), confirm they're scaled. good = they reply \"yes, scaled to 10k tps.\" 5. prime day dashboard: metrics = the getemployeebalance api traffic, error rate, p99 latency, ddb throttles, the downstream routing api call latency. action: create dashboard, share link in team slack. good = sdm can watch live on prime day. drill 6 — ticket kpis: spot the systemic problem every se team tracks ticket metrics monthly: volume, time to resolve, repeat issues, category breakdown. these metrics tell you if you're reacting well (time to resolve is low) and if you're preventing well (repeat issues are dropping because you fixed root causes). the metrics you track volume: how many tickets this month? trend up/down vs last 3 months? if volume is climbing, why? new feature launched? more customers? or a new recurring bug? time to resolve (ttr): median hours from ticket open to close. if ttr spikes, you're either short staffed or hitting complex issues. break it down by priority (sev2 vs sev3). repeat issues: same root cause, multiple tickets. example: 8 tickets about \"getshiftdetails timeout\" in 2 weeks. if you see a cluster, file one cr to fix the root cause. category breakdown: what % of tickets are config issues, code bugs, user errors, dependencies? if 40% are \"the downstream routing api returned 503,\" you have a dependency reliability problem, not a your service problem. top 3 issues: every month, call out the top 3 most frequent issues. propose fixes or mitigations for each. drill: analyze this month's tickets you're the se for submittimeoff api. here's april's ticket data: volume: 32 tickets (up from 22 in march) ttr median: 4 hours (same as march) repeat issues: 9 tickets about \"validation error: employeeid not found\" (all from india contingent workers). 6 tickets about \"the downstream routing api timeout.\" 4 tickets about \"duplicate submission blocked.\" category breakdown: 50% code bugs, 30% downstream dependency, 20% user error. your task write 3 bullets: (1) what's the biggest problem, (2) what's the root cause hypothesis, (3) what do you do this month to fix it. model answer 1. biggest problem: 9 tickets in one month about \"employeeid not found\" for india contingent workers. that's 28% of all tickets, all the same failure mode. 2. root cause hypothesis: submittimeoff validates employeeid by calling the downstream routing api or checking a local cache. india contingent workers (yellow/green badge) might not be in the cache or the downstream routing api might not have them indexed yet. alternatively, there's a data sync delay between the hr data feed (the third party payroll vendor india feed) and the downstream routing api. 3. action this month: file one cr to improve the error message (\"employeeid x not found in the downstream routing api, check the hr data feed ingestion status\") and add a fallback: if the downstream routing api returns 404, call a secondary lookup (the internal schedule store or the hr data feed direct). this fixes the customer experience and reduces repeat tickets. also: ping the hr data feed pipeline owner (check a reference doc) to confirm the the vendor to internal pipeline is healthy. drill 7 — weekly rhythm checklist (the se3 cadence) proactive ses run on a rhythm. here's the weekly/monthly checklist that separates an se3 from an se2. daily (15 min) scan your service dashboard: traffic, error rate, latency. any anomalies? if yes, investigate. check open sev2s / sev3s. any stuck for 1 day? unblock or escalate. glance at pipeline: any stages red? any deploy waiting on approval? weekly (1 2 hours) monday morning: the security vulnerability scanner risks. fix anything 20 days old. file pull requests for high severity cves. wednesday: deployment health. review last week's deploys. any rollbacks? any post deploy issues? document in your ops log. thursday: alarm audit. did any alarms fire this week? were they real issues or false positives? tune thresholds if needed. friday: ticket analysis. count repeat issues. if 3+ tickets on the same topic, file a pull request to fix the root cause. monthly (half day) ticket kpis report: volume, ttr, repeat issues, top 3 problems. share with sdm. security dashboard deep dive: the security vulnerability scanner + the dependency compliance scanner + the cloud policy scanner. close out risks older than 30 days. capacity planning: look ahead 2 months. any peak events (prime day, black friday)? any new features launching that will increase traffic? file capacity increase requests now. fleet/imr review: are your asgs / ecs services scaled correctly? any cost optimization opportunities (over provisioned)? ops review prep: most teams have a weekly or monthly ops meeting. bring your top 3 operational wins (fixed a recurring issue, tuned an alarm, scaled for peak) and top 3 risks (aging the security vulnerability scanner cve, upcoming capacity crunch, brittle deployment). the big picture all of this — alarms, metrics, security hygiene, deployment health, fleet/capacity, ticket analysis — is the proactive half of the se job . the reactive half (troubleshooting sev2s) gets you baseline competence. the proactive half gets you promoted. se2 behavior: wait for the alarm to fire, then investigate. se3 behavior: tune the alarm so it fires at the right time. fix the root cause so the alarm stops firing. se2 behavior: clear the security vulnerability scanner risks when your sdm asks about them. se3 behavior: check the security vulnerability scanner every monday, clear risks before they hit 20 days. se2 behavior: deploy when the pipeline is green, rollback when it's red. se3 behavior: pre scale your fleet for prime day 1 week in advance. create a dashboard. dry run the capacity bump. write the rollback runbook before you need it. master the drills in this file and you'll own the operational health of your service. that's the se3 signal. next steps you've now trained: troubleshooting (01), aws/tools (02), rca (03), se interview (04), daily se work (05), this one (06 operational excellence). the 7th and final drill bank will be: \"career growth + se3 signal\" — how to demonstrate se3 behaviors in your first 90 days, how to write your self review showing operational impact, and how to frame your work for promotion. that one ties it all together. after that, you'll have a complete se1 → se2 → se3 training corpus. run these drills until the moves are muscle memory. then you'll walk into your se role and own it from day 1.","words":3632},{"id":"training-writing-drills","section":"Training","title":"Writing drills","html":"<h1 id=\"writing-drills--coes-runbooks-status-updates\">Writing Drills —\nCOEs, Runbooks, Status Updates</h1>\n<p><em>What this trains: the writing an SE does most — clear fix-it\nrecipes, blameless COEs with 5-Whys, crisp updates, data over\nfluff</em></p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"a-tech-company-writing-rules-plain-words\">a tech company Writing\nRules (Plain Words)</h2>\n<p>Clear over clever. Data over adjectives. Active voice. Short\nsentences. Say it and stop.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Active voice</strong> — \"We rolled back the deployment\" not\n\"The deployment was rolled back\"</li>\n<li><strong>Data not adjectives</strong> — \"latency jumped from 200ms to\n4500ms\" not \"latency got really bad\"</li>\n<li><strong>Short sentences</strong> — one thought per sentence. If a\nsentence has \"and\" twice, split it</li>\n<li><strong>No hedging</strong> — \"This caused 2300 errors\" not \"This\nseems to have possibly caused some errors\"</li>\n<li><strong>Say it and stop</strong> — no preamble, no \"it should be\nnoted\", no \"in conclusion\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you can cut a word without losing meaning, cut it.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-is-a-runbook\">What is a Runbook?</h2>\n<p>A runbook is a fix-it recipe for a tired person at 2am. Step-by-step,\nno guessing. If the alarm fires at 3am and you are half asleep, the\nrunbook walks you through the fix.</p>\n<p>Good runbook = title + when to use + step-by-step with decision\npoints + verification + escalation.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"runbook-drill-1--high-memory-alarm\">Runbook Drill 1 — High\nMemory Alarm</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Your service throws a \"High Memory Usage\"\nalarm every few weeks. Investigation shows a memory leak in a background\nthread that processes event batches. Temporary fix = restart the\nservice. Permanent fix = code change (already filed as a backlog item).\nWrite a runbook for the oncall person who gets paged at 2am.</p>\n<p><strong>Your turn:</strong> draft a runbook with:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Title</li>\n<li>When to use this runbook</li>\n<li>Step-by-step fix (check memory, restart if needed, verify recovery,\nlink to ticket for root fix)</li>\n<li>Escalation (who to ping if restart doesn't work)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Model Runbook:</strong></p>\n<h3 id=\"runbook-high-memory-alarm--restart-service\">Runbook: High Memory\nAlarm — Restart Service</h3>\n<p><strong>When to use:</strong> CloudWatch alarm \"ServiceMemory &gt;\n80%\" fires.</p>\n<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Check current memory via CloudWatch Insights:</li>\n</ol>\n<pre><code>fields @timestamp, memory_used_percent\n| filter serviceName = &quot;YourService&quot;\n| sort @timestamp desc\n| limit 10</code></pre>\n<p>If memory &gt; 80%, proceed.</p>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Restart the service:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Go to the deployment tool (like Spinnaker or Argo CD): your team's\ninternal docs</li>\n<li>Click \"Restart Fleet\"</li>\n<li>Confirm restart</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"1\">\n<li><p>Wait 5 minutes. Check memory again (same query). Should drop\nbelow 50%.</p></li>\n<li><p>Check error logs for 10 minutes after restart:</p></li>\n</ol>\n<pre><code>fields @timestamp, @message\n| filter level = &quot;ERROR&quot;\n| sort @timestamp desc\n| limit 20</code></pre>\n<p>If errors spike, rollback and escalate.</p>\n<ol start=\"5\" type=\"1\">\n<li>If memory stays below 70% for 30 minutes, issue is mitigated.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Root cause:</strong> Memory leak in batch processor.\nPermanent fix tracked in the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty)\nticket a ticket.</p>\n<p><strong>Escalation:</strong> If restart fails or memory climbs again\nwithin 1 hour, ping @oncall-lead in #team-oncall Slack.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"runbook-drill-2--api-5xx-spike\">Runbook Drill 2 — API 5xx\nSpike</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Your API throws 5xx errors when a\ndownstream dependency (PartnerService) times out. Happens once a month,\nusually during traffic spikes. Temporary fix = increase timeout from 3s\nto 10s via a runtime config service. Permanent fix = partner team needs\nto optimize their endpoint. Write a runbook.</p>\n<p><strong>Your turn:</strong> draft a runbook with:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Title</li>\n<li>When to use</li>\n<li>Steps to increase timeout via a runtime config service</li>\n<li>Verification (check error rate drops)</li>\n<li>Rollback (how to revert if something breaks)</li>\n<li>Escalation</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Model Runbook:</strong></p>\n<h3 id=\"runbook-api-5xx-spike--increase-downstream-timeout\">Runbook: API\n5xx Spike — Increase Downstream Timeout</h3>\n<p><strong>When to use:</strong> Alarm \"API 5xx Rate &gt; 2%\" fires AND\nCloudWatch logs show <code>TimeoutException</code> from\n<code>PartnerService</code>.</p>\n<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Confirm root cause:</li>\n</ol>\n<pre><code>fields @timestamp, exception, downstream_service\n| filter exception like /TimeoutException/\n| filter downstream_service = &quot;PartnerService&quot;\n| stats count() by bin(5m)</code></pre>\n<p>If spike is clear, proceed.</p>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Increase timeout in a runtime config service:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Go to a runtime config service console: your team's internal\ndocs</li>\n<li>Edit configuration profile <code>prod-config</code></li>\n<li>Change <code>partnerServiceTimeoutMs</code> from <code>3000</code>\nto <code>10000</code></li>\n<li>Deploy to prod environment</li>\n<li>Wait 3 minutes for config to propagate</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Verify error rate drops:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Check CloudWatch metric <code>API5xxCount</code> — should drop below\n1% within 10 minutes</li>\n<li>Check logs for <code>TimeoutException</code> — should stop\nappearing</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"1\">\n<li>Monitor for 30 minutes. If error rate stays low, issue\nmitigated.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Rollback:</strong> If errors spike or different errors\nappear, revert timeout to <code>3000</code> in a runtime config service.\nDeploy immediately.</p>\n<p><strong>Root cause:</strong> PartnerService slow during traffic\nspikes. Permanent fix = partner team optimization (tracked in their\nbacklog).</p>\n<p><strong>Escalation:</strong> If timeout increase doesn't help or new\nerrors appear, ping @partner-team in #cross-team-support Slack.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"what-is-a-coe-correction-of-errors\">What is a COE (Correction of\nErrors)?</h2>\n<p>A COE is a blameless post-incident report. What broke, why it broke,\nwhat we are doing so it never breaks again. The core tool = 5 Whys. Keep\nasking \"why\" until you hit the root cause (usually a missing safeguard,\nnot a person mistake).</p>\n<p>COE structure:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Summary (one paragraph — what broke, how many customers hit it, how\nlong it lasted)</li>\n<li>Impact (numbers — requests failed, customers affected, revenue if\nrelevant)</li>\n<li>Timeline (bullet list with timestamps)</li>\n<li>Root Cause (the 5 Whys chain)</li>\n<li>Action Items (what we are fixing, who owns it, target date)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Blameless = no \"Engineer X forgot to check Y\". Instead: \"Deployment\nlacked automated validation for Y\".</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"5-whys-drill-1--database-connection-pool-exhausted\">5 Whys Drill\n1 — Database Connection Pool Exhausted</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Your service threw 500 errors for 20\nminutes. Investigation shows the database connection pool was exhausted\n(all 50 connections in use, new requests timed out). After restarting\nthe service, it recovered. Walk the 5 Whys to root cause.</p>\n<p><strong>Your turn:</strong> ask \"why\" 5 times.</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p>Why did requests fail? (your answer)</p></li>\n<li><p>Why did that happen? (your answer)</p></li>\n<li><p>Why did that happen? (your answer)</p></li>\n<li><p>Why did that happen? (your answer)</p></li>\n<li><p>Why did that happen? (your answer — this is usually the root\ncause)</p></li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Model 5 Whys:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>Why did requests fail?</strong> Because the service could\nnot get a database connection.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Why could the service not get a connection?</strong>\nBecause the connection pool was exhausted (all 50 connections in\nuse).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Why were all connections in use?</strong> Because a slow\nquery was holding connections open for 30+ seconds.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Why was the query slow?</strong> Because a missing index\nforced a full table scan on a 10M-row table.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Why was the index missing?</strong> Because the schema\nmigration two weeks ago added a new column but did not add the\ncorresponding index.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Root cause:</strong> Missing index in the database after a\nschema change. No validation step caught it before deploy.</p>\n<p><strong>Action items:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Add the missing index (owner: DBA team, target: today)</li>\n<li>Add query performance tests to CI/CD (owner: dev team, target: next\nsprint)</li>\n<li>Add automated index checks to schema migration pipeline (owner:\nplatform team, target: 2 weeks)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"5-whys-drill-2--cache-stampede\">5 Whys Drill 2 — Cache\nStampede</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> During a traffic spike, your service\nlatency jumped from 100ms to 5000ms for 10 minutes. Investigation shows\nthe cache expired at the same time a spike hit, all requests went to the\ndatabase, database got overwhelmed. Walk the 5 Whys.</p>\n<p><strong>Your turn:</strong> ask why 5 times, reach root cause,\npropose action items.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Model 5 Whys:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>Why did latency spike?</strong> Because all requests hit\nthe database instead of the cache.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Why did requests hit the database?</strong> Because the\ncache entry expired.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Why did all requests hit the database at once?</strong>\nBecause they all tried to rebuild the cache at the same time (cache\nstampede).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Why did the cache not have stampede protection?</strong>\nBecause the cache library we use does not support \"lock on miss\" (only\none request rebuilds, others wait).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Why are we using a library without stampede\nprotection?</strong> Because we picked a simple caching library 2 years\nago before traffic grew, and we never revisited the choice.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Root cause:</strong> Cache library lacks stampede protection.\nNo review process for library choices as traffic scales.</p>\n<p><strong>Action items:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Migrate to a cache library with lock-on-miss support (owner: dev\nteam, target: next sprint)</li>\n<li>Add cache stampede load test to performance suite (owner: QA,\ntarget: 1 week)</li>\n<li>Quarterly review of libraries for scale concerns (owner: tech lead,\ntarget: ongoing)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"coe-drill-1--api-outage-from-bad-deploy\">COE Drill 1 — API\nOutage from Bad Deploy</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> A deployment introduced a null pointer\nexception in the request handler. The service threw 500 errors for 30\nminutes until the deploy was rolled back. 12,000 requests failed. No\ncustomer data lost, but 200 customers saw errors.</p>\n<p><strong>Your turn:</strong> write a COE with:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Summary</li>\n<li>Impact</li>\n<li>Timeline (make up realistic timestamps)</li>\n<li>Root Cause (use 5 Whys)</li>\n<li>Action Items (at least 3, with owners and dates)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Model COE:</strong></p>\n<h3 id=\"coe--api-500-errors-from-nullpointerexception-in-v241\">COE — API\n500 Errors from NullPointerException in v2.4.1</h3>\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong> On 2026-06-03 between 14:15 and 14:45 UTC,\nthe API returned 500 errors due to a NullPointerException in the request\nhandler. The issue was introduced in version 2.4.1 and resolved by\nrolling back to 2.4.0. 12,000 requests failed. 200 customers were\nimpacted. No data loss.</p>\n<p><strong>Impact:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>12,000 failed requests (5xx errors)</li>\n<li>200 unique customers affected</li>\n<li>30 minutes downtime</li>\n<li>No data loss, no security breach</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Timeline:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>14:10 UTC — Deploy v2.4.1 to prod completed</li>\n<li>14:15 UTC — CloudWatch alarm \"API 5xx Rate &gt; 1%\" fired</li>\n<li>14:17 UTC — Oncall investigated logs, found NullPointerException in\nUserRequestHandler</li>\n<li>14:20 UTC — Rollback initiated to v2.4.0</li>\n<li>14:25 UTC — Rollback completed</li>\n<li>14:30 UTC — Error rate dropped to 0%</li>\n<li>14:45 UTC — Monitoring confirmed stable</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Root Cause (5 Whys):</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Why did requests fail? — NullPointerException in\nUserRequestHandler.</li>\n<li>Why was there a null pointer? — Code assumed\n<code>request.getUserId()</code> was always non-null, but it can be null\nfor guest users.</li>\n<li>Why did the code not handle null? — The developer missed the edge\ncase.</li>\n<li>Why was the edge case missed? — No test for guest users.</li>\n<li>Why was there no test? — Test suite did not cover all auth states\n(logged-in, logged-out, guest).</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Root cause:</strong> Missing test coverage for guest user\nedge case. Code review did not catch it.</p>\n<p><strong>Action Items:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Add null check in UserRequestHandler (owner: dev team, done:\n2026-06-03)</li>\n<li>Add guest user test to integration suite (owner: QA, target:\n2026-06-05)</li>\n<li>Add \"edge case coverage\" checklist to CR template (owner: tech lead,\ntarget: 2026-06-07)</li>\n<li>Quarterly audit of test coverage gaps (owner: dev team, target:\nongoing)</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"coe-drill-2--database-overload-from-missing-index\">COE Drill 2 —\nDatabase Overload from Missing Index</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> A missing database index caused queries to\ntake 20+ seconds, exhausting the connection pool. The service was\nunavailable for 15 minutes. 8,000 requests failed. DBA team added the\nindex and service recovered.</p>\n<p><strong>Your turn:</strong> write a COE following the same structure.\nInclude a 5-Whys chain. Propose at least 3 action items with owners.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Model COE:</strong></p>\n<h3\nid=\"coe--service-unavailable-from-database-connection-pool-exhaustion\">COE\n— Service Unavailable from Database Connection Pool Exhaustion</h3>\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong> On 2026-06-04 between 09:30 and 09:45 UTC,\nthe service was unavailable due to database connection pool exhaustion.\nA missing index on the <code>orders</code> table caused queries to take\n20+ seconds, holding all 50 connections. The DBA team added the index\nand the service recovered. 8,000 requests failed. No data loss.</p>\n<p><strong>Impact:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>8,000 failed requests (503 Service Unavailable)</li>\n<li>300 unique customers affected</li>\n<li>15 minutes downtime</li>\n<li>No data loss</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Timeline:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>09:25 UTC — Traffic spike (2x normal load)</li>\n<li>09:30 UTC — Alarm \"Connection Pool Exhausted\" fired</li>\n<li>09:32 UTC — Oncall checked slow query log, found query scanning 10M\nrows</li>\n<li>09:35 UTC — DBA team paged</li>\n<li>09:38 UTC — DBA identified missing index on\n<code>orders.status</code></li>\n<li>09:40 UTC — Index creation started</li>\n<li>09:43 UTC — Index creation completed</li>\n<li>09:45 UTC — Connection pool recovered, errors stopped</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Root Cause (5 Whys):</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Why were requests failing? — Connection pool exhausted.</li>\n<li>Why was the pool exhausted? — Queries took 20+ seconds, holding all\nconnections.</li>\n<li>Why were queries slow? — Full table scan on 10M-row\n<code>orders</code> table.</li>\n<li>Why was there a full table scan? — Missing index on\n<code>orders.status</code>.</li>\n<li>Why was the index missing? — Schema migration last week added a new\nquery pattern but did not add the index.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Root cause:</strong> Schema migration did not include index\nfor new query pattern. No automated index validation in migration\npipeline.</p>\n<p><strong>Action Items:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>Add index on <code>orders.status</code> (owner: DBA team, done:\n2026-06-04)</li>\n<li>Add query performance tests to CI/CD (owner: dev team, target:\n2026-06-10)</li>\n<li>Add automated \"explain plan\" check to migration pipeline (owner:\nplatform team, target: 2026-06-15)</li>\n<li>Pre-migration query review with DBA (owner: tech lead, target: new\nprocess starting 2026-06-07)</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"status-update-drill--weekly-ops-report\">Status Update Drill —\nWeekly Ops Report</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> You are writing a weekly ops update for\nyour manager. Last week: handled 3 Sev-3 tickets, cleared 2 the\nsecurity-vulnerability scanner risks, pushed 1 deploy, tuned 1 alarm\n(false positives), monitored Prime Day traffic (no incidents).</p>\n<p><strong>Your turn:</strong> write a 5-bullet weekly update. Each\nbullet = one sentence with data.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Model Update (Wordy Version — DON'T DO THIS):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>I worked on several tickets this week and managed to resolve most of\nthem, including some Sev-3s that came in through the queue</li>\n<li>Also spent some time looking at the security-vulnerability scanner\nrisks and was able to clear a couple of them</li>\n<li>We had a deployment that went smoothly</li>\n<li>Fixed an alarm that was being noisy</li>\n<li>Monitored Prime Day and everything seemed fine</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Model Update (Tight Version — DO THIS):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Resolved 3 Sev-3 tickets (memory leak, timeout, config drift)</li>\n<li>Cleared 2 the security-vulnerability scanner risks (outdated\nlibrary, missing CloudWatch logs encryption)</li>\n<li>Deployed v3.2.1 to prod, no rollback</li>\n<li>Tuned \"High CPU\" alarm threshold from 70% to 85%, eliminated 12\nfalse positives per day</li>\n<li>Monitored Prime Day traffic (2.3x normal load), zero incidents</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"status-update-drill--manager-update-after-incident\">Status\nUpdate Drill — Manager Update After Incident</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> An incident happened yesterday (API down\nfor 20 minutes due to bad deploy). You rolled back, wrote a COE, filed 2\naction items. Your manager asks for a brief update in Slack.</p>\n<p><strong>Your turn:</strong> write a 3-sentence update. Keep it\nfactual, blameless, forward-looking.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Model Update (Wordy — DON'T DO THIS):</strong></p>\n<p>Hey, so about yesterday's incident, I wanted to let you know that we\nhad some issues with the API being down for a bit, but I managed to roll\nit back and get things working again. I also wrote up a COE with some\naction items so hopefully this doesn't happen again.</p>\n<p><strong>Model Update (Tight — DO THIS):</strong></p>\n<p>API was down 20 minutes yesterday (bad deploy), rolled back\nimmediately. COE filed with root cause (missing test for edge case). Two\naction items: add edge-case test (dev team, target Friday) and CR\nchecklist update (me, target tomorrow).</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"data-not-adjectives-drill\">Data Not Adjectives Drill</h2>\n<p><strong>Your turn:</strong> rewrite these 5 vague sentences with\nconcrete data.</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>\"The service had really high latency during the incident.\"</li>\n<li>\"A lot of customers were affected.\"</li>\n<li>\"The deployment took longer than usual.\"</li>\n<li>\"We get frequent false alarms from this metric.\"</li>\n<li>\"The new feature significantly improved performance.\"</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Model Rewrites:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li>\"The service latency jumped from 150ms to 4200ms during the\nincident.\"</li>\n<li>\"320 customers hit errors (out of 15,000 active that hour).\"</li>\n<li>\"The deployment took 45 minutes (normal is 12 minutes).\"</li>\n<li>\"The 'High Memory' alarm fired 18 times last week, 16 were false\npositives.\"</li>\n<li>\"The new caching layer reduced database query count by 60% (from\n5000/min to 2000/min).\"</li>\n</ol>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"writing-self-check-list\">Writing Self-Check List</h2>\n<p>Before sending any COE, runbook, or status update, check:</p>\n<ul class=\"task-list\">\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Active voice (who did what, not \"it\nwas done\")</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Data not adjectives (numbers, not \"a\nlot\" or \"significantly\")</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Short sentences (one thought per\nsentence)</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />No hedging (say it or don't, no\n\"seems like\" or \"possibly\")</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Blameless (no \"Engineer X forgot\",\nsay \"missing validation step\")</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Concrete action items (who, what,\nwhen)</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Verification steps in runbooks (how\nto know the fix worked)</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Escalation path in runbooks (who to\nping if it fails)</label></li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you can cut a word without losing meaning, cut it.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>END OF DRILLS. Now go write a real runbook or COE and feel it\nclick.</p>\n","text":"writing drills — coes, runbooks, status updates what this trains: the writing an se does most — clear fix it recipes, blameless coes with 5 whys, crisp updates, data over fluff a tech company writing rules (plain words) clear over clever. data over adjectives. active voice. short sentences. say it and stop. active voice — \"we rolled back the deployment\" not \"the deployment was rolled back\" data not adjectives — \"latency jumped from 200ms to 4500ms\" not \"latency got really bad\" short sentences — one thought per sentence. if a sentence has \"and\" twice, split it no hedging — \"this caused 2300 errors\" not \"this seems to have possibly caused some errors\" say it and stop — no preamble, no \"it should be noted\", no \"in conclusion\" if you can cut a word without losing meaning, cut it. what is a runbook? a runbook is a fix it recipe for a tired person at 2am. step by step, no guessing. if the alarm fires at 3am and you are half asleep, the runbook walks you through the fix. good runbook = title + when to use + step by step with decision points + verification + escalation. runbook drill 1 — high memory alarm scenario: your service throws a \"high memory usage\" alarm every few weeks. investigation shows a memory leak in a background thread that processes event batches. temporary fix = restart the service. permanent fix = code change (already filed as a backlog item). write a runbook for the oncall person who gets paged at 2am. your turn: draft a runbook with: title when to use this runbook step by step fix (check memory, restart if needed, verify recovery, link to ticket for root fix) escalation (who to ping if restart doesn't work) model runbook: runbook: high memory alarm — restart service when to use: cloudwatch alarm \"servicememory 80%\" fires. steps: 1. check current memory via cloudwatch insights: if memory 80%, proceed. 2. restart the service: go to the deployment tool (like spinnaker or argo cd): your team's internal docs click \"restart fleet\" confirm restart 3. wait 5 minutes. check memory again (same query). should drop below 50%. 4. check error logs for 10 minutes after restart: if errors spike, rollback and escalate. 5. if memory stays below 70% for 30 minutes, issue is mitigated. root cause: memory leak in batch processor. permanent fix tracked in the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) ticket a ticket. escalation: if restart fails or memory climbs again within 1 hour, ping @oncall lead in team oncall slack. runbook drill 2 — api 5xx spike scenario: your api throws 5xx errors when a downstream dependency (partnerservice) times out. happens once a month, usually during traffic spikes. temporary fix = increase timeout from 3s to 10s via a runtime config service. permanent fix = partner team needs to optimize their endpoint. write a runbook. your turn: draft a runbook with: title when to use steps to increase timeout via a runtime config service verification (check error rate drops) rollback (how to revert if something breaks) escalation model runbook: runbook: api 5xx spike — increase downstream timeout when to use: alarm \"api 5xx rate 2%\" fires and cloudwatch logs show timeoutexception from partnerservice . steps: 1. confirm root cause: if spike is clear, proceed. 2. increase timeout in a runtime config service: go to a runtime config service console: your team's internal docs edit configuration profile prod config change partnerservicetimeoutms from 3000 to 10000 deploy to prod environment wait 3 minutes for config to propagate 3. verify error rate drops: check cloudwatch metric api5xxcount — should drop below 1% within 10 minutes check logs for timeoutexception — should stop appearing 4. monitor for 30 minutes. if error rate stays low, issue mitigated. rollback: if errors spike or different errors appear, revert timeout to 3000 in a runtime config service. deploy immediately. root cause: partnerservice slow during traffic spikes. permanent fix = partner team optimization (tracked in their backlog). escalation: if timeout increase doesn't help or new errors appear, ping @partner team in cross team support slack. what is a coe (correction of errors)? a coe is a blameless post incident report. what broke, why it broke, what we are doing so it never breaks again. the core tool = 5 whys. keep asking \"why\" until you hit the root cause (usually a missing safeguard, not a person mistake). coe structure: summary (one paragraph — what broke, how many customers hit it, how long it lasted) impact (numbers — requests failed, customers affected, revenue if relevant) timeline (bullet list with timestamps) root cause (the 5 whys chain) action items (what we are fixing, who owns it, target date) blameless = no \"engineer x forgot to check y\". instead: \"deployment lacked automated validation for y\". 5 whys drill 1 — database connection pool exhausted scenario: your service threw 500 errors for 20 minutes. investigation shows the database connection pool was exhausted (all 50 connections in use, new requests timed out). after restarting the service, it recovered. walk the 5 whys to root cause. your turn: ask \"why\" 5 times. 1. why did requests fail? (your answer) 2. why did that happen? (your answer) 3. why did that happen? (your answer) 4. why did that happen? (your answer) 5. why did that happen? (your answer — this is usually the root cause) model 5 whys: 1. why did requests fail? because the service could not get a database connection. 2. why could the service not get a connection? because the connection pool was exhausted (all 50 connections in use). 3. why were all connections in use? because a slow query was holding connections open for 30+ seconds. 4. why was the query slow? because a missing index forced a full table scan on a 10m row table. 5. why was the index missing? because the schema migration two weeks ago added a new column but did not add the corresponding index. root cause: missing index in the database after a schema change. no validation step caught it before deploy. action items: add the missing index (owner: dba team, target: today) add query performance tests to ci/cd (owner: dev team, target: next sprint) add automated index checks to schema migration pipeline (owner: platform team, target: 2 weeks) 5 whys drill 2 — cache stampede scenario: during a traffic spike, your service latency jumped from 100ms to 5000ms for 10 minutes. investigation shows the cache expired at the same time a spike hit, all requests went to the database, database got overwhelmed. walk the 5 whys. your turn: ask why 5 times, reach root cause, propose action items. model 5 whys: 1. why did latency spike? because all requests hit the database instead of the cache. 2. why did requests hit the database? because the cache entry expired. 3. why did all requests hit the database at once? because they all tried to rebuild the cache at the same time (cache stampede). 4. why did the cache not have stampede protection? because the cache library we use does not support \"lock on miss\" (only one request rebuilds, others wait). 5. why are we using a library without stampede protection? because we picked a simple caching library 2 years ago before traffic grew, and we never revisited the choice. root cause: cache library lacks stampede protection. no review process for library choices as traffic scales. action items: migrate to a cache library with lock on miss support (owner: dev team, target: next sprint) add cache stampede load test to performance suite (owner: qa, target: 1 week) quarterly review of libraries for scale concerns (owner: tech lead, target: ongoing) coe drill 1 — api outage from bad deploy scenario: a deployment introduced a null pointer exception in the request handler. the service threw 500 errors for 30 minutes until the deploy was rolled back. 12,000 requests failed. no customer data lost, but 200 customers saw errors. your turn: write a coe with: summary impact timeline (make up realistic timestamps) root cause (use 5 whys) action items (at least 3, with owners and dates) model coe: coe — api 500 errors from nullpointerexception in v2.4.1 summary: on 2026 06 03 between 14:15 and 14:45 utc, the api returned 500 errors due to a nullpointerexception in the request handler. the issue was introduced in version 2.4.1 and resolved by rolling back to 2.4.0. 12,000 requests failed. 200 customers were impacted. no data loss. impact: 12,000 failed requests (5xx errors) 200 unique customers affected 30 minutes downtime no data loss, no security breach timeline: 14:10 utc — deploy v2.4.1 to prod completed 14:15 utc — cloudwatch alarm \"api 5xx rate 1%\" fired 14:17 utc — oncall investigated logs, found nullpointerexception in userrequesthandler 14:20 utc — rollback initiated to v2.4.0 14:25 utc — rollback completed 14:30 utc — error rate dropped to 0% 14:45 utc — monitoring confirmed stable root cause (5 whys): 1. why did requests fail? — nullpointerexception in userrequesthandler. 2. why was there a null pointer? — code assumed request.getuserid() was always non null, but it can be null for guest users. 3. why did the code not handle null? — the developer missed the edge case. 4. why was the edge case missed? — no test for guest users. 5. why was there no test? — test suite did not cover all auth states (logged in, logged out, guest). root cause: missing test coverage for guest user edge case. code review did not catch it. action items: 1. add null check in userrequesthandler (owner: dev team, done: 2026 06 03) 2. add guest user test to integration suite (owner: qa, target: 2026 06 05) 3. add \"edge case coverage\" checklist to cr template (owner: tech lead, target: 2026 06 07) 4. quarterly audit of test coverage gaps (owner: dev team, target: ongoing) coe drill 2 — database overload from missing index scenario: a missing database index caused queries to take 20+ seconds, exhausting the connection pool. the service was unavailable for 15 minutes. 8,000 requests failed. dba team added the index and service recovered. your turn: write a coe following the same structure. include a 5 whys chain. propose at least 3 action items with owners. model coe: coe — service unavailable from database connection pool exhaustion summary: on 2026 06 04 between 09:30 and 09:45 utc, the service was unavailable due to database connection pool exhaustion. a missing index on the orders table caused queries to take 20+ seconds, holding all 50 connections. the dba team added the index and the service recovered. 8,000 requests failed. no data loss. impact: 8,000 failed requests (503 service unavailable) 300 unique customers affected 15 minutes downtime no data loss timeline: 09:25 utc — traffic spike (2x normal load) 09:30 utc — alarm \"connection pool exhausted\" fired 09:32 utc — oncall checked slow query log, found query scanning 10m rows 09:35 utc — dba team paged 09:38 utc — dba identified missing index on orders.status 09:40 utc — index creation started 09:43 utc — index creation completed 09:45 utc — connection pool recovered, errors stopped root cause (5 whys): 1. why were requests failing? — connection pool exhausted. 2. why was the pool exhausted? — queries took 20+ seconds, holding all connections. 3. why were queries slow? — full table scan on 10m row orders table. 4. why was there a full table scan? — missing index on orders.status . 5. why was the index missing? — schema migration last week added a new query pattern but did not add the index. root cause: schema migration did not include index for new query pattern. no automated index validation in migration pipeline. action items: 1. add index on orders.status (owner: dba team, done: 2026 06 04) 2. add query performance tests to ci/cd (owner: dev team, target: 2026 06 10) 3. add automated \"explain plan\" check to migration pipeline (owner: platform team, target: 2026 06 15) 4. pre migration query review with dba (owner: tech lead, target: new process starting 2026 06 07) status update drill — weekly ops report scenario: you are writing a weekly ops update for your manager. last week: handled 3 sev 3 tickets, cleared 2 the security vulnerability scanner risks, pushed 1 deploy, tuned 1 alarm (false positives), monitored prime day traffic (no incidents). your turn: write a 5 bullet weekly update. each bullet = one sentence with data. model update (wordy version — don't do this): i worked on several tickets this week and managed to resolve most of them, including some sev 3s that came in through the queue also spent some time looking at the security vulnerability scanner risks and was able to clear a couple of them we had a deployment that went smoothly fixed an alarm that was being noisy monitored prime day and everything seemed fine model update (tight version — do this): resolved 3 sev 3 tickets (memory leak, timeout, config drift) cleared 2 the security vulnerability scanner risks (outdated library, missing cloudwatch logs encryption) deployed v3.2.1 to prod, no rollback tuned \"high cpu\" alarm threshold from 70% to 85%, eliminated 12 false positives per day monitored prime day traffic (2.3x normal load), zero incidents status update drill — manager update after incident scenario: an incident happened yesterday (api down for 20 minutes due to bad deploy). you rolled back, wrote a coe, filed 2 action items. your manager asks for a brief update in slack. your turn: write a 3 sentence update. keep it factual, blameless, forward looking. model update (wordy — don't do this): hey, so about yesterday's incident, i wanted to let you know that we had some issues with the api being down for a bit, but i managed to roll it back and get things working again. i also wrote up a coe with some action items so hopefully this doesn't happen again. model update (tight — do this): api was down 20 minutes yesterday (bad deploy), rolled back immediately. coe filed with root cause (missing test for edge case). two action items: add edge case test (dev team, target friday) and cr checklist update (me, target tomorrow). data not adjectives drill your turn: rewrite these 5 vague sentences with concrete data. 1. \"the service had really high latency during the incident.\" 2. \"a lot of customers were affected.\" 3. \"the deployment took longer than usual.\" 4. \"we get frequent false alarms from this metric.\" 5. \"the new feature significantly improved performance.\" model rewrites: 1. \"the service latency jumped from 150ms to 4200ms during the incident.\" 2. \"320 customers hit errors (out of 15,000 active that hour).\" 3. \"the deployment took 45 minutes (normal is 12 minutes).\" 4. \"the 'high memory' alarm fired 18 times last week, 16 were false positives.\" 5. \"the new caching layer reduced database query count by 60% (from 5000/min to 2000/min).\" writing self check list before sending any coe, runbook, or status update, check: [ ] active voice (who did what, not \"it was done\") [ ] data not adjectives (numbers, not \"a lot\" or \"significantly\") [ ] short sentences (one thought per sentence) [ ] no hedging (say it or don't, no \"seems like\" or \"possibly\") [ ] blameless (no \"engineer x forgot\", say \"missing validation step\") [ ] concrete action items (who, what, when) [ ] verification steps in runbooks (how to know the fix worked) [ ] escalation path in runbooks (who to ping if it fails) if you can cut a word without losing meaning, cut it. end of drills. now go write a real runbook or coe and feel it click.","words":2730},{"id":"training-30-60-90-first-week-playbook","section":"Training","title":"30/60/90 & first-week playbook","html":"<h1\nid=\"the-transition-playbook-first-week-306090-and-manager-conversation\">The\nTransition Playbook: First Week, 30/60/90, and Manager Conversation</h1>\n<p><strong>What this trains:</strong> How to land smoothly on day one,\nbuild to SE3 strength by day 90, and run the conversation that puts you\non the right ladder rung from the start.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-day-one-question-that-changes-everything\">The Day-One\nQuestion That Changes Everything</h2>\n<p>Before you do anything else, before you read a single wiki page,\nbefore you join a single Slack channel, ask your manager this:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"Does this team have an SE role-scope page and an on-call\nrunbook?\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Why this question wins:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>It tells you if the team is organized.</strong> Teams with\nmature SE practices document them. Teams without them expect you to\nfigure it out yourself, which means your 90 days will be slower.</li>\n<li><strong>It frames you as someone who thinks like an SE.</strong> You\ndidn't ask \"what should I do?\", you asked for the team's own playbook.\nThat's ownership.</li>\n<li><strong>It gives you the map.</strong> If they have both, you just\ngot handed the blueprint. If they don't, you now know your 90-day\ndeliverable: create them.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If the answer is yes, read both docs that afternoon. If the answer is\nno, your 30/60/90 just wrote itself.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"first-week-access-context-and-the-shadow-list\">First Week:\nAccess, Context, and the Shadow List</h2>\n<p>Your first week has one job: get unblocked and find the pattern.\nHere's the checklist, in order:</p>\n<h3 id=\"day-1--access-and-onboarding\">Day 1 — Access and Onboarding</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>the onboarding plan tool module.</strong> This is a tech\ncompany's standard new-hire flow. Do it. It's boring. It also unblocks\nyour badge permissions.</li>\n<li><strong>Request access.</strong> Ask your manager for the groups you\nneed:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>CloudWatch Logs/Insights (read access to the team's log groups)</li>\n<li>the ticketing system (ticket system)</li>\n<li>Alarm console (the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool or\nwhatever the team uses)</li>\n<li>On-call schedule tool (PagerDuty, Chime, or team-internal)</li>\n<li>Fleet management tools (if they run ASGs or Kubernetes)</li>\n<li>the security-vulnerability scanner/the dependency-compliance\nscanner/a cloud-policy scanner (security dashboards)</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Find your buddy.</strong> Every SE team assigns one. If they\ndidn't, ask for one. Your buddy is the person you shadow for the next\ntwo weeks.</li>\n<li><strong>Join Slack channels.</strong> The team channel, the on-call\nchannel, the ops channel. Read the last 30 days of on-call\npostmortems.</li>\n<li><strong>Read the team wiki.</strong> Look for the service catalog\n(what services exist, what they do, who owns them), the alarm runbook\n(what alarms fire, what they mean, how to fix them), and the on-call\nguide (who pages you, how to acknowledge, when to escalate).</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"day-2-3--find-the-teams-role-scope-page\">Day 2-3 — Find the\nTeam's Role-Scope Page</h3>\n<p>This is your homework. Every mature SE team has some version of a\ntypical SE team's role page. It might be on a wiki, it might be in a\nteam wiki, it might be in a README. Ask your buddy. If it doesn't exist,\nwrite down what you think it should be based on a real SE team's example\n(6 buckets: tickets, health, security, deploy, fleet, ops review).\nYou'll validate this in your 30-day manager 1:1.</p>\n<h3 id=\"day-4-5--shadow-a-ticket-end-to-end\">Day 4-5 — Shadow a Ticket\nEnd-to-End</h3>\n<p>Pick a low-severity ticket (Sev-3 or Sev-4). Watch your buddy handle\nit from intake to close. Take notes in this format:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>What happened</strong> (the symptom the customer\nreported)</li>\n<li><strong>How they diagnosed it</strong> (logs they checked, metrics\nthey graphed, commands they ran)</li>\n<li><strong>Root cause</strong> (the one-sentence technical\nexplanation)</li>\n<li><strong>How they fixed it</strong> (the exact change or rollback or\nconfig flip)</li>\n<li><strong>How they prevented it</strong> (alarm added, runbook\nupdated, monitoring improved)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Repeat this 3-5 times during week one. By Friday you should have a\npersonal runbook with 3-5 entries. This is your first real SE\nartifact.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-306090-plan-in-concrete-steps\">The 30/60/90 Plan in Concrete\nSteps</h2>\n<p>This is the muscle-memory checklist. Every 30 days you hit a\nmilestone. By day 90 you are the go-to person for 2-3 problem areas,\nwhich is the SE3 bar.</p>\n<h3 id=\"days-1-30-shadow--small-tickets--personal-runbook\">Days 1-30:\nShadow + Small Tickets + Personal Runbook</h3>\n<p><strong>What you're building:</strong> confidence in the\ntroubleshooting method, familiarity with the top 5 issues, a runbook you\ncan defend.</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Shadow 10-15 tickets.</strong> Mix of Sev-2, Sev-3, Sev-4.\nTake the notes format from week one. By day 30 you should have a\npersonal runbook with 10-15 entries covering the team's most common\nissues.</li>\n<li><strong>Take 5 small tickets solo.</strong> Sev-4 only. Your buddy\nreviews your work before you close the ticket. The goal is to practice\nthe method: understand -&gt; hypothesis -&gt; evidence -&gt; root cause\n-&gt; mitigate -&gt; fix -&gt; prevent.</li>\n<li><strong>Map the services.</strong> Draw a box-and-arrow diagram of\nthe team's services. What calls what? Where's the data stored? What\nalarms fire when X breaks? This is your mental model. Keep it in a file\nyou can update.</li>\n<li><strong>Join the weekly ops review.</strong> Sit in the back.\nListen. Take notes on what the team considers \"operational health\"\n(alarm noise, deployment blockers, fleet size vs plan, security risks).\nBy the end of 30 days you should know what the team's top 3 operational\npain points are.</li>\n<li><strong>Read the hands-on onboarding workshop.</strong> This is a\ntech company's internal \"how to be a builder\" training. Do the\nCloudWatch module. Do the troubleshooting module. Do the on-call module.\nLink: your team's internal docs</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>30-day checkpoint with your manager:</strong> \"Here's my\npersonal runbook. Here are the 5 tickets I closed. Here's the service\nmap I drew. What should I focus on next?\"</p>\n<h3 id=\"days-31-60-sev-2-independent--shadow-on-call--first-coe\">Days\n31-60: Sev-2 Independent + Shadow On-Call + First COE</h3>\n<p><strong>What you're building:</strong> the ability to handle a Sev-2\nwithout help, a full mental model of on-call, and your first reviewed\nCOE (correction of errors = a tech company's RCA doc).</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Take 3-5 Sev-2 tickets solo.</strong> Your buddy is backup,\nnot driver. You drive. You write the RCA. You write the COE. Your buddy\nreviews before you publish.</li>\n<li><strong>Shadow a full on-call rotation.</strong> This is a week (or\ntwo weeks depending on the team). You don't take pages, but you sit next\nto the on-call person and watch them handle every page. Take notes\non:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>How they triage (what do they check first?)</li>\n<li>How they escalate (when do they pull in another team?)</li>\n<li>How they mitigate fast (rollback? config flip? scale-up?)</li>\n<li>How they follow up (RCA written? alarm tuned? runbook updated?)</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Write your first COE.</strong> Pick a Sev-2 you handled.\nWrite the full RCA. Use the 5-whys method (keep asking \"why did that\nhappen?\" until you hit root cause). Have your buddy review it. This is\nyour first artifact that goes to leadership.</li>\n<li><strong>Improve the runbook.</strong> Add 5 new entries to the\nteam's runbook based on the tickets you've handled. This is Ownership LP\nevidence.</li>\n<li><strong>Proactive health check.</strong> Pick one service. Check its\nalarms. Check its metrics. Check its the security-vulnerability scanner\nrisks. Check its pipeline. Write a one-page health report. This is the\n\"monitor the right things\" muscle.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>60-day checkpoint with your manager:</strong> \"Here's the COE\nI wrote. Here's the on-call rotation I shadowed. Here's the runbook I\nimproved. I'm ready to go on-call solo with backup. What's the\ntimeline?\"</p>\n<h3 id=\"days-61-90-solo-on-call--improve-runbooks--be-the-go-to\">Days\n61-90: Solo On-Call + Improve Runbooks + Be the Go-To</h3>\n<p><strong>What you're building:</strong> the SE3 bar. You are the go-to\nperson for 2-3 problem areas. You can handle a full on-call week solo\n(with backup available). You have improved the team's operational health\nin a measurable way.</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>Take your first solo on-call rotation.</strong> You are\nprimary. Your buddy is backup. You handle every page. You write the\nRCAs. You tune the alarms. You update the runbooks. This is the SE\nbar.</li>\n<li><strong>Become the go-to for 2-3 areas.</strong> Pick 2-3 services\nor problem domains where you've handled 5+ tickets. Write a deep-dive\nguide for each one. Add it to the wiki. When the next person gets paged\non that issue, they read your guide. This is SE3 signal.</li>\n<li><strong>Improve operational health measurably.</strong> Pick one\nmetric: alarm noise (reduce false positives by 20%), deployment speed\n(reduce pipeline blockers by 3), security posture (clear 5 the\nsecurity-vulnerability scanner risks older than 20 days). Deliver it.\nWrite a one-pager. This is your first promo artifact.</li>\n<li><strong>Write a second COE.</strong> Pick a Sev-2 from your on-call\nweek. Write the full RCA. This time no one reviews it before publish.\nYou own it. This is the SE3 bar.</li>\n<li><strong>Mentor the next new SE.</strong> If the team hires another\nSE during your 90 days, you buddy them for their first week. If not, you\nwrite the onboarding doc for the next one. This is Earn Trust.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>90-day checkpoint with your manager:</strong> \"Here's my solo\non-call week. Here are the 2-3 areas I own. Here's the operational\nhealth win I delivered. I'm ready for SE3 or I'm building the case for\nit. What's the path?\"</p>\n<hr />\n<h2\nid=\"the-manager-conversation-smart-questions-and-how-to-frame-your-earlier-experience\">The\nManager Conversation: Smart Questions and How to Frame your earlier\nexperience</h2>\n<p>This conversation happens on day one or day two. The goal is to align\non expectations, placement, and growth path. Here's the script.</p>\n<h3 id=\"opening-frame\">Opening Frame</h3>\n<p>\"Thanks for bringing me onto the team. I want to make sure we're\naligned on what good looks like in 90 days, and I have a few questions\nabout the role scope and growth path.\"</p>\n<p>This is ownership. You're not asking \"what should I do?\", you're\nasking \"what does success look like?\".</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-8-questions-to-ask\">The 8 Questions to Ask</h3>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><p><strong>\"Does this team have an SE role-scope page and an on-call\nrunbook?\"</strong> (You already know this is the day-one question. Ask\nit anyway. It frames you as someone who thinks SE-first.)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>\"What's the difference between SE2 and SE3 on this team,\nand where do you see me starting?\"</strong> (This is the placement\nquestion. Listen carefully. If they say SE2, you respond with the\ninternship frame below. If they say SE3, you ask \"what would I need to\ndemonstrate in 90 days to confirm that?\")</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>\"Which services will I be supporting, and what's the\non-call cadence?\"</strong> (You need to know scope. Are you covering 2\nservices or 10? Is on-call weekly, bi-weekly, monthly? What's the\nrealistic page load?)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>\"Is this a transfer or will there be an interview\nloop?\"</strong> (You need to know if you're being evaluated. If there's\na loop, you prep for it. If it's a transfer, you focus on 30/60/90\ndelivery.)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>\"What does good look like in 90 days?\"</strong> (This is\nthe success criteria question. Your manager will give you 3-5 things.\nWrite them down. These become your 90-day milestones.)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>\"What are the team's top 3 operational pain points right\nnow?\"</strong> (This tells you where to focus. If alarm noise is killing\nthe team, your 90-day win is reducing it. If security posture is behind,\nyour win is clearing the security-vulnerability scanner risks.)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>\"What's the growth path from SE2 to SE3, and what's the\ntimeline?\"</strong> (You want to know if this is a 6-month path, a\n1-year path, or a \"prove it first\" path. This frames your promo\nplanning.)</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>\"Who should I shadow first, and who's my buddy?\"</strong>\n(You need a name. If they don't have one, you propose one based on who\nseems like the strongest SE on the team.)</p></li>\n</ol>\n<h3\nid=\"framing-your-background-use-this-if-placement-is-unclear\">Framing\nYour Background (Use This if Placement is Unclear)</h3>\n<p>If your manager says \"we're thinking SE2\" or \"let's see how you do in\n90 days,\" bring concrete evidence from your past work. Name specific\nthings you owned: an investigation you drove to root cause, an RCA you\nwrote, a cross-team dependency you untangled, a migration you delivered,\na recurring problem you fixed at the source. Use real artifacts (ticket\nIDs, code reviews, docs), not adjectives. Position the 90 days as\nconfirmation, not evaluation: \"I've done this kind of work before, I'm\nhappy to prove it here. What would you need to see?\" That turns the\nconversation into a clear contract.</p>\n<h2 id=\"things-to-study-before-day-one\">Things to Study Before Day\nOne</h2>\n<p>You have a window between \"offer accepted\" and \"day one\". Use it.\nHere's the sprint:</p>\n<h3 id=\"week-1-python-practice\">Week 1: Python Practice</h3>\n<p>SE work is half troubleshooting, half scripting. You need to be\ncomfortable reading Python and writing small scripts. Focus:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Read and understand boto3 (AWS SDK for Python). This is how you'll\nautomate CloudWatch queries, the ticketing system (like Jira or\nPagerDuty) ticket creation, alarm tuning.</li>\n<li>Write 3 small scripts: one that queries CloudWatch Logs, one that\nfetches the ticketing system (like Jira or PagerDuty) ticket details,\none that lists all alarms for a service.</li>\n<li>Practice on your own AWS account or a sandbox AWS account.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"week-2-the-troubleshooting-method-drills\">Week 2: The\nTroubleshooting Method Drills</h3>\n<p>Re-read the troubleshooting method from drill 04. Then practice it on\n3 real scenarios:</p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><strong>a past routing investigation a routing-not-found\nerror.</strong> Walk through your own RCA. Write it out as if you were\nteaching someone else. Identify which step of the method (understand,\nhypothesis, evidence, root cause, mitigate, fix, prevent) took the\nlongest and why.</li>\n<li><strong>a past cross-month data bug duplicate rows.</strong> Same\ndrill. Write the RCA. Identify the step.</li>\n<li><strong>A hypothetical Sev-2.</strong> Make one up. \"Service X is\nreturning 500s for 10% of requests.\" Walk through the method. What's\nyour first hypothesis? What evidence would you check? How would you\nmitigate fast?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"week-3-cloudwatch-logs-insights-skim\">Week 3: CloudWatch Logs\nInsights Skim</h3>\n<p>Go to your team's internal docs Read the query syntax. Write 5 sample\nqueries:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Count errors by error type in the last hour.</li>\n<li>Graph P50/P90/P99 latency over the last 24 hours.</li>\n<li>Find all requests for a specific employee ID.</li>\n<li>Filter by exception type and show stack traces.</li>\n<li>Group by endpoint and count requests.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You don't need to be an expert. You need to be comfortable enough\nthat when you hit CloudWatch on day one, you're not learning the syntax\nwhile a Sev-2 is burning.</p>\n<h3 id=\"week-4-the-hands-on-onboarding-workshop\">Week 4: the hands-on\nonboarding workshop</h3>\n<p>Do the full the hands-on onboarding workshop course. Link: your\nteam's internal docs Focus on:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The CloudWatch module (logs, metrics, alarms).</li>\n<li>The troubleshooting module (the method a tech company teaches is the\nsame one you've been using).</li>\n<li>The on-call module (how a tech company expects you to handle pages,\nescalate, write RCAs).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This is 8-10 hours. It's boring. It also makes your first week 50%\neasier because you'll recognize the tools and the language.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-weekly-self-review-habit\">The Weekly Self-Review Habit</h2>\n<p>Starting on day one, every Friday at 4pm, spend 30 minutes writing a\none-page self-review. Format:</p>\n<h3 id=\"this-week\">This Week</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tickets closed:</strong> (list them with the ticketing\nsystem (like Jira or PagerDuty) IDs and one-sentence root cause\neach)</li>\n<li><strong>New thing I learned:</strong> (one technical thing you\ndidn't know on Monday)</li>\n<li><strong>One operational win:</strong> (alarm tuned, runbook updated,\nhealth check completed, COE written)</li>\n<li><strong>One question for next week:</strong> (something you're still\nconfused about or want to dig deeper on)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"next-week\">Next Week</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Focus area:</strong> (which service or problem domain you're\ngoing to own this week)</li>\n<li><strong>Goal:</strong> (close 3 tickets, shadow on-call, write a\nrunbook entry, deliver a health check)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Save these in a folder. By day 90 you'll have 13 of them. When your\nmanager asks \"how's it going?\", you hand them the folder. This is the\nevidence trail for SE3.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-north-star\">The North Star</h2>\n<p>By day 90 you want your manager to say this in a 1:1:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"You're the go-to person for [service X] and [problem Y]. When\nsomeone gets paged on that, they come to you. You've delivered\nmeasurable operational wins. You're ready to mentor the next SE. Let's\ntalk about SE3 placement.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That's the bar. Everything in this playbook builds toward that\nsentence.</p>\n<p>Now go build it.</p>\n","text":"the transition playbook: first week, 30/60/90, and manager conversation what this trains: how to land smoothly on day one, build to se3 strength by day 90, and run the conversation that puts you on the right ladder rung from the start. the day one question that changes everything before you do anything else, before you read a single wiki page, before you join a single slack channel, ask your manager this: \"does this team have an se role scope page and an on call runbook?\" why this question wins: 1. it tells you if the team is organized. teams with mature se practices document them. teams without them expect you to figure it out yourself, which means your 90 days will be slower. 2. it frames you as someone who thinks like an se. you didn't ask \"what should i do?\", you asked for the team's own playbook. that's ownership. 3. it gives you the map. if they have both, you just got handed the blueprint. if they don't, you now know your 90 day deliverable: create them. if the answer is yes, read both docs that afternoon. if the answer is no, your 30/60/90 just wrote itself. first week: access, context, and the shadow list your first week has one job: get unblocked and find the pattern. here's the checklist, in order: day 1 — access and onboarding 1. the onboarding plan tool module. this is a tech company's standard new hire flow. do it. it's boring. it also unblocks your badge permissions. 2. request access. ask your manager for the groups you need: cloudwatch logs/insights (read access to the team's log groups) the ticketing system (ticket system) alarm console (the alarm dependency map in your monitoring tool or whatever the team uses) on call schedule tool (pagerduty, chime, or team internal) fleet management tools (if they run asgs or kubernetes) the security vulnerability scanner/the dependency compliance scanner/a cloud policy scanner (security dashboards) 3. find your buddy. every se team assigns one. if they didn't, ask for one. your buddy is the person you shadow for the next two weeks. 4. join slack channels. the team channel, the on call channel, the ops channel. read the last 30 days of on call postmortems. 5. read the team wiki. look for the service catalog (what services exist, what they do, who owns them), the alarm runbook (what alarms fire, what they mean, how to fix them), and the on call guide (who pages you, how to acknowledge, when to escalate). day 2 3 — find the team's role scope page this is your homework. every mature se team has some version of a typical se team's role page. it might be on a wiki, it might be in a team wiki, it might be in a readme. ask your buddy. if it doesn't exist, write down what you think it should be based on a real se team's example (6 buckets: tickets, health, security, deploy, fleet, ops review). you'll validate this in your 30 day manager 1:1. day 4 5 — shadow a ticket end to end pick a low severity ticket (sev 3 or sev 4). watch your buddy handle it from intake to close. take notes in this format: what happened (the symptom the customer reported) how they diagnosed it (logs they checked, metrics they graphed, commands they ran) root cause (the one sentence technical explanation) how they fixed it (the exact change or rollback or config flip) how they prevented it (alarm added, runbook updated, monitoring improved) repeat this 3 5 times during week one. by friday you should have a personal runbook with 3 5 entries. this is your first real se artifact. the 30/60/90 plan in concrete steps this is the muscle memory checklist. every 30 days you hit a milestone. by day 90 you are the go to person for 2 3 problem areas, which is the se3 bar. days 1 30: shadow + small tickets + personal runbook what you're building: confidence in the troubleshooting method, familiarity with the top 5 issues, a runbook you can defend. 1. shadow 10 15 tickets. mix of sev 2, sev 3, sev 4. take the notes format from week one. by day 30 you should have a personal runbook with 10 15 entries covering the team's most common issues. 2. take 5 small tickets solo. sev 4 only. your buddy reviews your work before you close the ticket. the goal is to practice the method: understand hypothesis evidence root cause mitigate fix prevent. 3. map the services. draw a box and arrow diagram of the team's services. what calls what? where's the data stored? what alarms fire when x breaks? this is your mental model. keep it in a file you can update. 4. join the weekly ops review. sit in the back. listen. take notes on what the team considers \"operational health\" (alarm noise, deployment blockers, fleet size vs plan, security risks). by the end of 30 days you should know what the team's top 3 operational pain points are. 5. read the hands on onboarding workshop. this is a tech company's internal \"how to be a builder\" training. do the cloudwatch module. do the troubleshooting module. do the on call module. link: your team's internal docs 30 day checkpoint with your manager: \"here's my personal runbook. here are the 5 tickets i closed. here's the service map i drew. what should i focus on next?\" days 31 60: sev 2 independent + shadow on call + first coe what you're building: the ability to handle a sev 2 without help, a full mental model of on call, and your first reviewed coe (correction of errors = a tech company's rca doc). 1. take 3 5 sev 2 tickets solo. your buddy is backup, not driver. you drive. you write the rca. you write the coe. your buddy reviews before you publish. 2. shadow a full on call rotation. this is a week (or two weeks depending on the team). you don't take pages, but you sit next to the on call person and watch them handle every page. take notes on: how they triage (what do they check first?) how they escalate (when do they pull in another team?) how they mitigate fast (rollback? config flip? scale up?) how they follow up (rca written? alarm tuned? runbook updated?) 3. write your first coe. pick a sev 2 you handled. write the full rca. use the 5 whys method (keep asking \"why did that happen?\" until you hit root cause). have your buddy review it. this is your first artifact that goes to leadership. 4. improve the runbook. add 5 new entries to the team's runbook based on the tickets you've handled. this is ownership lp evidence. 5. proactive health check. pick one service. check its alarms. check its metrics. check its the security vulnerability scanner risks. check its pipeline. write a one page health report. this is the \"monitor the right things\" muscle. 60 day checkpoint with your manager: \"here's the coe i wrote. here's the on call rotation i shadowed. here's the runbook i improved. i'm ready to go on call solo with backup. what's the timeline?\" days 61 90: solo on call + improve runbooks + be the go to what you're building: the se3 bar. you are the go to person for 2 3 problem areas. you can handle a full on call week solo (with backup available). you have improved the team's operational health in a measurable way. 1. take your first solo on call rotation. you are primary. your buddy is backup. you handle every page. you write the rcas. you tune the alarms. you update the runbooks. this is the se bar. 2. become the go to for 2 3 areas. pick 2 3 services or problem domains where you've handled 5+ tickets. write a deep dive guide for each one. add it to the wiki. when the next person gets paged on that issue, they read your guide. this is se3 signal. 3. improve operational health measurably. pick one metric: alarm noise (reduce false positives by 20%), deployment speed (reduce pipeline blockers by 3), security posture (clear 5 the security vulnerability scanner risks older than 20 days). deliver it. write a one pager. this is your first promo artifact. 4. write a second coe. pick a sev 2 from your on call week. write the full rca. this time no one reviews it before publish. you own it. this is the se3 bar. 5. mentor the next new se. if the team hires another se during your 90 days, you buddy them for their first week. if not, you write the onboarding doc for the next one. this is earn trust. 90 day checkpoint with your manager: \"here's my solo on call week. here are the 2 3 areas i own. here's the operational health win i delivered. i'm ready for se3 or i'm building the case for it. what's the path?\" the manager conversation: smart questions and how to frame your earlier experience this conversation happens on day one or day two. the goal is to align on expectations, placement, and growth path. here's the script. opening frame \"thanks for bringing me onto the team. i want to make sure we're aligned on what good looks like in 90 days, and i have a few questions about the role scope and growth path.\" this is ownership. you're not asking \"what should i do?\", you're asking \"what does success look like?\". the 8 questions to ask 1. \"does this team have an se role scope page and an on call runbook?\" (you already know this is the day one question. ask it anyway. it frames you as someone who thinks se first.) 2. \"what's the difference between se2 and se3 on this team, and where do you see me starting?\" (this is the placement question. listen carefully. if they say se2, you respond with the internship frame below. if they say se3, you ask \"what would i need to demonstrate in 90 days to confirm that?\") 3. \"which services will i be supporting, and what's the on call cadence?\" (you need to know scope. are you covering 2 services or 10? is on call weekly, bi weekly, monthly? what's the realistic page load?) 4. \"is this a transfer or will there be an interview loop?\" (you need to know if you're being evaluated. if there's a loop, you prep for it. if it's a transfer, you focus on 30/60/90 delivery.) 5. \"what does good look like in 90 days?\" (this is the success criteria question. your manager will give you 3 5 things. write them down. these become your 90 day milestones.) 6. \"what are the team's top 3 operational pain points right now?\" (this tells you where to focus. if alarm noise is killing the team, your 90 day win is reducing it. if security posture is behind, your win is clearing the security vulnerability scanner risks.) 7. \"what's the growth path from se2 to se3, and what's the timeline?\" (you want to know if this is a 6 month path, a 1 year path, or a \"prove it first\" path. this frames your promo planning.) 8. \"who should i shadow first, and who's my buddy?\" (you need a name. if they don't have one, you propose one based on who seems like the strongest se on the team.) framing your background (use this if placement is unclear) if your manager says \"we're thinking se2\" or \"let's see how you do in 90 days,\" bring concrete evidence from your past work. name specific things you owned: an investigation you drove to root cause, an rca you wrote, a cross team dependency you untangled, a migration you delivered, a recurring problem you fixed at the source. use real artifacts (ticket ids, code reviews, docs), not adjectives. position the 90 days as confirmation, not evaluation: \"i've done this kind of work before, i'm happy to prove it here. what would you need to see?\" that turns the conversation into a clear contract. things to study before day one you have a window between \"offer accepted\" and \"day one\". use it. here's the sprint: week 1: python practice se work is half troubleshooting, half scripting. you need to be comfortable reading python and writing small scripts. focus: read and understand boto3 (aws sdk for python). this is how you'll automate cloudwatch queries, the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) ticket creation, alarm tuning. write 3 small scripts: one that queries cloudwatch logs, one that fetches the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) ticket details, one that lists all alarms for a service. practice on your own aws account or a sandbox aws account. week 2: the troubleshooting method drills re read the troubleshooting method from drill 04. then practice it on 3 real scenarios: 1. a past routing investigation a routing not found error. walk through your own rca. write it out as if you were teaching someone else. identify which step of the method (understand, hypothesis, evidence, root cause, mitigate, fix, prevent) took the longest and why. 2. a past cross month data bug duplicate rows. same drill. write the rca. identify the step. 3. a hypothetical sev 2. make one up. \"service x is returning 500s for 10% of requests.\" walk through the method. what's your first hypothesis? what evidence would you check? how would you mitigate fast? week 3: cloudwatch logs insights skim go to your team's internal docs read the query syntax. write 5 sample queries: count errors by error type in the last hour. graph p50/p90/p99 latency over the last 24 hours. find all requests for a specific employee id. filter by exception type and show stack traces. group by endpoint and count requests. you don't need to be an expert. you need to be comfortable enough that when you hit cloudwatch on day one, you're not learning the syntax while a sev 2 is burning. week 4: the hands on onboarding workshop do the full the hands on onboarding workshop course. link: your team's internal docs focus on: the cloudwatch module (logs, metrics, alarms). the troubleshooting module (the method a tech company teaches is the same one you've been using). the on call module (how a tech company expects you to handle pages, escalate, write rcas). this is 8 10 hours. it's boring. it also makes your first week 50% easier because you'll recognize the tools and the language. the weekly self review habit starting on day one, every friday at 4pm, spend 30 minutes writing a one page self review. format: this week tickets closed: (list them with the ticketing system (like jira or pagerduty) ids and one sentence root cause each) new thing i learned: (one technical thing you didn't know on monday) one operational win: (alarm tuned, runbook updated, health check completed, coe written) one question for next week: (something you're still confused about or want to dig deeper on) next week focus area: (which service or problem domain you're going to own this week) goal: (close 3 tickets, shadow on call, write a runbook entry, deliver a health check) save these in a folder. by day 90 you'll have 13 of them. when your manager asks \"how's it going?\", you hand them the folder. this is the evidence trail for se3. the north star by day 90 you want your manager to say this in a 1:1: \"you're the go to person for [service x] and [problem y]. when someone gets paged on that, they come to you. you've delivered measurable operational wins. you're ready to mentor the next se. let's talk about se3 placement.\" that's the bar. everything in this playbook builds toward that sentence. now go build it.","words":2606},{"id":"training-linux-host-drills","section":"Training","title":"Linux host drills","html":"<h1 id=\"linux-host-troubleshooting-drills-sysde-round-simulator\">Linux\nHost Troubleshooting Drills (SysDE Round Simulator)</h1>\n<p><strong>What this trains:</strong> the one interview round that\nscares engineers moving into ops the most. You SSH into a broken box and\nthe interviewer watches your command sequence. This file drills that,\nhost layer only, the five dimensions (CPU, memory, disk, network,\nprocesses).</p>\n<p><strong>Companion to:</strong>\n<code>sysde-modules/05-linux-host-troubleshooting-deep.md</code> (the\nteaching). This file is the practice. Read 05 first, drill here.</p>\n<p><strong>How to use:</strong> Drills 1 to 4 are STUDY mode (model\nanswer shown, read and absorb). Drills 5 to 8 are LIVE mode (no answer\nin the file, you walk it with your coach in chat, the coach plays\ninterviewer). Run one LIVE drill per turn so it sticks.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"progress\">Progress</h2>\n<ul class=\"task-list\">\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Drill 1 (study) — high CPU, app\nstill responding</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Drill 2 (study) — disk full at 100%,\ndu total doesn't add up</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Drill 3 (study) — service up but\nslow</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Drill 4 (study) — can't reach\nanother host</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Drill 5 (LIVE) — memory pressure /\nOOM</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Drill 6 (LIVE) — load average high,\nCPU idle</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Drill 7 (LIVE) — stuck\nprocess</label></li>\n<li><label><input type=\"checkbox\" />Drill 8 (LIVE) — the combined\nmystery box</label></li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"where-we-left-off\">Where we left off</h2>\n<p>Not started. First LIVE drill is 5. Coach kicks it off in chat.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-reflex-memorize-this-order\">The reflex (memorize this\norder)</h2>\n<p>Every broken-host question gets the same opening 30 seconds. Run the\nquick health check, THEN drill into whichever dimension is the\nbottleneck.</p>\n<pre class=\"bash\"><code>uptime # load average, how long up\nfree -h # memory + swap\ndf -h # disk space per filesystem\ntop # live CPU + memory by process (press M to sort by memory)</code></pre>\n<p>Then the dimension-specific tool:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>CPU spinning: <code>top</code> then\n<code>strace -p &lt;PID&gt;</code></li>\n<li>Memory: <code>free -h</code>, <code>top</code> (M),\n<code>dmesg | grep -i oom</code></li>\n<li>Disk full: <code>df -h</code> then <code>du -sh /&lt;fs&gt;/*</code>\nthen <code>lsof | grep deleted</code></li>\n<li>Disk slow: <code>iostat -x 1 5</code> (watch\n<code>%util</code>)</li>\n<li>Network: <code>ss -tuln</code>, <code>ping</code>,\n<code>curl -v</code>, <code>dig</code>, last resort\n<code>tcpdump</code></li>\n<li>Process stuck: <code>strace -p &lt;PID&gt;</code>,\n<code>lsof -p &lt;PID&gt;</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The single most common mistake: jumping to a fix before running the\nquick health check. Always check all five quickly before you commit to\none.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-1-study--high-cpu-app-still-responding\">Drill 1 (study) —\nHigh CPU, app still responding</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Alarm fires for high CPU on a host. The\napp is still serving requests, just using 100% of one core. 8-core box,\nload average 1.2.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><code>top</code> then look at <code>%CPU</code>. One process pegging\n~100% (one full core).</li>\n<li>Note the PID. <code>ps -fp &lt;PID&gt;</code> for the full command.\nConfirm it's your app vs something unexpected.</li>\n<li>Load average 1.2 on 8 cores means the box is NOT overloaded overall,\nit's one process spinning one core.</li>\n<li><code>strace -p &lt;PID&gt;</code> to see if it's stuck in a tight\nsyscall loop, or burning CPU in user space (strace quiet = user-space\ncompute, likely an app hot loop).</li>\n<li>Conclusion: this is an app-code problem (a hot loop or busy-wait),\nnot a host capacity problem. Next step is app logs / thread dump, not\nadding hosts.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The tell:</strong> high CPU on ONE core with low overall load\n= app bug, not capacity. Adding hosts would not fix it.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-2-study--disk-full-the-numbers-dont-add-up\">Drill 2\n(study) — Disk full, the numbers don't add up</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> <code>df -h</code> shows <code>/</code> at\n100%. You run <code>du -sh /*</code> and the total is 12G on a 20G disk.\nWhere are the other 8G?</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><code>df -h</code> confirms 100% on <code>/</code>.</li>\n<li><code>du -sh /*</code> totals ~12G. Gap of 8G is unaccounted.</li>\n<li>The classic cause: a process deleted a large file but still holds it\nopen, so the kernel hasn't freed the space (du can't see it, df\ncan).</li>\n<li><code>lsof | grep deleted</code> finds the process holding deleted\nfile handles.</li>\n<li>Mitigate: restart that process (or truncate via its FD). Space frees\ninstantly.</li>\n<li>Also worth: <code>df -i</code> to rule out inode exhaustion (full\ninodes look like \"no space\" even with free bytes).</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The tell:</strong> df and du disagree = deleted-but-open\nfile. This is THE trick question in this category.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-3-study--service-is-up-but-slow\">Drill 3 (study) — Service\nis up but slow</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Process is running, <code>ss -tuln</code>\nshows it listening on 8080, but API calls take 5 seconds instead of\n50ms.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><code>top</code> — load average and CPU. High load + low CPU means\nprocesses are blocked waiting, not computing.</li>\n<li><code>free -h</code> — is <code>available</code> low and is Swap\nbeing used? Swapping makes everything slow.</li>\n<li><code>iostat -x 1 5</code> — is disk <code>%util</code> near 100%?\nSlow disk drags every request that touches it.</li>\n<li><code>ss -s</code> — connection summary. Thousands of connections or\nlots of TIME-WAIT means connection churn.</li>\n<li><code>curl -v http://localhost:8080/health</code> — fast locally but\nslow externally points to network/LB, not the host.</li>\n<li>If all five host dimensions are clean, the slowness is downstream\n(DB, external API). You ruled out the host layer first, which is the\nwhole point.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The tell:</strong> \"up but slow\" is a process of elimination\nacross the five. Say out loud which one you're ruling out and why.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"drill-4-study--cant-reach-another-host\">Drill 4 (study) — Can't\nreach another host</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Your service can't reach\n<code>payments-service.internal</code> on port 9090. Started an hour\nago.</p>\n<p><strong>Model walk:</strong></p>\n<ol type=\"1\">\n<li><code>ping payments-service.internal</code> — responds? If no,\nnetwork down or host down or ICMP blocked (note: some hosts block ping,\nso a failed ping alone isn't conclusive).</li>\n<li><code>dig payments-service.internal</code> — does DNS resolve, and\nto a sane IP? Stale or wrong IP = DNS problem.</li>\n<li><code>curl -v telnet://payments-service.internal:9090</code> or\n<code>nc -vz payments-service.internal 9090</code> — is the specific\nport open? Connection refused = nothing listening; timeout =\nfirewall/security-group dropping.</li>\n<li><code>traceroute payments-service.internal</code> — where does the\npath die? Stops mid-path = network/routing.</li>\n<li>Last resort\n<code>tcpdump -i any host payments-service.internal</code> — are your\npackets leaving and are replies coming back?</li>\n<li>Distinguish: refused (fast) = service down. Timeout (hangs) =\nfirewall/security group. Wrong IP = DNS. Each points somewhere\ndifferent.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The tell:</strong> \"refused vs timeout vs wrong-IP\" are three\ndifferent root causes. Naming which one you saw is the senior move.</p>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"live-drills-no-answers-here-walk-them-with-your-coach\">LIVE\ndrills (no answers here, walk them with your coach)</h2>\n<p>These four have no model answer in the file on purpose. In chat, the\ncoach plays the interviewer: gives you the scenario, you say the FIRST\ncommand, the coach gives you the realistic output, you react, repeat,\nuntil you name the root cause. That back-and-forth is the actual\ninterview. Run one per turn.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Drill 5 (LIVE):</strong> memory pressure, possible OOM kill.\nThe box \"feels fine\" but a process keeps disappearing.</li>\n<li><strong>Drill 6 (LIVE):</strong> load average 16 on a 4-core box,\nbut <code>top</code> shows CPU 90% idle. Explain and find the\ncause.</li>\n<li><strong>Drill 7 (LIVE):</strong> a process is stuck, not dead, not\nusing CPU, not responding. Find what it's waiting on.</li>\n<li><strong>Drill 8 (LIVE):</strong> the combined mystery box, you get\nvague \"it's broken\" and have to drive the whole five-dimension sweep\nyourself.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"command-reflex-cheat-cover-the-right-column-recall-it\">Command\nreflex cheat (cover the right column, recall it)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>When you see / suspect</th>\n<th>First command</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>anything broken (always)</td>\n<td><code>uptime; free -h; df -h; top</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>one process eating CPU</td>\n<td><code>top</code> then <code>strace -p &lt;PID&gt;</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>out of memory / process killed</td>\n<td><code>dmesg | grep -i oom</code>, <code>free -h</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>disk full</td>\n<td><code>df -h</code> then <code>du -sh /&lt;fs&gt;/*</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>disk full but du &lt; df</td>\n<td><code>lsof | grep deleted</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\"no space\" but bytes free</td>\n<td><code>df -i</code> (inodes)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>disk slow (not full)</td>\n<td><code>iostat -x 1 5</code>, watch <code>%util</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>what's listening on a port</td>\n<td><code>ss -tuln</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>can I reach host:port</td>\n<td><code>nc -vz host port</code> or <code>curl -v</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>DNS wrong/broken</td>\n<td><code>dig &lt;name&gt;</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>process stuck</td>\n<td><code>strace -p &lt;PID&gt;</code>,\n<code>lsof -p &lt;PID&gt;</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>service status + logs</td>\n<td><code>systemctl status X</code>, <code>journalctl -u X</code></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<h2 id=\"the-takeaway\">The takeaway</h2>\n<p>The Linux round is not about memorizing flags. It's about always\nrunning the five-dimension sweep before you commit, and naming what\nyou're ruling out as you go. You debugged the service layer for a year.\nThis is the layer underneath. Drill the LIVE scenarios until the command\nsequence is reflex, and this round stops being the scary one.</p>\n","text":"linux host troubleshooting drills (sysde round simulator) what this trains: the one interview round that scares engineers moving into ops the most. you ssh into a broken box and the interviewer watches your command sequence. this file drills that, host layer only, the five dimensions (cpu, memory, disk, network, processes). companion to: sysde modules/05 linux host troubleshooting deep.md (the teaching). this file is the practice. read 05 first, drill here. how to use: drills 1 to 4 are study mode (model answer shown, read and absorb). drills 5 to 8 are live mode (no answer in the file, you walk it with your coach in chat, the coach plays interviewer). run one live drill per turn so it sticks. progress [ ] drill 1 (study) — high cpu, app still responding [ ] drill 2 (study) — disk full at 100%, du total doesn't add up [ ] drill 3 (study) — service up but slow [ ] drill 4 (study) — can't reach another host [ ] drill 5 (live) — memory pressure / oom [ ] drill 6 (live) — load average high, cpu idle [ ] drill 7 (live) — stuck process [ ] drill 8 (live) — the combined mystery box where we left off not started. first live drill is 5. coach kicks it off in chat. the reflex (memorize this order) every broken host question gets the same opening 30 seconds. run the quick health check, then drill into whichever dimension is the bottleneck. then the dimension specific tool: cpu spinning: top then strace p <pid memory: free h , top (m), dmesg grep i oom disk full: df h then du sh /<fs / then lsof grep deleted disk slow: iostat x 1 5 (watch %util ) network: ss tuln , ping , curl v , dig , last resort tcpdump process stuck: strace p <pid , lsof p <pid the single most common mistake: jumping to a fix before running the quick health check. always check all five quickly before you commit to one. drill 1 (study) — high cpu, app still responding scenario: alarm fires for high cpu on a host. the app is still serving requests, just using 100% of one core. 8 core box, load average 1.2. model walk: 1. top then look at %cpu . one process pegging ~100% (one full core). 2. note the pid. ps fp <pid for the full command. confirm it's your app vs something unexpected. 3. load average 1.2 on 8 cores means the box is not overloaded overall, it's one process spinning one core. 4. strace p <pid to see if it's stuck in a tight syscall loop, or burning cpu in user space (strace quiet = user space compute, likely an app hot loop). 5. conclusion: this is an app code problem (a hot loop or busy wait), not a host capacity problem. next step is app logs / thread dump, not adding hosts. the tell: high cpu on one core with low overall load = app bug, not capacity. adding hosts would not fix it. drill 2 (study) — disk full, the numbers don't add up scenario: df h shows / at 100%. you run du sh / and the total is 12g on a 20g disk. where are the other 8g? model walk: 1. df h confirms 100% on / . 2. du sh / totals ~12g. gap of 8g is unaccounted. 3. the classic cause: a process deleted a large file but still holds it open, so the kernel hasn't freed the space (du can't see it, df can). 4. lsof grep deleted finds the process holding deleted file handles. 5. mitigate: restart that process (or truncate via its fd). space frees instantly. 6. also worth: df i to rule out inode exhaustion (full inodes look like \"no space\" even with free bytes). the tell: df and du disagree = deleted but open file. this is the trick question in this category. drill 3 (study) — service is up but slow scenario: process is running, ss tuln shows it listening on 8080, but api calls take 5 seconds instead of 50ms. model walk: 1. top — load average and cpu. high load + low cpu means processes are blocked waiting, not computing. 2. free h — is available low and is swap being used? swapping makes everything slow. 3. iostat x 1 5 — is disk %util near 100%? slow disk drags every request that touches it. 4. ss s — connection summary. thousands of connections or lots of time wait means connection churn. 5. curl v http://localhost:8080/health — fast locally but slow externally points to network/lb, not the host. 6. if all five host dimensions are clean, the slowness is downstream (db, external api). you ruled out the host layer first, which is the whole point. the tell: \"up but slow\" is a process of elimination across the five. say out loud which one you're ruling out and why. drill 4 (study) — can't reach another host scenario: your service can't reach payments service.internal on port 9090. started an hour ago. model walk: 1. ping payments service.internal — responds? if no, network down or host down or icmp blocked (note: some hosts block ping, so a failed ping alone isn't conclusive). 2. dig payments service.internal — does dns resolve, and to a sane ip? stale or wrong ip = dns problem. 3. curl v telnet://payments service.internal:9090 or nc vz payments service.internal 9090 — is the specific port open? connection refused = nothing listening; timeout = firewall/security group dropping. 4. traceroute payments service.internal — where does the path die? stops mid path = network/routing. 5. last resort tcpdump i any host payments service.internal — are your packets leaving and are replies coming back? 6. distinguish: refused (fast) = service down. timeout (hangs) = firewall/security group. wrong ip = dns. each points somewhere different. the tell: \"refused vs timeout vs wrong ip\" are three different root causes. naming which one you saw is the senior move. live drills (no answers here, walk them with your coach) these four have no model answer in the file on purpose. in chat, the coach plays the interviewer: gives you the scenario, you say the first command, the coach gives you the realistic output, you react, repeat, until you name the root cause. that back and forth is the actual interview. run one per turn. drill 5 (live): memory pressure, possible oom kill. the box \"feels fine\" but a process keeps disappearing. drill 6 (live): load average 16 on a 4 core box, but top shows cpu 90% idle. explain and find the cause. drill 7 (live): a process is stuck, not dead, not using cpu, not responding. find what it's waiting on. drill 8 (live): the combined mystery box, you get vague \"it's broken\" and have to drive the whole five dimension sweep yourself. command reflex cheat (cover the right column, recall it) when you see / suspect first command anything broken (always) uptime; free h; df h; top one process eating cpu top then strace p <pid out of memory / process killed dmesg \\ grep i oom , free h disk full df h then du sh /<fs / disk full but du < df lsof \\ grep deleted \"no space\" but bytes free df i (inodes) disk slow (not full) iostat x 1 5 , watch %util what's listening on a port ss tuln can i reach host:port nc vz host port or curl v dns wrong/broken dig <name process stuck strace p <pid , lsof p <pid service status + logs systemctl status x , journalctl u x the takeaway the linux round is not about memorizing flags. it's about always running the five dimension sweep before you commit, and naming what you're ruling out as you go. you debugged the service layer for a year. this is the layer underneath. drill the live scenarios until the command sequence is reflex, and this round stops being the scary one.","words":1415}];
